{"Author": "A. Magill", "Date": "on July 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Miserable", "Text": "I was disappointed. Looking into this beforehand, it seemed aimed directly at my nerdy engineer heart. It's programmable with a well-documented language and API, it supports loads of third-party devices, and it's supposed to have enough of its own brains to work mostly independent of the cloud. I couldn't wait to start getting stuff hooked up to it.\n\nOnce I had it in hand, though, I was almost immediately frustrated and disappointed.\n\nActually getting devices to pair with it was a strangely major struggle. Following the normal instructions (didn't work), then the troubleshooting instructions (didn't work), then suggestions from around the internet, actually getting a device to pair took around an hour. This happened with all three devices I got (a dimmer plug, a dimmer switch, and a deadbolt, all different brands). Even then, communication was unreliable, had poor range, and often took several seconds to respond. At one point, I had somehow apparently paired a device twice at once- before it wasn't connected at all, and then suddenly there were two entries for it. Now they also make it surprisingly annoying to un-pair a device- you have to get the device to request that it be un-paired. But that only made my duplicate pairing situation worse, not better- it removed the working pairing, but left behind the one that didn't. So I had a device listed in the app with no apparent way of removing it. I finally found out if I go through a certain web site, there are advanced controls to just delete a device, and that fixed it.\n\nI found the Android app to be pretty annoying, the web site kind of terrible, and the Windows application that's advertised on the product page simply does not exist.\n\nAnother thing I was unhappy about was that it's absolutely dependent on the Cloud to function. Not even just for weather updates or for communicating with you from outside the house or that kind of thing, but for everything. Even if you write your own programs to control your devices, sometimes they might run locally on the hub, sometimes they might run on Samsung's servers and tell the hub what to do. There's no way to know or control that decision. So if you lose internet access, maybe your light switch stops working too.\n\nI've seen IoT-type devices done right. It's rare, but it happens. My RainMachine sprinkler timer, for example, is just about a perfect example of getting the technical details right. With this is looks like the developers set out with some great ideas, but then something went terribly wrong with the implementation. I have literally myself programmed electronic devices to be able to discover and communicate with each other wirelessly, and I'm baffled by how poorly the SmartThings hub does it. I've returned all of my Z-wave stuff."}
