{"Author": "Lee", "Date": "on July 4, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty disappointed since I bought this to replace my Wink ...", "Text": "Pretty disappointed since I bought this to replace my Wink hub. The Wink has much greater versatility working with the Schlage smart locks with remote code programming from the mobile app. Whereas SmartThings doesn't have that capability."}
{"Author": "Bernie", "Date": "on July 4, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I would suggest alternative options", "Text": "Not easy to use. Not able to set loud alarms on my phone triggered by sensors without purchasing a separate siren.\nI am almost sure there are more cost effective systems out there. Notice that I am Samsung fan and this time I was disapointed"}
{"Author": "Duane Kiser", "Date": "on July 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for real automation of the home....", "Text": "I have used the SmartThings hub for several months now... I rate it no better functional that any other hub based on what is provided by manufacture. One bright spot is that several companies are or have built 3rd party Rules Based Engines for SmartThings (IF/THEN/ELSE). The recent addition of Scenes to ST only brings it up to the level of other hubs like Vera. I dumped my expensive Vera hub directly for the reason of lack of a Rules Based Engine solution. The whole purpose of automation is that I don't have to be the brain to drive the system (push a button). I want a system that will look at the environment and on specific events (i.e. motion sensor = active then open multiple vents and turn on Fans & A/C, else close the vents and turn off the fans & A/C) and make decisions without further interaction on my part.\n\nScenes and routines require for me to decide it time for an action and press a button to make it work. I don't have the time to be the brain for my automation hub... That's what I bought the hub for in the first place...."}
{"Author": "Rob", "Date": "on July 2, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Easy to install. Works great"}
{"Author": "tdell", "Date": "on July 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Start your SmartHome with SmartThings", "Text": "If you are adding smart home technology, start with the SmartThings hub. It works with virtually every smart home sensor, switch or light and eliminates the need for other control hubs. The app is really simple to setup and provides macro control functions that you can customize.\n\nMy connected devices:\nChamberlain MyQ Garage Control\nAmazon Echo\nPhillips Hue bulbs\nGE SmartSwitches\nFireplace DrySwitch control\nNest Thermostat\nNest Alert 4x\nNest Cam Indoor 2x\nNest Cam Outdoor 4x\nSchlage Camelot Dead Bolt"}
{"Author": "Stevan H. Wofse", "Date": "on June 30, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bad news but getting better...", "Text": "Mine died after 3 months of quite limited use. That's the bad news...it may be getting better though. As I was filling out a complaint form a little popup drifted across the screen (quickly). Generally I hate those ymmv, but this time I figured why not see how Samsung handles it as I'm considering buying a TV from them. After 90 seconds or so Luis answered with an apology for the wait, heck I wait 2x longer for hot water from my 'instant on' water heater.\n\nLuis asked the usual questions at 1st but then, without asking , offered a replacement as a solution...here comes the hitch I thought. But no, he said they'll send it upfront and I can return mine in the packing box it comes in...WOW.\n\nNow I hope it happens, I'm cynical by nature. But so far so good.\n\nI will update this review after a final resolution."}
{"Author": "Timothy T.", "Date": "on June 30, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "User friendly app and a hub with pretty good reliability.", "Text": "It works like a charm except for when I try to use our phones as presence sensors. Then they work 75-80% of the time. I know support states that interference can come from all the WIFI and other devices and locations etc... so I will continue adjusting the hub location or my router or the geo fence distance and eventually the phone itself. For all of my other devices connected to the hub though, the setup, linking and programming is easy and my lights work exactly as programmed. I plan to add thermostats in the future but for now the outlets, switched, and garage controller work great."}
{"Author": "CC413", "Date": "on June 29, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am disappointed that the hub requires internet access at all times ...", "Text": "Timed events are not working reliably. I am disappointed that the hub requires internet access at all times to perform simple tasks. It makes me question the longevity of the system."}
{"Author": "fatgotti", "Date": "on June 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starting point", "Text": "The Samsung smart things hub is a great place to start on your home automation projects and it is a lot cheaper here than on there own website. Easy to setup and with the support from all the forums the possibilities are endless."}
{"Author": "Norm", "Date": "on June 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazon sold as new and it wasn't - had been repackaged and wasted over an hour to get support to make it work", "Text": "Not because it doesn't work - Amazon said it was brand new and I spent over an hour with Samsung support. They said the welcome code had been used before - I had to take a picture of the serial number on the unit and email to support for them to reset the device - of course that is after the time you figure out what is wrong - also my monitoring system reported the device disconnecting for a couple of minutes and then reconnecting a couple of times - don't understand why that would happen since it is hard wired."}
{"Author": "JocelynS", "Date": "on June 27, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth it", "Text": "I got this because I thought it'd manage all my smart devices easily.\nYes it connected to Alexa, yes it connected to Phillps Hue HUB, yes it connected to my Schlage Camelot Touchscreen Deadbolt, but it didn't integrate anything.\nCouldn't ask Alexa to start a routine/scene, couldn't replace the Hue Hub, and couldn't ask Alexa to lock or unlock my door. Couldn't manage PINs to deadbolt like Wink! Hub. TP Link Plug-in switches aren't compatible. Disconnected often.\nWorthless. Waste of money and time."}
{"Author": "Barry Laminack", "Date": "on June 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No complaints", "Text": "Love it. It does everything I need and want."}
{"Author": "Kathy B", "Date": "on June 26, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awful, get the Wink Hub 2", "Text": "We have a pretty good number of home automation products including Ring, Sonos, Nest, Chamberlain garage door openers. Recently added Schlage which required the Z Wave and a hub. I read a ton of reviews and the product descriptions for all the Z wave hubs and decided to go with the SmartThings because of the battery backup and some people noted Wink didn't work that well with the locks. Let me tell you what, this hub only gives you the most basic functionality of any product that you have, it's not even worth it. It was absolutely worthless with the Schlage Z Wave connect lock and I may as well have not purchased it at all, I had the same minimal functionality - to lock and unlock. For my other systems it was not as capable as the apps I already my phone that are connected to my wifi. We spent 4 hours trying to figure out how to do a developer app and finally just gave up. I ordered the Wink hub 2 and it's wireless (huge plus, doesn't HAVE to be plugged into your router like the Samsung) and I had that baby set up and humming in 15 minutes for all my products and with the same functions as my apps and more! There are a ton of cool robots easy as pie to program that can send notifications, emails, turn stuff on and off and all kinds of cool tricks. This Samsung is not ready for prime time, don't even waste your time. Get the Wink 2."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 25, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart HUB", "Text": "The HUB is small, light, and looks nice. Easy to add other z-wave devices to it if you follow the manufacturer's instructions carefully. I have no problem pairing with the Ecolink door/window sensors, but struggled a little with the Aeon Labs Siren. Samsung customer support is very good. I am still new to this Smart Home Monitor app and found it little tricky to configure."}
{"Author": "David Warner", "Date": "on June 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product- doesn't provide full function for Schlage locks", "Text": "Love this product (and no monthly fee) but it does not have any apps that allow programming user codes remotely on Schlage door locks. Need Nexia Bridge for that, so I am returning the Samsung SmartThings and getting Nexia with a $10/month fee."}
{"Author": "Sith101", "Date": "on June 24, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "NOTHING STAYS CONNECTED", "Text": "If you want a system we're you have to pair the sensors every other day then this is for you. Door and motion sensors always disconnecting. I was hyped about buying this after being disappointed with another system but this system is far worse. For a security system this is a bad joke and the only people who are laughing is Samsung all the way to the bank. Just look at the Apple App Store for reviews. The best answer I can get out of customer support is to keep pairing the sensors again again again again again and again. For a smart home system it is very dumb."}
{"Author": "Kevin Su", "Date": "on June 24, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the worst piece of sheit ever created. Save yourself the hassle and buy wink 2 if you want to have smart lock code mgmnt", "Text": "2X MORE expensive than wink hub 2 with 2 times less features. Does not have advance lock code management software as default. They want you to DOWNLOAD THIRD PARTY SOFTWARE for it to work!!\n\nBait and switch false advertisement. Samsung, you make great phones, but did not deliver on your commitments this time around.\n\nWhy are the developers so dam stupid and lazy for not fully creating this feature in the first place?"}
{"Author": "C. Stube", "Date": "on June 24, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... of home automation products over the years but the smart things hub is by far one of the easiest ...", "Text": "I've used a LOT of home automation products over the years but the smart things hub is by far one of the easiest and advanced for the average homeowner. It succeeds where others fall short. There is no complicated programming to learn, they've thought of everything that I would normally do and put it all in there for you to use right away. It's easy to set up, even for the uninitiated."}
{"Author": "smouanes", "Date": "on June 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. Very reliable so far", "Text": "Works great. Very reliable so far."}
{"Author": "C. Olson", "Date": "on June 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I've had nothing but great luck with smartthings", "Text": "I've had nothing but great luck with smartthings. Lots of integration options, great 3rd party app support (rboy), reliability ..all good"}
{"Author": "Tracy", "Date": "on June 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Didn't Know that it needed to be hardwired to the ...", "Text": "Didn't Know that it needed to be hardwired to the internet. I have to an Ethernet cable and run it through my house...... :("}
{"Author": "Bob", "Date": "on June 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "RBoy's SmartThings Applications", "Text": "I've been using SmartThings V 2 hub for just about 2 years for basic home security and automation. I've just subscribed to RBoy's applications to integrate a Foscam camera and in anticipation of the addition of Blink cameras. I found that RBoy's Foscam app easily installed into ST's. The support offered by the RBoy group allowed the Foscam camera to be used to its full potential within the ST environment. RBoy's group provider quick and accurate support."}
{"Author": "nopublicnameforme", "Date": "on June 19, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "asked for a refund before receiving it.", "Text": "i think i asked for a refund before receiving it."}
{"Author": "Michael T. Dugan", "Date": "on June 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "delivered quickly and as described"}
{"Author": "Michael P.", "Date": "on June 18, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Missing Critical Capabilities", "Text": "Great hub. Missing POE, WIFI, and USB cellular capabilities. When the Internet is down, the unit is useless. Needs to support a backup cellular Internet solution to really be functional. Cannot use for security system or critical systems or lights until there is a backup Internet. IF I had to do it again, I would get a different HUB that supports POE, WIFI, and a USB Internet backup solution."}
{"Author": "Ben D.", "Date": "on June 17, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not bad, but limited compatibility.", "Text": "Purchased to use with my Schlage Z-Wave Connect Century Touchscreen Deadbolt with Built-In Alarm, Works with Amazon Alexa via SmartThings, Wink or Iris, Satin Chrome, BE469 CEN 626 lock to make using the lock a little easier. Didn't do enough research beforehand, though. While it was easy to set up and connect to the lock, it could only handle lock/unlock actions. No user management or advanced monitoring, which apparently other hubs (Wink Hub 2, for example) can do. Long story short, make sure that it will not only be compatible with your device, but that it will handle the specific commands you want it to do."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was very easy to set up and connect to Alexa using the ...", "Text": "Don't have any \"things\" yet to control with it but bought it while it was on sale to eventually control light switches and motion sensors. Was very easy to set up and connect to Alexa using the SmartThings app on my phone (which was also easy to install and set up)."}
{"Author": "Diivious", "Date": "on June 16, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No internet? No workie.", "Text": "OK, I am going to grade this a bit harsh. In reality its likely 3 starts. Here is by biggest complaint - it does NOT work without internet connection. If you loose (or don't have) internet access then forget this as a hub. In my case i have DSL, but its bad about going out every hard rain. When that happens, the hub will NOT perform any of its actions (no at dark/dawn, no motion, etc)."}
{"Author": "C. M. Lance", "Date": "on June 16, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Erratic Automation Scheduling", "Text": "I purchased the Hub so I could program devices in my home to turn on and off on schedule. It's supposed to do that, the app has an automation section and I've programmed the thermostat and front door lock to change settings on schedule. It does change them ---- sometimes. Several times I've checked the front door after it's supposed to have locked and it wasn't locked. The morning heat setting has been missed on occasion and I've had to turn the heat on myself. Likewise with the Good Night heat setting. I've had to lower the heat manually. Most of the time it seems to work, but I'd guess that 10% of the time it doesn't.\n\nI bought this set up instead of a programmable thermostat. The programmable thermostat I had in my last house never failed. This one fails 10% of the time.\n\nI don't know if the Hub sends a signal and it's ignored or if it misses sending a signal, but either way, sometimes the program settings don't happen.\n\nIt is easy to set up or I'd rate it lower. But, it needs a way of checking to make sure the programmed changes take place. Now I'll worry when I leave on vacation about whether it will work."}
{"Author": "newbostonconst", "Date": "on June 16, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Samsung costumer support is lacking."}
{"Author": "diydiy", "Date": "on June 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great, but sensors and switches cost money and setup time.", "Text": "addicted to ST. my budget is sorry I bought this.\nseriously cool. but, seriously expensive things to connect to it. look at prices for switches, sensors before you get into this.\nif someone looks at my house I get a notification, lights, sirens... - but at what a cost!"}
{"Author": "Rick B.", "Date": "on June 14, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wink was easier to utilize", "Text": "I have both the wink and the Samsung smart things. The wink is so much easier to install and manage devices. I returned the smart things hub and stayed with the wink."}
{"Author": "Larry B.", "Date": "on June 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It sucks. Stay away!"}
{"Author": "KevinS", "Date": "on June 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A Good Start", "Text": "Have used this ST v2 hub for two months now and really like it. Not overworking it, with just a door lock and AC thermostat linked up but on the whole the hub has worked well and proved reliable even after smart app updates.\n\nLinking my two devices to the hub was straightforward and finding extended Device Handlers and more comprehensive apps on the development community / ST forum was well worth the effort.\n\nThe only issue I had (and reason for 4 stars) was activating the hub out of the box. As others have found, the activation code just did not work, failing time and again. Only after a hard rest could I get it to fire up. While I was happy to persevere, I'm not sure everyone would be as patient and would simply return for the refund. Samsung need to review this.\n\nIf you're dipping your toe into smart home technology, this hub is a good starting point. There's a enthusiastic community and lots of help and ideas out there for those that really want to explore the potential of this little box.\n\nI expect to add a few more devices in the coming months."}
{"Author": "Betty", "Date": "on June 14, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to install and get started. I am still learning it"}
{"Author": "craig cotter", "Date": "on June 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth it, stops working and I get no support from the manufacture", "Text": "The hub itself is awful. It stopped communicating with all my devices making it useless. I reset it twice and still looses all communication. I have asked for help from the manufacture and received nothing"}
{"Author": "Brizehouse", "Date": "on June 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not Impressed", "Text": "I've had smartthings for about 6 months now and I feel it is a total waste of money. I have it set up to turn on lights at sunset and to turn on lights at night when I get close to home.\nThe first couple months it worked great. Now I can be home for 30 minutes before it recognizes that I've arrived. And that's if it even knows I left. Lately it doesn't even recognize I've left, so it's not arming my house in the away mode. I only have 40 items connected to my smartthings hub. Not impressed at all and will definitely be shopping for a replacement soon."}
{"Author": "John Clark", "Date": "on June 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... which home system to go with and am so glad that I chose SmartThings", "Text": "I agonized over which home system to go with and am so glad that I chose SmartThings. I have integrated several devices seamlessly. The GUI is awesome, makes changes on my PC and everyone is updated."}
{"Author": "Ed", "Date": "on June 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy setup, configuration and use. Works well with Alexa and WeMo products."}
{"Author": "Michael B", "Date": "on June 12, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub purchase is nearing one year ... resolving an issue with support", "Text": "I try to admit when I make a mistake -- usually. I might have made a premature judgment on the support from Samsung. I will edit my review in a few days. Still working on an issue with the support team.\nSamsung SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excelent Automation Hub", "Text": "Excellent product, works very well"}
{"Author": "Scott Barnes", "Date": "on June 11, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Garbage", "Text": "Colossal sack of garbage. No grouping capability in the app. App can't change things like color within \"automations\", and no support for simple \"scenes\". I got this over the Wink hub because it was suppose to be more powerful. No sir. This is garbage and I'm returning it."}
{"Author": "CES", "Date": "on June 11, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worked after calling support", "Text": "Works as designed. Setup is tricky if you already have a Samsung account prior to buying this hub."}
{"Author": "JKR", "Date": "on June 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Sorry I spent so much money on this stuff", "Text": "The 25% of the time that the Smartthings devices actually work they are great. The issue is they don't work about 75% of the time. Smartthings support's answer is always remove and put back the batteries when the peripherals stop contacting the hub. The batteries are very difficult to remove especially when you have to climb a ladder to get to them. Sometimes a door sensor will not work then 5 minutes later it is working again then 2 days later it stops working again and does not work until the battery is pulled."}
{"Author": "schwizer", "Date": "on June 10, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No app for Windows Phone anymore", "Text": "-2 stars because windows phone no longer supported."}
{"Author": "SW", "Date": "on June 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Leaves much to be desired...", "Text": "When reading reviews on technical equipment, one must take into account that not all users are created equal. People will sometimes give a poor review to some piece of equipment or software stating \"it didn't work correctly,\" often without realizing \"operator failure\" to be the cause. That said...since this product has such mixed reviews, I decided to test it out primarily because of its ability to integrate with Amazon Alexa, Harmony Smart Hub, Schlage Keyless Entry, Linear Garage Doors and most importantly all of the Z-Wave outlets and switches throughout my home. The basic hub setup was relatively painless except for having to \"unpair\" each of the above items from the existing Z-Wave controller in order to then pair it with the SmartThings Hub. Once that tedious task is complete then you must set up each of your automations not only on the ST Hub but also with any controllers such as Alexa and Harmony. Depending on how many products you have to pair, this process can be fairly labor intensive. Once I completed the pairing processing it was time to set \"automations\". Here's where my issues began. Paired items either wouldn't operate or operated intermittently. My AV equipment and TV would turn on every morning between 10:45 am and 11 am. When requesting that Alexa perform certain functions she'd attempt to perform the action, however the item or items did not respond to her commands. After a week of unnecessary frustration, I was ready to return the Hub until I saw there was a \"major update\" on the horizon. I decided to hold off on returning the equipment until after the update in the event there was some \"WOW Factor\" improvements. Well folks, I'll close this review by saying, the only WOW factor with this product for me is \"WOW I can't believe I bought it!\""}
{"Author": "Jason", "Date": "on June 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good cheap hub for home automation", "Text": "The setup process took about 10 minutes, but only took a few seconds of actually inputting information. The rest of the time the phone was calibrating the Hub. I am impressed so far with the range that the hub has. Having a really old house I was able to have the Hub on the main level on one side of the house and have the leak sensor down in the basement on the other side. I have done many tests to verify that everything is connected and working, and every time I receive a notification within seconds of a sensor going off."}
{"Author": "MDN", "Date": "on June 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... outdoor z-wave lighting switches (via Alexa) and it works great.", "Text": "setup could be a bit easier but I'm using this with my GE outdoor z-wave lighting switches (via Alexa) and it works great."}
{"Author": "John Kash", "Date": "on June 9, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "DO NOT BUY UNLESS YOU WANT A NEW GEEKYHOBBY AND HOME HEADACHE.", "Text": "I am very disappointed. CONS FIRST: This device is not yet ready for market and every item purchased which is listed as compatible on the app have not worked as advertised. EXAMPLES 1. None of the battery powered wall mounted dimming switches will actually adjust light brightness. On and off is the only option from the wall switch. Dimming can only be done with the phone app. 2. SONOS owners beware-every time you use the app to search for a new device (thing), your SONOS speakers are hijacked and their operation from your SONOS controller is compromised. Even after you remove the SONSO speakers (1 at a time) from the app they are wonky for a a few hours. Samsung phone tech support says this is a known issue with no fix in the pipeline. 3. Tech support relies heavily on the online user groups for help. They even sent me there because they had no answer. This is fine if you want SMARTTHINGS as a hobby. Geek out if you want. If you want an easily installed, stable and reliable smarthome system, this is not for you. Bear in mind, I am a bit of a geek, but when it comes to something the rest of the family has to use, I want it to be simple and bullet proof. SMARTHINGS is neither. 4. SAMSUNG's compatibility list is outright false advertising. 5. If your idea of a smarthome is controlling everything with the SMARTHINGS app, you may be fairly satisfied with this device. If you want wall switches and remotes to also control your home (you know, walk into a room and use a dimmer on the wall to control lights like cavemen did) this thing stinks. 6. Do not use Amazon's frequently-bought-together guidelines for compatability. Even SAMSUNG tech support said that is giving them headaches. PRO LAST: 1. Very attractive 2. Built in battery backup 3. Small footprint. 4. No range issues in a 4,000 3 floor home 5. No port forwarding required yet 6. Easy initial installation except for the SONOS problem. Devices (things as samsung calls them) install easily (but many advertised features are simply not available. There are cheats for this on the message boards sometimes, but that's a pain in the butt). TO CONCLUDE: I had high hopes for this device, which are in the crapper. I am so close to returning it and all devices I have bought for it. The only thing stopping me is the huge amount of time I have into troubleshooting. SAMSUNG tech support even sent me a $50 Amazon gift card for all my troubles. Their phone log for me goes on for hours. I know networks and tech better than most and I am very frustrated. I would not buy it again and I obviously do not recommend this product."}
{"Author": "SHAUN D PARKS", "Date": "on June 8, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "NO BLUETOOTH MESH SUPPORT!!!!!!!!!", "Text": "This hub will NOT communicate with any of the GE/Avi-on Bluetooth Mesh technology equipment.\n\nThe good people at ST customer support had this to say \"The Hub v2 is future-ready to support Bluetooth, but the Bluetooth radio is not currently activated\"\n\nFYI the V2 release date was September of 2015"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works like a charm", "Text": "Interesting solution for home automation.\n\nI have attached a few dimmable light bulbs, switches, and 3 amazon echos. Works like a charm. I was also able to coonect this unit to a external data visualization platform (initial state). Happy with this purchase."}
{"Author": "Steve", "Date": "on June 7, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This really is a waste of time and effort", "Text": "This really is a waste of time and effort. The product has yet to connect and the support from Samsung is even worse. DO NOT BUY AT ALL!"}
{"Author": "Sherman Robinson", "Date": "on June 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Decent hub with user complications", "Text": "UPDATE 9/26: I reached out to Samsung about the issue I was having with my hub. They quickly responded with the reason why it happened and the solution. Unfortunately, I had to re-sync all of my z-wave light switches to it but now it's back working fine. My only major gripe to this hub is that it's not completely user-friendly; you have to fool with it a bit to get it to work the way you want it to. But otherwise great.\n\nUPDATE 9/22: Apparently, this hub only works for about 4 months. Purchased this back in May, now it's no good. It randomly deleted all of my devices and refuses to add them back. Shame on you Samsung!\n\nI purchased this in order to connect a few GE Z-Wave switches to my Echo Dots. Getting the hub setup and going was pretty easy. Connecting the switches to it wasn't that difficult either. Very easy to integrate with Alexa thru the app and all of my switches work effortlessly with Alexa. I also like that the Smartthings app notifies you when you're connected/disconnected from the WiFi. That help me troubleshoot any modem connection issue I may be having."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Bad Stuff"}
{"Author": "Gabriel Silva", "Date": "on June 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "Love it! I get to slowly build and customise my own automated home. No monthly fees or payments. I can monitor everything in my home and get alerts. Really great to have. Love it!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy without research", "Text": "Doesn't work with any other product I bought, YI camera or Phillips lightbulbs. Have a useless piece of electronics sitting around.\n\nSo no idea if it is a good piece of hardware or not."}
{"Author": "Sven AW", "Date": "on June 3, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product if you can do everything yourself", "Text": "You have to get it done yourself. SmartThings technical service really sucks"}
{"Author": "Big Bubba", "Date": "on June 2, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "All the tech you buy with them is 100% only useful with them", "Text": "Usless upon comcast, Time Warner(Spectrum) take over. All the tech you buy with them is 100% only useful with them."}
{"Author": "John H Chappell", "Date": "on June 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "great price"}
{"Author": "Robert Ewart", "Date": "on June 1, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hardware is fine. Android app is an accident waiting to happen.", "Text": "I got the first generation hub two years ago. The hub is working fine. The android app to control it is a major disaster. Every time they release a new version, I loose contact with my things.\nI bought it to turn on the outside lights when I'm coming home after dark. Not having a reliable way to turn them on is potential for a major disaster."}
{"Author": "John S. Peraino", "Date": "on May 31, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I bought the Samsung and couldn't be happier.", "Text": "I originally bought the VeraPlus. After going through 2 of them, I bought the Samsung and couldn't be happier."}
{"Author": "S. Stone", "Date": "on May 31, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The hub worked fairly well with the exception of it ...", "Text": "The hub worked fairly well with the exception of it going off line, around the same time every day. Turns out it picked up the same IP as my Samsung TV. Hub should have the ability to assign a static IP, as my TV does. Took a few weeks to figure it out, as the hub takes a bit of investigation to find it'd DHCP IP address. Still have issues with a Leviton switch loosing connectivity, trying another Leviton device placed closer to act as a repeater. Its a shame to spend $ 29 for a device I don't really need to act as a repeater. My switch that looses connectivity is only 20 feet from the hub"}
{"Author": "James", "Date": "on May 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Decective, does not work", "Text": "Hub stopped working a month after purchase. I bought two new sensors from two different companies, and both work...for an hour or two. Then I have to reboot the hub. I have to now do this constantly. The hub is defective."}
{"Author": "May yim", "Date": "on May 29, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It worked good, set it up had problems which called IT ...", "Text": "It worked good, set it up had problems which called IT he helped a lot . But the controller was not I expected it , I thought it can add code and remove code or somehow I can see codes on my phone? It only does is lock and unlock the door on phone . Little disappointed."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 27, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not an automatic installation", "Text": "In theory I love this device. As of yet I have not implemented the purpose for which I purchased it. I have a Schlage CONNECT lock tht I want to connect. I have not found it easy to get this up and running. To be fair I have given little to no time to the project because of a buy work schedule. I hope to carve out some time to resolve this soon. I gave this 4 stars because it is not yet doing what I bought it to do. But to be fair it is largely miy fault."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Meets expectations", "Text": "Works as expected."}
{"Author": "Matthew W.", "Date": "on May 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love to tinker and the support of this device with ...", "Text": "I love to tinker and the support of this device with different sensors and monitors is great. The SmartThings IDE and community opens a lot of home automation opportunities."}
{"Author": "Scott Moore", "Date": "on May 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the best Smart Hub PThis is the best Smart Hub Period!!!eriod!!!", "Text": "This is the best Smart Hub Period!!! Handles all my WeMo products like the Mr Coffee. So now I have it so when the Alexa alarm (Alexa set alarm for 6am) goes off it starts making coffee. We can change the morning alarm when ever we want and don't have to worry about re programming the coffee pot. Just one example."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 26, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If using as a light switch perfect but as security device running smart apps on android ...", "Text": "If using as a light switch perfect but as security device running smart apps on android app and a Samsung, problematic and I do not recommend. Randomly fires apps that are a real concern especially if a door lock or other safety items connected. Samsung phones do not work well as location but iphones do so I would recommend this with iphone"}
{"Author": "lou", "Date": "on May 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The samsung is a good hub to centralize many different smart devices for you ...", "Text": "The samsung is a good hub to centralize many different smart devices for you home. The samsung name keeps representing quality products that work."}
{"Author": "Yarrow10", "Date": "on May 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great when you set everything up and figure it out.", "Text": "We did a lot of research on emerging smart home technology and what system would work best for us. Over the last couple of years, Samsung has left a bad taste in our mouths with business and production scandals, so we were a little reluctant to buy from them. I have to say that this is the way to go. They are supporting many third party manufacturers and adding to their list of supported devices all the time. We bought this along with sensors from samsung and other companies, and all of them have paired easily and been great to use through the app. We are going to continue to add new devices and sensors to get more use and automation. It takes a little getting used to using the app and setting up routines but in the long run it makes sense and makes things easier."}
{"Author": "Frank", "Date": "on May 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The command center, works perfectly", "Text": "This is the command center of my house now"}
{"Author": "amozan", "Date": "on May 23, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "This works great, android app doesn't always though, Google home works with it well"}
{"Author": "Damage Inc XLE", "Date": "on May 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for starting home automation and basic security.", "Text": "Very cool device to start out home automation. The ability to add non-native devices is great. Adding devices via code is straight forward and easy and adds lots of less expensive nice hardware. I set mine up for security and door chimes very easily using Bosch motion detectors, Visonic door sensors and the Zooz chime/siren. Easy to setup and seriously happy with the results."}
{"Author": "Rajeev Goel", "Date": "on May 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great home automation platform!", "Text": "I love SmartThings! It's the only open platform that publishes their API and extensibility, and works on Android and iOS It supports a large ecosystem of compatible devices made by a variety of popular manufacturers. So far, I've only been using SmartThings to control my lights, based on switches and motion sensors. My daughter set all this up for us with no problems. I'll be adding an Ecobee thermostat and Ring video doorbell in the coming weeks. Can't wait!"}
{"Author": "SHARON", "Date": "on May 21, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not the best for controlling locks", "Text": "This was purchased primarily to control a kwikset deadbolt. There was no problem connecting the device, however there are very limited options for controlling the lock remotely. The only option for remote control through the app is to lock or unlock. You can not add or change entry codes. I needed a hub that would allow me to add codes for different users and grant or deny access remotely. For this I ended up purchasing the iris hub at lowes. It works great with the lock and also controls a light switch I bought. It was also about half the price."}
{"Author": "Common Sense", "Date": "on May 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with all my home automation products. Integrates well with Google Home."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 20, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I purchased this solely to control one z-wave recepticle outlet ...", "Text": "I purchased this solely to control one z-wave recepticle outlet, because recepticles are not recognized by the Phillips Hue hub. The recepticle is only about 10 feet from the SmartThings Hub, but the hub has to be rotated to aim it toward the recepticle, otherwise it isn't recognized. It seems to me that its wifi signal is a bit weak."}
{"Author": "Rodney McKay", "Date": "on May 19, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Painfully unreliable with Alexa", "Text": "Actually, it's not that I don't like SmartThings (or Alexa/Echo), is just that the two of them are an extremely frustrating combination. The problem is, the Alexa app's \"Discover Devices\" way too often fails to work with devices that are registered (and working perfectly) with SmartThings. If you search online, you'll find all sorts of \"tricks\" for getting around this well-known problem, mostly involving removing the devices from SmartThings, reinstalling them, and then running Alexa's Discover Devices again. Doesn't work.\n\nThis came up for me again recently because I wanted to rename a light switch that had been working fine with SmartThings and Alexa. So, following the directions, I removed the device from Alexa's list, renamed it in SmartThings, and tried to get Alexa to re-Discover it. No go! I also tried removing it in SmartThings and reinstalling it in both, and that didn't work either. I've been working on it for a week now, and am tearing my hair out with frustration.\n\nSo, I would say that using Alexa and SmartThings together is something to take on only if you have an unusual amount of patience and significant technical savvy. And by the way, it's also well known that this is a problem with SmartThings rather than with Alexa's Discover Devices. So, if you're addicted to Alexa (I am!), you might want to consider a home control solution other than SmartThings.\n\nEdit, May 29, 2017:\n\nAfter a week of useless discussions with SmartThings tech support, and many more hours of wasted time, I have given up and switched to using a Wink Hub 2. So far, it has NONE of the problems that I've been having with SmartThings. It is very easy to add devices to Wink, and they quickly & easily appear in the Alexa app when I run the device discovery. Why can't SmartThings fix this absurd problem that so many users are having?! As it is, Alexa and Wink are a wonderful combination, but SmartThings with Alexa is a very masochistic experience.\n\nThe one problem I can see with Wink compared to SmartThings is that the Wink hub does not have battery backup. This is a really bad decision on the part of the Wink developers (especially since Wink doesn't always reset itself correctly after a power failure), but a simple workaround is to plug the hub into an inexpensive uninterruptable power supply (UPS). The hub draws very little power, so even the smallest UPS can keep it running for a long time.\n\nI'll edit again if the SmartThings problems get fixed (I'm not holding my breath...) or if I run into trouble with Wink, but so far I'm a very happy camper with Wink and Alexa.\n\nFor all the time I've wasted on SmartThings, I could have manually operated the devices I'm trying to use with it thousands of times. What's the point of home automation if it costs you far more time & effort (and money...) than it saves?"}
{"Author": "Brandon", "Date": "on May 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product.", "Text": "Great hub, very easy to navigate system. I am using it with echo dot and it works great!"}
{"Author": "EB", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great Product"}
{"Author": "beachbum", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lives up to it's review", "Text": "Decided to add automation to my house. This ties together any z-wave device. I have several light switches , light dimmers, and remote outlets on this to control room lights, lamps, and fans. Works great on a phone app so you can control your devices anywhere and works with Amazon Alexa. It was also fairly easy to install and set up."}
{"Author": "Norm", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent unit, Now how about some more devices to work with it!"}
{"Author": "A.Wheatley", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best SmartHub for the $", "Text": "First time smart home DIYer. Took the plunge on the Samsung and I have no regrets. Fantastic integration, compatibility, and community support. It has proven to be very reliable and easy to configure."}
{"Author": "13Alumen", "Date": "on May 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works very well with the z-wave sensors"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Limited support for only the most common devices", "Text": "When I purchased this, last December, the Samsung website wave very guarded about the supported device; I had a mix of trendnet and belkin switches and outlets, and a Honeywell thermostat. I only got the thermostat to work and threw the hub to the trash."}
{"Author": "C E", "Date": "on May 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Frustrating. No amount of justification can explain. Just ...", "Text": "Frustrating. No amount of justification can explain. Just get it and give it try. Combing through threads and threads of geek speak plus youtube videos just to get one of the most popular thermostat - Nest - to work and still not get it right is just wrong. I also have wink and it was completely the opposite experience. ST is a complete novelty at this point."}
{"Author": "HG", "Date": "on May 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Automate your home", "Text": "SmartThings is generally great. Still an evolving product not entirely finished. Nice integrations and 3rd party smart apps. Check out RBoy smart apps and device handlers. Very cool integrations."}
{"Author": "Matthew Martini", "Date": "on May 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dead after less than 2 days", "Text": "Installed and setup on a thursday night. Got my Belkin Wemo switch (outlet) hooked up and working great. Woke up saturday morning with an alert that the hib had lost internet connectivity. When i went to investigate i saw no lights on the hub. I unplugged, waited a minute and repowered. Nothing. Removed backup batteries and tried again. Nothing. Going to try to return for a new one. Will update if the new one lasts linger than 48 hours"}
{"Author": "Cal Robert", "Date": "on May 12, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "wasted a tun of time on this product", "Text": "did not work with the lights I bought, very unpredictable, with in a close range only would it work. Emailed and didn't get any help, wasted a tun of time on this product, wait till they come out with better technology."}
{"Author": "Topher C", "Date": "on May 12, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great performance, cloud based home automation", "Text": "Great performance, cloud based home automation. Works well with a lot of Aeotec products, requires some coding knowledge or at minimum to be technical savvy to really dig into the meat of advanced home automation."}
{"Author": "Justin", "Date": "on May 12, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "sporadic outages", "Text": "i have had this for a few months now and I love it, until it gets a little glitchy. There are sporadic outages."}
{"Author": "James Stroud", "Date": "on May 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it and use it all the time - also love the rboy apps and \"device handler\"", "Text": "I waited a while before I jumped into the Smarthome world. I bought 5 years ago an entire Insteon but never implemented it so I sold it all off on ebay. It was one of the premier systems but closed in terms of standards they supported at the time. Then about 2 Years ago I got the Samsung SmarThings hub to do 2 things\n1) Create a garage door opener that I can control from my iPhone\n2) Install and control Schlage Connect BE468 Touchscreen Deadbolt At Schlage smart lock\nI created a kludge for garage door opener based upon HSM200 and I posted in the SmartThings forum how I got all that to work\n\nI did not want to pay any subscription fees. I also liked that SmartThings worked with all standards such as z-wave and zigbee. So that is what I liked about the SmartThings platform and the Schlage lock and garage door \"hack\" I put together. Now to enhance the Schlage smart lock I bought a few \"Smartapps\" from rboy (google \" rboy apps SmartThings\" as amazon won't let me put the link here) These have been a godsend. For a small one-time fee (I think $35 - I can't remember but this gets me lifetime access to all of the apps here) I got this app\nUser Unlock/Lock Door Notifications and Actions\nwhich sends me texts and let me know which code was used to unlock my door, I also get a notification and history in my app.\n\nAnd just this past week I worked their support to figure out a minor issue that annoyed me. In summary my smart lock was sending a note every minute that the \"Code 1 is Not Set\" \"Code 3 Is Not Set\" etc. I suspected this was draining my batteries in my smart lock.\nThe support from rboy apps had me install a new \"device handler\" for my smart lock vs. the generic one. Think of a device handler as software driver for the smart lock. This was very easy to do and it solved my issue of the notifications occurring every minute and battery drain has been greatly reduced. I also got some new nifty features such as disable the keypad from my phone (also known as vacation mode).\nFYI I changed from \u201cZ-Wave Lock\u201d to \"Enhanced z wave Handler\u201d for the device handler. Instructions for this are very clear on rboy's site.\n\nThe only thing out of the ordinary is that you can't just install these enhanced smartapps from your phone, you need to create an account on the SmartThings ide webpage (google \"SmartThings ide\") and on this web page install the\napp. It is not hard at all.\n\nOverall I'm very happy, I also bought a few switches that allows me to turn on a fan while I'm cycling indoors from my phone. I tried to put in smartphone enabled lights from GE but my house did not have a neutral wire to allow this (my house is 30 years old).\n\nI also can control my sonos which may seem pointless but if am away I can put music on to look like I am home.\nI also bought as GE smartbulb and when I go away I turn that lamp on with this bulb and then schedule the light to turn on and off at various times to make it look like I am home."}
{"Author": "bori", "Date": "on May 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "Arrived on time. Instructions on how to setup were simple to follow. Getting other zwave or ST devices to pair up to it has been flawless. Still new to it so haven't really dived into it's full potential. Love being able to manage things via schedule or with just the touch of a button. Automating my home had become a very expensive addictive hobby. If you run into an issue, the ST community is very informative and helpful. There's a good chance you'll find a solution there."}
{"Author": "Jaime Bula", "Date": "on May 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Best home automation for entusiasts. Open platform."}
{"Author": "E1D1", "Date": "on May 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Really inconvenient - not recommended", "Text": "Lost a star as it did not accept the welcome code, lost another as it was clearly used, lost a star as the gui is not that great and limited in function - took several tries and waiting to get factory reset to work +1 star as samsung customer service was quick to respond, but not 5 stars as it seems to restrictive in its options and was not new - the former may improve as i learn to write apps but for now gui is more limited than i wanted.\n1 star - Samsung cloud is terrible - needing to type in username and password every few days, no Touch ID, and now it wants me to setup all over again - looking for a replacement within a month of getting it going. (FYI no phone update etc has prompted this it worked when I went to bed and now this!)"}
{"Author": "M. Shulman", "Date": "on May 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product at a great price!", "Text": "Having just moved into a new home, I was looking at putting in some sort of DIY alarm system. I paid far more then I'd like to think about using ADP in our last place. I looked at other competitors and ultimately decided on this due to it supporting a lot more devices then the competition.\n\nI've had it up and running for 2 weeks and it's been great. I have over 20 devices monitored and so far it was worked flawlessly. Another big plus for me was that they have a windows phone app. Using a windows phone, this has been great. My only complaint about that is that the app isn't consistent with the android app (I also have a couple android devices). I can do all the same things, but how you get to some things varies a bit.\n\nWhile I gave it 5 stars, because I do love it, there are some things that a casual user might find more frustrating. A number of newer sensors and zwave devices don't work with it out of the box. But there is a great community behind smartthings and every device I've purchased that didn't work out of the box is working with it. You just need to manually install a custom device handler for these devices - do a search and you will easily find plenty of info on this and it isn't that difficult to do. There's also a lot of smartapps and it seems people are always working on more. I know over time, this will just keep getting better.\n\nSo if you are looking for a DIY system that can not only provide alarm type features (siren, door/windows sensors and motion sensors and alerting via the app or even via text message) but also home automation features such as turning on lights when you enter a room, or turning them off after a certain time..etc. Then this is a great device! I've even used smart switches on our outside lights to turn them on at sunset and off at a specific time. Much more flexible then a standard timer!\n\nIn summary: I'd highly recommend it! With one caveat - If you don't have a neutral wire in your light switches, you will NOT be able to use smart switches - but there's plenty of work around's for this."}
{"Author": "Loves To Read", "Date": "on May 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Replaced my v1 which was a major headache to use. Reliable so far and pretty snappy response by system.", "Text": "Migrated from first generation to this (2nd gen). Old hub almost caused me to have a aneurysm trying to keep everything working reliably. Got fed up and figured I'd give Smart Things another chance, as most first gen products have many design flaws and bugs to work out. Was not able to exclude Aoetec products during the migration (kept getting errors) and since they were poorly designed by not allowing a factory reset to allow them to re-pair with a new hub that was $200 down the tube. Going with Smart Things products as they allow for this contingency. Everything works quite well, no more constantly resetting hub, router, etc. So far this is win..."}
{"Author": "Jason S.", "Date": "on May 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is a product that I could not live without, and should be in any smart home!", "Text": "Samsung SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation\nAfter I got an ecobee3, I got very into making my apartment a Smart Home. Well It could not have been one without this Smartthings hub. It's essentially the intermediary between your devices and Alexa. Sure theres a lot of devices now that says works with Alexa and such, but having this hub can run all the devices through it, and then Alexa. It enables you to create rooms with ALL the different devices even from different companies, and make them work together. This enables you to incorporate many diifferent products and control them from one place. I have at least 8 ifferent brands of product running through this hub, and It. also. works well integrated with IFTTT. You can also create your own automations through this hub, like I have the lights turn on in the morning to wake me up. It even recognizes Belkin WeeMo Smart Bulbs when the weemo app won't. I highly recommend this to anyone who wants to start a smarthome because it is so versatile. It's easy for beginners because of the interface, an that you can control most all of your devices that are wifi, z-wave, or Zigbee thst are within range. Most products mention whether or not they work with this hub, and most do. I think I have over 100 devices going through SmartThings now, and Alexa Integrates right with Smartthings so you can use your voice to control everything. Sometimes it even finds devices for you. I included a few pics of the interface on the app on my Iphone7. I would highly recommend getting one for your smarthome, so you can bring everything together. It's the best hub on the market in my opinion right now."}
{"Author": "jimbeaurama", "Date": "on May 6, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy it!!", "Text": "I have had this for a while now and does not work. One day is it online, the next not, and for no reason. Now the $400 in sensors we have aren't working. Worst security system ever!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome", "Text": "Love it just beginning to automate my home will love it even more when I get a chance to \"play\" with it more. Fairly easy to work with"}
{"Author": "Robert Mackey", "Date": "on May 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just as I expected. Took a while to sync ...", "Text": "Just as I expected. Took a while to sync with my z-wave water heater switch. The app could desperately use a time-cycle feature for irrigation and electrical switching timed every 5 minutes, every hour, etc... It took me about 2 hours to manually program the cycle timing as I need it to accomodate my demand rates between my water heater, electric car charger, and other devices."}
