{"Author": "Lawliss", "Date": "on March 18, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Quality Device with a Very Modern Mobile Interface - But Basically Worthless - Unless You Upgrade all your Existing Devices", "Text": "I purchased this new, 2nd Gen Samsung home automation hub basically as an upgrade to the Wink Hub that I have been using the past few years for my home automation needs. Having been an early adopter of the Wink system, I was OK with the Wink Hub itself but always a bit disappointed with the Wink mobile app with respect to it being very basic/limited (in fact, while many of my home automation devices are connected to my network via my Wink Hub, I most always use the mobile apps from the manufacturers of the various home automation devices instead of using the Wink mobile app - especially the Honeywell Thermostat mobile app, as its 10x better than the Wink interface). In addition, or so I thought, I was a bit disappointed with the lack of devices available/compatible with my Wink Hub. As Wink recently rolled out its next-gen hub, I did a little research about the current other available hubs on the market (e.g. Nest, etc.) and from the reviews I read, it seemed as if the 2nd Gen Samsung SmartThings Hub offered everything I was looking for that I thought was lacking with respect to my Wink hub (and instead of upgrading to the 2nd Gen Wink Hub, I would simply upgrade to the Samsung hub as it was about the same price). Wow, did I make a terrible mistake.\n\nAs an initial matter, my research was correct with respect to the Samsung SmartThings Hub having a much better mobile app and having a lot more to offer than my original Wink Hub. However, as I quickly realized, the Samsung Hub was basically worthless to me as it is not backwards compatible with most all devices and in order to utilize same, you will need to upgrade all of your existing home automation devices to newest version of same (and even then, the devices available for the Samsung Hub are very limited, much more so than my old Wink Hub). For example, one of the home automation devices I currently utilize is the SkyBell video door bell (which I found was far superior to its more expensive competitors). Unfortunately, when I attempted to link my SkyBell device to my new Samsung Hub, I quickly discovered that the Samsung Hub will only work with the newest HD version of the SkyBell video doorbell (and which is 2x the cost of the original SkyBell device that works just perfectly).\n\nI could go on and on, especially with respect to the cameras supported by the 2nd Gen Samsung Hub. Speaking of cameras, if you desire to link cameras to this Samsung Hub, you will need to get your checkbook out as all, not just a few, but all of your existing cameras will not work with the 2nd Gen Samsung SmartThings Hub. If money is not an object, than you will have an excuse to upgrade all of your home automation devices if you purchase the new Samsung Hub (and on a side note, you will be better off keeping your cameras separate from your hub and investing in some quality POE IP Cameras - trust me).\n\nAs I have missed the return deadline, I basically have a $100 plastic box that does absolutely nothing. As pride myself on being an Amazon/eBay Buyer, and only a \"buyer,\" selling this worthless device is not an option so I have relegated myself to keep my new Samsung SmartThings Hub, for the next couple of years, in the back of my basement, by my server rack (with the hope that someday down the road, I will just happen to purchase some odd home automation device that will only work with this fancy new Samsung SmartThings Hub - so as to justify me throwing away $100 on it). If anything, I am keeping it as a reminder for me to be more diligent in my research when purchasing such devices (e.g. making sure that when the product says it supports a device, such as a SkyBell doorbell, I confirm that it supports the specific make/model of device I am looking to connect to it).\n\nLast but not least, I did end up purchasing the new 2nd-Gen Wink Hub and I could not be more pleased with same (as the folks at Wink finally figured out that having an Ethernet port on the hub was one of those important things they should have thought of when they rolled out the 1st gen Wink Hub ----- I can only assume that the design team at Wink finally hired a few younger folks who know what a RoKu device is and how important it is to be able to link same via a hardwire network connection.\n\nI hope the foregoing assists you with your decision making process and, so that we are clear, the Samsung SmartThings Hub is a quality device and has a modern/updated mobile app to make using it easy. But as discussed above, should you elect to go with this device, get your checkbook out as you will be buying all new devices for your home automation needs!\n\nM"}
{"Author": "K. Culp", "Date": "on March 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Smart Home Hub!", "Text": "We've been using this for a few weeks now, works with Alexa and GE Z switches. Samsung search functions are a bit funky after wiring a switch, but always seemed to work out in the end. You want a hub in-between Alexa and the switches for extra security (if you were wondering, imagine the consequences if it went rogue). There's battery back-up and it is really compatible with a variety of SmarThings type product outside the Samsung domain. I envision a future where this is likely to be installed as standard in Samsung televisions. Anyway, create an account and start adding your devices! The only thing to worry about is to be patient with the search function. I like that the hub has a battery back-up and that Samsung provides firmware updates on a routine basis."}
{"Author": "Peter Van Ryder", "Date": "on March 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Control All your Tech through ONE app!", "Text": "Recently discovered this hub and am loving it! I had no idea that I could control almost ALL of my smart home tech through one interface!?!? My only concern is that there is no computer based interface to do programming, steps can become tedious on a phone."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wish there was a thorough instruction manual", "Text": "as advertised"}
{"Author": "JusLaugh", "Date": "on March 17, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't Pair with Many Smart Home Devices", "Text": "So far, this thing is useless. It does not recognize my Sensi smart thermostat, my ADT alarm, my Logitech Harmony Elite remote, or my Hausebell wifi plugs. It always says my iphone is away, even if I am holding it right next to the thing with the app open. The only reason I haven't returned it yet is because it recognizes my door lock and I have some GE switches on order that I am hoping it will work with. Samsung needs to work better with others in general and stop being to proprietary."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on March 16, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Such a let down", "Text": "DOES NOT WORK WITH LUTRON WITH OUT BRIDGE. Its more picky then my old wink hub and needs to be closer to devices to pick them up. samsung needs to do some major overhaul if they want to compete with a cheaper more open product like wink. im returning the hub and getting the new wink hub."}
{"Author": "Pawel Z.", "Date": "on March 16, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works like I want \ud83d\udc4d"}
{"Author": "MP3", "Date": "on March 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "These products are just not ready for prime time", "Text": "I love every other Samsung device I have. I am a technology consultant. I know how to make technology work. In my opinion, the Samsung hub and the Leviton power outlets and the Iris power outlet and the Belkin WEMO power outlet I tested are hours of frustration and still don't work or work reliably. I would have returned the Samsung Hub but due to buying amd testing three different outlets I went past the return date. Ugh. These products are just not ready for prime time."}
{"Author": "Jason Ballard", "Date": "on March 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "All in 1 home security and automation hub."}
{"Author": "christophmine", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love being able to use my goggle home to turn ...", "Text": "Love being able to use my goggle home to turn off the lights. I like that I can use several brands of products with the Samsung smarthing hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung SmartThings hub", "Text": "Easy to set up, easy to connect devices, and operates as described. Zero issues."}
{"Author": "Art", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great idea, but terrible interphase and not reliable.", "Text": "Since posting my old review, things have gone down hill. Frankly, they completely crashed. SmartThings updated their app and it is now useless. I get no alerts when water sensors go off, and one sensor says it is wet even though it is not... for two weeks now. Pathetic, I don't even know how this company can keep selling this piece of garbage. A cardboard cutout would be more effective than this. I cannot believe I spent hundreds of dollars on the hub and sensors/outlets. Don't believe me? Check out all the negative reviews on Apple's app store about their mess of a new \"upgraded\" system.\n\nMy Old Review:\nI have had SmartThings for over a year now, and love the idea of it, but the execution is not great. The user interphase is clunky, unintuitive, and difficult (and I am good with computers). Also, it is really glitchy that only works about 75% of the time. I had a leak that this did not notify me of until I was wiping the water detector dry... and then it alerted me six times with timestamps going back hours?!?!?!\nAlso, it has not notified me when offline several times now.\nBottom line, they need a better app, easier to use, and more reliable."}
{"Author": "Mr. A. MCROBERTS", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup", "Text": "Easy to setup, Easy to move. Given the frequency range, best to put it far away from other electronic equipment. I found I had put it behind my PVR, TV, Router, Apple TV and the signal was weak, but moving it in front of these dramatically increased it's performance."}
{"Author": "dirpubsaf", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very poor range.", "Text": "Very poor range. Probably 20 feet line of sight"}
{"Author": "AlanRob", "Date": "on March 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth the price", "Text": "Did not work as advertised. Many of my smart home devices could not be found by this hub"}
{"Author": "Steve", "Date": "on March 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart things has a way to go to be perfect, but having the hub gives you access to the app which makes automation easier.", "Text": "I decided that if I was going to get any further in to home automation than a couple light bulbs, I should invest in smart things so that I could use one central app to do a lot of the automation. Hubs might sound like something you don't want to purchase if you are just getting in to smart home tech, but to do automation, it helps to be able to control most of the stuff from one app, which smart things manages to do well to a certain extent.\n\nThe hub is an unfortunate necessity to the app, and while the smart things app is not perfect, it presents the easiest way to trigger automations across devices somewhat reliable through the echo, geofence triggers, and other triggers.\n\nI found that reliability percentage for whether or not the device triggered by smart things will do what it is supposed to do varies from device to device. My hue lights work 99% of the time when triggered by smart things. Plain old z-wave wall switches work 95% of the time. Some more complicated devices like the smarthings wall outlet only work about 75% of the time.\n\nSmart things has a way to go to be perfect, but having the hub gives you access to the app which makes automation easier."}
{"Author": "Seewolf", "Date": "on March 13, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Probably great if you have the right smart devices in your home.", "Text": "I bought this in the hopes I could consolidate control over several of my smart devices that currently require their own app. When I was done setting it up, it really only helped with some of the switches I have in my home. I went through the SmartThings support community and the \"SmartThings Labs\" to set up additional devices but had very little success. For me, it ended up being an extra piece of hardware and a redundant app. I ended up sending it back.\n\nI think this would be fantastic if you are starting from scratch and will be using supported devices or have several devices that are already on their official support list.\n\nEdit: Changed review from two to four stars. I spent some more time with it and was able to get some more functions that I really wanted to work with the hub. I am planning to add some more sensors/switches as I expand my smart home.\n\nListen to the people who say you need to tinker with it. Unless you are using devices that are explicitly supported by the hub, you will need to take some time to work with the system to get what you want."}
{"Author": "AliAnne84", "Date": "on March 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing!", "Text": "We switched from Wink to SmartThings and I am so glad I did. It works really well with no downtime and worked with all our Wink products. Although it isn't compatibly with everything, their open source allows so much more customization. For instance it connects with our alarm system, Nest and all lights. It is set so that if everyone is gone, the alarm sets, lights go off and temp goes down. It works so well. My only complaint is that the accessories are expensive; we want to do our whole house!"}
{"Author": "M. Vigod", "Date": "on March 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings Hub Good Z-Wave Plus Hub for my Setup", "Text": "My SmartThings Hub has been working great since I set it up. I had been looking to setup a 2nd z-wave network in my house for a few months and finally pulled the trigger. I already had ADT Pulse setup with many switches and cameras but wanted to put any new devices on SmartThings going forward. The other reason was ST (SmartThings) is Z-Wave PLUS and my first new switch was going to be about 80 feet from the house behind our pool. I felt I needed the Z-Wave Plus range and ADT does not support it.\n\nI bought the new GE Z-Wave Plus 14291 Switch and was able to pair it quickly. I did have a problem with the light only turning on fine but not turning off. I moved the ST hub to a closer location and removed and added the switch again but still could not turn GE switch off reliably. After 4 hours of playing with it I could not determine if the switch or the Hub was the issue (or just the range). I gave up for the night. The next morning I tried it and it worked perfect. I didn't change anything it just started working so all good now.\n\nI also bought the Aeon Labs Minimote\nhttp://amzn.to/2nk05PM\n\nI set this up to turn the light switch on and off. Setup took under 2 minutes and it also now acts as a simple remote control for the light switch. It is setup as a secondary controller for ST Hub for those looking to do same.\n\nI also setup the Amazon Echo ( http://amzn.to/2mgTd4W ) to respond to commands to turn the light on and off (\"Alexa turn on backyard light\"). That worked great too and setup was without any hiccups.\n\nI look forward to adding more devices to my ST setup and updating this review as my system grows."}
{"Author": "Spooked-or-Crazy", "Date": "on March 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Perfect!"}
{"Author": "Kyungho Lee", "Date": "on March 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Best smart home hub."}
{"Author": "M. Williams", "Date": "on March 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Makes my home so smart!"}
{"Author": "TX gadget nut", "Date": "on March 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Its kind of a bridge troll, hiding in a closet making other stuff perform magic, or sometimes not..", "Text": "I bought a warehouse deal item and it had been used so I had some difficulty with the security code: had to call and have it reset etc... A bit confusing but understandable given the circumstance I suppose. As the hub maker, Samsung does have an undue burden managing all of the software and such when most of the device content in my house is from other companies. There are definately quirks.\nI installed lots of Z-wave smart switches (~15) throughout the house (mostly GE) but a couple of items from another maker.\nFast forward several months and several firmware updates, some of my automated routines quit working (specifically the sunrise sunset ones). So following advice from forums I removed my home \"location\". I didn't realize at the time that this would wipe out ALL of my switches that were set up. So I had to go through a complicated process of excluding each switch so that it could be detected and added again. I have one switch in a storage space under my patio with steel and concrete floor so that switch does not see the hub directly. It works once set up by using another switched plug adapter that I installed purely to act as a Z-wave repeater. I guess though that the repeater does not work during setup and device exclusion process. So I had to move my hub with a long ethernet cable to a place that it could see this switch.. In the process of all of this and holding my phone over my head so that it would connect to wifi in the house while I pressed the switch for the exclusion process I ended up dropping my new galaxy S8 phone and breaking the display glass. So thanks Samsung for that..\n\nUpdate: Today I got some email from support folks at Smartthings about my welcome code issue. I had already gotten past that issue but took the opportunity to clarify some other things and got great support from them. They were able to log into my account and see my devices and routines and find a little problem with one of them. (kinda creepy but helpful)!"}
{"Author": "Jonnathan", "Date": "on March 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It is working well even when the power went out ...", "Text": "It is working well even when the power went out it didn't take long to get back online. It works flawlessly with my Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "bruce johnson", "Date": "on March 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Doing the job needed"}
{"Author": "R. Goodman", "Date": "on March 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The SmartThings Hub is easy to setup and works as advertised", "Text": "The SmartThings Hub is easy to setup and works as advertised. And just as important, online support is highly responsive with clear, concise help whenever I've had an issue. It is one of the best technology products I've ever purchased."}
{"Author": "Dave", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "tv and PS3 shut off all simultaneously really cool!", "Text": "I have the this hub a couple motion sensors, outlets, light bulbs, cameras and echo. When I'm ready for bed O just say Alexa turn on sleep and the lamp shuts off, tv and PS3 shut off all simultaneously really cool!"}
{"Author": "tom", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waste of time", "Text": "So, the device is not compatible with any of the twenty wifi devices I have in my home... not a single one. So, it is useless. It was marketed as compatible with Echo... it is not. I returned it for my money and continue getting emails that tell me I can not unsubscribe... I am usually a Samsung fan, but not this."}
{"Author": "Dan", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great device for home automation. I hope it keeps expanding.", "Text": "This is an item I am really enjoying. It is a pretty good home automation tool and does a pretty good job at notifying us either through the app or through a txt msg when something is going on. Occasionally it doesn't seem to talk to some of the z-wave devices. I think its the other devices and not the Hub but I'm not sure. There are a few advanced features I wish it could do but overall I'm pretty happy with the device and keep adding onto my network all the time."}
{"Author": "mr_et2", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product.", "Text": "I'm loving this. Makes home automation a breeze. Easy to set up and use."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "J Smith", "Date": "on March 7, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Generally great IOT. Sometimes disconnects"}
{"Author": "Andrea Kearns", "Date": "on March 7, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "we returned it- just was not what we needed"}
{"Author": "B. Orr", "Date": "on March 7, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to use, but only minimal control of door locks", "Text": "Easy on her face, but two problems I have with this. For one, it takes a really long time to configure the device to be connected with the Internet, nearly 10 minutes just to download and install updates and connect with my home network. At times I thought it wasn't ever going to connect.\n\nSecond, I easily assumed thy Samsung would have the ability to control all the door codes of my schlage deadbolt. Including adding codes and removing codes.\n\nTo me it's a given that if you're going to allow me to control the locking and unlocking of my Schlage Z wave door lock, that you would also give me the ability to control the configuring of the codes as well as knowing when those codes are used. Only allowing me to either lock or unlock my door is it very \"SmartThing\" to me.\n\nI found out that the wink device actually does allow you to control the code configurations. So I will be returning this unit for the wink.\n\nYes, apparently if you are adept at tinkering, you can find code that you can install on your smart things device that will allow you to have more functionality, but I'm just not interested in wasting my time trying to figure out how to custom code my smart thing box... it's not very smart if I have to add programing code to it. This kind of control should work right out of the box."}
{"Author": "Jerry B.", "Date": "on March 6, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I can't connect my Samsung smart tv to the hub", "Text": "Out of the box, I can't connect my Samsung smart tv to the hub. Still waiting for support to fix."}
{"Author": "Chuck R.", "Date": "on March 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "works great", "Text": "easy to install and setup"}
{"Author": "flamalizzie", "Date": "on March 6, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay away from this hub", "Text": "This is a piece of crap!!!! Trying to set up devices that it can work with with no luck Only device that set up is the honeywell 9000 thermostat. the sensors do pick up or schlage lock doesnt work lightify rgbw dont work I have rebooted and reset this thing 3 time back to factory default. Have unplug all other hubs in house. Can not get this to see devices . My hub is within 25 ft of all these. My wink hub works great and my lightify work great. Why this one doesnt have no Idea????"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Mixed feelings but overall content", "Text": "I've got about 20 sensors, lights, sonos, a Honeywell thermostat all hooked up. Ease of use of App - 3 stars, ease of connecting things 4 stars, ease of how many things can be connected 5 stars, smart things support 4 stars. Would I rely on it as an actual security system? Absolutely not, because the system has a connectivity issue at least 2-3 times a week. Does it serve my needs? Mostly. More of a hobby thing for me, but considering I've only got $400 into smart things and sensors specifically, it ain't bad."}
{"Author": "Cash", "Date": "on March 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "finally I found the perfect combination of hardware and software", "Text": "I used other hubs and controllers before smartthings, finally I found the perfect combination of hardware and software. Easy to install, support is effective and kind, after a few days you get use to the app and it's tabs. Super b desig."}
{"Author": "Mr. Jack Badger", "Date": "on March 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Open source integration + solid samsung build/support = winning smarthome product!", "Text": "Simply the best smart hub out there for your home. A full IDE awaits as well as an active development community."}
{"Author": "Terry B.", "Date": "on March 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great"}
{"Author": "Digital_Age_Man", "Date": "on March 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love this, best decision I made for HA"}
{"Author": "J. Ellis", "Date": "on March 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Addictive for Home Monitoring", "Text": "I was slow to adopt the home automation/IoT trend, but once I dipped my toes in I was hooked. The SmartThing that sold me was the moisture detector - I now have six throughout to house after already being burned by a water main leak and a faulty sump pump... with a water heater soon to go. The detectors are small enough to leave underneath washing machines, by fridge ice maker lines or even behind drywall.\n\nOn top of that the SmartApps IDE, management and SmartThings debugging is phenomenal. Adding community-supported apps from GitHub is not too hard, even with OAuth integration. IFTTT integration is ready to go, but I've been able to find SmartApps that have easily bridged the gap. There is even an unofficial Nest SmartApp that builds a bridge between Nest products and SmartThings, which is invaluable.\n\nFantastic extensibility and a wide support for connected \"things\" makes this a great buy."}
{"Author": "jmanz6", "Date": "on March 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Makes adding smart devices easy.", "Text": "Easily add smart controls to Amazon Echo Dot. So far, no issues. Allows use of items that would require different hubs, everything connects to SmartThings Hub to limit how many different connection points I have to manage."}
{"Author": "Robert Hillmon", "Date": "on March 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works perfectly with all my ge zwave switches"}
{"Author": "Gottlich", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesnt work. Doesnt like code brandnew.", "Text": "Brand new and the code in the box doesnt even work. Terrible product."}
{"Author": "Ostrander", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent bridge", "Text": "App is slow and unwieldy, but if you know how to use scripting languages you can make it do anything you want. Install CORE as soon as you get this and automate everything with CORE pistons."}
{"Author": "Thom Thomas", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Supporting home automation shouldn't be a part time job. But when it works, I love it.", "Text": "Pros: When SmartThings engineers don't break your automation, it is awesome to be able to turn lights on and off just by talking to Alexa or Google Home. Clicking the remote to turn on the TV is a joy now - it turns on the TV, switches to Netflix and dims the lights.\n\nCons: Unreliable. Unreliable. Unreliable. Unreliable. Irritatingly unreliable.\n\nI've owned this device for a year. When it works, I love it. It was fun to begin with. Then, SmartThings had server issues and things worked hit or miss. Then they got things fixed. And for about 200 days straight, everything was great. But very recently, the engineers at SmartThings casually made a change in the \"device type\" of the smart bulb that I use throughout my house and that change rendered all my bulbs dumb. These bulbs are supposedly officially supported. Now, none of my automations work. I can no longer turn off or on lights with my phone or my Alexa.\n\nI work in IT as a network and server guy - I work all day with much more complicated hardware and software - but when I come home, I don't want to troubleshoot my home automation system and network - especially when the vendor broke it, not me.\n\nAfter contacting tech support, they tell me I might be able to get on a chat with them and they might be able to see what is going on with my SmartThings hub and maybe fix the device type issue BUT ... if that doesn't work, I'll have to delete all my bulbs and reconfigure my setup from scratch.\n\nI have hours upon hours of automations and timers setup. If I have to start over again, I'm going to buy the Wink 2 Hub and try my hand at that. Maybe it is more reliable."}
{"Author": "George N", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "The product was used successfully for one device. I need to add more devices to test its capabilities."}
{"Author": "N. J. Barcellos", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "\"This device is great at easily adding things to your smart home. The downside is the reliability of the system itself.\"", "Text": "This device is great at easily adding things to your smart home. The downside is the reliability of the system itself. While the system does seem to stay online most of the time, the automation's are flaky at best.\n\nMy home and away modes trigger way off their set times, id say this would happen 3 out of the 7 days a week. I quickly started using Home Assistant and having had any of those type of issues.\n\nI think it is a great device that if could have a more consistent maybe \"offline\" mode and not use the cloud would be great. I do use it to test ideas and automation's to see if I enjoy them (when they work) so I can hard program them into my Home Assistant.\n\nSince I am still learning how to program I prefer using something easy like smartthings to test a otherwise intense automation, then once I like it I learn to code it."}
{"Author": "TimexVA", "Date": "on February 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "It works great and was easy to set up. I have purchased 2 more for family."}
{"Author": "Santo Cheen", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Installation was pretty much plug-n-play", "Text": "Installation was pretty much plug-n-play. I have a z-wave plus network of about 10 devices. Everything works as advertised. I will say though that the programming interfaces and terminology seem to have evolved over the years. If you are developer of device handlers or smart apps, you will find some stale references and older examples when you search on the web."}
{"Author": "Thomas Desfosses", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This hub has worked flawless for me.", "Text": "This hub has worked flawless for me. interface is not as flashy but very functional and usable by my technophobe wife"}
{"Author": "Carl", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This works great, mainly using with motion detectors and GE smart ...", "Text": "This works great, mainly using with motion detectors and GE smart switches, the app is a bit clunky and slow, but it gives you a wide variety of options and works well."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "easy install.", "Text": "It works, easy install."}
{"Author": "marstf", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product, Samsung can lead home automation if it keeps investing", "Text": "Great product, much superior than any other in the market at the moment (fev2017)\nEasy to setup.\nMulti technology, connects with Bluetooth, ZWave, ZigBee.\nIntegrates with new techs like Alexa, Philips Hue.\nIntegrates with old ZWave and ZigBee things.\nAllows automation IF-THEN."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to set up to coordinate Alexa with other products"}
{"Author": "toms_jeep", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "5 - Star", "Text": "Easy install..\n\nI am new to Smart Home stuff and this was very easy for me to install and set up. I have the system up and running in less than 15 minutes. Connecting the water sensor, Motion sensor and 2 door switches took seconds each.\n\nThe possibilities are endless..... Looking at adding Thermostat, Sprinkler timer and light switches"}
{"Author": "joe", "Date": "on February 24, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as advertised", "Text": "Works as advertised. Must connect to router with an ethernet cable so placement may be limited."}
{"Author": "HTDNET, LLC", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easier than the clapper", "Text": "Easy to setup with minimal experience needed. This enabled us to install a Leviton switch that runs to two fluorescent lights over a counter that we can now control on mobile devices, through Alexia, or manually if desired."}
{"Author": "Dr. Supratik K. Moulik", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great hub for linking z-wave smart home devices to alexa", "Text": "Just bought a new house and I am wiring up some of the main rooms with GE z-wave switches and wall outlets. This hub works great and is zero hassle to set up. I haven't had any issues with it connecting to the z-wave devices I buy... the android app is super easy and intuitive to use. If you are looking to add some smart home stuff to your house, this is a great hub. Also works seamlessly with Alexa... any time I add new devices, I just need to update the echo skill and everything works seamlessly."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Really good product. Can be integrated with Alexia. Highly recommend."}
{"Author": "Victor Briceno", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Helped out so much with our home and family activities.", "Text": "Bought this because we had purchased the Yale Deadbolt Lock and wanted to be able to use our smart phones to lock and unlock the door wirelessly.\nhttps://www.amazon.com/Yale-Assure-Touchscreen-Deadbolt-Standalone/dp/B005NLKG1E/ref=sr_1_2?s=hi&ie=UTF8&qid=1487798999&sr=1-2&keywords=yale+deadbolt.\n\nWe ended up loving the system so much that we now have the Smartthings sensors and Z-Wave Smart Dimmable Switches.\nWorks great for our family. Unlocks and turns on lights when we arrive home and turns off lights when we leave as well as locking the door.\n\nWe recommend this product if your looking into turning your home into a smart home an letting home automation make your daily chores a little bit easier."}
{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An Excellent Home Automation Tool", "Text": "I have been using SmartThings for a couple of years in my home. I have about 30 devices connected via z-wave, zigbee, and Wi-Fi. While it is not 100% perfect, it is very reliable, and an excellent tool for controlling \"stuff\" in your home. Among the greatest things about it is the community of users who assist with SmartApps and tips. One of the best is found at rboyapp.com where you can find a multitude of Device handlers and SmartApps to help you cleverly and easily control many of the more complex items you may wish to add (e.g, Thermostats, Garage Door Openers, Door Locks, etc.). My most recent addition is a kickspace heater in my kitchen (which had limited heating and was always cold) controlled by an Intermatic relay that is connected to SmartThings, which turns on the heater only when the temperature is below a certain point and there is motion detected in the room.\n\nI also have several Amazon Dots integrated with SmartThings to make it even easier to control lights and other devices. If you are looking for a flexible, reliable, and powerful Home Automation Hub, I recommend that you select SmartThings."}
{"Author": "Tony J.", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not a reliable home security system", "Text": "I have been using Smartthings as my home security system for more than a year. The problem with the system is, it is not reliable to use as a security system.\nHere is the problem I have been facing.\n\nI have two Sirens, one in the garage and one in the hallway. When there is an intrusion (I forget to disarm before opening), it fails to trigger the siren. I will have to power cycle the hub (disconnect power, remove battery) to get it back to working. So I used to periodically power cycle to make it reliable! Now recently even the power cycle is not helping. I am using it as a home automation system now. I have to keep looking on the dash board for any intrusions and then trigger sirens manually!!! What a waste of money"}
{"Author": "AppWorx Bill", "Date": "on February 20, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Complicated but worth it.", "Text": "I love my new smartthings hub. It is not for the non-technical types if you want to do door locks or flow valves. Cutting and pasting code for drivers and apps takes a bit of work. I am slowly moving from nexus to smartthings. So far two motion sensors, a garage light, and a schlage digital lock with 6 different user codes. So far everything works as advertised."}
{"Author": "Blackjack", "Date": "on February 20, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The device SUCKs when there is only one device connected", "Text": "So-far-so-good. The device SUCKs when there is only one device connected, but now that i have 12 devices the system works great, and impresses the ladies :-)\nI'm going to completely automate the house for ease."}
{"Author": "L. Mcquay", "Date": "on February 19, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product with only one issue", "Text": "works great, except for compatibility issues with other big name brands, otherwise would be 5 stars, after 2 months, that is the only issue, some lightbulbs work perfectly with easy set up and some not at all, Alexa repeats can't find any devices, though the Smart Things app shows it is compatible with Phillips Hue, it required reprogramming with outside help to make them work, once the reprogramming was done, all was good so I still give it 4 stars"}
{"Author": "micky daniels", "Date": "on February 19, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "High hopes, but falsely advertised", "Text": "In building our smart home, things are getting cluttered and messy. We have Alexa, Nest, Philips hue and Ge link bulbs, and ring video products.\n\nFrom our understanding Smartthings hub and app would be one device to rule them all so to speak and also allow the addition of other things such as door, and motion sensors etc. WE WAS WRONG!\n\nOne received i immediately removed my Hues &Ge from their bridge and disconnected it. I settled in for a day completely redoing everything through the Smartthings Hub and app. I hooked up the the Hub, downloaded the app, set up my account and the app began searching for my things. After several moments of not finding ANYTHING I was prompted to configure them manually. I began fumbling through the atrocious UI to little avail.\n\nI managed to get Ring Doorbell set up! But, its functionality with the hub and app was useless. No motion detection or video, and the only thing it would do is notify me when the doorbell was rang, pointless since the native app already does this and more.So I began searching their support site to only find out this Hub/app doesn't really do much. It wouldn't control my lights without their proprietary bridges or hub, a complete misrepresentation if I do say so myself. Nest wasn't supported either. In short this thing is really only good interacting with other hubs/apps with their sensors. We bought this thing to consolidate, not expand. I also learned a couple of other key things in my search, you will need to learn to code as well as set up additional accounts with coding platforms' such as Github.\n\nI broke down and called their customer service, who was less than enthusiastic about taking my call and answering my questions, and quite frankly rude. He also then told me that this was all my fault for not going to their website and fully reading ALL their forums on what and how things work before purchasing! I tried to explain that I bought the product on how it was advertised and I did go to their page to see what was supported, but more or less was told I was stupid for not understanding technology! Now, I'm not a genius but have greater than fair understanding of how things work. I have set up all these other things with no issues and integrated them with Ifttt. Plus I learned that they are cancelling their Windows app which means in a month or so I would not be able to use this anyhow as I only use Windows products.\n\nBottom line, if you want or need a bunch of sensors for tripping things like your lights then go ahead. But this really doesn't do anything your native apps can't do with IFTTT integration."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Garage Door Opener - Didn't work with Chamberlain", "Text": "I returned it since it didn't work with my garage door opener. I went out and purchased a Wink and it works great with Chamberlain MyQ system"}
{"Author": "DaveR12", "Date": "on February 18, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product", "Text": "Does everything I need and has a great developer community. Would give 5 stars if it also had a Web interface instead of just a mobile app."}
{"Author": "Scott J", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's an expensive hobby to have a smart home, but this works flawlessly and send to ...", "Text": "Works well once paired with compatible products. It's an expensive hobby to have a smart home, but this works flawlessly and send to be the most universal. No complaints, would recommend."}
{"Author": "MS", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Battery and Code Issues.", "Text": "I was more or less happy with my hub until I received a warning email letting me know there was a code issue causing batteries to drain rapidly. The email said this could cause the batteries to discharge in the unit. Samsung sent me 4 new batteries for free, but I spent half an hour scraping as much of the gunk as I could out of the battery box. Not so much as an apology for that."}
{"Author": "PT", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome Hub!", "Text": "Crazy Fast Delivery, The Product Was Easy To Setup."}
{"Author": "G. Lyons", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Compatibility with other brands' Z-Wave devices has been perfect for me", "Text": "Pairing devices and all the built-in functionality has worked for me flawlessly. Compatibility with other brands' Z-Wave devices has been perfect for me, and that's almost everything that I have connected with it today. Everything from installation to simple automation tasks have been easy and reliable. The only thing keeping this from being 5 stars for me is that there is very limited capability to add your own custom automation that doesn't rely on the SmartThings cloud. If something goes wrong with my Internet connection, a lot of functionality goes away with it. There are certain things that clearly require the power of the cloud, but there are also a lot of things that could run autonomously that don't."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product and compatible with a lot of things", "Text": "Great product and compatible with a lot of things. It is not wireless though so watch out for that if you are expecting a wireless product. It sits next to my router though, so no big deal. I would highly recommend this though because it is compatible with the most products on the market, except security cameras."}
{"Author": "Wayne Degolier 2", "Date": "on February 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "easy to hook up and get going", "Text": "Fast shipping, easy to hook up and get going. Had it up and connected to smart switches and door lock in less than a couple of minutes. No issues yet, seems to work great."}
{"Author": "Some fishes and a Frog", "Date": "on February 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beautiful Things", "Text": "Once you get it to work the way you want it, it's a beautiful Thing..."}
{"Author": "JD", "Date": "on February 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Upgrade from Gen 1 = horrible experience", "Text": "I upgraded from 1st Gen SmartThings, and it has been terribly painful. The process involves excluding then re-including every device manually with the new hub. The fact that Samsung provided no upgrade path makes me feel like they don't care about loyal customers, early adopters or their time."}
{"Author": "AR Creative", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Platform reliability/response times aren't great sometimes, but generally works well", "Text": "Pretty good system, but a little worried about platform reliability"}
{"Author": "Michael W.", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "easy setup merged with echo"}
{"Author": "Danny DeGhetto", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Horrible app, inferior to native apps of smart devices renders this product useless."}
{"Author": "Ian Marshall", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great, reliable way to keep tabs on your house ...", "Text": "I got this namely as a home monitoring system. Connecting with devices (1 camera, 1 alarm, multiple motion and window sensors) was seamless via the iOS app, no outages once everything was connected, box has structurally stood up to at least 1 heavy thing being dropped on it. Firmware auto-updates with no discernible downtime, even though they notify you via email. I researched alternatives a lot and I think I made a winning choice. I wish there was a cellular data or some sort of non-Internet connectivity option and that it could connect to the web via WiFi instead of an ethernet cable but that's about the only downside. 0 downtime or technical issues whatsoever, smooth setup, great, reliable way to keep tabs on your house with no contract or obtrusive hardware needed."}
{"Author": "mitcha3154", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "All my stuff is connecting painlessly", "Text": "Works perfect for me. Before buying this I tried using wemo switches with the wemo app and Alexa and it was disastrous so I returned the wemos. Then I ordered this. Setup was painless. I have installed 3 or 4 other smart devices to the system and all connected without any issues. I'm thinking that using a hub like this is the way to go, rather than trying to use just wifi devices."}
