{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on January 12, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup and configure", "Text": "This has worked out well so far. Easy to setup and configure. Knocked a star because you can only use this with a smartphone or tablet."}
{"Author": "Gadget Fanatic", "Date": "on January 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I like it", "Text": "So far, so good. I have 16 devices, and everything is working as expected so far (about 2 months in). Devices: 6 CREE Connected Bulbs, 2 Lutron dimmers, 1 Lutron switch, 2 Minimotes, 3 SmartThings motion sensors, 2 Ecobee 2 thermostats, GE Outdoor Controller, Leviton Lamp Controller."}
{"Author": "Jerry L. Herrington", "Date": "on January 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does what it says it will, even for a beginner!", "Text": "SmartThings always does what it is supposed too do! It's also very easy to use."}
{"Author": "Adidas1976", "Date": "on January 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent starting point for home integration", "Text": "I recently purchased this in November 2016 with the soul purpose of integrating my new Amazon Echo with it to voice control my house. My current set includes: Amazon echo in the kitchen, an Amazon dot in the playroom, an Amazon dot in our master bedroom, approaching 30 different GE Zwave and Zwave+ light switches/dimmers and add on switches (more on that later) and 3 HUE colored light bulbs (more on that later, as well).\nGoods:\n1. Pretty easy installation of the hub and app\n2. Easy recognition of newly installed z-wave devices\n3. Very active community board with multiple \"How-To's\" and FAQs on the smartthing website to help with products\n\nBad:\n1. The Hub is moderately priced, but buying devices to integrate into the hub is dang expensive\n2. Occasionally, does not always do what it is meant to do\n3. Hub has to be plugged directly into the router\n\nDownload the app (I have an iPhone 5). Plug in the hub and DIRECTLY CONNECT THE HUB TO THE ROUTER. This means that the hub has to be in close proximity of the router (I have the latest generation of Apple's AirPort, which hasn't changed in 5+ years). Follow the instructions on the app and you're up and running! I had no issues.\n\nIntegration goes like this: Purchase GE Zwave light switch, which runs between $35 an $40 a pop! There may be cheaper ones, but not by much. (I recommend staying with the same brand throughout your house. It makes it easier to trouble shoot later on.) Multiply that by how many switches you have in your house! But, you can do this one switch at a time. No need to do all of them all at once. Turn off breaker. Pull out old single switch. Connect the black line wire to the LINE connector on the zwave switch (this is the power coming into the switch box). Connect the black load wire to the LOAD connector on the new switch (this is the black wire coming from the light to power it). Now, these switches need to be connected to the white Neutral wire that is crumbled up in the back of the switch box. These switches come with a pliable extra white wire. Wire nut the whites together. Turn on the breaker and the blue LED light comes on that's on the switch. Test the switch manually to make sure that you can turn on and off the light. If the blue lights not on, you probably have the black wires switched. Open the app, tap on \"Add a Thing\", press up on the switch and the hub recognizes the new switch. Rename it and you're set.\n\nSounds complicated, but the hardwiring the switch is more complicated than integrating the new switch with the Hub. With the app, I have it set so when both my phone and my wife's phone break connection with our home wi-if, SmartThings turns off everything. (Have to always remember to remind the babysitter!)\n\nAmazon Echo has it's own app that needs to be integrated, but SmartThings has step by step instructions on that. Had no problem. Now I say, \"Alexa, turn off living room lights\" and all the lights in the living room turn off. Awesome!\n\nThe only problem I have had is with 3 way switches. This is where there are 2 or more switches doing the same light. When you pull out the switch on these bad boys, you'll be met with black, white and red wires. These are wired differently than normal 3 way switches. The way it is suppose to work is that there is one main zwave switch and an add on switch (which has no receiver). When you press the add on switch, it's suppose to turn off the lights AND send a signal to the main switch, to send a signal to the Hub, so that it registers as on/off on the app. I've had some of the newer zwave+ switches that do not register on the app. I.e., I turn off the light with the add on switch, but the app still says the light is on. Not a big deal, but it is annoying. This has only happened on the newer GE 14xxx Zwave switches with the older 12xxx add on switches.\n\nBesides this issue, everything has worked flawlessly. Other issues that have appeared are due to my figuring out complex 3 way switches that power multiple different lights. Overall, I would recommend this to anyone interested in an easy entry into home automation!"}
{"Author": "Chris Silveri", "Date": "on January 11, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Required a painful support call to remedy", "Text": "Unit was sold as new but was registered to someone else's account. Required a painful support call to remedy. Samsung support has a long IVR based front end to collect personal info before they transfer you to the support tech. Power supply cord was sloppily bound which makes we wonder how new this unit was. Support hours end at 6pm so be prepared to take the unit to work if you need support. Very poor out of box experience."}
{"Author": "Slag", "Date": "on January 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice piece of technology so", "Text": "Installed and integrated effortlessly. Nice piece of technology so far"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best thanksgiving investment", "Text": "Best thanksgiving investment by far. Using it for controlling lights and security so far. Works well with IFTTT and has plenty of out of the box automation features that you can use. Example: Change home status to \"away and armed\" when everyone leaves. Disarm when someone comes back (it uses your phone as your presence sensor). Slowely turn on a light over 30 minutes in the morning.\n\nMy only complaint is that it does not send voice output to Google Home speaker. It only works with Bose and Samsung speaker."}
{"Author": "Brandon", "Date": "on January 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Reliability has improved last few months.", "Text": "It works as intended. Lot of people complaining about reliability and connectivity issues. I've not experienced any. Running locks, lights, garage door and water sensors and it's be rock solid since I purchased it. However I was aware that 8 months ago there were some issue with reliability but that does not seem to be the case anymore."}
{"Author": "Louis Pochet", "Date": "on January 10, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waaaaay too much tinkering for what it gets you", "Text": "1) Too much work - get a vera\n2) Support is terrible - get a vera\n3) no web app - just phone interfaces - so you can't organize stuff with a keyboard/mouse - get a vera\n\nThe \"Must be willing to tinker\" review is absolutely correct. I got this because it 'works with Alexa' but just barely. At the time my Vera wasn't supported in Alexa. Now it is. After a month going around with support - I'm going back to Vera.\n\nMy Vera just added a 7 button scene controller - for things hub it's a 2 hour slog through github to find someone's personal code that lets me use the 7 scene button controller. THe guy that wrote it did a fine job . but in Vera - the 7 scene button just showed up.\n\nThe things hub can't control anything through alexa that's not within like 10 feet of the things hub. Anything that needs to relay through other z wave switches gets a timeout and fails. Relay zwave + alexa works fine with vera.\n\nIn vera - I can set a max- time for lights to be on. In things hub - you need a separate \"app\" and about 20 minutes of digging.\n\nSomeday it'll be fine but it's maybe 1/2 as useful as my 5 year old Vera Lite and 2 times harder to use."}
{"Author": "GalvezGuy", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Never Worked Once", "Text": "Never worked. I was able to plug it in discover it and do a firmware update. After that, nothing, it did not discover any of the smart devices I tried including Cree Smart Bulbs and GE Smart Switches. I went to a big box store and purchase a Wink 2 hub an it was completely different. The Wink saw every device on the first try and the pairing with the Echo was about as seamless as it gets. I cannot recommend this device at this time. I think that looking at other reviews that the QA process for producing these is not working well. Thankfully I can return this dud and purchase other smart devices with the credit."}
{"Author": "Ryan Potter", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy and Reliable", "Text": "Setup on this is really easy and it connects my zWave devices to my Echo and Echo dots easily."}
{"Author": "Larry", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "works great.......excellent vendor and the device works as advertised"}
{"Author": "Petemax13", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The interesting thing too is that I sent an email thinking I would get responses pretty quickly to address my issues", "Text": "So I bought this system over the Wink because i thought they would have less issues. Turns out was wrong about that. The interesting thing too is that I sent an email thinking I would get responses pretty quickly to address my issues. The problem with the Hub is that whenever you remove something specifically the (Wemo light switch) and try to bring them back in it doesn't see the switch at all. This is extremely annoying and Yes I read the disclaimer with them saying they are not exclusive. But, i did get them to work and about 2 or 3 weeks later they kept coming up as offline. Great technology but a lot of bugs. To make matters worst I went and bought the GE switches which they support completely. The issue is once you install them and follow the procedure to connect them you have no idea that the switches are connected because it doesn't tell you. You literally have to come out of the search and boom its already there. So you would be sitting on that screen waiting for it to confirm. I only figured this out because I was frustrated and backed out of the screen. Needs more work definitely. When it works it works but when it doesn't good luck!"}
{"Author": "Laura A. Westphal", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well, not thrilled with interface...", "Text": "Wish it had more detail in the screen options. Have to bounce around to find the screen I needed...maybe I'm just too old...\nAlso, did two separate live chats with their Tech, and in both cases they had no answer for me other than to look for 3rd party applications. Would have been nice to be able to customize the screen options for my uses.\n\nOtherwise works as promised."}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works like magic", "Text": "Works simply and quickly! I ordered this hub and an external wall plug. Connected everything, downloaded the iPhone app, and in less than 10 minutes, I could turn the plug off and on with the app through the hub. Then I connected the Alexa and SmartThings apps together, and after 20 minutes, I could tell Alexa to turn my plug on and off with voice commands. Simple!! I ordered and installed a wall switch and connected it very quickly."}
{"Author": "Brian K. Maynard", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "ASWESOME...cant wait to see what new Z-Wave products come out to work with the hub", "Text": "Was using Xfinity home protection, now I have moved to my own system and now pay no monthly cost. I paid over $600.00 for all the Xfinity gear, which is now usless, and a monthly fee of $45.00. Now, I have invested around $400.00 in various Z-wave devices to work with my Smartthings and have greater coverage than what I did with Xfinity. If you want to keep an eye on your home without paying someone to do it,,smarthings is the way to go."}
{"Author": "TnSmitty", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with good wifi!!!!"}
{"Author": "Garry L. Robinson", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "useless if it won't activate", "Text": "can't use it. Activation code fails. Samsung support efforts so far have been unfruitful. Also, no instructions with it, just an item on the box with a web address for \"how to use\", but there's no such information at that site.\nEDITED 1/9/17: Samsung responded with a phone # which I used to get the activation code working. So far so good. Jumping to 3 star but not quite 4 since the code activation problem is something they need to fix.\nEDITED LATER THE SAME DAY: DAMMIT, ENOUGH IS ENOUGH. Got home and the so-called activated code is no longer working. This is a piece of junk, or the company is... not sure which. Back to one-star, only because I cannot do ZERO."}
{"Author": "Ed Kummel", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It is the perfect extension for Alexa!", "Text": "This is exactly what the Alexa needs to extend her usefulness! No matter what device I go and purchase, this thing can talk to it, and by proxy, can be controlled by Alexa! I used to use X10 devices throughout my house with schedules and macros. Now, with this SmartThings hub, I can modernize my entire system with whatever smart devices I want to use."}
{"Author": "Rick", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good.", "Text": "I purchased this to do home automation for our vacation home. Very simple set up. The app is very well laid out and intuitive. Little to no issues connecting to sensors, switches etc. I cannot comment on long term reliability or connectivity issues because I've only had it for a week but so far so good."}
{"Author": "I Love Google Home", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. Being controlled by Google Home", "Text": "Works great. Being controlled by Google Home, I use it to control my Harmony Remote which in turn controls my TV and sound. My Harmony Remote also controls my Insteon Hub which controls my Insteon switches. Bottom line with this, Google Home almost controls my entire house....hopefully my internet never goes down, which would force me to get off the couch :-)"}
{"Author": "Kenneth Foringer", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I don't mind that I have to do alot of tinkering to get it to work the way I like. I would not recommend this to someone who ...", "Text": "As an person who makes a living working with and engineering complex IT infrastructures, this product is right up my alley. I don't mind that I have to do alot of tinkering to get it to work the way I like. I would not recommend this to someone who is not comfortable with the idea of manipulating code. There is a very large online community devoted to developing this platform and they are very helpful."}
{"Author": "Robert Czachorski", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup and configure and has worked with every ...", "Text": "Product works well and does exactly what it needs to do. Easy to setup and configure and has worked with every smart device I have thrown at it so far, including switches, plugs, water sensors, light bulbs and Alexa."}
{"Author": "Customer", "Date": "on January 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Simple to setup and add \"things\" to. Active community support and integrates well with Google Home."}
{"Author": "jw", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Im really enjoying making my house a smart home!", "Text": "Loving this hub. Bought it as a Christmas gift for the family. Works really well with the Amazon Echo. Im really enjoying making my house a smart home!"}
{"Author": "Arnold S.", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Didn't work. Poor support", "Text": "Couldn't get to work. Poor support. Samsung didn't want to replace. Threw it away"}
{"Author": "Amy L. West", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is awesome and their tech support is great and responsive", "Text": "This is awesome and their tech support is great and responsive. I was having some challenges with the location services. Turns out, at least in Android Nougat, virtually all services are turned on for battery optimization. Their recommendation is to turn battery optimization off for the SmartThings app. I also turned battery optimization off for location services and it's been flawless."}
{"Author": "Etso", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Hub works great with my sylvania and ge light bulbs/switches. Also hooked up easily to Amazon echo"}
{"Author": "L.Love", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great home automation hub", "Text": "Best hub for home automation. Supports a lot of devices and has active community support."}
{"Author": "Moose", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy so far", "Text": "Works Well. Very happy so far, after 3-weeks, with its simplicity and how it works. App works well but would like App also for Windows or Apple computer operating systems. Read the directions carefully on the controller and your devices and it works."}
{"Author": "SPQR1805", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great addition to smart home."}
{"Author": "Kimo", "Date": "on January 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It worked as expected. Transfer from Hub v1 to ...", "Text": "It worked as expected. Transfer from Hub v1 to Hub v2 was a pain, but I didn't have a lot of profiles/smartapps, so it didn't take too long."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Well worth the investment", "Text": "The hub is simple, reliable and has an excellent interface. Be aware that initial pairing with an in wall smart switch/dimmer may require moving the hub close to the switch. After that, everything will operate fine at a distance. Alexa integration is simple."}
{"Author": "Jon", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Great", "Text": "I'm using this with a mix of z wave, zigbee and WiFi devices, when you add in the community support this is great. I have half a dozen kankun outlets using WiFi, two Wemo's, one z wave lock, and three zigbee outlets along with a few moisture and multi sensors. This was simple to import all the different devices and the Knakun plugs worked with a community supplied bit of groovy code."}
{"Author": "SG In NC", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Google Home!", "Text": "Works great with Google Home and the Smartthings mobile app. It's very easy to set up and use. I also bought the Lightify LED lights and they work with the Smartthings Hub perfectly without purchasing the Lightify hub."}
{"Author": "Chris F...", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect", "Text": "The best thing I could have every bought, This home automation stuff is cool."}
{"Author": "Ben Levine", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I find the hub is very easy to use with the app as a beginner", "Text": "I find the hub is very easy to use with the app as a beginner. I'm just using built-in functions, nothing special. I'm using this with:\n3 TP-link outlets (through amazon dot)\n2 GE Dimmer Switches\nOsram Lightify LED Strip lighting\n2 Leviton VRMX switches\nNo problems, fast reacting"}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "its fairly easy to use and setup", "Text": "I purchased this to help automate my home and connect with my Amazon dot. So far, its fairly easy to use and setup. My only complaint is setting up the Routines, either I'm doing something wrong or its not easy to setup, but I haven't had good luck setting up the Routines to correspond with my Amazon Dot. I'm still in the process of installing more automation in the house, but so far its worked fairly good."}
{"Author": "Talani C.", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "false sense of security", "Text": "The system sometimes gets disconnected from the sensors. The system does not notify you if a sensor is disconnected or not responding properly. What am I supposed to do? Go from door to door every night checking to see if the sensor is still working? This thing DOES NOT WORK. DO NOT BUY. It is not reliable.\n\nNot the first incident. This has happened several times after working properly for a while. All of a sudden the sensors will stop communicating with the hub, so \"performing good night\" does NOT mean that your doors are closed. It doesn't mean anything. I am so disgusted with the trouble shooting and buggy system. And even when I get it working for a while, I have no way of knowing when it stops working again. This is a complete waste of time and money."}
{"Author": "sanjay", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Useless, cannot connect thermostate even when I tried to ...", "Text": "Useless, cannot connect thermostate even when I tried to sync manually, took forever for it to sync my individual lights. As a matter of fact, I had to manully add the lights as it was having trouble finding my light switches"}
{"Author": "Greg H", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I also have a smart light switch and motion sensor", "Text": "The hub has been working well. I also have a smart light switch and motion sensor. No problems."}
{"Author": "FEDcop", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great hub!", "Text": "Easy to set up!\nWorks seemlessly with my Samsung robot vac and Kwikset deadbolt.\nGoing to add more automation and I'll update if there are any problems m"}
{"Author": "Johnnyricko", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to use, works great!"}
{"Author": "Alisha Reedy", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product and husband loves it."}
{"Author": "Dennis S.", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love this thing, and works like a champ."}
{"Author": "Joe M.", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Slowly converting entire house to smart home--this is THE hub for the job!", "Text": "Simply put....plug this thing in and it works. Setup my account, followed directions and started adding \"things\". This is great and is compatible with lots of smart things out there in the market, including Arlo cams, GE plug outlets, wemo switches, Schlage locks, and door sensors."}
{"Author": "CD", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub works", "Text": "My hub works really great"}
{"Author": "Tom", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings hub works as advertised", "Text": "After a few years of having a nexia bridge and paying for the service I decided to try a non-subscription route. After looking around and reading reviews, I decided on the Smartthings Hub. One consideration was that while I like gadgets, not everyone else in the house does, so I had to keep it user friendly. The Smartthings app has been that, and it is easier to use than the nexia app which I always found to be buggy. I also like that there are 3rd party apps such as Smartrules that work with the system allowing for more customization. It does what I want it to do, control some lights, turn on lights automatically when we get home and shut things off at night. It is capable of a lot more than I use it for."}
{"Author": "johnd", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "love smart things. Once you get it gong - very robust !"}
{"Author": "Edwin", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good, but still a work in progress", "Text": "Mostly love. It was easy to set up, has paired well with all my z-wave devices, paired with Alexa, and I look forward to expanding my system.\n\nIssues: Doesn't access all functionality of some devices reducing their usefulness. Limitations on Alexa access of security functions. Amazon overcomes purchasing issues with passwords or pins, couldn't the same be applied for home security if desired?\n\nHoping new apps will improve function."}
{"Author": "Rebecca O'Brien", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to setup, install, activate, and connect to other products."}
{"Author": "DRCNY", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... to that company forcing us to upgrade to their worse version 2", "Text": "I bought this to replace my v1 version of Iris from Lowes due to that company forcing us to upgrade to their worse version 2.0. I was considering smart things and vera and landed on smart things. While it is NOT perfect, none of the main smart home hubs/systems are. There are things I like and things I don't like. Overall, it is easy to setup and connects to just about any z-wave or zigby devices. Compared to Iris/Lowes, there are at least online users groups who will help you figure things out (there is zero support for iris). There are some 'quirky' things I've noticed over the last year, one of them being that it is possible to have an action such as turn off/on a light based on a 'time' and if you later remove that, it still seems to be there. You typically can get around that by removing the device or even renaming it, but I had to learn this. It is not a 'big' negative and it literally is on one of my switches at this point. It also does not (or at least I cannot find) where you can see the strength of the connection to the hub of devices. This does come in handy for my devices that are in my backyard or to see if I need to add/move other devices to create a better 'mesh' of connectivity.\n\nBut, with those few negatives, overall it has worked well. It can be used as a basic system and as you get more into the smart home, you can do more things although I think if you are not overly techy you may struggle with some of the non-standard apps you can add. BUT, there are users online who do point you in the right direction.\n\nI also cannot speak to using it as a security system. I know some people require/want this, but for me I prefer to keep my smart home separate, perhaps someday that will change for me. I use it to control lighting, locks, thermostats, motion sensors and contact sensors to turn things on/off based on different times of day or even different days. I have contact sensors on my back door so for those days I may leave the door open, if it is more than a set number of minutes it will turn off the heat or AC until the door is shut. I use a motion sensor in my mailbox to text/alert me when mail arrives. So, you can get creative.\n\nIt does integrate with Amazon Alexa, so I can use voice commands to turn lights on/off or dim them, adjust thermostats.\n\nOverall, I\"m happy with it. I have not yet really used 'scenes' or 'geo fences' and may attempt those but they were never priorities. So, one must consider how advanced you want to be.\n\nOn the very big PLUS side compared to Iris, there is no monthly cost for features you will NEED. So, once you buy the hub there is no monthly cost. You will of course need to buy the 'things' (lights, switches, sensors, thermostats) that all work with the hub. I also feel that Samsung will continue to improve the product, whereas, I think Lowes will ultimately drop Iris especially after their change to version 2.0 which was a nightmare.\n\nSo do your research for what you want to use it for, but for me I've been happy with the system."}
{"Author": "Brian", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bringing light to a dark house.", "Text": "I love this product. This thing works great with all the items in my house. I have the safety of my house increasing with this product."}
{"Author": "Gertnerbot", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great versatile hub", "Text": "So far, I LOVE this hub. Samsung does have a developer portal for attaching custom items such as Arduino and Raspberry Pi modules. For the developer side, it takes some getting used to. For non-developers(i.e. normal consumers), I would say on a scale from 1 to 10 on setup difficulty (10 being hard), I'd put this at a 6."}
{"Author": "Clayton Spann", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Powerful home integration", "Text": "I upgraded my older hub to the new V2. The previous system was pretty dormant for about 1.5 years and wanted to revisit my home automation hobby. The new hub was easy to install. I did a fresh install using a new smartthing account (could have used my old account to transfer but I messed something up part way so started fresh). A lot of progress has been made since I last used it. The smartthing developer web site has a lot of good information. Currently I have integrated; lights, home entertainment center, presence sensors, smart switches, lights, Sonos, and google home. Using both the mobile app and the web based development site (for creating virtual switches) I can create custom commands that google home can execute. I like the fact that smartthing integrates with a wide range of devices. You do have to be a bit of a techy for some of the more complex script developments. But the outline community is very helpful and patient"}
{"Author": "Ellis", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "I am absolutely loving the SmartThings Hub. I chose to buy the GE dimmable switches to connect to the hub and it was really easy to connect them. It really comes down to what you want to do. Buying a bunch of smart bulbs seems to be much more expensive. The GE switches cost about $32. I bought 14 of them and had someone come install them. Typically, I would install switches myself, but you have to connect a neutral wire, which for me meant I was going to have to cut a couple of wires. That was outside my comfort zone. I hired a handy man and he had them installed in about four hours.\n\nCurrently, I have it set up to where it recognizes when I leave the house and automatically turns off all the lights. It also recognizes when I get close to home and turns on all the lights. I also have an automation set up for when I watch movies so it turns off certain lights, turns on certain lights, and dims others to the level I chose while setting up the automation. There is so much you can do. It's going to take time to figure it out, but I like tinkering with things like this so I will enjoy it!\n\nThings to keep in mind: For three way switches where you can turn on lights from two locations, you will need the kit. Or, you can just install one switch and the other won't be able to turn the light on or off. I went with the second option for the moment. If you want to control fans, there are specific switches for that."}
{"Author": "Justin Gould", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fine for my smart house", "Text": "Great for multi use smart homes."}
{"Author": "Husker Ron", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very good!! works better than any other smart hub i have"}
{"Author": "M. Mickley", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy with Samsung hub", "Text": "I previously owned the Iris hub from Lowe's and had all kinds of trouble with it dropping off line, losing connection with my smart switches, etc. Finally got so frustrated that I bought the Samsung hub and it has worked wonderfully. None of the issues with Iris and much more functionality especially with built-in smart apps and add on apps. I am now very happy with how my smart home functions."}
{"Author": "Jose Gonzalez", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it's working fantastic. The app is a little confusing to set ...", "Text": "I'm using this to secure a house with door sensors and motion sensors and a siren alarm. For that purpose, it's working fantastic. The app is a little confusing to set everything up, but once you figure it out, works like a charm. You can even have it give you a phone call when the alarm is tripped."}
{"Author": "Brent Shipley", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome product", "Text": "This is an easy to install and easy to use product that gives me some peace of mind when I leave my house."}
{"Author": "Eric P. Muffley", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wonderful product", "Text": "It just works"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Would recommend", "Text": "Great product, lots of support, and easy to sync!"}
{"Author": "kyle Duffin", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great", "Text": "Buy it and don't look back. The sky is the limit."}
{"Author": "PapaJ", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love It", "Text": "My son bought me one of these for Christmas along with the Alexa. It works great and was a breeze to set up. And it works flawlessly with the Alexa commands to turn on and off devices. And you can also control all the devices with your smart phone or tablet just as well."}
{"Author": "richard lalli", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart things hub", "Text": "I found the hub easy to set up and pairing the smart things devices was also easy to do. I am looking forward to adding additional devices giving me greater control over the devices in my home"}
{"Author": "Lawdg", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent", "Text": "Works well. took minutes to hook up. I had to call tech support to figure out why a setting wasn't working. Well it was a setting in my Alexa app. I spoke with tech support via online chat on my cell phone. They were quick to answer an very helpful. HINT- You must allow Alexa to use the device in the Alexa App and turn the features on. Works well, I'm very happy with it.It has more features than I realized. Very impressed with the Samsung Tech support !!!!!!!!"}
{"Author": "Jay", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I think it works great overall. Given that the technology is still evolving", "Text": "I think it works great overall. Given that the technology is still evolving, you have to have a little patience - some components might not be available yet, and there may be occasional hiccups. But I think it's overall pretty reliable. Every few weeks it's offline briefly for an upgrade. The app is very polished and versatile; does not seem to be a battery hog. Setup wasn't too complicated; it helps to have a little bit of patience and slightly above average in technical abilities, but you certainly don't need to have advanced computer knowledge or be a programmer."}
{"Author": "Cameron", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I wish you could easily group switches together but other than that it has ...", "Text": "I wish you could easily group switches together but other than that it has everything I need and works very well. This was my first hub so I cannot compare to other hubs."}
{"Author": "PhantomDev", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Loving my smartthings."}
{"Author": "JxA", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Functional & Priced right!", "Text": "The SmartThings Hub was on sale for ~$50 so I scooped it up right away in order to automate my home wit h Amazon Echo.\n\nI am technical; however, I appreciate the simple setup of this unit. Once it was installed I had no issues connecting 7/8 GE Smart Dimmer, Z-Wave, In Wall, 12724 devices to it. I would say that the one dimmer that gave me trouble may have been due to the location - I moved it, applied power and then it worked perfectly.\n\nThe system will alert you if it is disconnected, thus it serves as an internet connectivity monitor...\n\nIf you're going to automate with ZigBee, then this device will work quite nicely - especially for the price."}
{"Author": "Dave G", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it", "Text": "Good product easy to use. Great customer support.\nI bought the product used from Amazon and unfortunately, the previous owner had already registered it. I thought (mistakenly) of a protracted process to fix. I popped to the link on the setup page, sent an E-Mail with a photo of the back of the unit. Within five minutes I was up and running.\nExperience:\nSetup was simple, just follow the steps - download apps, hook up device, wait a few minutes, you are then hooked up.\nConnecting devices was also easy, using the app. I successfully linked to my Oshram Zigbee lights plus my WeMo switches.\nIntegration: I successfully integrated with Amazon Echo as well as the Harmony Companion system. All this in about one hour.\nPros:\na. Connects to a lot of devices - more than listed on their website. App has full list of currently supported devices.\nb. Integrates with other control devices, so you can have multiple paths to control devices (smartphone, Echo, Harmony)\nc. Active development community and vendor updates (SmartThings Lab) with plans for more equipment (TP Link items).\nCons:\na. Does not have a Generic Device capability to try to link to other devices.\nb. Connects to Ethernet wire, which may limit installation locations (or buy a wifi to ethernet bridge)\nI will update this review if I see anything else."}
