{"Author": "Jared R", "Date": "on December 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dont buy", "Text": "My main complaint is that the App only has access on mobile devices, so I can't control anything from my computer. This factor alone would lead me to choose a competitor if I was buying a smart home hub again.\n\nDowngraded my review. It constantly has issues connecting to a Honeywell Thermostat it should be fine with."}
{"Author": "Deborah", "Date": "on December 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great but installation instructions are a bit unclear", "Text": "I had a little trouble setting up this hub to handle smart devices in the house. Directions for doing so simply aren't very good, not because it's very complicated to do, but because the overall *theory* of how these things work is not conveyed to the amateur user. It was not clear until I was in the middle of installation that first of all, the hub should be installed into the main modem coming into the house and not a repeater, and that the first switch you install has to be within about 10 feet of the hub and not behind a wall. The devices (light switches, outlets, smart thermostat, etc.) all sort of link together into a network of their own, so the idea is that the first device is close to the hub, the next device has to be somewhat close to the first, the next somewhat close to one of the devices previously installed, and so forth. In other words, every smart device in your home is approximately 10-15 feet from at least one other device, and at least one of the devices is close to your hub.\n\nI hope that explanation makes sense to all the amateur installers out there! I had to google stuff and it was a little tricky because I didn't really \"get it\" for a while. But once I got it, it was a piece of cake.\n\nAnd everything works great -- I can run the lights from a mobile app or tell Alexa to turn them on/off/up/down, etc. The possibilities are endless!"}
