{"Author": "Jean Parker", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Happy with my Smart Home", "Text": "Device support and customizability is awesome. Love the open ecosystem. After connecting devices things have been stable and the mobile application (IOS for me) has worked for me. I connected it with Amazon Echo and the voice integration works well and has been popular with family friends. I have been adding more devices (switches, motion sensors, lights) - and everything works together as one system."}
{"Author": "Seth A. Munroe", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Integrates all my home automation devices into one place.", "Text": "I bought the SmartThings hub to set up a timer for my fish tank light. I ended up buying the Google Home at the same time. I quickly learned that the SmartThings hub is the workhorse that really brings all my devices together in one spot. The Google Home makes it easy to turn things off and on or find out if they are already on. I've been really impressed that the SmartThings hub works just as well with other brand devices as it does with SmartThings branded devices.\n\nI'm a software developer and I found the developer support for SmartThings is really the aspect that sold me on SmartThings. I'm able to write apps that do exactly what I want. In most cases I could use existing SmartApps or IFTTT rules, but it's nice to be able to fine tune exactly what I want by writing my own SmartApps."}
{"Author": "Brian Card", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "nice idea doesn't work", "Text": "could never get it to sync with items, returned it"}
{"Author": "Objective Reality", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup, high compatibility with a large number of 3rd party products", "Text": "Easy to setup, high compatibility with a large number of 3rd party products. Using extensively with Cree Connected bulbs. The secret to getting these to pair is get yourself a desk lamp and put it about a foot away from the hub. Every bulb pairs quickly and flawlessly this way. Then move the bulb to its final location."}
{"Author": "E.Penn", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "New to the automation game, so ease of use is key.", "Text": "The hub works pretty well. Was easy enough to connect my Osram Lightify lights to it and my Google Home. The website for creating recipes however could be a little more user friendly. I'm fairly new to automating my house so I wanted something that could connect to multiple systems like Z-wave, Wifi, and Zigbee so this seemed like a great deal. It's been working well so far though the phone app for grouping together systems has me perplexed at times also. I think I made a routine work and then, fizzle, nothing, but I'm chalking this up to user error for the time being."}
{"Author": "D. White", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It works, but it's not completely simple and easy yet", "Text": "This is fun, useful, and works, but folks should know that this is still somewhat early days for home automation in terms of ease of use in setting things up, and support for some devices requires a little extra effort. There is an excellent Smartthings community at Smartthings.com, where you can find other users offering tons of help. You can also find out there how to use devices outside the officially supported items.\n\nReliability has been great, I've had little or no drop outs, and being able to monitor and manage my home via voice (using both Alexa and Google Home), and remotely via the Smartthings app."}
