{"Author": "Mal R", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So, is Smartthings the one to go with?", "Text": "It's difficult to find a home automation system that suits you, in what is a minefield of choice. You want a bit from this one, a bit from that one and so on. This one is pretty good and you can set it up as an easy & simple system, or as a complex techy version. Some devices from other makes and systems will work with it, (such as smart plugs) but whenever possible, get the samsung ones 'cos they just work better. Samsung use a protocol called Zigbee, but will also work within the Zwave system. Any device you add that is plugged into the mains (like a smart plug) will help to extend the network range.... But only for the protocol that it uses, so it's best to stick with one if you can. Here's a tip. Building up a good range is not as easy as just adding another plug, so you need to do some research and understand how it happens. With zigbee, get them paired with your hub, then place them around the house. Then, completely shut down the hub for at least 10 minutes, so that the plugs renew their connections with each other, therefore increasing the range. Then restart the hub. If you don't do this proceedure they all just carry on trying to communicate directly with the hub even if the signal is weak.\nThe system is pretty bomb proof and recovers easily from interruption of power or loss of internet connection. The current app that will control stuff works, it's useable, but isn't ideal. It's poorly thought out, often confusing, contains some minor bugs and is not a nice & easy \"flowing\" experience to use. The fact you can set up and control more than one system within the app is good and suits me as I need 2 systems. One system will replace British Gas \"safe & secure\", which was good but got neglected by BritishGas as they went off to do something else, so don't trust them with Hive!!! (Shame on you BG, you had loyal customers that you abandoned.)\nIf you have a failure of a component, dealing direct with Samsung is painfull. With me, one plug failed. I was back and fore with their customersupport for weeks sending emails, uploading videos to youtube, waiting for their agreement that it's faulty, returns notes, etc etc. I'm still waiting for the replacement. They don't see that I would not have requested a replacement if it was working..... Bad aftersales proceedure. Bad. I would not buy anything direct with them again. Use Amazon, or a local shop, or something.\nHowever. All in all, a good product. It works. I hope Samsung carry on developing it because it is almost superb!"}
