{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on December 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "When it works it is amazing, when it doesn't it is a nightmare", "Text": "When it works it is amazing, when it doesn't it is a nightmare. Frequently get told that devices are unresponsive and have to reboot my router constantly to reset everything.\n\nZ Wave devices fail to update and repairing my Z-wave network does not help either. Specifically this device does not work:\nhttps://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0013V1SRY/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&th=1"}
{"Author": "Matthew Leffel", "Date": "on December 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Working great so far"}
{"Author": "Jeffrey Basso", "Date": "on December 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This platform is evolving. There are some challenges with ...", "Text": "This platform is evolving. There are some challenges with stability that said it does have the right model and it very expandable if you want to customize it."}
{"Author": "Radcon", "Date": "on December 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No monthly plan needed!", "Text": "Hooked up to my router seamlessly then to my door lock via Alexa. I did have to use IFTTT to get it to work via voice and alas no way to unlock with my voice using Alexa but that does make sense for security reasons."}
{"Author": "CNAshley", "Date": "on December 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Broken --- never worked", "Text": "Never recognized by my model/router. Even spent $259 for someone to trouble mshooot. Defective and I can't return it"}
{"Author": "FiveFlavors", "Date": "on December 9, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The hub is good but the support is FANTASTIC", "Text": "The hub is good but the support is FANTASTIC. A real phone number a human answers. Unless you love to tinker, support is a key factor in your purchase. My water sensors work but they have a battery that is very difficult to remove and seem to get used fast. I can not compare that to other sensors but overall, would buy this again.\n\nThank you again Antoine"}
{"Author": "Keron", "Date": "on December 9, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I have not been able to install. It takes ...", "Text": "I have not been able to install. It takes some effort to configure. I wI'll post an update once I get it up and running."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works 100% with Google Home", "Text": "Works 100% with Google Home and any devices that use Zigbee and Z-Wave WiFi standards."}
{"Author": "Darcy Myers", "Date": "on December 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "so easy to set up", "Text": "so easy to set up. i'm controling most of my lights and Samsung Cameras with the SmartThings App and it works flawlessly. i hope to add Locks, Garage Opener, a few outlets and more Light switches in the future."}
{"Author": "John362", "Date": "on December 8, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I really wanted to rate this better", "Text": "Let me start by saying I have an echo, 8 lifx bulbs, 2 ge wall switches, 2 locks, and several Appliance switches. My Emerson thermostat doesn't work with it. When you get this Hub it's a bit of a learning curve to start, but not too bad, adding the lifx bulbs was fairly easy. The rest of the devices were a little more difficult but not much. The Hub is basically a controller and there is no dashboard for your switches for Android or iPhone. That's disappointing but okay for me for the most part since I have the Amazon Echo. The built-in automation, or routines, is very basic, it does a lot less than IFTTT. Actually most of the functions on this are very basic, you can't even make groups. Any functionality beyond that is added through Community apps. So without custom Community apps it doesn't even do as much as the echo for the most part. Installing Community apps and device handlers is a much steeper learning curve. I found a community made device Handler that allows you to add lifx groups, like living room or patio, but the Hub often doesn't register their state correctly, so when you go to turn one off it will think it's off already. This happens often with all of the lifx bulbs, it doesn't pull their state correctly or often enough. If you want to make more complex automation like change my bulbs to daylight white during the day there is a community app called CoRE which is a rules engine. You can make really complex routines based off of all kinds of triggers, but it doesn't work half the time, and it's Community made so it's not like you can complain to anyone. My night mode routine is set to dim all the lights but one and turn off the TV through my Harmony Hub but it only works 50% of the time. It always worked on IFTTT. Actually one of the most reliable things this can do is trigger IFTTT commands but it's a pain to set up and the Echo already does that. I may be able to get it working after spending an additional 10 hours on community threads, but ultimately The Hub is just really disappointing and you are 100% reliant on community apps which may or may not be updated or maintained, or reliable."}
{"Author": "Darren Richnafsky", "Date": "on December 8, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SMART THINGS- Smart Buy!", "Text": "SMART THINGS is a nice device to have for home automation. I've been tinkering with automation over the past two months with ST as my hub. Thus far I like it, but as with anything, there can be draw backs. Set-up is easy and prices are dropping on the hub as newer versions hit the market. I chose ST hub largely because of the field devices that are compatible with it. I worried about the merits of the hub communicating with devices in the farther reaches of my home, but it has handled things fine thus far. A few matters that prevent me from giving 5-stars being; once in a while, it logs me out of the app (iPhone). This becomes a pain while driving to get a quick glance of my home while at a stop light. This happens about once per week. The display of individual devices under the \"RECENTLY\" tab is hard to read ( I think because of the color of the font being used). It may not be the most user friendly platform, but it does perform a lot of cool functions. If you are somewhat tech savvy, you will like it. If you are not, it's still manageable. **Final note: hub MUST be within cable reach of your wireless router**\nPROS:\n> handles many field devices- look around, some great prices out there\n> Reasonable cost of hub\n> Small, compact\n> Range is good\n> New devices easy to add\n\nCONS:\n> Occasional log-outs\n> Device(s) fall asleep (rare)- need to be refreshed\n> Some fonts hard to read within app menus\n> TILES (PC app) is clunky and not very accurate\n> Wish it had more customization"}
{"Author": "WontPontificate", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Software is not yet ready for Prime Time.", "Text": "The SmartThings hub has the potential to be an excellent product, but is hobbled by its overly-simple rules system. When I purchased this, I expected to be able to set up an automation routine such as \"Set living room light brightness to 20%, set accent blooms to 50% and red, turn off dining room lights, turn on bathroom light to 100% and run \"Netflix\" routine on Harmony hub.\" Unfortunately, the overly simplistic rules engine of the Hub doesn't allow anything this complex.\n\nWithin the SmartThings environment, I can create an activity, select items to turn on, items to turn off, and a global brightness for the activity. I have no option to set colour of selected lamps in an activity, and while I can activate Harmony routines, it treats them as lightbulbs. The system is very rigid and inflexible, and is in need of an overhaul to even support simple \"watch a movie\" routines like the one I was trying to create.\n\nSmartThings uses a system of \"smartapps\" to integrate with other smart home items. I have to say that the Harmony, Hue, and Alexa apps tend to discover and add things more or less seamlessly, and the system tends to \"Just work\" as long as you aren't trying anything too complicated.\n\nSmartApps also attempt to replace some of the missing features in the rules engine. There's a SmartApp for changing lightbulb colour, but it has very specific conditions under which it can effect a colour change, but notably missing are triggers for a routine. Since routines have no way of altering the colour of a lightbulb, I'd expect to be able to use a smartapp to set light bulbs to change colour when that routine is run, as a sort of an attachment to it, but there is no way to link the two.\n\nOverall, when it works, it works, and it does do quite well for itself, within its limited scope. For now though, its usefulness is thoroughly hampered by the overly simplistic and rather confusing software. It is my hope that we'll see an update that improves the quality of the rules engine to allow for more complex routines, to make your home truly smart."}
{"Author": "WDavidO", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stupid architecture that causes long delays for bad reasons", "Text": "The smart things architecture was a stupid idea based on cloud computing for everything. So say you want to turn on a light? First you press a button then the hub sends the button request to a server over the internet which loads your code into memory if it isn't already there and then sends signals back to your hub. Sometimes this can take several seconds which of course is something you'll be happy with when you're turning a light on or off. When I got some new smart dimmer switches that were drastically affected by this absurd problem I did a lot of reading on the smart things community to find out that virtually nothing runs locally on the hub (that was the major selling point of the v2.0 hub,) I sent in a complaint to customer service and the response was that they hated to be the bearer of bad news but virtually nothing runs on the hub and they had no way of enabling some sort of developer mode that would let me do what I wanted with the hub I paid them money for. I don't know who designed the smart things architecture but they made a lot of ludicrous decisions which apparently the company is unable to fix."}
{"Author": "ROBERT KIMBROUGH JR.", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "purchased this for my wife she loves it"}
{"Author": "Don", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy set up and decent app", "Text": "Very easy set up and decent app. Works well with my harmony remotes and ecobee T-stats.\n\nI knocked a star off because replacing a existing smart switch with a dimmer switch is not a simple task."}
{"Author": "Brian Thompson", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Powerful and easy to use!", "Text": "The Samsung SmartThings Hub is a powerful, easy to use, device that connects almost all the Smart Home gadgets you can think of. With a little bit of reading and some technical know-how, you can find SmartApps that will connect devices that aren't even supported by Samsung."}
{"Author": "SBS", "Date": "on December 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cutting edge but not complicated", "Text": "Very cool and relatively easy to set up. Allows us to see and control all sorts of things from anywhere. Just have some lights and the \"Ring\" doorbell hooked up so far but will definitely be adding more soon. Combine this with the Echo and you can control by voice too."}
{"Author": "Tom DiBello", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seems to be the best of a not so great selection of hubs on the market", "Text": "I didn't realize that this unit must be wired directly to the modem/router. It really should work on wifi so I can hide it. The counter with my modem and router is getting really cluttered. Also had an outage the first day. If there's a problem with the cloud service, the unit doesn't work. While that may also be true for my Wemo switches, I've never had a problem with them (they don't need a hub). All things considered, however, this does work well with my zwave switches and my Echo. It's probably the least restrictive hub on the market right now, so for that reason I will love it."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "WORTHLESS WITHOUT CONSTANT INTERNET CONNECTION", "Text": "Why does it REQUIRE an internet connection to simply turn off lights? Why does everything have to be about the \"cloud\"? Can I get one device that doesn't need to be sending data to a third party to be logged and recorded? Would it be so difficult to have a device on my private network, send a command to another device on my private network that can send out the Z-Wave signal to control a switch? Is it really necessary to cripple a hub because it doesn't have an internet connection. I figured it would need an internet connected router to set up and maybe connect local devices, but I didn't realize it would be completely crippled and worthless if connection to the internet was ever lost."}
{"Author": "Lucinda Hanson", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product."}
{"Author": "Josh Bergstrom", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fantastic Zwave Hub and Integrated Easily with Amazon Echo! Beats the pants off Wemo!!!", "Text": "I bought this to work with the Zwave GE smart switches in my home. It also synced up to my Amazon Echo and Alexa perfectly. Had I done a little more research prior to buying the wemo lights, I would have bought the smartthings hub in a heartbeat.\n\nEasy to install, fantastic phone app, so much more control over my smart home lights than with wemo. Multiple lights at a time, geofencing automation, scene setups, integrates with IFTTT, excellent hub for smart home at a great price.\n\nI would highly recommend this hub to anyone using Zwave products and or interested in making their home a smart home."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Most versatile hub I have found; stable and just works."}
{"Author": "KEmerick", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm so glad I switched from the Lowe's Iris system to the ...", "Text": "I'm so glad I switched from the Lowe's Iris system to the Samsung Smartthings. It pairs much easier and is compatible with many more devices. Google Home controls it and makes my life easier."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 5, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "MUST have internet, stops working if internet drops.", "Text": "It works well, it detects the devices but there are two thing that are issues. First, it is totally depended on the access to the internet. If you lose internet connectivity your whole system does not work! Whatever state your system is is is the way it stay unless you manually go to each device and switch it. In my view they should backup the devices and groups etc locally so it still works if your internet drops.\n\nSecond, they don't supply a native ipad app, so if you are an ipad user you get the magnified version of the iphone app. So it only runs in portrait mode and not as nice as if it was a native ipad app.\n\nOther than that it is very easy to install etc."}
{"Author": "L. D. Smith II", "Date": "on December 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No, it doesn't do scenes - ignore their hype", "Text": "I'm ashamed I bought this simply because they don't support lighting scenes. I've spent hours researching this one topic and it seems that everything you really want to do with lighting is so unbelievably complex it makes me want to throw the whole system out. There are \"smart\" apps and \"virtual switches\" (that require a technology expert to install because they aren't list in the - wait for it - switches list) and if this then that nonsense and triggers and on and on. Just because it only allows ONE dim level for all lights you turn on in a Routine. Junk in my mind for this one flaw."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "recommended", "Text": "very helpful"}
{"Author": "Mark Grano", "Date": "on December 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Universal", "Text": "Automated my entire Apartment using this, Alexa, and Google Home. I have both to figure out which voice service I will end up liking best but the point is that smartthings works with everything and bridges the gap so you don't get stuck in one eco-system whether it be Amazon or Google. Both voice clients have their merits so I enjoy using Smartthings to get the best of both worlds easily and seamlessly."}
{"Author": "Nikunj Parekh", "Date": "on December 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dead on arrival; lousy quality", "Text": "dead on arrival.\nLousy quality and waste of time"}
{"Author": "Pkripper", "Date": "on December 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings v2 hub works flawlessly", "Text": "At first, I was apprehensive about buying this hub after reading the mixed reviews. I did some research and homework on what Home Automation hub and environment I would invest in. I narrowed it down to between SmartThings and Wink. I chose SmartThings because of the wider options of components and devices. I'm sure Wink works as well too.\n\nI'm glad I listened to the positive ones and ordered it. I have not had any problems with it. Both Z-Wave and Zigbee devices have synced and work without any trouble. Notifications and alerts from the SmartThings app are instant. It'S great that my powered devices like outlets and switches act as a signal extender/repeater. That way my devices farther away from the hub act just as reliable as being next to it.\n\nFor anyone in this environment, I suggest downloading the SmartRules app. It offers an even more configurable automation process based on more detail circumstances - more than what the SmartThings app offers.\n\nI highly recommend the hub to anyone."}
{"Author": "J. Thompson", "Date": "on December 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent home automation device.", "Text": "Excellent home automation device. I have much of the home automated around this, also tied well to the use of Siri."}
{"Author": "ribbett2012", "Date": "on December 3, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not for the Tech Afraid!", "Text": "Do NOT get this if you are not tech savvy....my mother is not, and this was a nightmare. It simply would not connect and I didn't feel like spending every day at her house fixing it!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product. Easy to set up."}
{"Author": "Seawind", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much Better Than Wink", "Text": "Just bought this last week to replace my Wink hub which had become unreliable. No problems moving all the lights, lock, garage door opener and a couple of sensors. Also coupled with my Amazon Echo. Works a lot better than the Wink hub. Response is almost instantaneous even when turning on groups of lights. Still getting used to the app. but otherwise couldn't be happier so far."}
{"Author": "Milo Grika", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great automated home addition", "Text": "Easy to set up and works great. Only complaint is that I could have used a longer ethernet cable."}
{"Author": "Jael", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Community makes this work", "Text": "Love the hub, but the app is still a confused mess even after the recent updates. Thank goodness for the community!"}
{"Author": "z45677", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Horrible App Can't group lights.", "Text": "Unfortantely this did not work as I had planned to use it for: Hue lights and wink plugs. I got this product hoping that it would be able to control all of my \"smart\" devices from one \"simple app\". This was not the case. The samsung smartthings app is very poorly designed and confusing even for people that are not new to smart home devices. You are unable to group a collection of light bulbs together on the app so you have to control each light and plug individually that in itself makes this useless. A house could have 20-30 bulbs in it nobody has a switch for each individual bulb."}
{"Author": "SHARON_SD", "Date": "on December 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "WORKS AMAZING. ITS INTERNAL WITH WEB ACRESS AND APP FOR ...", "Text": "CRAZY CRAZY DELAY FROM ONE ACTION TO THE ANOTHER - SINCE IT GOES THRU THE WEB. I GOT VERA INSTEAD. WORKS AMAZING. ITS INTERNAL WITH WEB ACRESS AND APP FOR MY PHONE - SO THE VERA IS MUCH MUCH BETTER"}
{"Author": "Andres J Quinones", "Date": "on November 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy setup and had my house automated in no time. Great product!"}
{"Author": "R", "Date": "on November 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect.", "Text": "Awesome. Easy to setup and set routines. Works with most smart home devices on the market today."}
{"Author": "Marc A. Ripley", "Date": "on November 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works. It just works as advertised. That's about the best compliment that you can give any product.", "Text": "Works. It just works as advertised. That's about the best compliment that you can give any product."}
{"Author": "Austin Thompson", "Date": "on November 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "This thing came USED!!! batteries in and it wouldnt accept the code."}
{"Author": "rik", "Date": "on November 28, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It looks like this combination will not work for my purproses", "Text": "I got this to use with 2 DLink security cameras that I already had, and I also got the SmartThings Multipurpose sensor. I wanted to use the multi as a 'doorbell' at my business, and have the cameras link to it so I could receive notifications at home and be able to connect to the cameras from home when I got an altert. It looks like this combination will not work for my purproses. The cameras are apparently not compatible with this hub (did a lot of reading before purchasing, but now can't find what made me think they'd work), and the sensor will not work as a doorbell. What it does is send you a text when the door is opened, and continues to do so (once per hour) if you don't dismiss the alert. However, a bell that plays over the house speakers (connected to computer) does not seem to be an option. Just a text. It's a bit frustrating that details of how these things can actually be used are unavaliable till you have it in hand. And even then, information is not readily available."}
{"Author": "Dalton", "Date": "on November 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Perfect as Described!!!"}
{"Author": "Colin", "Date": "on November 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Choice", "Text": "I love how quick and responsive the app is with the hub, all of the devices it supports, and the quality of the app. Very pleased I went with this ecosystem."}
{"Author": "Edited Visions", "Date": "on November 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Loved V1 and not V2 is even better", "Text": "Started with Hub V1 and now on V2. everything is working great. I wish they has a better system for upgrading to the new hub besides doing everything all over again but I got it done and all is working. I do notice a faster response time to triggers and I like the idea of having more processes being controlled locally instead of in the cloud. The battery back up is cool just not really part of my system now. If the lights go out I wont need smartthings to turn them on for me (no power). Besides that with the back Friday discount I could not find a reason not to upgrade."}
{"Author": "Peter Z.", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "V2 is still not stable.", "Text": "4/23/2017 Update - I really tried to get this to work but I am completely fed-up. Loosing connectivity with 1-2 random devices each week. Response from support has been the same - \"I found ghost devices and removed them, reconnect disconnected devices and run network repair\".\n\nAfter 4 years with Vera, I moved to Smartthings for ECHO integration. Compared to Vera Smartthings is unstable. I lose connectivity to at least 1 device every couple of days. Today I had to remove and add back 2 thermostats 4 in wall light switches and 1 appliance switch. I never had problems like that with Vera. Smartthings is a lot easier to use and modern product, but constant disconnects are huge problem for me. Tech support did not have solution but offered to send me new unit. I will take them up on their offer."}
{"Author": "Kevin Brown", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Design disaster starting with the app", "Text": "Design disaster from the beginning. Control app only available for android and ios. It has a 3.5 rating !!! Unable to download because my device is not compatible? Could find no requirements on website. Forums say they side loaded the apk. No apk on web site. Forum offered sketchy sites to get the apk. NO embedded web server for controls from browser. Only been a standard for routers for 10 years. NO windows desktop app. Have no faith in product to waste any more time on it."}
{"Author": "AZ Goat", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... this for quite a few months now and really like it. I have a few Amazon Echo's for ...", "Text": "I have had this for quite a few months now and really like it. I have a few Amazon Echo's for voice controlling my lights, door locks, thermostat and some AC outlets, and everything works very well. There is a second or 3 lag every now and then, but so infrequent that it doesn't bother me. The motion sensor from GoControl I use to turn on my office light takes 2-3 seconds to turn on my light - a little longer than it takes my Echo/Alexa to do it, but not too bothersome. You do need Internet for this, as it's connected to the cloud to perform everything, but the connection is supposedly secure (encrypted and access via username/password). The platform has been very stable and I've had no crashes or outages except when Samsung updates the software, which they alerted my to prior to the upgrades. The GUI is OK - could be worse, but some tasks are not super intuitive. However, do it a few times and it's fine. Community support is really good. Lot's of info out there, and there are several people that have developed additional functionality for supported devices, and even developed code to add some unsupported devices. Overall, I'd take a half star off for the GUI and the Internet requirement."}
{"Author": "Shawn D", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Replaced my Wink with SmartThing and much happier", "Text": "I replaced my Wink with the SmartThing hub and I am much happier. The true difference is the SmartThing Development site that allows users to develop there own programs to support more devices. I had multiple devices which was not supported on Wink or SmartThing but due to the developer site they now run on my SmartThing. I would recommend for the average user the SmartThing over Version 1 of Wink. I would be interested to see what improvements Wink made in Version 2.\n\nUPDATE: A must with SmartThings is to sign up with RBoy Apps, they develop additional SmartApps for SmartThings that expand the uses of the product."}
{"Author": "Paul Mullen", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to get started, endless possibilities to extend and customize, and super reliable.", "Text": "For the home automation generation, this is the best platform yet. Since 1993, we have used X10, Insteon, and some home grown things, and this is both the most flexible, extensible, and reliable technology we have used.\n\nA few detailed points:\n1) This is a relatively young technology and though it is very good as is, it should continue to improve.\n\n2) If you're setting up your first home automation there is much to learn regardless of your purposes. There is a relatively easy-to-use app for the phone. You can get going with this with relatively low effort.\n\n3) There is a very robust development community (discussion group, GitHub) that is terrific for those who want to extend SmartThings to do more through customized applications.\n\n4) Signal strength for wireless devices seems to be adequate. We are in a medium-sized ranch-style home with the hub at one end, and one of the wireless devices in the basement at the other end of the house works reliably.\n\n5) The platform reliability seems very solid. When the cloud network is going to go down for maintenance (once or twice in several years that i remember and always in the middle of the night US Central Time), you get advanced notice by email.\n\nPart of the fun is that SmartThings is extensible to other web applications throught IFTTT. For instance, I can say to Amazon's Alexa, \"Trigger Basement Off\" and Alexa will talk to IFTTT who will talk to SmartThings and boom, the basement lights go off. However, I have found that IFTTT has been unreliable... either in absolute terms, or in it's connection to SmartThings... I'm not sure which.\n\nAll in all, this is one of the most encouraging developments in the home automation world. Well done, Samsung!"}
{"Author": "Ronnie C", "Date": "on November 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Had High Hopes", "Text": "I was really excited about this but I could never get it connected properly even after spending 3 hours on the phone with tech support. Returning this along with the other items that I purchased to work with the hub. Disappointed"}
{"Author": "Haley", "Date": "on November 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty Cool Device!", "Text": "I researched the different Smart hubs. From my research I was most interested in the Wink or the Smart Things Hub. I decided to go with the Smart Things Hub since it is backed by Samsung and I figure it will get better and better. Upon opening the box I was able to get things up and running very easily. I connected the hub to my router. Next I paired 3 light dimmers. After that I set some automation to automatically turn off these lights at 11:00 pm each night. I created an automation to turn them all off or all on. Everything was pretty straight forward and has worked well so far."}
{"Author": "A. Simpson", "Date": "on November 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "excellent home hub!", "Text": "best thing I have bought in quite awhile. So easy to setup. Added a few z-wave sensors and a honeywell totalhomecomfort thermostat in minutes. Bought this to work with a set of OSRAM outdoor garden lights. easy to deal with, smart, etc...\n\nprobably the best hub out there, and worth the money."}
{"Author": "E.W.N.", "Date": "on November 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love this: works with my Alexa (Amazon Echo)", "Text": "Love this hub! Easy to install and configure via app. Adding new switches and lights, etc is easy with wizards, just takes a little experimenting to get everything right. Best part: works with my Alexa (Amazon Echo) so I can voice-control pretty much all that connects to this hub!"}
{"Author": "J. Brewer", "Date": "on November 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My Favorite Gadget of all Time", "Text": "My favorite purchase in a long time! I love this product. I use it for 2nd home to keep up with who's there and turn lights on automatically for security. I have leak detectors in bathrooms on 2nd floor, motion sensors for outside lights, wall switches and light bulbs on the system. All works perfectly. Super easy to pair and program."}
{"Author": "Cwazy Wabbit", "Date": "on November 22, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Okay product"}
{"Author": "Autobot Trader", "Date": "on November 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A solid experience so far. Much easier than HomeSeer Hometroller Zee with z-stick", "Text": "I have HomeSeer Zee as well and this one is easier to work with and more family friendly. Not as flexible but a lot less hassle if you just want it to work and don't need to do anything super fancy."}
{"Author": "Roberto Gonzales", "Date": "on November 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great purchase! Works great with Amazon Alexa", "Text": "Youll be playing with your devices remotely in no time, great purchase! Works great with Amazon Alexa!"}
{"Author": "Gale Barth", "Date": "on November 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love Love Love this hub", "Text": "Love Love Love this hub. Currently only use it for lighting, but will probably hook up other features later. Also paired it easily with my Amazon echo."}
{"Author": "MCC", "Date": "on November 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. Was everything I'd hoped.", "Text": "Easy to set up. I've connected two zwave light switches, two external zwave outlets, two zwave bulbs and 5 zigbee bulbs so far. I've set some of the lights to come on at sunset and go off at midnight. I can turn them on or off or even dim them from anywhere with my phone and so can my wife. I just added two echo dots and now can just say, \"Alexa turn on the porch lights\" or even \"Alexa turn on all the lights\". It's great! I continue to add to it as I can. A smart thermostat is in my future and sensors to turn on and off closet and utility room lights when someone enters and leaves. The sky is the limit and you can do it yourself at your own pace. I've had mine a little over a year."}
{"Author": "Ross", "Date": "on November 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy I went this route", "Text": "Very flexible with most if not all zwave devices. And very customizable programming especially if you use the SmartThings IDE development site. Very happy I went this route."}
{"Author": "cm", "Date": "on November 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Mistake", "Text": "Ugh.\n\nThe whole platform reeks of instability. The basics work just fine, but if you want to do anything deeper, get something else.\n\n- Documentation is often out of date\n- Stupid opaque errors\n- Kludgy and difficult to work with"}
{"Author": "Samuel Grund", "Date": "on November 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great, but limited IFTTT support", "Text": "Caution to anyone looking to this as a way to control Z-Wave thermostats via IFTTT - it does not work. Setup and the program are very nice, but please provide us better IFTTT support so we can control Z-Wave thermostats from Alexa and such"}
{"Author": "Ehh, Well", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easiest setup I've ever seen.", "Text": "My first \"smart hub\". Considering I've read next to nothing, I have all my lights under voice command through Alexa and Dots. Outstanding little device. The only other hub that I have interest in is the Vera, which is about double the price. I don't know what the Vera can do better than this hub, but nothing seems to beat the ST hub for compatibility right now. It seems to work with pretty much anything. Including my \"Harmony Hub\". It may not be your last hub but I can vouch for it being a good first."}
{"Author": "Michael Manning", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Avoid!", "Text": "Routines are unreliable. If you like to tinker with gadgets, this is for you. You will spend hours trying to figure it out. Otherwise avoid it."}
{"Author": "Riata B.", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great capabilities for the cost", "Text": "Can be a challenge to set up with some devices, but the system is extremely powerful for the cost."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Basic functionality is solid, but lacks standard \"scene\" controls", "Text": "Setup of the device was smooth and straightforward - previously reported issues with setup and reliability seem to have been addressed. I was able to pair GE and Cooper Aspire Z-wave dimmers, and setup control via Google Home and IFTTT.\n\nHowever, I was surprised to find that SmartThings has no built-in support for basic lighting \"scenes\" - where the dimming levels, colors, etc. of multiple lights are set to specific levels for e.g. cooking, home theater, etc. There are some clumsy workarounds available if you're willing to modify the code of \"SmartApps,\" but without native support for this functionality, this means you WON'T be able to control them from Google Home, Amazon Echo, and IFTTT.\n\nIf controlling multiple lights is one of your goals, I suggest looking elsewhere unless/until Samsung addresses this major feature gap"}
{"Author": "John", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love this device easy to setup not like link", "Text": "Love this device easy to setup not like link. I change out the router in my home could never get link back up. Link support suck, they can not figure it out. I discover that link us wireless and it not compatible with new wireless protocol. Got Samsung Smartthings never have a problem."}
{"Author": "Colin B.", "Date": "on November 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Save your money", "Text": "I wouldn't suggest this. The v2 of the hub has some HUGE problems, the primary one being that it's almost impossible to setup without calling support. A quick google of \"smartthings hub stuck at setup screen\" will reveal a lot of people with the same problem: the device just won't get setup. If by some miracle you DO manage to get the device claimed, which has happened to me twice, a simple reboot will render it unusable as the app will just constantly say that the hub is \"offline\".\n\nI really wanted this hub so that I could do more than just phillips hue (I have the bridge), but to tap into the existing hue stuff, you need the bridge, which isn't something they tell you. That combined with the PITA setup makes that a giant no-go..."}
{"Author": "Kelly Chen", "Date": "on November 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The glue that connects all of our smart devices together.", "Text": "I bought this device a while ago -- and I'll admit, I WAS *meh* at best with it. Now -- it is the hub of my in home automation.\n\nThe REAL power behind the device is the customization that is possible with it. If you are willing to roll up your sleeves and write (or look for) the device handlers/smart apps you need -- this thing will link all of your smart devices to both an external cloud (access from outside your home network) as well as the new automation devices coming out.\n\nI use SmartThings to connect all of my devices to Alexa. With some tinkering, I am now able to (using voice commands)\nAsk Alexa to:\n1. Turn on a bunch of disparate devices (that don't have native Alexa integration) -- Denon, Yamaha\n2. Control my Tivo (turn on guide, switch channels, pause/play, turn on captions etc)\n3. Connect to my home audio system (HTD) and even older systems (Squeezebox)\n\nI'm enjoying sitting on my couch and having Alexa turn everything, change channels, and then shut everything off. My spouse can finally watch TV again (and not worry about the huge variety of inputs)"}
{"Author": "Anthony Diaz", "Date": "on November 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "easy to install and compatible with many other products -- ...", "Text": "This product do what they say , is elegant , easy to install and compatible with many other products -- 1000% recommended"}
{"Author": "Architect", "Date": "on November 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Best investment in security for doors."}
{"Author": "Isaac", "Date": "on November 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Migrated from mi casa Verde Veralite 2", "Text": "Migrated from mi casa Verde Veralite 2\n\nThis thing could not been any better and smoother with its app and setup. For those coming from mi casa verde. Make sure to reset the z wave network otherwise you will have issues pairing. On my case I had to exclude one at a time in order to pair with new Samsung Hub. Once this was done it was easy.\n\nWishlist: Canany Support, Nest Support, Carrier Infinity Thermostat Suppport, Built In Wireless on the Hub."}
{"Author": "Eric Rynerson", "Date": "on November 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy Install, good App, great price.", "Text": "Easy Install, good App, great price. Was able to set up the hub, a Cree Connect Bulb, and water sensor in minutes."}
{"Author": "Karen Patricia Palmer", "Date": "on November 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "We actually love this product", "Text": "We actually love this product. We purchased it with a single multi-purpose sensor. We were constantly questioning whether we remembered to close the garage door and hoped this gizmo would solve that problem for us. It did. This little system was easy to get up and running and it works like a charm. Purchasing three more sensors, we will monitor motion on our back gate, front gate and washing machine(to alert me when the cycle is finished). We will see how it works with multiple sensors.\n\nThe only disappointment was the battery in the sensor did not last long. Maybe 6 weeks. We are trying a better quality battery. If that makes a positive difference and the multiple sensors are easy to get up and running, I wil amend this review to a 5."}
{"Author": "James S.", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This was horrible. Ended up buying a wink", "Text": "This was horrible. Ended up buying a wink."}
{"Author": "Brian", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fantastic hub", "Text": "So I've had philips Hue lighting for quite some time. I've had wall plugs that would turn off an on my lights with my security system. I had \"automation\". I thought it was cool. Others thought it was neat.\n\nI finally took the plunge into a smart hub after being a bit weary of them. I'm here to say, I'm glad I did.\nNow, the hub wasn't the only thing I purchased. I got some Door sensors, motion sensors, leviton smart switches, etc. Nearly my entire house now has a schedule. Nearly everything is done automatically. I can open my basement door and all the basement lights will turn on. Once I close the door, they'll turn off in a half hour. When my doorbell is rung, my Sonos speaker will announce \"somebody's At The Front Door\". Garage lighting will come on when the garage door is opened or senses motion. My outside lights come on at sunset and turn off at dawn. Cabinet lighting is controlled by schedules and times. It works GREAT with philips Hue. I can't say enough good things about this hub. I have over 50 individual items paired as of now and I will continue to grow my devices!"}
{"Author": "Henry C.", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it, easy to connect.", "Text": "Tried others and I had problems connecting, even after calling their customer support. Spending hours trying to connect. With the SamsungThings Hub, I was up and running in a matter of minutes and connected to my Amazon echo, tap and puck. Love it so much I've immediately order 3 more outlets. Oh and I wasn't given anything for my review."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Failed hub will cause you a world of pain!", "Text": "Our hub died after six months this last weekend. It was out for about six hours, with the dreaded red LED. Kudos to Samsung for having someone available to work through the issue, but in the end they also concluded it was dead and set up an RMA. I left the hub sitting there unplugged in disgust and amazingly once the rechargeable batteries completely died and I plugged it in that night it booted up and came back to life. So that was the good news. The bad news is that there is ZERO support from Samsung to migrate from the old failed device to the new replacement unit when it arrives. I would have to go through 90 devices, exclude them from the network and then add them back manually, the pain would not be over then as all of the various routines for motion sensors, timed lighting, thermostat controls would also have to be rebuilt. At a minimum we are talking a couple of days effort. I was stunned to discover this, for heaven's sake Samsung - get your act together on this, before more customers hubs fail."}
{"Author": "Dennilee A. Beck", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easily configured. The only thing that I found to ...", "Text": "Worked as advertised. Easily configured.\n\nThe only thing that I found to be a problem is that I own iSmartAlarm devices and I've not be able to add them to the SmartThings hub."}
{"Author": "Phil", "Date": "on November 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Think twice before upgrading from V1 to V2... Get ready for big pain.", "Text": "I owned the V1 Hub and got tired of the delays associated with that model. So I decided now was time to get the V2 model since has faster event handling.\n\nI got quite a shock when I got the unit and found no instructions on how to migrate easily from the V1 Hub to V2. I then searched google and found the procedure. The procedure is to delete everything from V1, get all of the devices off of the V1 Hub, remove all of the apps, remove the phone and it goes on and on. They even tell you that this procedure can take hours! My first thought is that Samsung must really hate smarthings and hate their customers.\n\nAfter going thru the whole procedure today, it is confirmed... They hate their customers.\n\nEven after going thru the procedure, one of the sensors didn't properly get excluded (although the V1 Hub said it did). I had to search around on the internet to find how to reset this device. Aweful"}
{"Author": "JoSuNW", "Date": "on November 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The realization of the concept is questionable", "Text": "I use the hub now about a half year.\n\nSurveillance:\nI have other surveillance systems running, which accesses the router direct and store their results in the cloud. The Samsung method/ approach is not reliable.\n\nHome Control:\nThe additional functions like switch on and off lights, or sound systems - the hub is not reliable. He does not always recognize the status of the devices.\nThe related app is not well developed. You can not modify your home concept on the computer. You have to use the app.\nMy home showed up, for what reason ever, twice. I (thought, I) deleted one of them - but lost the whole configuration with all devices and the hub. Problem: You can only setup your system if you remember the activation code for the hub. I didn't store him. And Samsung stores ...??? I don't know.\n\nGeneral:\nMaybe the concept is good. But then is it bad realized.\n\n--> The concept does not work for me!"}
{"Author": "David S.", "Date": "on November 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect for adding Harmony support to Google Home", "Text": "This thing is a bit overkill for what I need it to do but it does the one thing I bought it for. It allows you to control Harmony Hubs via Google Home. It works really well for this. I was a bit worried there would be a delay between giving Google Home commands and it relaying the info to the Harmony since it had to route through the Smarthings Hub, but it's fast and works perfectly. It's just as fast and easy to use as the built-in Harmony support for Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "Javo44", "Date": "on November 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I need a device to remotely create many user codes that are like hotel. Effective ddmmyyyhh", "Text": "Me thinks not.....( For vacation rental usage)\nWanted to use for VACATION RENTAL. This product was released to market WAY TOO SOON..... There is NO software app on this device to control door locks other than to OPEN\\LOCK.\nI need a device to remotely create many user codes that are like hotel. Effective ddmmyyyhh:mm - Expire ddmmyyyhh:mm.\nThis product IS NOT IT.....\n\nNOT SUITABLE FOR VACATION RENTAL MANAGEMENT OF HOME.\n\nCOuldnt discover the YRD210 initially, had to get on the phone with support and burn entire day only to determine they are (Purchased 2) are going back today.\n\nStill searching"}
{"Author": "skynet", "Date": "on November 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The center of my home automation system", "Text": "I love Samsung Smarthings hub. I have it hooked up to multiple GE z-wave wall dimmer switches and also a Logitech Harmony hub and an Amazon Echo dot for full (voice, manual or automated) control of the lights in my house and my entertainment equipment (TV, stereo and cable box)."}
{"Author": "Dale A. Panattoni", "Date": "on November 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product"}
{"Author": "michael brooks", "Date": "on November 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Create your smart home with smart things,", "Text": "Works well, had some issues with the hub, but the SmartThings support team is excellent. they tirelessly worked to sole my issues and when troubleshooting did not work sent me a replacement Hub by FedEx this hub rocks 99.9% reliability"}
{"Author": "phoenix", "Date": "on November 9, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nope. Returning", "Text": "They say it will do far more than it really will"}
{"Author": "Hu Sea", "Date": "on November 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This TERRIBLE product has forced me to write a review...", "Text": "I am a software developer. This is my 22nd year of being an enterprise solutions architect. I am quite savvy in all things technological.\nSo, imagine how excited I was when I purchased my home to have SmartThings automating the heck out of it. Fast forward to 2 months later...I am trying to see if I can sell it on Ebay.\n\nMy sensors are perpetually in a \"closed\" state -- even when they are open. I have sirens going off 60 seconds after the event that triggered them. I have doors being opened -- and the app (I've tried ios and android) not even recognizing it.\n\nI just got off the phone with Samsung support, no more than 20 minutes ago, and their support rep said this to me:\n\"...sometimes when we push out updates, we've found that you have to reset all of your sensors.\"\n\nNow, resetting a sensor involves one detaching it from the wall, removing the battery and repairing. I have over 20 sensors, and many are in locations that not easily accessible (i.e. 15 feet up).\nBeyond that, based on this rep's proclamation, the sensors can become inoperable (until the aforementioned reset) unbeknownst to me, and for no doing of my own -- simply because an update was pushed to the Hub.\n\nThis is terrible for the use that I THOUGHT it would work for: Home Security.\nImagine Samsung pushing out an update at 12am, and someone opening the garage door (which I've armed, mind you) at 1am. See where I'm going with this?\n\nI have nothing but terrible things to say about this product. It's lack of reliability elicited me to write this review. The money spent on the Hub and the sensors, coupled with the many hours that I've lost resetting and calling support -- one of the worst investments I've ever made.\n\nI urge you, turn away. Flee. Do not purchase this product.\n\n**************** UPDATE 11/15/2016 ****************\nEven though I spent $700 on the enter system, Samsung was nice enough to call me an offer me ~$100 back for returning two sirens that I purchased from them. I declined their 14% reimbursement offer. My review stands, my unhappiness remains and my disgust is steadfast."}
{"Author": "M. Ledesma", "Date": "on November 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Meh, not much use as a light bulb timer.", "Text": "After living with an Intermatic HA07 for a year, I purchased this device to gain more granular control of some zwave lights, and to prepare for future expansion of zwave devices at home. I set up the hub and programmed some lights to turn on at sundown. After a couple of days I realized this feature did not seem to work. I can control the lights manually (using the app), and also by specifying specific on/off times in the smart lighting automation programming portion thereof. But specifying sundown does nothing. Nothing shows up in the logs, no errors.\n\nOne has to wonder; if a basic feature such as controlling a light bulb on a schedule does not work as intended, why would anyone trust this product to control critical devices such as thermostats, door locks, etc.? I'm returning this for a refund."}
{"Author": "Dominique", "Date": "on November 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An Absolute MUST-BUY For SmartHomes", "Text": "I love SmartThings. I was around early on and first got the 1st generation hub along with several things. Back then, SmartThings worked however there was a lot of support issues. Eventually when Samsung bought them out, they had the capitol to fix all the woes the original company had. On of my favorite \"things\" (SeeWhatIDidThere) about SmartThings is that it has a lot of connectivity. IFTTT integration is huge and allows my hub and connected devices to be controlled by all kinds of 3rd party apps, or events.\n\nI highly suggest SmartThings over any other hub on the market. There is no monthly fee, once you buy it it is yours!"}
{"Author": "Amber Saxby", "Date": "on November 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Samsung Smart Things Hub arrived very quickly after I ordered it ...", "Text": "The Samsung Smart Things Hub arrived very quickly after I ordered it from Amazon. The packaging was done very nicely and the box wasn't damaged at all. I'm a pretty savvy DIY'er type of guy so, after all the reviews and YouTube videos, I immediately took it out of the box and knew what I was doing. Really straight forward connections, Power, Ethernet connection to my Router and I was good to go. Downloaded the App to my Iphone, set up an account with SmartThings (as usual), added the code for the HUB that came with it, and I was done. Since I only have a ZWave door lock, once I made that discoverable to the HUB I was set. The only reason that I'm not giving this a 5 star review is because I haven't seen the performance of the HUB over a period of note worthy time. But all in all its working well, and I'm very pleased with this purchase."}
{"Author": "Y. Wang", "Date": "on November 7, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Turning off lights has never been so hard...", "Text": "This thing is so unreliable. Since installing this together with some compatible bulbs and outlets, I found my life gets a lot more complicated and harder. You press a button on the phone and think you turned off the light? Check again, the light is still on! You have to press the button again and cross you fingers. Sometimes this needs to repeat up to three times.\n\nTurning off lights has never been so hard..."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 7, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not impressed.", "Text": "Looks great but had a hard time setting up devices with this. A lot of additional online research needed. Typical Samsung quality product. Looks good, works not so good."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The SmartThings hub works extremely well with every Z-wave and/or ...", "Text": "The SmartThings hub works extremely well with every Z-wave and/or Zigbee device I have purchased. I use it to open & close my garage. Lock and unlock doors and automatically turn on lights. I also use it to automatically lock all my doors and close my garage every night at 11pm."}
{"Author": "family5", "Date": "on November 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it", "Text": "Very dependable hub and reliable."}
{"Author": "SC", "Date": "on November 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works exactly as it should and easy to use!", "Text": "I needed new door locks, so I bought Schlage Connect locks and the SmartThings hub. The Schlage lock was highly rated for security and I liked the idea of being able to lock and unlock the doors remotely with my iPhone. I read a lot of reviews, from both professional reviewers and homeowners who purchased various hubs, and none of the hubs sounded perfect, but SmartThings came out ahead of the others, so I chose this. I was prepared for a difficult user experience, but have had no problems at all. Setup was simple, the app is easy and user friendly, and the locks were recognized right away. I then added lightbulbs and an outlet and everything is working exactly as it should. I wish I could control things with Siri, but I knew prior to buying that only HomeKit allows for that, and there were downsides to that system for me. I've been very happy with SmartThings and recommend it. I've been using it for about 2 months."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love that this hub has a battery backup", "Text": "I purchased this hub to replace my old hub. It's going to be a pain reconnecting everything to the new hub, but it'll be worth it when I'm done. I love that this hub has a battery backup, so my alarm stays active in an outage. If you are into SmartThings, you should definitely get a new hub if you haven't already. It adds a lot of functionality."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "this have a lot aplications"}
{"Author": "Sandeep", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "love the simplicity of the iphone app", "Text": "love the simplicity of the iphone app. great product with very less lag to refresh the current state. all the automatic functions perform very well. may be this product had bad firmware long time back to get bad reviews. but now things seem to be sorted out. i would suggest this to anyone.\n\nthe only downside is that they do not have enough accessories with it. example is multi sensor which has less battery life if i need to use it as a door/window sensor. but since it is zwave/zigbee controlled you can get other brand products which have better battery life."}
{"Author": "Mike Chombeau", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Warning. This requires a hardwired Ethernet connection.", "Text": "Warning. This requires a hardwired Ethernet connection. You need to have extra ports on your router to use this. I had to buy a network switch to connect this."}
{"Author": "Tom R.", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works great"}
{"Author": "Donald", "Date": "on October 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "very good product"}
{"Author": "Zeego", "Date": "on October 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Absolute garbage.", "Text": "This product rarely works and the app UI design is simply the worst I have used in my life. Another typical Samsung product."}
{"Author": "Matt", "Date": "on October 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung ruined Smarthings", "Text": "Samsung ruined Smarthings. They have recently migrated everyone over from their Smarthings login to use Samsung. I've only had issues since. Their app no longer works consistently. Every couple days it gets into a state where it never logs in, and hangs. Each of these times is when I have monitoring alarms going off that I can now not silence"}
{"Author": "AB", "Date": "on October 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Slow start, but after some research, easy to use and set up.", "Text": "Labor free install. I downloaded the app and connected this to my network. I had the Amazon Echo Dot connected within a few button presses. It is important to not to stack this on top of other electronics. I signed up for the SmartThings account and had no trouble with getting it connected. This hub is in my basement in a computer closet with my other electronics. I have it plugged directly into a switch, but I did experiment with plugging it into a hardwired CAT6 connection that runs to a keystone patch panel before connecting to the switch and it also functioned as I would have expected. It took a bit of research to figure out how to connect the first Z-Wave light switch to the hub. I found out that you start your \"things\" search with your phone or tablet and simply turn the switch on and then off after it's been wired in and it connected right up. I've found that the paper documentation for the products is pretty vague, and had to turn to the internet for better instructions, so the first IOT installation was a bit painful. After educating myself, I find that the installation is simple and straight forward so far, but I've only connected 1 item to this hub. If you want to connect other tablets or phones to the hub, sign each user up for their own account and share your account with them. That way, your notifications and logs are correct and presence shows correctly. This will help when setting up automation. The app could use a bit more work for ease of use."}
{"Author": "mnmike", "Date": "on October 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A useful gadget. Powerful options. Opens up endless ways to spend more money on gadgets.", "Text": "I bought this initially to monitor two sets of GoControl door and motion sensors. Since then I've connected this to my Honeywell thermostat, two connected light bulbs, and a garage door opener. If you have the time to tweak everything you can make this do a lot of great stuff.\n\nI recently tied this in with IFTTT so that I can control the lights and garage from my Pebble smartwatch."}
{"Author": "Jody Albritton", "Date": "on October 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best Smart Home Hub on the market.", "Text": "I have been a customer since 2012, having started with hub v1. In full disclosure I have been an employee of SmartThings since 2015. I am first and foremost still an enthusiast. Today I can honestly say that there is not another home automation platform that even comes close to the feature set offeered by hub v2 and the SmartThings platform. I now have over one hundred connected devices in my home connected to the platform. Everything from lights to robot vacuum cleaners. If you are a tinkerer there is a very active community that has built solutions for anything you can think of."}
{"Author": "ID", "Date": "on October 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works great so far. So much flexibility on what can be achieved. Great user community always there to help"}
{"Author": "Michael T. Moriarty", "Date": "on October 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Too large a list of items it will NOT work with.", "Text": "works great, except for older components."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on October 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wow", "Text": "Excellent and easy to set up works with a lotta stuff"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I would never recommend the Smartthings Hub without firing the engineers who came up with this piece of crap and starting over.", "Text": "I am very comfortable working with most things technology related and willing to give them a chance, but the SmartThings hub has to be the worst designed piece of garbage I have ever seen. I would be amazed if any of the good reviews are anything other than paid advertising or from people who have any experience working with these devices. Without a complete redesign of the software to be a stand alone environment I would never recommend the SmartThings Hub."}
{"Author": "MIT Guy", "Date": "on October 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Zero Functionality !", "Text": "Absolute HORROR !\n\nLet me preface and state that i am an Avionic design engineer with over 30 years of circuit design and programming experience.\n\nI could not get this hub to recognize a single Z wave device. Waste of my time and total frustration.\n\nThings should not be so complicated or bad."}
{"Author": "skippy", "Date": "on October 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with the door and light switch", "Text": "It is working great so the product it self does what they say it will do. Then I read some reports and makes me wonder about the security of the actual concept of z-wave. So I'm using it and doing more research."}
{"Author": "Bryan", "Date": "on October 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Best thing I have purchased this year!!"}
{"Author": "Richard A. Snyder", "Date": "on October 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great For Use With Amazon Echo and Other Z Wave Devices", "Text": "Works very well with the Amazon Echo. We can use voice commands to turn on and off lights. Using a tablet or cell phone you can also provide commands directly."}
{"Author": "J.H.", "Date": "on October 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Let me say though that I LOVE this product", "Text": "I have been using SmartThings for 6 months now so its high time for a review! I recall a bit of apprehension when I ordered this because the reviews were 3.4 stars on average with some apparently well considered criticism. Let me say though that I LOVE this product! I use my SmartThings hub primarily for lighting control and so far have 8 GE Z-Wave switches (also highly recommended), 2 Samsung leak detectors and a Schlage Camelot Deadbolt all controlled via SmartThings. I encountered a minor issue during setup and had to call Samsung support but they answered quickly and solved the problem within minutes. Since then, I have had no need of support. I use the Android App and it works well for my purposes. The service itself has been amazingly reliable and the switches work almost instantly. I have also had no issues adding new Things to my Z-Wave network. Its truly rare to find a product that outperforms expectation - this is definitely one of those products!!\n\nA word of advice though: I was in a rush to order the product and did not pay close attention to the details - I just knew that it was around $75. Well I mistakenly ordered it from a seller named 'Amaz247' and paid $100. I guess its a practice called Arbitrage where a seller is actually a middleman who just pockets a (large) portion of the profit and never actually has possession of the product. Avoid these sellers if possible. In the case of SmartThings, you can buy it directly from Amazon."}
{"Author": "william", "Date": "on October 17, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you are looking for a set it and forget it system.. you can forget about this hub...", "Text": "Even with the price break this device is not worth it.. They should pay you for the hours of frustration you will have trying to make this work. Even the simple things like Philips Hue bulbs are currently broken. Call support and they tell you they are working on it. Do yourself a favor and either wait or look at a competitors product. If you are a coder/hacker/digital tinkerer then you may be happy with the hours this hub will give you to try and figure out why it won't work as advertised... You have been warned."}
{"Author": "Amber Rose Trombley", "Date": "on October 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to set up and works seamlessly."}
{"Author": "muralidhar mulpuri", "Date": "on October 16, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very difficult to rest smart things, both technically and manually", "Text": "its not stable. Very difficult to rest smart things, both technically and manually."}
{"Author": "JASON C.", "Date": "on October 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Have had no problems with the hub it's self, ...", "Text": "Have had no problems with the hub it's self, but plenty of problems with smartthings cloud, I which they would run more thing locally."}
{"Author": "C J", "Date": "on October 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does most everything needed.", "Text": "Very easy to hook up and takes care of everything needed in the SmartThings app."}
{"Author": "Strunk", "Date": "on October 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works okay, but I am still tinkering can comparing ...", "Text": "Works okay, but I am still tinkering can comparing it to my Wink. The Samsung advertises a very versatile product, but it is not very \"Non-tech Savvy\" friendly."}
{"Author": "mobile_traveler", "Date": "on October 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works the way I had hoped it would and the Echo integration lets my whole family use it!", "Text": "Arrived in perfect condition, very nice packaging, works great. Setting up the hardware is easy, the app is clunky and difficult to navigate. I have been experimenting with home automation for many years so I didn't have much trouble configuring the hub but I imagine someone with less experience could easily be confused by the user interface of the app. Setting it up to work with Amazon Echo was a bit tedious but after a couple of times starting over I got it working properly. The unit has performed reliably and I like the text message I get when it goes offline for any reason (it helped me fix an intermittent connection problem with my cable modem). There is some delay in command execution that seems to be variable (I suspect part of this may be due to how busy the cloud server is) so I tried upgrading to a faster android device which seems to have helped a lot.\nOverall everything works the way I had hoped it would, and the Echo integration has turned it into something my whole family is able to use."}
{"Author": "Julie Hall", "Date": "on October 9, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home automation will eventually get there.", "Text": "I'm not 100% sold on this thing yet, though some of the frustration is with equipment as well. Home automation isn't quite there yet. They do update frequently, but in my experience that's caused more problems.\n\nBut when everything works... It's pretty awesome."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good, the interface on the app took some getting ...", "Text": "So far so good, the interface on the app took some getting used too but other than that the ST hub is working perfectly. Would highly recommend."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best Tech Support in the World for the Samsung Smart Things Hub", "Text": "I purchased a Samsung Smart Things Hub, 2nd Generation and easily connected 10 Cree bulbs throughout my house. I then linked these to the Amazon Echo and it was an easy connection. All worked well until a power outage from a hurricane that hit Florida. I lost all connections and could not sync the bulbs with the Hub. I immediately went to the very accessible chat for the Samsung Smart Things Hub. I immediately was connected and the employee (Stephanie) immediately started to help me. It was a challenge since it was possible that the bulbs were fried by the sudden power surge. She tried everything and took the support to another level. Eric M. the Technical Support Manager contacted me by phone (vow) a while later and through his problem solving skills got to the root to the problem of why my bulbs no longer connected. He spent over an hour on the phone talking me through the process in a thoughtful and calm way--even with a good sense of humor. At the end I have all my bulbs connected. I really can't thank Eric M, (Technical Support Manager) enough for his help, expertise, and perseverance. I highly recommend the Samsung SmartThings Hub because it flawlessly works with the Amazon Echo and with such wonderful support coming from Eric M and his Team you can't go wrong buying one and connecting all your smart devices."}
{"Author": "D. Mccoy", "Date": "on October 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The unit has worked great for the front door lock but takes a time ...", "Text": "The unit has worked great for the front door lock but takes a time to recognize the back lock 30 foot away.."}
{"Author": "P. Miller", "Date": "on October 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Safe and Sound", "Text": "I'm impressed. Compatible with ZigBee and Z-Wave.\nService seems very reliable on local network WiFi and Cellular connections.\n\nI'm still working to get more automation, but setting up simple security with affordable Go-Control sensors took only minutes.\nI get a notification and text any time one of my sensors is triggered.\n\nIf you are doing lighting as well I recommend Z-Wave instead of ZigBee.\nWhy? Longer range (lower frequency) and Z-Wave bulbs act as Z-Wave repeaters to extend the range of this unit!\nGo Control LED lamp is a bit more money than the GE, but the Go Control is a Z Wave repeater and the other is not."}
{"Author": "MK", "Date": "on October 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing!! You can setup automatic routines", "Text": "Amazing!! Amazing!! Amazing!! Did I say it was amazing lol? it really is. I got it mainly for a security system. But I use it for all the smart features. Turn on the bathroom light at night when I walk by, close the garage when I forget, and have the living room light come on before I get home at 8pm everyday. I love that you can setup routines."}
{"Author": "PublicName", "Date": "on October 6, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Check compatibility prior to purchase...", "Text": "Returned after a very brief and disappointing couple of hours.\nDoes not work with any of the \"smart\" things I already own: Caseta lights, Arlo Q cameras, Carrier Infinity Thermostat..."}
{"Author": "Jennifer C. Dentry", "Date": "on October 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Pretty easy to set up. Lots of (maybe too many?) options to control and automate stuff."}
{"Author": "Chase the Dog", "Date": "on October 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy set up", "Text": "I cannot believe how easy this is to use and set up. Coverage amazing in larger home 7000sqft. I've paired Cree and ge bulbs without issue. Much easier to program on and off than intermatic timers. I also use IFTT with Ring and Arlo to automatically turn on lights upon detection at night."}
{"Author": "wiliam", "Date": "on October 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you lose this paper you will be in great trouble. I don't know what to do right ...", "Text": "Came with an activation code on a card inside box. I can't activate the hub so I throw out the box as I do with all my devices.\nActually we find setup guides and firmware upgrades on support websites\nWhen I was setting up my SmartThings hub I was surprised with the requirement of activation code and it is on a small paper that you need to store in a safe place forever. If you lose this paper you will be in great trouble.\nI don't know what to do right now!"}
{"Author": "Yesef Medina", "Date": "on October 5, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "better interface than Wink buuuuuut wink support EVERYTHING", "Text": "I want an of the box \"plug and play\" feel an it's just not that as NEST and MyQ are not supported...better interface than Wink buuuuuut wink support EVERYTHING. THere are also a few, and I mean a few, features that Wink just does better."}
{"Author": "Robert Bouillon", "Date": "on October 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible product. Don't let the Samsung name tempt you... get something else", "Text": "UPDATE 5/5/2018\nI've had the device almost two years now, and it's seriously awful.\n\nOne update they pushed to the device caused it to respond incredibly slow. So while I was mashing \"on/off\" repeatedly and turning the brightness up and down, trying to get the thing to respond, little did I know I was actually queuing up commands that would then execute extremely slowly over the course of the next 30 minutes. So for the next 30 minutes, I watched as my bedroom light turned on and off and changed in brightness until the command queue finally cleared.\n\nI just updated to a new phone and tried to connect it to the hub. When I logged in, it didn't show the hub, so I tried to re-add it, and it said that the hub was already registered to another account. I tried to contact customer support, and first tried the \"live chat\" option, which ended up being a seriously stupid chat-bot that opened with \"I see you are interested in not-supported. Would you like some help with that?\". I then tried to e-mail customer support, and their home-automation products are not included in any of the REQUIRED \"product-type\" fields for obtaining support. I had to get connected to TV support to get a real person to tell me there's a specific number for \"smart things\" -\n520-441-3272. So I called the number and found out that the hub is associated with a different account. Smart Things actually has TWO mobile applications right now - one's a \"classic\" app. The new app logged me into my SAMSUNG account. So I have to download the CLASSIC app and can't use the newer app, and thus can't use any of the newer features. I also can't manage my current account until the \"migration\" happens, so anything I need to do, like reset my password, I have to call support. I seriously have wasted so much time just trying to log in, just to find out I need to use a different (older) version of the application. Everything about this application's design is terrible.\n\nORIGINAL REVIEW\n------------------------\nI bought this because I generally love Samsung products. There's a lot of home automation stuff out there, and most of it fairly terrible or expensive (or both), so I was pretty excited and optimistic about this product. I could not have been more wrong.\n\nI have one light hooked up. Just one. And I have a light switch. When I press the light switch, I expect the light to turn on. When I click it again, I expect the light to turn off. Simple enough, right? Well when I press the switch, there's a 6-12 second delay between when I press the switch and when the light turns on / off. It's terribly annoying and I haven't found a way to change it. At first I thought it might be a communication problem between the hub and the devices, but I can activate / deactivate each device individually without issue, it's only when I use their \"Smart Lighting\" SmartApp (by Samsung) to trigger the light by the switch that it fails. I can turn the light on and off instantly with my phone, but the switch on the wall? 10 second delay. Dandy.\n\nSeriously this thing can't control a light switch correctly -_-\n\nCreating a user account was painful as well. I first tried to do it online: why use my smartphone when I have a full-sized keyboard at my PC? Well I couldn't because it refused to accept that I clicked the \"captcha - I am not a robot\" button no matter how many times I tried. I then signed up on my phone without issue.\n\nI'm a software engineer, so I'm like \"okay well I'll just log in and make my own API to make the light switch work\" - that's one of the reasons I bought this device. So I logged in under the SAME ACCOUNT I used to connect with my phone, and none of my devices are listed there and there are no instructions. All I see is \"You have no devices.\" Not content with this, I fumble around the site a bit and find a way to access my devices (It's a terrible UI - I had to essentially click around until something worked under location, and then re-login with the SAME credentials for some reason and then my devices appeared). So I see my listed devices, but the lighting app I installed to control the lighting isn't there. Well that's great... how am I supposed to update it? I double-checked and the smart app is still showing up in the android app. What kind of black magic is this?\n\nSo I log into the main site (sso.smartthings.com) thinking I can mess around with it there and it doesn't even take my credentials (nor does shop.smartthings.com). The main SmartThings login keeps telling me my password is bad - the same one I used to log into the android app AND the API site. I've tried to log into the main site periodically since I bought the device to no avail.\n\nI don't know how this product could get any worse. Everything about how this works is overly complicated and STILL doesn't work properly. I can't wait to get rid of it... if only I could return it...."}
{"Author": "A. Hall", "Date": "on October 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "would recommend", "Text": "Does all that I ask, would recommend"}
{"Author": "JC Strout", "Date": "on October 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Tops VeraEdge!", "Text": "Switched to SmartThings from a VeraEdge, absolutely zero regrets. I would recommend this to everyone!"}
{"Author": "M Miller", "Date": "on October 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This home automation hub is awesome. Easy to install and offers incredible flexibility and ...", "Text": "This home automation hub is awesome. Easy to install and offers incredible flexibility and ability to use Amazon Echo to automate your home."}
{"Author": "JC", "Date": "on October 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to setup and countless devices can be added. Glad I chose this one"}
{"Author": "I Love Reading Romances", "Date": "on October 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is way easy, even for a non-tech type person!", "Text": "I have to admit that I was very intimidated by the whole concept of home automation, and it was only at the urging of a friend that I took a deep breath and ordered the Hub and a few pieces to get started... and I'm SO glad that I did!!!! This is fabulous!! I had the Hub up and running in no time flat. Way easy to use (even for me). I got Philips Hue Bridge and light bulbs, and control the whole thing with the SmartThings app on my phone. I'm still waiting on other Things to get set up with it, like an outlet and motion detector and thermostat, but honestly, once you get started with one or two things you see how easy it is to do more and more!! I'm busily creating \"routines\" for everything! LOL. I\"m REALLY happy with this, and can't wait for the Echo Dot to be released to use with this!"}
{"Author": "Bill in Arizona", "Date": "on October 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easiest automation system to set up, use, enjoy, expand, brag to your Nerd friends about.", "Text": "I have been using Vera, or MicasaVerde, to automate clients homes. I even have used it in my own home. I decided to purchase the Sumsung SmartThings after some in depth research. After my first install, I immediately purchased another for my own home.\n\nThe first install was for a clients home that was up and running on Vera. The home is a beautiful luxury Airbnb rental owed by sophisticated client. When my client advised they never used the Vera System. I felt like someone had gut punched me. After all, I had spent days setting it up, working through macro scenes and settings. Often on the phone with Vera tech support in Romania. When I asked why? The answer was one I had heard before, it's just too confusing , the app is too cluttered. Reasearch lead me to Samsung SmartThings. I was able to convert 34 nodes to work with the SmartThings Hub in about 2 hours. No Coding, No Complicated formulas. Just a simple set up procedure . I was even able to do everything on my IPad. I could quickly pair the door locks, the three thermostats, the doorbell, exterior lighting control, even the pool heater. The SmartThings Hub works across many platforms. It even has easy to use options for cameras.\n\nThe most important feature for this system, (based on my years of home improvement) is ease of use. This system is a snap to understand. Walks you through the automation process step by step. Even will direct you from the app to online manuals for individual products! I expect the system will get even better as Samsumg Engineering and Product Development innovates and updates the product. It works with such a wide range of accessories. I just finished installing at my home too. I highly recommend to first time Automators, to Advanced IT Nerds like me. I will have some Vera units to drop off at the goodwill."}
{"Author": "David Tr", "Date": "on September 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "All the features in the world mean nothing when it's reliability on working has proven time and again completely unreliable.", "Text": "I've been using smartthings since the kickstarter days. The ability to log into the developer panel is great, and allows you to either create or install custom apps that others have made made it one of the most flexible and customizable.\n\nThe entire Home Automation industry has been, and continues to be one of the most difficult and frustrating things to setup, get configured, and then support and maintain. It's not Smartthing fault, and they have a lot to consider and design around.\n\nThe V1 hub when it was initially designed put all the smarts and logic of the smart home in the cloud where they could continually improve, and update the code that makes your smart home run. Great when you're a kickstarter and small, but just considering that each devices can send 50-200 status updates a day, and when you start getting 20+ devices, and 100,000+ customers the network load for such a system is extremely complex to implement and maintain. Samsung bought out the kickstarter company, and eventually they released a V2 hub (this device).\n\nFirst, migration from old to new didn't exist (not sure if it does now). So basically for all your individual devices you had to figure out how to manually uninstall each device, which required manually removing each device from every smartapp it was hooked to. Delete all your setup. Then manually join each device to the new hub, and then re-program all your smartapps, and logic. REDICULOUS.\n\nSecond, they put more powerful hardware and more storage into the V2 hub, and it looked like they were going to put more of the processing locally into the hub to make things more reliable. Never happened. There's been 9 documented outages of the server infrastructure became non-responsive for hours (and one time it was down for 9 days) due to load. Still to this day they are still having problems. The straw broke the camels back today, when my alarm sirens are not configured ANYWHERE in my configuration to do anything other than flash (because of the unreliability) started having the siren go off. Login to the app to turn them off? Unresponsive. Luckily I was home and could pull the power and batteries out to silence them.\n\nI can't forsee anywhere in the future where they are going to reengineer their system to remove this utter reliance on 1) web connectivity and 2) their servers being 100% reliable. Why do I say that? Because for the long term business model to make this product profitable they need to have a recurring fee - and that recurring fee will one day be their alarm system and camera integration/cloud recording. So their corporate structure relies on them not moving the smarthome logic into the hub from the cloud.\n\nGoodbye SmartThings."}
{"Author": "bill", "Date": "on September 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Smart Hub", "Text": "After researching many hubs, this one has the most potential and connects with many smart devices. Works great with Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "PHmaddnes", "Date": "on September 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's time to JUMP IN.", "Text": "I have been on the fence about this technology for awhile, first I received an Amazon Echo for my birthday and that got me going, next a simple Wemo switch, now I had the bug, Made an impulse buy at local box store of the Smartthings Hub and started figuring out what I can do. I just added multiple Smart Switches, integration to the SmartThings Hub and Echo was seamless and straight forward. I have now created rooms, automations, geofencing, scenarios etc.\nHere are some things I have done:\nWhen a family member pulls into the driveway the driveway lights, front door lights and interior hallway lights come on.(soon I will have front door unlock as they walk up).\nWhen I tell Alexa (Amazon Echo) \"Alexa, turn on Emergency Lights\" all my exterior flood lights come on.\n\nIf you are on the fence, JUMP IN. the technology, setup and use are understandable to the average person, and so far works flawlessly.\nI plan on adding more switched, locks, cameras, thermostats etc. The possibilities are endless."}
{"Author": "Brian Schouten", "Date": "on September 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Better than most with the current state of home automation", "Text": "The debate will continue as to what the best solution is for home automation but Smarthings (for all it's shortcomings) has struck a balance between cost, usability, features and product support. I'm still shopping for an affordable solution that will replace this thing but I have not found one yet. Lots of hours spent have been spent messing with these things over the years. I have 50 z-wave devices of all different types, smart thermostat, Karotz, echo, other stuff for reference.\n\nRating some capacities of Smarthings vs other systems -\n\nProduct Support - You can find ways to make these devices work easier than the other systems. Sometimes that means a custom device handler, but the community has doe its homework and will help.\n\nEase of Use - Really the best feature of this system. The app is pretty good. I'm more interested in automating and not using my phone. I would appreciate a native app that worked on tablets or even a nice wall mounted interface product from Samsung.\n\nCustom Process Ability - This is OK but has some issues with local processing and threaded race conditions. Don't think that you can persist variable data in the cloud to be used .05 seconds later! The community helps with this but it is definitely not ironed out. Most issues are with processes that occur over time. Anything immediate is fairly well supported. You have to get out of the old \"synchronous\" style of thinking.\n\nLatency - Even a little latency kills me with motion lights. I'm half way through the hall before it turns on and this is too slow. I don't think this latency is acceptable because it is cloud based or weakly locally processed (and I have nice Internet and network gear).\n\nWhat I've tried -\n\nVera edge - ok, but buggy. Scripts run locally and in a big recurring LUA loop that ends up blowing up for intense processes. The web interface was not always telling you the truth as well. Not a bad tinkering system because things work.\n\nHome Assistant - This is the open source version of Smarthings! Not a bad interface, but the need for lots of configuring and debugging all my z-wave inclusions has steered me clear of this. Also the threaded processing is not what I'm looking for. This is the one to watch if you are looking for a new system. I think in 6 months this one will be worthwhile trying again with the short release cycle.\n\nOpenHAB - less user friendly and configuration heavy. Home Assistant is the better of the 2 Open systems I tried.\n\nAnyway, Smarthings has its shortcomings and will make you angry - but the other systems will too. So is the current state of the home automation hub selection."}
{"Author": "Jeong Cheol Park", "Date": "on September 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Good"}
{"Author": "Tyler", "Date": "on September 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great for having a central control of Hue lights", "Text": "Works great for having a central control of Hue lights, Wemo switches and other sensors. Allows me to see room temperature as well as control the AC unit hooked to a Wemo switch from one app. Haven't gone any further with sensors other than the Zooz 4 in 1 but have had no issues with reliability/uptime of the unit itself. Figuring out the difference devices and how to add the code for the things like Zooz is a bit difficult but can be done."}
{"Author": "scatterbrn", "Date": "on September 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My first smart hub. I was torn between this and Wink", "Text": "My first smart hub. I was torn between this and Wink, but wink support and features doesn't seem as strong plus I got a great deal on Prime Day, so Smarttthings it was. I wish it could be a bit more complex in some of the routines without having to program but so far it does what I need it to do. I like that it has batteries and can run things locally if need be. The whole 'everything in the cloud' sounds great but sucks if you lose internet. combine this with an amazon echo to introduce voice control and you can really impress your friends and neighbors."}
{"Author": "Jay Carsman", "Date": "on September 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Z wave hub", "Text": "Works fine except for problems with Echo interface"}
{"Author": "Michael Rolle", "Date": "on September 24, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "While I wish there was better web site configuration (not everything is convenient to config ...", "Text": "Edit: down from 4 stars to 3. Remember this, no internet, no home automation. This hub does not work without an internet connection. While I wish there was better web site configuration (not everything is convenient to config on a phone or tablet) this unit seems to work pretty well, with the exception of considerable lag when using the app with only about 15 devices connected. I believe the cause to be that it must hit the internet before completely \"coming alive\". It does seem to draw about 6 watts steadily, which I wish was a little lower."}
{"Author": "J. M.", "Date": "on September 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "These work well"}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on September 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Home", "Text": "This thing is awesome, works very efficiently and is very quick to respond to requests. Connecting to multiple sources like zwave and others it doesn't have any issues. Responses from the app work great, while in the house it instant. Remotely it also happens prettt quick depending on the cellular signal. Great product."}
{"Author": "Bonkers Bill", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Sigh. Limited compatibility - this supports several \"lightswitch\" remotes, but not the ones I have.", "Text": "Sigh. Not compatible with several things I already own. Should have done my homework better.\n\nI like the idea of this better than the Wink - The Wink sends commands to through the internet to the \"cloud\" so responses are sometimes delayed or dropped. In theory the SmartThings makes all the decisions locally. Unfortunately it is not compatible with the Lutron buttons I have several of.\n\nAs others have said, the \"app\" isn't especially intuitive or pretty compared to some others, but it is functional.\n\nI'll keep this thing around and if I wind up with controls that are compatible or they upgrade the software to fix that I'll revise my review.\n\n[Update - Sept 24 2016] I got a polite \"We're sorry you are unhappy, here is a list of compatible devices\" email from SmartThings customer support. Unfortunately, they don't offer have any compatible remote controls that look and act like a regular lightswitch - I really want something that mounts in by the door in the place where a light switch normally lives that operates the lights - for the 75 year old mother-in-law, the cleaners, guests, etc. I've give up on trying to teach all these people to \"look for the umptey-zizzle sitting on the end of the whatchamacallit and press the top left button. No, the other one.\" If someday there is a \"3rd Generation\" that offers a control that works as smoothly as a (non-automated) Leviton Maestro while controlling smart lamps, I'll try all this again."}
{"Author": "honest.review", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "We often have intermittent power outages and it triggers on ...", "Text": "We often have intermittent power outages and it triggers on every devices connected to it when such event occurs. It is definitely not reliable source for automating your devices until they improve such issues unless don't mind racking up on the electricity bill as well as going through frustrations of turning off all connected devices manually every time when it occurs."}
{"Author": "EngineeringEverythingTech", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starter", "Text": "The product is working flawlessly. I purchased a couple light bulbs that weren't supported by Smartthing and (Boom!!!) it worked right out the box. Seems to be better than having the Aeon USB connected to a Raspberry Pi. NOTE:I will be updating this experience for the next couple weeks."}
{"Author": "Rickey L. Shaw", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "WORKS GREAT!", "Text": "EXACTLY WHAT I ORDERED. WORKS GREAT!"}
{"Author": "Stephen Dolan", "Date": "on September 20, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Decent for Beginner Home Automation", "Text": "Updating things like the names of devices, or adding/removing Hue bulbs was a bit of a challenge. It's also sometimes a bit slow/unreliable. Overall, decent as a starter kit for home automation. I'll be moving my whole setup to Home Assistant ASAP"}
{"Author": "R. Brazeau", "Date": "on September 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent product", "Text": "Working great. I would recommend this product. I called support and they were very helpful. Best support that I have worked with in a long time. A little extra time to setup."}
{"Author": "Dave", "Date": "on September 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings Customer Service second to none", "Text": "I bought the hub + 1 switch for starters, I intend to get door/window sensors going forward. I went with SmartThings because it integrates with Amazon Echo which allows voice control, but I guess they were still working out the kinks with Echo until recently. Voice control was working intermittently at first, and it was not easy to pinpoint the problem. I credit the tireless customer service of SmartThings, particularly Trevor R. who seemed to take it as a personal mission to help me get the system up and running. We exchanged so many email I lost count. I can now control a lamp in my living room room by speaking to Echo. Thank you SmartThings and Trevor. If not for you I'm sure I would have given up and returned the Hub to AMZN."}
{"Author": "David H.", "Date": "on September 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A good companion to Amazon Echo", "Text": "So far, so good. I like that it links with Amazon Echo (Alexa) but wish it had a more zwave device compatibility. Being able to use my cell phone as a geofence is pretty cool and has worked well so far - all desired devices are automatically turned OFF when I leave the house. Next step is to integrate this capability into my zwave security devices (motion sensors, door sensors, sounders) - as soon as they are supported."}
{"Author": "RKrider", "Date": "on September 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works with all kinds of devices."}
{"Author": "KT in Orlando", "Date": "on September 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "Works Great - slowly but surly turning my entire house to a 'smart home'"}
{"Author": "GoldenEye", "Date": "on September 17, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Didn't seem ready for primetime", "Text": "Wanted it to work as advertised, but seemed like it wasn't ready for prime time."}
{"Author": "Brad D Brown", "Date": "on September 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's like Lord of the Rings, 1 HUB to rule them all!", "Text": "I am very satisfied with my Samsung hub. This hub works with a lot of different manufacturers for it's things/ accessories. This Hub is easy to use and has an Android app and also and IOS app. The app allows you to control and monitor your devices that are hooked to the hub.\n\nI have been able to use multiple other manufacturers with this hub such as GE light bulbs, Cree light bulbs, Lowe's Iris accessories as well as the Samsung SmartThings brand.\nI did have a small problem with Philips Hue however to my understanding a contract is being worked on as we speak so SmartThings will be able to control the Hue Lights without having to purchase the Hue hub.\nI love that this product is truly an open system because even though Samsung SmartThings might not support a particular manufacturer there are workarounds 2 getting those items to work as long as there is zigbee or Z-Wave or Wi-Fi devices. The contact customer service links are answered by the Developers for smart things and they are very helpful and knowledgeable and allow for you to send screenshots and accept screenshots and I have been nothing but please with their eagerness to help and emails being answered back the next day.\n\nThe only thing I can say that I wish was a little better was the app 4 SmartThings. It isn't bad and it is easy to navigate through however it does take a couple days to remember all the different steps you have to do to make rules for your devices.\nAn example would be how I wanted to make a rule that my motion detector increase my porch light to 100% and decrease back down to 40% when the sensor doesn't detect movement. It was easy to make the light come on and go off completely when sensing motion however to keep the light on at a dinner level was complicated and required me to do some extra steps. Those steps and rules are laid out in the app but it's just not as straightforward as doing the basics cenarios of turn on the light when I come near or when the door opens turn on the light or sound the alarm when the window opens exedra.\n\nAll in all I am very happy with my hub from SmartThings and I also like how the app does have a place in it called Marketplace inside the SmartThings app that will tell you the different devices that it supports and show you a picture of those devices plus the model number plus even have a link to where to buy those devices so you can really make the most of your experience. I am convinced that this is the best head out there because I don't see anything else doing anything that this one doesn't already do or isn't capable of being programmed to do and best of all there is no monthly subscription and I don't have to pay anybody if I choose not to. There is a security company that will monitor your cameras and things through SmartThings if you choose to go that way however you don't it's purely optional."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on September 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best Smart Hub. Period.", "Text": "I'm gonna keep this brief. The SmartThings hub is changing my life! I've been slowly adding switches and door locks each month to my house. I love this thing! The app is great and support forums are very helpful. Thinking about getting a smart hub? Get this! It handles everything you throw at it!\n\nSome people are intimidated by the cost of making their house smart. I started with SmartThings and a zwave switch to turn my porch lights on/off at sunrise/sunset. It takes time! Unless you've got money laying around... :-)"}
{"Author": "Alex P.", "Date": "on September 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good multi-protocol hub for home automation", "Text": "This is my first hub for home automation. This works great. It took over for a dead Wemo bridge that was just such a hassle to use. Now we have all sorts of protocols in the house and no longer bound to just Wemo. I'm going to eventually swap out the Wemo lights as they do not work as well as ZWave especially over any distance.\n\nIt is easy to use and even my wife uses the mobile app. When the wife uses it you know it is better than average."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on September 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Remarkable product and customer service."}
{"Author": "Amazon Don", "Date": "on September 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "BEST Smart Home Hub of them ALL !", "Text": "Works with multiple Z-Wave and ZigBee products as well as with Amazon Echo.\n\nEasy to use and configure.... This one is quickly becoming the \"de facto\" \"Best Smart Home Hub\".....\n\nI HIGHLY RECOMMEND it.."}
{"Author": "BizzeMom", "Date": "on September 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Reliable but could use extended range", "Text": "Although completely happy with the way the SmartThings hub is working with the front door deadbolt system, the range of its connection prevents me from giving 5 stars. Our router is upstairs in the game room and the front door is, well, downstairs. The hub has to sit out in the middle of the room to be able to connect with the smart lock on the front door. It looks like a booster of some kind would help but it's just not in the budget at this time."}
{"Author": "Po345", "Date": "on September 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does the job. App could improve.", "Text": "The app needs some work in terms of ease of creating actions. They should follow IFTT example."}
{"Author": "Thomas Zwahlen", "Date": "on September 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Setup was as easy as they make it sound."}
{"Author": "John R. Schubnel", "Date": "on September 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love the interface"}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on September 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't waste your money", "Text": "Junk! The range os so small, and the software so cumbersome and buggy, this could never be used as a reliable home-automation system, much less an alarm system. Don't waste your money."}
{"Author": "Ganglefang", "Date": "on September 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub not ready for prime time.", "Text": "It didn't work out of the box. It would not find new things/devices/whatever. Contacted their customer service about a month ago--still no response. I will try to return it but have misplaced the box after waiting so long for a customer service reply. There is very little documentation. The Android app is mostly trying to sell you home monitoring for a monthly charge. It is not clear if it will work from a PC--perhaps with an android emulator. (For the record, yes it is plugged in, connected to an active router, shows it being online, and the device it is trying to discover is within 2 feet.) On the plus side, ZWave seems to be the way to go. I have been using Insteon and X10 for many years, and their equipment has a half life of about a year before needing replacement. ZWave has many more options and suppliers, and works in my house using a GE remote without repeaters. (Insteon requires repeaters on each floor, and those don't even last a year.)"}
{"Author": "Howy", "Date": "on September 9, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings has had long delays between sending and executing commands to turn on/off lights/outlets.", "Text": "Samsung SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation, was great for the first month. It made it possible and simple to configure multiple Aeon minimotes to control the same light and outlets and a 1-second or less delay from pressing a button to seeing it's effect.\n\nHowever, now there are very long delays between triggering and executing the desired switch/outlet on/off.\n\nWhen ST fails to signal the switch or outlet and you press it again and nothing happens and then pressing other buttons to see if anything is working...it \"catches up\" if/when it does finally carry out the command and the effect of each of the button presses that have been sent seem to eventually come through...minutes later.\n\nPerhaps someone has figured out if this has to do with Samsung's SmartThings Hub internet/account/website accessibility and availability?\n\nUnfortunately, SmartThings has become unreliable lately."}
{"Author": "Hal", "Date": "on September 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "So much better than IRIS."}
{"Author": "James V.", "Date": "on September 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love this thing!!", "Text": "I have my whole house setup through this. I couldn't imagine not having a Smartthings hub after living with it for a while. I have my Amazon Echo working with it. I can walk in to my home and turn on any light by voice, change the temperature by voice. Turn on my whole house fan, tell if a door is open or a window. I even have a sensor on my kids door that kicks on my hall way light so I don't have to have it on all the time. If you can think about it, this can pretty much do it."}
{"Author": "Anthony P. Brown", "Date": "on September 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Must have for the home automation enthusiast", "Text": "Like everyone I am really into Home Automation right now. When I saw the SmartThings Hub I knew I wanted to integrate it into my systems. Very simply to set up and works with numerous other products. I use it with the SmartThings Water Sensor and Multi switch. Great product"}
{"Author": "Michael Schmidt", "Date": "on September 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "then it would probably be an amazing addition to our home", "Text": "I can't really rate this product fully because I didn't really use it. I bought it thinking it did more than it does. If we didn't have the Amazon Echo and the Hue Bridge for our lights, then it would probably be an amazing addition to our home. However, we have everything in these two product to control our apartment. Alexa can control our lights, outlets, and turn our TV on and off. Now, if we had a home and needed CO2 and flood sensors, that would be a nice addition. The setup was extremely easy. It just didn't give us any additional controls. So, nothing negative about this product. We just pretty much tell Alexa everything we need and she does it. The SmartThings Hub needs your smartphone to control it."}
{"Author": "Brian", "Date": "on September 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you want a smart house, this is the first step.", "Text": "Absolutely love the hub. Have had issues with the mobile presence detectors, but I think the problem is with the phone not the Hub. Couldn't be happier with it."}
{"Author": "Amazon Prime customer", "Date": "on September 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings is very unpredictable. I got two SmartThings Leak ...", "Text": "SmartThings is very unpredictable. I got two SmartThings Leak sensors and one of them takes forever to connect and the other one connect quickly. The First Alert Smoke and Carbon Monoxide Alarm doesn\u2019t connect no matter what I do. Once I removed the leak sensors as part of working with SmartThings customer support, now they are not able to connect at all. Some times the Hub shows as Inactive using IOS App but Active via SmartThings website. Hue lights show as Inactive but I know for the fact they are active and I can use the Hue App to turn on and off. Just weird behavior and buggy. I've factory reset the hub three times now. Just painful.\n\nAlso, if you are using ADT Pulse and Zwave devices such as GE Light switches, they will not work with SmartThings evenif you Join the ADT Pulse Zwave network. Do not connect SmartThings as a secondary Zwave controller -- that was the cause of my First Alert not connecting forcing me to factory reset the hub per SmartThings customer service. Total mess.\n\nI am thinking twice now about keeping SmartThings or returning it back to manufacturer\u2026 Waste of time for me, Amazon and everyone involved."}
{"Author": "Eddie", "Date": "on September 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works with Alexa", "Text": "Worked great in the beginning. Does periodically drop offline from time to time. Some of the smart apps I use just stop working. Don't know what happened."}
{"Author": "frogwild", "Date": "on September 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings was a Smart Purchase for me.", "Text": "I purchased this item to work with my Amazon Echo to include more items into my Home Automation project. I haven't been disappointed. Although I've only had this item for a week or so, I have been easily able to attach light bulbs from Cree and & GE, wall switches from GE, a Honeywell Lyric (2nd gen), my UP device, smartphone and with the help of the SmartThings community my Simply Safe alarm system. I now have voice (via Echo) and remote (via smart phone) control over almost all the lights in my home as well as 2 ceiling fans and the thermostat. It's nice to be able to turn off the home office light & fan after you get into bed and remember that you left them on.\n\nThe app is a little clunky but once you figure it out, you can add \"things\" with relative ease and the incorporation of smart apps and IFTTT allows for even more control. Lights on at dusk, ceiling fan off when the temperature gets below 70 and more.\n\nSo far I'm happy with the SmartThings hub and it's ability to integrate with so many items. It was a smart buy."}
{"Author": "Alan Bui", "Date": "on September 5, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Review of hub, several \"things\", and demo video", "Text": " After 10 months of use, and SmartThings/Samsung expanding upon their development of the product, I feel like I can give it a proper review. When we initially got it there was major inconsistencies in pairing \"things\", as well as instability in keeping those \"things\" paired. After several updates, we're finally seeing improved stability in our devices/things, and really appreciate Samsung's commitment to improving their product. Below is a pros and cons of the current system:\n\nPros:\n* Works seamlessly with Amazon Alexa.\n* More and more compatible devices being added slowly.\n* Improvements in stability with updates.\n* Faster initial pairing of \"things\" (use to take 1-30 min., now less than 2 minutes per pairing)\n* SmartApps allow for a variety of customization, but not seamlessly (e.g. using motion sensors to trigger lights requires downloading a SmartApp vs. programming it from the \"things\" or routines menu in the app)\n* IFTTT compatible\n\nCons:\n* Some major brands not added as compatible devices (e.g. Nest, Arlo, Dropcam, etc.)\n* Samsung SmartCam has no functionality in Smarthings App (only live view)\n* Some \"things\" get unpaired due to distance, requiring re-connecting (3rd floor -> 1st floor), slightly less often now (every few months)\n* Pairing requires \"things\" to be close to hub for faster \"adding/connecting\", or for connecting at all. (Tip: use a nearby lamp that's next to the hub to swap in and out bulbs to connect)\n* SmartThings App not user friendly for advanced programming (e.g. SmartApps functionality)\n\n\"Things\" Reviews:\n* GE Link 65W Equivalent Soft White BR30 (3-star)- Least stable of all bulbs tested/used, but the cheapest. Initially, it took 20-30+mins. to pair each bulb, now it only takes 2-3 minutes. The pairing is lost over time, if the distance is too far (2 stories away). Re-pairing, or resetting is required every few months, but again, updates have improved this. The small ring of leds in the bulb are more annoying to look at since there is no opaque covering.\n* Sylvania Ultra 11-Watt BR30 (5-star)- Better flood light than the GE link in all aspects: faster pairing (instant), opaque shell for better look and even lighting, more stable at longer distances, and faster/smoother dimming.\n* Cree Connected 60W Equivalent Soft White (5-star)- Very stable, fast pairing, good at long distance, smooth dimming and nice warm lighting. Only con is that it could be brighter.\n* SmartCam HD Pro 1080p Full HD (3-star)- Fast pairing, and very stable. Pros: 2 way audio, good night vision, sd card storage, can turn off status light. Cons: SmartThings app is live view only (requires SmartCam app for programming), even with customizable areas to ignore, still to sensitive (e.g. still senses dog or lights), no optional colors.\n* Zen Thermostat (4-star)- Fast pairing and very stable. Pros: Integrated into SmartThings App, sleek look, compatible with Alexa. Cons: Slight delay from change on App, to change on thermostat/AC, App degrees is in decimals, while thermostat degrees isn't (e.g. 75.6 vs 75 degrees)\n* Samsung SmartThings Motion Sensor (4-star)- Good sensor, but loses pairing every now and then (e.g. 1 sensory every few months). Easy reconnection. Stability improving with updates.\n* Aeon Labs Door/Window Sensor (4-star)- same quality as Samsung motion sensor above. Only difference is size/look.\n* Aeon Labs Siren, Gen 5 (4-star) - stable, and fast pairing. Only con is that some of the alarm choices aren't loud. It also needs to be plugged into an outlet, and in the open (not behind an object) for best volume and sound quality.\n* Aeon Labs Minimote (5-star) - great steady and customizable remote. Allows each button to be configured with \"things/devices\", modes, routines, or notfications. Option to press or hold each button, so 8 total programmable buttons.\nZ-Wave Garage Door Tilt Sensor (4-star) - pretty stable, fast pairing. Lost connection once in 6 months. Tape that comes with the sensor does not stick well to aluminum garage doors; use 3M instead.\n\nPlease view video for demo of \"things\" with the App and Alexa.\n\nOverall, the updates have vastly improved the quality of the smart home system. With Samsung slowly adding new compatible devices, and the system able to maintain more consistent connections with it's things, we are happy with our purchase and recommend it to all tech savvy people. For those who just want basic functions such as turning a light on and off/dimming, the system might be a pass. In my opinion, the SmartThings system is best suited for people who 1) Use Amazon Alexa, 2) Use IFTTT, 3) Can figure out SmartApps for advanced customizing of \"things\".\n\nPlease see video demo for ideas on how we use our \"things\"."}
{"Author": "Jason S.", "Date": "on September 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it, but be must be a tinkerer to get everything up and running."}
{"Author": "Cohoman", "Date": "on September 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub for making your home smarter!", "Text": "I've been using this Smart Devices Hub in my house for the last few weeks and it's been working great. I use it to control the following items:\n\n- Several WeMo Light Bulbs\n- Two WeMo light switches\n- Honeywell Lyric 2.0 Thermostat\n- Schlage Z-Wave Door Lock\n\nSo far, it's been working flawlessly, telling me which devices are on or off, which code was used to unlock the front door, and if my thermostat is cooling or heating (and the inside/outside temps). Through \"Geofencing\" the Smartthings app can also tell me who is present in the house (by checking our smartphones) so I can tell when my wife and son arrive home after work and school. I have a few IFTTT recipes running to which control a few of my devices. Pretty cool stuff."}
{"Author": "Shark928", "Date": "on September 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great technology", "Text": "This has worked very well and has been super reliable - my biggest concern. I love the app and the remote control ability. Will likely continue to build out more components for our vacation rental."}
{"Author": "Scotty D", "Date": "on September 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Limited IP Camera Support & ZERO Support for Third Party Integrations", "Text": "[2017-11-28] Reached out to support for help debugging and issue with my hub and this is the response I received, \"The Stringify app is a 3rd party integration on the SmartThings platform. We don't officially support 3rd party integrations, and in the event they fail you must contact the support channel for the 3rd party app.\"\n\n[2016-10-06 Update] It appears that wired Sonos devices are now working. Upped my rating to three stars until I can dig in deeper into this product.\n\nSmartThings claims to be an \"open platform,\" but IP cameras such as the Foscam FI8910W are not supported. Also, Sonos support is limited to their wireless speakers. Neither the Sonos Connect or Connect:AMP can be controlled."}
{"Author": "naveen pandrangi", "Date": "on September 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works as promised"}
{"Author": "CJS", "Date": "on September 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Way better than wink", "Text": "Just wish they would get this thing working with MyQ garage door opener. Way better than wink though"}
{"Author": "rs8451", "Date": "on September 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best community support", "Text": "Not perfect could have more devices supported by default but is easily remedied by the community that writes custom device code."}
{"Author": "dustinhunt78", "Date": "on August 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Never got it to connect to a single device", "Text": "As the headline says, I never got it to connect to a single z-wave device. Apparently, you have to be wired to your router and get the hub within 15 feet of the device you want to pair, which is impossible to do with a device such as a light switch. I'll be returning it and going with a Vera Plus."}
{"Author": "old mojo", "Date": "on August 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worth the money", "Text": "works great. I got rid of Lowes Iris..it's a joke now. Anyway, just about everything I had with Iris, this works with, including now the Hue lights. Very easy to pair up and manage"}
{"Author": "Marc", "Date": "on August 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product", "Text": "Sometimes gets disconnected, i want to say because the signal of my Wifi is low. Even tho is a great product."}
{"Author": "Raymond Gallagher", "Date": "on August 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the Hub you're looking for!!", "Text": "So I spent a long long time looking for which hub to purchase. After a lot of research and ton of reviews I went with the SmartThings hub two and I haven't looked back since. You can just stop you're search here, this is the zwave/zigbee/dlink/whatever hub you're looking for! It has paired with all of my things very easily! GE switches, cree LED bulbs, g2g thermostat, GoGarage door opener, door locks...just everything. Right now I have about 30 Things connected to it and at least 12 Routines and just a bunch of SmartApps. If you are confused at what \"Things\" are or \"Routines\" or \"Smartapps\" than its ok. I was too when I was first buying a ST, but i got the hang of it in no time, its very intuitive. I had a little problem with the door locks at first but with a little persistence I figured that our in no time. What I love about ST is that you don't have to be too techy to use it. Its very easy to add new Things and add new smart app to your Things. Its very easy to make new routines and to activate them. We have three phones connected to our ST hub and all of them are used as presence sensors which I think is supper cool. The presence sensing works most of the time, but sometimes I find myself and the garage door that hasn't opened yet or some to a dark house. It usually catches up in no time and i've never had it mis a routine completely, just a little delayed sometimes when using the present sensor on the phone. Don't get me wrong, it is a little glitchy sometimes, but most of the time it works great! I absolutely love how easy it is to lick switches with Amazon Alexa and ST. Just download the ST skill in alexa and in no time she knows all your switches and lights. For your locks and stuff there are some work arounds to get alexa to recognize them, but as a default alexa is not allowed to recognize those things. But ya, once you got everything set up on smarthings and named, but pair it with alexa and thats it. I just say \"Alexa, turn on/off (name) lights\" and she says \"ok\" and it just works! I haven't touched a switch in a while because I've ether been using alexa or things are just automated now. Using the ST to keep track of your home while you are gone it great as will. You can open the door for someone who is pet sitting, you can control the temp in the house, you can take a look at whats going on in the house or your front door, or wherever you might have a camera.\nAll in all getting a ST hub was the best choice! There is zero to very little delay and things have never just catastrophically failed on me. Some patience is required sometimes and some frustration might happen sometimes, but in all its been an amazing experience so far and I'm very happy with my ST hub. I've heard from other with a wink or others hubs and they are ether not doing as much with there hub or just can't do as much with their hub. Living in Florida we get random blackouts and the hub has survived well through all of it and never lost any setting! Im continuously growing my smart home and Im glad ST is at the center of it!"}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on August 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy.", "Text": "Don't buy this. It's not ready for prime time. I have two lights attached to it and it can't even reliability turn them on and off. I had a 20 year old x10 unit that was more reliable. Also it can't even turn the lights on if it's not connected to the Internet. Why it can't do that is beyond me.iit has some cool features like using wit Alexa but the overall system is very , very unreliable. An I have GB fiber so it's not my internet ,"}
{"Author": "Nino V.", "Date": "on August 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One of the better DIY home automation systems out there.", "Text": "This hub has been great. I've matched it with GE switches and will soon be adding devices for home security. Easy to use and good for multiple users. One drawback is that you cannot monitor two hubs at the same time. For most people this might not be an issue, but it was for me since I have two locations with the hub"}
{"Author": "Chase Michelotti", "Date": "on August 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You're so smart", "Text": "This unit makes my house so much more functional while at home and even while I am not. From my ac, front patio, night lights, etc. I have control whenever and where ever. Very easy setup and functionality!"}
{"Author": "iknoweverything", "Date": "on August 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worked like a charm and is cheaper", "Text": "Could not get it to recognize any devices. Returned it and bought a Wink. Worked like a charm and is cheaper..."}
{"Author": "Jack Mccarthy", "Date": "on August 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy set up and great apps to go with it. Very happy I made the purchase."}
{"Author": "fuel98rider", "Date": "on August 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Super easy to use and set-up", "Text": "I love this! It was incredibly easy to set up, both the initial setup with the interface, and then to add the devices. I currently have two switches (GE), three bulbs (GE), and two thermostats all running off this. Configuring the devices was easy, and the Smartthings app was able to quickly find them, identify them correctly, and set up the parameters for each device. Up time has been tremendous, even with the summer thunderstorms we have had this year. I look forward to many more devices being added to the z-wave ecosystem in the future."}
{"Author": "Ben", "Date": "on August 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Constant Buzzing but Nice User Layout", "Text": "Bought this as a replacement for the Wink Hub. The user interface of the hub is amazing as devices are organized by room instead of by type (Wink). However, adding devices to the hub has been problematic for me as some items couldn't be detected (even if they were supported by SmartThings). Also, the reason for the low rating is the constant buzzing sound emitting from my hub which was the reason for the return."}
{"Author": "david allen", "Date": "on August 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "For smart home enthusiasts or even the beginner that only needs a few features, this is the product for you.", "Text": "I absolutely love this thing. I've wanted to get my home into the current century with technology. This thing is amazing. I've linked it up to my front door so when someone unlocks it, I know who and when they entered. I've had to program this one because the door only says it was opened or closed. It does let me know it was code 1 or 2 or etc... So I programmed this to recognize that and actually tell me who it is. Each family member has a unique code that only they know. Perfect! I've connected it to my phones so I know when they come in my neighborhood and I turn on lights when its dark automatically. I turn on lights in the morning in the kitchen as I get ready for work and then they turn off when I leave. I will be getting door sensors and alarms as well. My brother had a water sensor that went off when his fish tank overflowed. It has a lever that fills up the tank as the water dissipates. He was hours away from the house. The alert went to his phone and he drove home as fast as he could. There was still damage to be fixed, but the whole house wasn't completely under water. Amazing community and company product support for this. I also bought a Philips hue hub because I liked the options for the lighting. I connected it to my SmartThings so I only have to control one device. Amazing.\n\nThe only bad thing is I have xfinity products that I was hoping this would connect to. Maybe there will be a firmware upgrade in the near future that will allow this. But for now I just plan to replace my xfinity stuff with products that work with this.\n\nPros: Great for making your home smart. Fully configurable to your own needs. Great support when you need it. Works with several connection types which gives you hundreds of products to use and customize your way.\n\nCons: Doesn't work with my xfinity products."}
{"Author": "SixtyFour", "Date": "on August 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good!", "Text": "I've been keeping tabs on home automation since dabbling in X10 many years ago and its seems that both my interest in having some of this functionality and my belief that the market has matured enough have suddenly crossed paths and reached critical mass! I started with just the hub, one switch and an Echo from Prime Day. It all went in easy and worked as expected. One month later I now have about 6 switches including one 3-way switch and all are working fine with or without Alexa. A water sensor, a deadbolt and more lighting are next along with more rules/scenes/smart apps. I believe the reason some people are having issues is because their mesh network device distances are too far.apart so I've been growing my network out from where the hub is located and am adding simple plug in outlets as a 'booster' to ensure full and consistent coverage to the actual device I want to use. We'll see if this holds true as my network grows and becomes more complicated. btw: my devices so far are all Linear/GoControl except for the water sensor (not yet added) which is labeled for Iris zwave system from big blue box store. That device is apparently identical to one or two others available here on Amazon under other names but which cost 20% more. I'll certainly update this review if SmartThings is anything less than stellar but for now... I'm loving it!"}
{"Author": "Jonathan Allred", "Date": "on August 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Impressive and MUCH better than Nexia", "Text": "I was concerned on ordering this due to some reviews, but I have had zero issues. I came off of Nexia, which I paid 9.99/mo. The only thing I have noticed that is different is that the item you are pairing, has to be much closer to the hub than it did with Nexia. Once paired, the distance isn't an issue."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on August 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product. No issues whatsoever. Would love if it could run if Internet is out though. Mabe in time."}
{"Author": "Chris A.", "Date": "on August 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "Has made my home a SmartHome. Love it!"}
{"Author": "AT-Rex", "Date": "on August 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The SmartThings Gen2 Hub has connected to almost everything I've thrown at it.", "Text": "Initially, when I purchased the SmartThings Gen2 Hub in March 2016, I had problems getting it configured. The code to setup the unit would not work in the app until I reached out to support and they \"fixed\" a glitch of some sort. Once up and running, and learning how to properly connect the \"things\", all started coming together. Most of the issues I encountered were because of the SmartThings app, rather than functionality of the Hub. With support for WiFi, I was able to use the two Belkin WeMo outlets I've owned for years with the system. The Zigbee support worked with the two Arrival Sensors I purchased at the same time as the Hub, and the Z-Wave support for the GE12724 Smart Dimmer Switch I also purchased. I have purchased several other \"things\", and all have connected and worked with the Hub except one Cree Smart Bulb (which I believe the bulb was at issue). With help from the SmartThings community, I was even able to connect my WiFi Foscam cameras. Overall, I'm pleased with the SmartThings system, and other than some needed changes to the app, the automation and control capabilities are top notch. I also have two Amazon Echo Dots which integrate perfectly with SmartThings, and an Echo or Tap would be one of the first accessories I'd recommend with SmartThings."}
{"Author": "Joe R", "Date": "on August 21, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Great product with excellent help desk."}
{"Author": "Jeff Peterson", "Date": "on August 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great"}
{"Author": "Sahab Jee", "Date": "on August 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings is a very unreliable hub, tremendous features, ...", "Text": "Smartthings is a very unreliable hub, tremendous features, more than anybody else, but the software and app are having a lot of issues. check forums before buying."}
{"Author": "Gary Dawson", "Date": "on August 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The motion detector's work great.", "Text": "It works as expected. I'm adding new things one at a time. The motion detector's work great."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on August 17, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It works great with the phone app", "Text": "It works great with the phone app. However I bought this to work with the Amazon Echo and it works for a while and then Echo can't find the device anymore. Have to re-configure constantly to get it to work with Echo. After a while I just gave up and just use the phone app to operate my lights."}
{"Author": "JR", "Date": "on August 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cool gizmo for automating your home.", "Text": "I installed this unit about 60 days ago. It is an easy install and you really should have at least a dozen items ready for remote control. I used Z-Wave GE light and fan switches for some simple on/off and dimming solutions. There is a learning curve, don't overextend your patience. Or, overextend the WAR (Wife Approval Rating) factor. We now can control the AC (Honeywell), lights, and have Alexa doing certain things. GE Switches are easy to link, Cree bulbs not-so intuitive.\n\nPros\nThis is fun.\nLights (and other things) can be set to timers, events, or whatever you can dream up with new products available on a regular basis.\n\nCons\nNo web interface. All scripting has to be done via phone or ipad\nEasy but not intuitive. Complex scenes are just that -- complex.\nExperiment carefully least you decrease the WAR factor and have to sleep on the couch.\n\nWould I recommend it to a friend? On a limited basis.\n\nPrice point -- Excellent for what it can do."}
{"Author": "Nick M. Atalla", "Date": "on August 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung software sucks", "Text": "Although this product works as advertised, the software sucks. Nothing intuitive about the software. Samsung needs to fix otherwise I'm considering moving away from there products"}
{"Author": "J.E.", "Date": "on August 13, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not for the layman, not for the poor - no reason to sugarcoat it.", "Text": "For DIY home automation (or the pursuit of), this is pretty good. However this is not a turn key solution, nor does the cost stop at this $99 hub.\n\nIf you are looking to get the most out of this thing, you must have some technical know-how and you must be willing to fork over some coin. If you lack either, there's a decent chance you'll be disappointment/overwhelmed/frustrated.\n\n- You need to know how to use the developer API site (Google \"smartthings api\"). This will help to fine-tune devices.\n- Being able to write custom SmartApps opens many doors in the way of adding functionality which isn't offered out-of-the box. They are written in Groovy using the web-based IDE on the developer API site.\n- In regards to actually 'automating' home actions...you have to be able to create rules and routines which make logical sense - sometimes \"if-this-then-that\" just doesn't cut it.\n\nZ-Wave and ZigBee, likely the two most popular protocols supported by SmartThings, both operate using a mesh networking topology. What this means is that if your hub is point A, and you want to use a device at point B, you may need to install (this includes buying) one or more devices between point A and point B in order for the connection to be stable. I see many negative reviews about light switches or other devices not reporting an accurate state - Well, you probably need to throw a repeater somewhere between the switch and your hub.\n\nDaisy-chaining devices like this gets pricey, but is absolutely necessary in order to build up a stable mesh network. The cheapest device/repeaters usually cost around $30. Hardwired devices like light switches, dimmers, and wall outlets are closer to $40 or $50.\n\nIf you lack the coin, honestly, adjust your priorities and put your money to better use.\nIf you lack the technical expertise, save yourself many frustrations and contact a home automation provider. They offer professional installation services, using equipment they have been professionally trained to configure, and will happily do so for many, many of your pretty pennies.\n\nEdit: Works great with Amazon Echo for added voice control."}
{"Author": "Brad King", "Date": "on August 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Had Vera Lite this is very different and much better overall. have 60 connected devices and 2 amazon ...", "Text": "Had Vera Lite this is very different and much better overall. have 60 connected devices and 2 amazon echo's. Very different in the way it functions but much more reliable that Vera."}
{"Author": "Derek W. Beck", "Date": "on August 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "unfairly rated poorly by people that had other systems", "Text": "I'd prefer to give this 4.5 if half stars were allowed on this review system. But as halves are not, I rounded up.\n\nSeems to me like most of the complaints are coming from people that have used other systems. I agree some hardward connectivity can be clunky, but once you have it setup, and if you are not doing anything terribly elaborate, the system works great. I've had it for a year now. We love it overall. Software clunkiness aside, at least they constantly push updates to the app and the device. As for complaints they wasted all this month on zwave devices: the controller here, if it doesn't work for you, use another. The devices, such as zwave light switches, can work with any zwave controller, so all of those zwave switches are not a waste. I'd buy it again. I've never used another system (i.e. Vera)."}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on August 11, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not as good as Vera - nowhere near as much functionality", "Text": "Not as good as Vera - nowhere near as much functionality. Only got it because Vera is too slow with Amazon Echo Dot support"}
{"Author": "Ray", "Date": "on August 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it. Allows you to take different proprietary devices ...", "Text": "Love it. Allows you to take different proprietary devices and connect them all. Price is great, set up easy and when I did have questions/issues support was good too."}
{"Author": "Mike Goddard", "Date": "on August 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Product does not perform well, unable to turn off ...", "Text": "Product does not perform well, unable to turn off the sensor when at home. I see from numerous posts that this is a two year old problem."}
{"Author": "Link4me2", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not a Revolv hub, but it works.", "Text": "I purchased this unit to operate a Z-Wave garage opener as well as having multiple radio technologies for other smart-home products. Setup was very easy and has worked without issue for me. However, I wish there were more devices, other than just a few security related products, that have been developed for smart home systems that can connect with this system.\n\nNest seems to be holding everyone up on their with their acquisition of Revolv, which killed a great product line and seems to have stunted development all around."}
{"Author": "rah", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "works great, I wish it had a longer range"}
{"Author": "Barkis", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost Ready for Prime Time", "Text": "This is a love/hate relationship: I own two of these hubs (one in a primary residence, the other in a remote second home) and use them primarily to control lighting and monitor the indoor environment. It could do so much more (like perform as a security/alarm system), but is simply not-quite-ready for prime time.\n\nAs a hobby or platform for part-time development, it is wonderful: the open API allows one to write apps and device type handlers to adapt the system to just about any Z-Wave (or Zigbee) device of your choosing. A vibrant and active on-line community of developers and users supplements the SmartThings support operation in welcoming and encouraging new users. The failure of the product is the unpredictable and unreliable behavior of the platform at this time, perhaps due to cloud scaling issues, undependable databases, or code that was rushed to market before it was completely wrung out. [All common problems in today's software arena. I've been in the field for years and, believe me, there are lots of products our there in the same condition.]\n\nThere is *huge* promise for this product and I wait patiently as it gradually gets better. Let's just hope Samsung doesn't pull the plug on this wonderful start-up idea..."}
{"Author": "CraigNC", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good. Installed the Hub - hardwired to my router ...", "Text": "So far so good. Installed the Hub - hardwired to my router in a central room in my home. Easily connected four Cree (Zigbee) bulbs, and a Schlage z-wave lock - the lock is about 30 feet away, and there are 2 walls and a stair case between it and the hub. No problems. None of the devices were within 10 feet when I connected them to the Hub. They ranged from 15 to 30 feet away with at least one wall between them.\n\nI selected this over the Wink hub because: 1.) It is not wifi - I have so many devices already connected to my wifi router I didn't want to risk issues with connectivity, especially regarding the door lock. 2.) Apparently Wink commands have to make a round trip from the Hub to their servers and back again, and that slows the execution of commands - SmartThings does not. 3.) Wink's parent company has gone bankrupt whereas SmartThings was recently purchased by Samsung - The uncertainty of long term support was definitely a factor in my decision.\n\nUpdate 8/23. Still going strong. One quirk: when adding new \"things\", sometimes nothing is found, however when I return to the list of things, it's there."}
{"Author": "Mooret1979", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth it", "Text": "This hub did not connect with the devices and caused me a lot of problems. Was not reliable. Switched to WINK."}
{"Author": "Lauren Tack", "Date": "on August 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Better with the Echo.", "Text": "I like being able to control my lights with the Echo. Slowly turning my home into a smart home and SmartThings is making it super easy."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on August 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "changing my review 5 stars", "Text": "This thing works great. Took an update right away, they should tell you to reboot after. Once rebooted it is now rock solid. Would recommend to a friend."}
{"Author": "Phil Ehrlich", "Date": "on August 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Did some Google searches and found this to be a common issue with smart things and z wave lights", "Text": "Slick app but the controller was not reliable for me. It would say that lights were on when they were off and vice versa. Did some Google searches and found this to be a common issue with smart things and z wave lights. Switched to Vera and haven't had any problems."}
{"Author": "Dr. Guich", "Date": "on August 2, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Otherwise set up was easy. The app is a bit difficult to navigate ...", "Text": "So far this is working well, the distance is a bit disappointing so working on that, it cant seem to reach by entry way door that is about 30-40ft away. Otherwise set up was easy. The app is a bit difficult to navigate but once you get the hang of it not all that bad. It is compatible with a lot of devices which is why I am very happy with it."}
{"Author": "Cromagnum Man", "Date": "on August 2, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Otherwise I am mostly happy with my decision to buy", "Text": "Still don't understand why it doesn't work with Nest while several other zwave hubs do, i.e. Wink. Otherwise I am mostly happy with my decision to buy. I might end up changing my Nest to an Ecobee anyway."}
{"Author": "Arthur O. Harris", "Date": "on August 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A work in progress but gets the job done", "Text": "Purchased to pair with a remote valve shutoff unit and water sensor.\nPairing with remote \"things\" was not difficult, but no as straight forward as it could have been.\nOverall, with time and patient this hub paired with remote shutoff unit and water sensor, sends a notification when water is sensed and closes the cold water valve to hot water tank in the presence water around the tank.\nAll pieces operate and function as expected.\n\nNot overly impressed with IOS or Android apps, but they are functionally useful when used with the PC Web interface.\n\nSpent most of my time trying to identify the proper device handler, other than that very straight forward."}
{"Author": "Jordan", "Date": "on August 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great so far", "Text": "I was apprehensive about buying this hub after reading the mixed reviews but I'm glad I listened to the positive ones and ordered it. So far I primarily use it as a home monitoring device and I have had zero errors with it.\n\nBoth zwave and zigbee products have synced and work without any trouble at all. Notifications through the app are literally instant and I've had no false alarms. I have also started to add on outlets and light switches with ease and even outlets in my garage that are far away from the hub are working perfectly. This system has truly given my family extra peace of mind with the added benefit of being able to control other features in my home. I highly recommend the hub to anyone looking to add DIY home monitoring to their house."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on August 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup and install iOS app", "Text": "No complaints here. Easy to setup and install iOS app. Can now lock/unlock doors. Now I just need to get some SmartThings bulbs and outlets!"}
{"Author": "Walter I", "Date": "on August 1, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Connects to Echo Easily", "Text": "Works well and has connected to Echo easily."}
{"Author": "John W Briggs", "Date": "on August 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "I have used x10 technology for many years. This product is far superior"}
{"Author": "Thomas Shively", "Date": "on July 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It will not work with 99% of Home wireless devices suchesGE The Nest smoke detectors Schlage door knobs"}
{"Author": "Michael T. Hanley, CPA", "Date": "on July 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup", "Text": "Easy to setup, works great. We connected our bedroom lights and ceiling fan to it and now we control them through our phones."}
{"Author": "Tinkerer", "Date": "on July 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dream product for people who like to tinker.", "Text": "I absolutely love this thing - although I am spending way too much on devices to use with it.\n\nAlthough some will complain about the fact that not everything is plug an play, I just love the development environment and the active community that has allowed me to do everything I have ever wanted to with the product. (I am a developer by trade, so maybe I have more tolerance for this than most people - but the added flexibility of the development environment has meant that I am never just stuck when something doesn't work the way I want it to.)\n\nI'm using both Zigbee and Z-Wave devices - although I have chosen Z-Wave to be my standard (because of the longer range).\n\nOf particular interest to me was the great integration with Alexa (but only for switches and thermostats - and a lock by work-around and IFTTT). My wife (who very rarely uses the app on her phone - is more than happy to use Alexa to control the lights and thermostats.)"}
{"Author": "Loran J. Termine", "Date": "on July 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Junk. Don't bother. This is not the end ...", "Text": "Junk. Don't bother. This is not the end solution for home automation. It's not supported well. This is just tweener tech that you'll dump a few hundred dollars replacing switches and dimmers and to what end? Right now this is just a hobby than anything else."}
{"Author": "YMO", "Date": "on July 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am so happy with this Hub", "Text": "I am so happy with this Hub. it's easy to setup, very easy. This will let me unsubscribe my existing service and I won't need to pay monthly fee anymore!!!. The instruction for enrollment \"exiting\" device is not clear. But basically you will need to remember that you will have to un-enroll your existing device first if your device has connected previously (In my case, I have shlage lock and Trane Thermo, all z-wave devices). Once you un-enroll them, add devices to the hub is so easy, very happy for the purchase."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Still working great..."}
{"Author": "Bondo", "Date": "on July 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Find another home automation solution", "Text": "This system is complete garbage. The mobile app's interfaces for both iOS and Android are abysmal. The are extremely difficult to navigate, and they data they show is almost always wrong. I have two z-wave smoke detectors and iPhones as proximity sensors. One of the sensors ALWAYS, 100% of the time, says it is away. I can delete it & re-add it and it will say \"Home\" for a few minutes, then give me an alert saying it has left, even thought I'm sitting right there with it in my hand right next to the HUB & connected to the wifi. The I will occalionally get false notifications that a smoke alarm is going off - pretty anxiety inducing when you aren't at home. After I get the alert, quite often the app will never update that the alert has cleared - going to the dashboard will say \"smoke detected\" for one of the alarms. After some undetermined amount of time it will finally change to \"clear\".\n\nI know this is more a review of the mobile apps, but the fact of the matter is that you really cannot interface with this HUB without them unless you want to go through their web interface, which is basically just a scripting interface. I would strongly recommend going with a different home automation solution and avoiding the Samsung piece of trash."}
{"Author": "Jason", "Date": "on July 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the best home automation controller out there", "Text": "This is the best home automation controller out there, especially if you are techy, you can interface almost any device with the help of the Smartthings community"}
{"Author": "KTL", "Date": "on July 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm just getting started with smart home devices", "Text": "I'm just getting started with smart home devices. This works with Schlage Connect deadbolt locks. It does not work with Nest fire and carbon monoxide alarms at this time. It is suppose to work with Amazon Echo, but I have found that your smart home devices are not necessarily compatible with both this hub and Echo."}
{"Author": "Olliesshop", "Date": "on July 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very flexibile", "Text": "I purchased this as the foundation for my security system. So far it's works well and I love the flexibility it offers to link non-Samsung sensors, like my Ecobee3 thermostat. I'm still have a lot of sensors to add, though, and hope they will link smoothly as well. You can also get very immersed in programming SmartApps and Devices if you have a special need."}
{"Author": "Will B", "Date": "on July 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Horrible waste of time.", "Text": "Enormous waste of time and horribly designed product. The iOS app (which is how this is controlled) is a total mess that breaks every convention of both internal consistency and embracing convention. It's impossible to navigate. There's very little user feedback, for instance if you try to turn on a light, and the hub got unplugged, the app will tell you that you turned off the light (or whatever you tried to do) even if it didn't work. Expect multiple sequential firmware updates for no good reason. If you do get it set up perfectly, expect it to work about 80-90%. Those extra 10% might not seem like a big deal, but the whole point is to make life easy, and this doesn't. And if you bought this for its much-advertised home security features, then failing 10% of the time can be a disaster."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 26, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Ok, but not as versatile as I expected."}
{"Author": "Fiston", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "too complicated", "Text": "maybe I'm just slow but I was looking for something that worked with ALEXA out of the box but this is a completely separate device that has more things learn, to set up I want I wanted simple. You need to buy other gadgets for this to be of any use."}
{"Author": "kelly43h", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Way better than Wink in every way!", "Text": "I will start this off by saying that I am switching to the SmartThings Hub from a Wink hub. The Wink was an absolute nightmare, it never worked right from the start and customer service wasn't the most helpful. With the SmartThings Hub the experience has been everything I had hoped for when I purchased the Wink. All of my devices work, I don't loose connection every couple of hours and it doesn't keep telling me that I need to do an update that never works. It works really well with Alexa and I like the app. So far this has been a great purchase and I have been very happy with it."}
{"Author": "J.B.", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent when it works, but impossible to fix when it doesn't.", "Text": "I love the control and peace of mind this gives me - I have the status of my locks, Hue lights, door sensors, and landscaping lights available on my phone at all times. The routines are great, especially the ability to program things to turn on/off when I leave.\n\nIt's not perfect. I have been unable to connect it to my Samsung security camera, Sonos music system, or any Nest devices, despite lots of reading and multiple attempts. Unfortunately the only recourse seems to be to \"try again.\"\n\nStill, I cannot overstate how much security it gives me to be able to lock my doors remotely, and ensure that the doors are closed, so four stars it is."}
{"Author": "Gary W. Hawkins", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to program in new devices and Alexa works it ...", "Text": "Enjoying this so far. Easy to program in new devices and Alexa works it it so it's nice!"}
{"Author": "GM", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The start of something new...", "Text": "Used as the first piece of my home automation beginnings; I have nothing negative to say about it so far (only had it for about a month). Setup was very easy and it paired quickly with the light switches I used. I do plan on modifying this review as I continue adding devices. My plans include motion sensors, cameras, a nest thermostat, and (2) smoke/CO detectors. Every device communicated via Z-wave and Wifi, and according to my research I can also pair them with my home security system."}
{"Author": "Steven T.", "Date": "on July 24, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Need way more options and a more user friendly interface"}
{"Author": "Stipman", "Date": "on July 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far, really liking it. It does not ...", "Text": "So far, really liking it. It does not work without an internet connection though\nI took the shell off my racing snail, thinking it would make him run faster.\nIf anything, it made him more sluggish"}
{"Author": "Erik", "Date": "on July 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wait until they figure this stuff out", "Text": "Don't do it,\n\nIt works at first but it is buggy at best. Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't. It is so not worth the money. Wait until they figure this technology out. As of now, it sucks!"}
{"Author": "Tim D.", "Date": "on July 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy with this purchase", "Text": "This hub works great. I'm really glad that I bought the second generation. After I read how horrible the 1st gen was, I almost didn't get this one. I'm glad I did because it's now the backbone of my smart home.\n\nIt is impressive how many smart devices (from other companies!) are supported through smartthings. It's very rare to find a \"smart thing\" that doesn't work with it, and even the ones that don't work now could easily be integrated through a firmware update by Samsung."}
{"Author": "Eric Ventura", "Date": "on July 21, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I would love to give this a 5 star review - it ...", "Text": "I would love to give this a 5 star review - it really does do everything they say it can. It can connect to and control so many things! But what gives it three stars is the fact that Samsung seems to be relying on the open source world to build in all the features, and it's just not working out. I love that I can connect any Z-wave device, and they have support for common Phillips and GE colored LED bubls and light strips - but they don't have any fun programming like syncing up a room full of lights and going through a slow color-changing effect. Or Scene setups like if I want to sit down and watch a movie and want most lights off but a couple at 10% so I could see enough to walk to the bathroom. You'd think they'd have work out these very common expectations, but no, you need to go to open source programmers...usually some clever random guy on the web, who might not have the same hardware or wants/needs as you...so you waste time downloading and trying out apps that don't fit your simple needs. It's good hardware and can do everything you expect it to, I just really wish Samsung put more time into having a better built in software suite; even as geeky as I am, I'm just not in the mood to spend hours and hours trying out half-baked 3rd party apps to make this meet my simple expectations."}
{"Author": "Ccinca33", "Date": "on July 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I cannot say enough good things about this hub", "Text": "I cannot say enough good things about this hub! It has calmed my worry about locking doors, closing the garage, ect. so many times!! I wouldn't use it for an alarm system but I trust it for automating my home. It is a bit buggy sometimes but the Smartthings team is always working to update things and keep everything moving forward. Also, the Smartthings customer base is so helpful when you have questions for devices that aren't meant for Smartthings per se. And the Smartthings tech support is amazing! They are so fast on emails and willing to help. I definitely recommend this hub!"}
{"Author": "sism3477", "Date": "on July 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Still Needs Work", "Text": "Great when it works but not reliable enough to keep as my primary home controller."}
{"Author": "Ron R", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "As good as it gets right now.", "Text": "I use this with my Ecobee 2 thermostats, First Alert fire alarms, GE Z wave switches, Amazon Echo and Logitech Harmony Hub and I must say it works well 99 percent of the time."}
{"Author": "RogTechGuru", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I like Wink", "Text": "Cannot connect some of my z wave devices. I like Wink better"}
{"Author": "Paul B.", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "So far we like this hub. Could have more compatible products for HVAC control."}
{"Author": "Luke", "Date": "on July 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "awesome"}
{"Author": "Geekster", "Date": "on July 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This geek approves", "Text": "I love this thing! After my Link relay died, I was going back and forth between this and the Wink Hub. I am so glad I chose this one. Any outages are resolved quickly, and there are always new things being added. Very active developer community and user forums."}
{"Author": "Beer Man", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great purchase so far.", "Text": "I'm two weeks in and still loving the hub. Everything paired up on the first try. I had the whole house set up in one day. I found it easy to configure straight from the app. I have added a smart lock, several door sensors, motion sensors, garage door, and started with some lighting. Next I plan to add some cameras and smoke alarms. So far a great project."}
{"Author": "tazzmom", "Date": "on July 13, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "be careful before you buy this", "Text": "not bad but bought to work with the outlet. outlet does not work. not an easy installation either. No online support available from samsung"}
{"Author": "Chad Curvin", "Date": "on July 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So Easy Even A Flip Phone User Can Use It - As Long As They Have A Tablet Handy", "Text": "Solid device, easy to setup, easy to figure out.\n\nMost of the difficulty in getting this device up and running came from me thinking I could do it from a desktop program. Once I realized I **needed** to use a Smartphone/Tablet app, the rest was a breeze. The software isn't as simple as I'd expect, but that's more a review of the app than a review of the hub (but I think this is import to review here nonetheless, so see below). This hub has some indicator LEDs to explain whether it's connected or not, and if it's installing a firmware update. That's about the extent of the hub, very simple and easy to setup/configure. One last thing to note, it requires you to use the Ethernet port to connect it to your network, there is no built in wireless option. There are devices you can find that can bridge an Ethernet port to a wireless network though, should you absolutely need a wireless option.\n\nThis hub **requires** you to use a Smartphone/Tablet app to setup external devices and to do anything more than look at blinky lights. I find that a bit odd since really the apps aren't incredibly complex, but are mostly just displaying what the hub and the devices are doing. A desktop option, even a browser-based would seem to be just as simple.\n\nOnce inside the app, it isn't always intuitive to figure how to carry out things as simple as setting up a door sensor to alert you when the door is opened. You have to click through about 94 screens before you finally get to the point to set this alert, and if you decide to change it, another 94 screen taps are required. It just seems like a poorly designed UI for common/simple tasks. Does that make it more robust? Yeah, probably. But documentation would go a long way to help with that then. Something even more useful would be a desktop version so I didn't have to clickity tap for hours and hours to try to figure out what you might think I want to do with my sensors.\n\nOverall I gave this hub 5 stars, really because the hub is insanely simple and works exactly like I'd hoped it would. If this were also a review and rating for the app, this would definitely be a 1-2 star review. In the end, you don't have to use the SmartThings app to use this device, and because of that, this device should be reviewed on its own merit. Feel free to browse on over to OpenHab.org if you feel the SmartThings software to be lacking."}
{"Author": "Nathaniel Q. Seaman", "Date": "on July 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buy a Wink instead", "Text": "No support to set up. Very hard to do. Ended up returning it for a Wink and super happy I did."}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on July 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great, Easy setup, just follow the instructions"}
{"Author": "AZ", "Date": "on July 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love it!", "Text": "I replaced my Wink Hub for the Samsung, I love it!"}
{"Author": "Timothy D Flynn", "Date": "on July 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great and east to set up"}
{"Author": "Middle aged male", "Date": "on July 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works fine: )", "Text": "Always on time. Works fine :)"}
{"Author": "Technology Enthusiast", "Date": "on July 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "this is garbage. samsung has no idea what they are doing ...", "Text": "biggest piece of junk i have ever purchased.. avoid at all costs, this is garbage. samsung has no idea what they are doing with this platform and have continually failed miserably. they have even scared off anyone that cares to develop for it by being complete idiots. my automation system fails daily, do NOT buy"}
{"Author": "Stephen", "Date": "on July 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "BIG MISTAKE!", "Text": "I've been in IT over 20 years. I love gadgets, but I also love reliability. As of now, this is just a big toy. The reliability is so poor, my family and I have had enough. Above all else, this category of product needs to be reliable and it's not. The problems have resulted in all sorts of articles published around the web, especially on tech blogs like CNET.COM. You'll see the issues publicized on the smartthings community (forums). I had the first iteration of this hub and it worked so well I jumped at the chance to buy this version, version 2. I tried the Wink hub before and Smartthings v1 hub was a huge upgrade from that. \"Upgrading\" to the Smartthings v2 hub was the biggest downgrade I've made in 20 years. I really don't think I'm overstating it. It was a big mistake. I never spend the time to write reviews, but this will product will waste so many hours of your life, it necessitated a VERY NEGATIVE REVIEW! However, if you're bored and have time to burn, you've found your product!!!!!"}
{"Author": "Adam Baer", "Date": "on July 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good unit", "Text": "Had some trouble with serial number at initial set up. Support was pretty responsive. I am running This along side a mi casa Verde."}
{"Author": "Goodnuzz", "Date": "on July 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "as I didn\u2019t have a clue that my thermostat was smart. There is a long list of products that ...", "Text": "I recently purchased the SmartThings Hub v.2 and it has worked flawlessly from day one. There was one small hiccup in the installation process involving the SmartThings app. The app instructs you to wait for a confirmation that the hub has installed correctly before tapping \u201cNext.\u201d It should take 5-20 minutes the app states. I never received the confirmation and tapped Next after 20 minutes, since I had solid green lights on the hub. Everything had installed correctly.\nThe app found my Kwikset 916 SmartCode door lock immediately. I had to push and hold the button on my Leviton dimmer switch in order for SmartThings to find it. Connecting all of my Leviton switches was very simple. It also found my Honeywell thermostat. That was a bonus, as I didn\u2019t have a clue that my thermostat was smart. There is a long list of products that are compatible with SmartThings on their website. But if you visit the SmartThings Community, you will find that a lot more products are compatible. If you have any questions, issues or are looking for bright ideas, I would visit the SmartThings Community first. It is fantastic.\nI was able to connect Amazon Alexa to SmartThings in seconds. You can use the SmartThings app to control all of your devices and you can schedule routines based on a time or event. But I find it is much more fun to ask Alexa to do it."}
{"Author": "mean_old_teacher", "Date": "on July 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cowardly company--avoid at all cost", "Text": "I have used Smarthings for about a year and a half with TCP Connected bulbs. With no warning from either company, these two organizations have stopped working together. Tech support says that SmartThings no longer has access to TCP servers, and service has been discontinued. My investment in both is substantial, and now, I have to change one of them. They have both acted in an irresponsible fashion. If you are thinking of either of them, my advice is to seek home automation products elsewhere."}
{"Author": "darrix", "Date": "on July 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not so smart!", "Text": "I wanted this to work! But it fell short of my expectations. Routines not working consistently! This should work out of the box! This is going back to amazon!"}
{"Author": "Krystopher Douglas", "Date": "on June 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Garbage."}
{"Author": "Caroline T", "Date": "on June 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Problems reconnecting ALL things", "Text": "I upgraded so I'd be able to add the Samsung smart cams. So far, haven't been able to get the correct password. But worse, none of my schlage locks or Belkin/WeMo/Z-Wave switches or motion/temperature sensors will even show up. Tried connecting by specific products and also with the general \"connect now\". Neither works for any of these \"things\". Not smart."}
{"Author": "bsanker", "Date": "on June 29, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good hub/Needs more user support", "Text": "I like this hub compared to others I have tested. I do with Samsung would take more interest in what users are asking for. This device works great for home automation but don't count on it as a security system. It is just not there yet. Smartthings solution for alarm relies on presence detectors with do not always broadcast on fast cycle. Even the Smartthing presence detector can cause false alarms when sending the signal back to the hub. There needs to be a delay on the alarm to allow for this. This product has a great community based forum with homemade integration and testing of third party products."}
{"Author": "Dougboffl", "Date": "on June 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... in the display and programming but runs and updates great.", "Text": "A little quirky in the display and programming but runs and updates great."}
{"Author": "AZ Dude", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unlocks doors on it's own.. I turned it off.", "Text": "It seemed to work ok for a time, then things started to go south.. Today was the one that got me to shut it down. I was setting here alone, phone in another room, and Hub in still a different room when I heard the deadbolt unlock. No one was around anything but the deadbolt just unlocked for no reason.. What a waste of money."}
{"Author": "James S.", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Inconsistent performance and substandard support", "Text": "I wanted a SmartThings system for a long time and much to my delight, I received one along with the Zen Thermostat I purchased. Sadly, my recent experiences with support for this and and the Zen Thermostat leave me dismayed. The short version of the story is that since day one I have had problems between the SmartThings and Zen. Temperature changes happen randomly and without any cause that I can see in the logs. Sometimes they don't happen at all even when they are scheduled or sometimes a manual change of a few degrees at once leaves you with only a partial temp change. All of this leaves me with a severe lack of confidence that the SmartThings hub and my Zen Thermostat are working properly which causes both comfort issues and has a financial impact when your AC runs for three days as a very low temperature when you're out of town.\n\nI just \"dealt\" with these quirks for the longest time until very recently after having woken up in a sweat one too many times after the temperature in my house got up to 80+ degrees due to issues between these two devices. I started by contacting Zen support, who, of the two support departments has been much more responsive than the SmartThings people. After a few weeks, they finally referred me to SmartThings support saying it was a SmartThings issue. SmartThings support is very slow and when they did respond, the explanations or advice were often not clear or made assumptions about things that were not obvious. After 2-3 weeks with them, I finally opened a chat session with support and after quite some time, they said this was a Zen problem. So, I emailed Zen. Guess what they said on my first email back to them? You guessed it! It's a SmartThings problem! So, here I am stuck between two support departments who are pointing fingers at each other and I still don't have a solution. To Zen's credit, they did suggest something that needed to happen on the ST side and they sent a followup email this morning with the ST support group CC'd asking if we'd made any progress. Two full business days since my last communication with ST and they are still silent.\n\nSO, I'm done. I'm going to just go buy another smart thermostat and ditch both the Zen and SmartThings. Fortunately, I didn't invest much in SmartThings like I originally intended and really the only thing I was using it for was my Zen. Regrettably, I did end up buying two Foscam video cameras on the rumors in the SmartThings forums that they would eventually be supported. To this day, nothing. While disappointing, that one is on me as I rolled the dice and lost.\n\nIn short, if you are VERY tech savvy with code and such, have a lot of time and LIKE to tinker, then SmartThings might be a great choice for you. If like me you just want a product that just works, with an intuitive interface and from a company who will be helpful when it doesn't, then this product isn't a good fit. My past experience with companies that are the \"middle-ware\" between multiple other vendors (like SmartThings) has taught me that success is predicated on the ability to support the products with which they integrate. Customers don't care and don't have time to navigate two support groups to cobble together a solution. This means going the extra mile, suggesting out of the box solutions and not simply saying at the first convenient opportunity, \"Oh, that's the other guy's problem.\" Sadly, SmartThings didn't do this for me, so buy at your own risk."}
{"Author": "WLR", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Security needs Hub.", "Text": "It was easy to install and because my Electronic Dead Bolt works great. I use Kwikset and Ring video doorbell together and they work great. Couldn't happen without the Hub."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as advertised", "Text": "I've been very happy with this hub. Setup was a breeze and it has performed flawlessly in the first month of operation."}
{"Author": "Jo Jo", "Date": "on June 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product, highly recommended.", "Text": "Great Product, highly recommended."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy to install and get things started", "Text": "Very easy to install and get things started , but app needs a major overhaul\nAlso I'd prefer if the hub had wifi connectivity"}
{"Author": "Maurice", "Date": "on June 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Now Very Good", "Text": "So far so good. The negative reviewers made me wonder. We only use it with Z-wave products (three kwikset locks, motion detectors and a water alarm. Also like that we can use our Samsung smart phones as fobs, so that when we both go out and forget to lock up, the hub does it for us once we are out of wi-fi range. It took us FOREVER to settle on this hub, as every one we looked at had such varied reviews.\n\nUpdate: Most disappointing. After our initial success, the hub became erratic. Locks would unlock on their own. The hub would fail to recognise things already installed. Reaction times are often very slow. Locks show 'locked' or 'unlocked' in error. Pressing 'lock' sometimes shows activity and then success, but looking at the lock nothing had happened. At one point the whole system stopped working. This is unacceptable for a security system device. I'm not sure how much of the problem is the device and how much is the app; but since they are inextricably linked it really does not matter. If either fails the other is useless. Using the phones as fobs was useless as the hub often reported that one or both of us were present when we were not, or vice-versa. Our previous hub was a Honeywell Tuxedo Touch. It never failed to work properly the three years we were in that house. I reset the hub and now have most of the devices re-paired onto it. Time will tell if my next update removes another star or adds one.\n\nUpdate 2: It's official, I hate this thing. Devices work sometimes, don't work, sometimes pair, don't pair. Devices start and stop working as the spirits decide. The worst thing is Smartthings report that it locked doors that remain unlocked. I've gone so far as deleting all my settings and starting over, twice... if anything it got worse. My GE light switches, which once worked nearly instantly, now will turn off but not on, or vice versa, and sometimes after a long delay will switch. We just had a firmware upgrade push and it helped nothing. I never had any trouble with my old Honeywell Tuxedo Touch, using many of the same sorts of sensors, but it would not send messages to my phone, like this does (except they can't be trusted).\n\nUpdate 3: Hmmm...going up from one to two stars. Perhaps firmware pushes from Samsung have had some effect. It is still not perfect, still lies to us about a few things, but for the most part it has started working quite a bit better. We still do not rely on it for home security...just not reliable enough, but it works okay for home automation. We're thoroughly disappointed that the TCP Connected bulbs, remote and interface box, which we bought because they were compatible, have now been dropped by SmartThings. They still work on their own, but no longer with SmartThings. We've added more devices, mostly GE switches and modules, and they all are working. Perhaps Samsung will eventually get this right...time will tell. The only 'good' thing about this disaster is that we've learned a lot, and we see that most of the other hubs have mixed reviews too. This stuff should work better, much better, out of the box. We're adding an Echo to the system and will report on how that goes.\n\nUpdate 4: The ST hub seems to have settled in and is now working properly most of the time. I must stress that we've done nothing since we downgraded our rating to 1-star and pronounced hatred. So, it must be the firmware pushes that SmartThings has been sending. We added an Echo and an Echo Dot (also reviewed) and they work better than expected to voice control the ST hub. We don't know who to blame, Samsung or Amazon, but the ST hub and the Echos are only PARTIALLY COMPATIBLE; not all the devices registered on the ST hub are discoverable on the Echos. For example, we cannot voice-control our Kwikset locks. On the strength that Samsung may be getting this right, we bought a second hub for our cottage. We'll use it to alert us to any alarm there (full-blown Honeywell automation, perimeter, smoke, motion system), using a contact switch, and to control the Honeywell thermostat.\n\nUpdate 5: We have two of these hubs, one in our home and one in our cottage, together with a plethora of devices on each. It has been a love-hate relationship. That said, Samsung continues to push firmware updates into the hubs, the reliability is now very good and the companion software (app and web site) reasonable. We have not had to do a total reset in ages, and added devices now pair easily. The kwikset locks, which were at one time not working reliably at all, now work 99% of the time. So, we are adding a star to give this hub a 4-star rating, which is really saying something, as at one point we hated the thing. We've only limited experience with competing hubs, but based on continuous study, this seems to be one of the front runners."}
{"Author": "Ryan B.", "Date": "on June 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just new to this home automation thing and this hub ...", "Text": "Just new to this home automation thing and this hub could not be any easier. Looking forward to adding more things to it."}
{"Author": "Douglas", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... my veralite with this hub and I couldnt be happier. Smartthings community is great and the support from ...", "Text": "I replaced my veralite with this hub and I couldnt be happier. Smartthings community is great and the support from smartthings is quick."}
{"Author": "Digidealer", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good for remote monitoring, but not much else.", "Text": "SmartThings is a cloud-based solution. As such, it works best for remote monitoring and alerts. I would not recommend it as a home automation controller though. SmartThings claims to support scenes (oddly called \"Routines\") and schedules, but they work sporadically at best. Schedules are often missed, routines routinely don't fire, etc. Service outages lasting several hours are not uncommon. Check out SmartThings Community forums for user feedback before buying."}
{"Author": "Donald j Winters", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Things Hub", "Text": "Smart Things Hub is a excellent product"}
{"Author": "Deej", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good hub", "Text": "Good hub, it's working well for me so far."}
{"Author": "Junswifey", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does not do the job.", "Text": "This device worked wonderfully when I first received it. Connected to the Open/Close door sensor I bought and the GE light bulb i purchased for testing. Thought that I should purchase zwave devices because they were more cost effective. Bought and returned 5-6 different z-wave devices because they would not pair with my hub. I contacted Smartthings customer services...while they were helpful had admitted the problem was probably with my hub. Returned first hub to Amazon and purchased another. Now none of my devices will now pair with the hub even after exluding and including devices. My hub will not even pair with the Smartthings open/close sensor even after following video exclusion instructions."}
{"Author": "Lisa B.", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent", "Text": "I have one of these in my home, and am rolling out GE Z-wave switches in the rooms. Our house is nearly 6000 sq ft and so far no coverage problems. The app for an Android phone is easy to find, the appointment for an Amazon Fire tablet, not so easy to find but it is out there.\nAnnoy spouses, kids, the pets and burglars by turning things on and off wherever you have a wifi or 4g connection."}
{"Author": "Zha93", "Date": "on June 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Flaky and unreliable", "Text": "I love the idea of this thing. Too bad it's SUPER flaky. The reliabilty of built in apps, terrible, ones other write the same. Their cloud platform dies ALL THE FIRGGEN TIME.. most times they won't even acknowledge the issues. Simple thing like turning off/on Lights via the app fail. Just all of it = bad/flaky platform. Too bad, it's a cool idea, but these things are still very much in the alpha world."}
{"Author": "albert pozar", "Date": "on June 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not bad product but it doesn't support the kwikset 910 z-wave ...", "Text": "Edit Samsung is supporting this product with free automatic firmware updates that add more supported products all the time. I just keep getting more pleased and have changed my 4 stars to 5. This is the product to get.\nNot bad product but it doesn't support the kwikset 910 z-wave lock even though it states it does. You will have to download a custom app that someone developed on the internet and copy and paste code. This is doable and fully supports the locks functions but unfortunately the lock is not so smart and the codes only have a 50/50 chance of working. I do like that it has open source code so smart folks can right apps and share them in the forums instead of waiting for Samsung to catch up to the new products.\nUpdate the new firmware helps still no support for the 910 kwikset zwave. I am using a Chinese lock set and that works fine so far. Still the occasional glitch but I can get it working with my smartphone. I really need this to work 100% of the time and it's closer. Fingers crossed for the next update."}
{"Author": "Brian Mooney", "Date": "on June 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but still the best and only home automation that integrates SONOS", "Text": "Not much difference from the 1st generation other than camera support. PITA to switch from 1st generation, but still the best and only home automation that integrates SONOS."}
{"Author": "AR", "Date": "on June 17, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What is good: It is compatible with lots of sensors", "Text": "What is good:\nIt is compatible with lots of sensors, even sensors not on the official list.\nLots of cool integrations that you can do with this if you are a tinkerer\n\nThe Bad:\nIncredibly bug prone, The hub and apps are frequently not working. sometimes you get error messages, but they do not help troubleshoot the problem\nThe support is poor. Customers are not happy and when they ask for help, the support team does not have the answers.\nThe hub is updated frequently, yet the bugs remain. As an engineer, I see how the development team is working this product, and I believe the future is bleak. I do not get the impression that they know what they are doing.\nFinally, all of the above points indicate a system is vulnerable to hacking and it turns out, this system has been shown by researchers to be incredibly vulnerable to hacking and Smartthings has been slow to send out fixes to hacks that have been disclosed. Bottomline, this \"Security\" system may make you more vulnerable."}
{"Author": "Toby", "Date": "on June 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not Ready for Primetime", "Text": "The app was buggy. I could never get my lights to do what I wanted. I was really excited about this, but it turned out to be an expensive disappointment. I actually returned the hub and the LED bulbs I purchased to use with the hub."}
{"Author": "Lee V", "Date": "on June 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Migration Nightmare - Avoid", "Text": "If you have a V1, do not attempt to buy and migrate to V2. They say \"Migration\" online, but what they mean is you literally have to manually remove each device. You then have to re-add every device to V2. It is extremely hard to get the Z-wave devices to unassociate from the V1. Do not even bother with the V2."}
{"Author": "Richard", "Date": "on June 15, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Many have pointed out that a simple timer might work better. Not very smart", "Text": "Hardly works. Do not get if you need it to be reliable. It only controls my porch light so it's not a big deal, but it works probably only three nights a week. Many have pointed out that a simple timer might work better. Not very smart, Samsung."}
{"Author": "Candy", "Date": "on June 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "my favorite! suggest!"}
{"Author": "Michael Wiggin", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Of course it could use some software work, but the hub is rock solid!", "Text": "This is definitely not for those that want an all in one app written for them. But, for those of us that like to tinker, you can install apps for your devices that have customized behaviors to that which you want, and you gain functionality that way. It's a little clunky to get setup, but has never not worked for me yet. I use it to control about 20 3-prong outlets, light dimmers and switches, one of my garage doors, a CT-100 thermostat, and a Yale Real Living door lock. So far, once I got the right apps installed, the hub has been perfect. Never missed a control.\n\nAll the nice said, it definitely needs some improvements to be great, but they are working on it constantly. They have a good community that contributes continually. I think simple functionality like smart door locks should have user access control built in, lighting schedules by default, thermostat schedules, etc. There are some huge gaps, but once they get the software side worked out, it's going to be a solid smart home hub!"}
{"Author": "Kevin M Agard", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far I am liking it. At the moment ...", "Text": "So far I am liking it. At the moment we only have it controlling lighting. I've set up about a dozen Cree dimmable LED bulbs.\n\nHad a little trouble with syncing the first couple of bulbs but that was more and issue of me not reading the instructions properly. Once I did that, I had no further issues syncing the rest.\n\nThe down side is that you are forced to do the syncing and all the configuration on the mobile app. The stock system totally lacks a web based interface. When setting up a number of devices and routines, having to do all work on a phone can get old fast."}
{"Author": "Linda S. Baldree", "Date": "on June 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "excellent device, I no longer have to get up to turn on the light or ceiling fan"}
{"Author": "KT", "Date": "on June 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So LIMITED...I would NEVER buy again! WASTE of money!", "Text": "I bought the Samsung Smart Things hub specifically to work with a new Schlage Camelot Touchscreen smart door knob, which requires Z-Wave technology. I bought both items (after confirming compatibility) for my vacation rental in order to control door knob codes, entrance and departure access and even know the time of entrance and departure for my housekeeper. So I finally make it down to my place, install the new door knob and Smart Things Hub with great anticipation...only to find it ONLY LOCKS AND UNLOCKS the doorknob. After calling Schlage, I found out the Smart Thing app does NOT provide any other functions available on the Schlage Camelot!! I had to buy WINK at Home Depot...WINK does it ALL!! While Smart Thing limitations are a HUGE disappointment. And, a WASTE of money. One more thing...there's NO Smart Thing customer service phone number; it's always nice to TALK to someone...you can only EMAIL Smart Thing. WINK has awesome customer service, just a phone call away!"}
{"Author": "Marcelo L. Da Silva", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy with it so far", "Text": "It is a hub and it does what is supposed to do, Very happy with it so far."}
{"Author": "Matthew Sievers", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It was super easy and effective", "Text": "First off, SmartThings requires a working order Cloud. If you don't understand, this means Samsung has to have their servers up and running, the network between you and them has to be up, your internet needs be up, and your home router needs be operating failure free. If you're using this for home security, you are extremely un-secure.\n\nThe thing booted right up, updated for 10 minutes or so, the app loaded and followed the router, setup was a breeze with my garage door tilt sensor using a time of day notifications rule. It was super easy and effective.\n\nNext I went looking for the rule. Not so easy. Then an extra back button press on the home screen apparently logged out my account off the phone and reset all of my programming and device linking.\n\nThe hub would not link to the tilt sensor again, and then it just fell offline according to the app, even though the hub showed a proper green link. After an hours worth of reboots, I contacted support. The next day, after it had come online all by itself 12 hours later, support told me the Could was having trouble and that's what I was seeing. Danger, Will Robinson.\n\nThe thing never would link back up to the garage sensor and I sent it all back. I consider this engineering fundamentally flawed."}
{"Author": "Wessel Family", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Tons of functionality, very happy with SmartThings", "Text": "I started my Home Automation journey with a Wink hub after reading several comparisons between SmartThings and Wink. I had not read much good about either, but a lot of bad about ST, so I went with Wink. After setting up Wink, I was quickly disappointed with the lack of anything more than basic functionality. I did some more searching on the SmartThings community site and found a few threads from a month or so ago that were talking about significantly improved SmartThings reliability, so it seemed that all of the negatives I had read earlier had been fixed. One day after I had my Wink hub up and running, I requested a return and ordered a SmartThings hub.\n\nNow, 3 days after setting up my ST hub, I have been able to automate nearly every switch that I have, using time-based triggers, triggers like plugging cell phones in, performing different actions when different people get home at different times of day, controlling one switch with another, using one dimmer to set the dimming level of another dimmer, etc. The app and web interface have TONS of functionality, and the community forum has an answer for nearly every question that is not \"officially\" supported. It took me a little bit to get used to the app layout, but after playing around for a couple days I'm pretty comfortable with it. The SmartThings IDE web interface is good, and offers a lot of \"power user\" type of functionality. Between Amazon Echo integration, IFTTT channel, custom user-created SmartApps, and Logitech Harmony integration, this hub has an answer for nearly everything. Very happy with the purchase."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "worked out great.", "Text": "It was easy to integrate sensors and lights. worked like a charm for me."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Now works perfectly for me, after I found these two workarounds", "Text": "Although I bought my SmartThings hub directly from Samsung, I wanted to write a review here, because I believe most of the reviews here don't reflect the situation today. I'm glad I waited to buy this device, because I hear it used to be slow, buggy and unreliable. My experience so far has been mostly great. No missed events. No false alarms. Motion sensors work very well. Water sensors on the multisensor work well. Amazon Ech support works well. The only two issues I've had is getting the system to detect new devices. I found it helps if you place the device very close to the hub. In the case, where I can't move the device, like a wall outlet, I sometimes use a long extension cord to move the hub. Not ideal, but you only have to do this once. Another solution is that most devices have a button you press, or a sequence like press the button on the device, while plugging it in and wait until the light changes color. That seems to work, although it still sometimes takes a minute or so to find devices. My other issue was not understanding that only powered devices are repeaters and a ZigBee repeater won't help with Z-Wave devices. Once I understood this and bought 2 repeaters to extend the range, my accuracy went to 100%. I only have 16 devices on my network, so I hope my good luck continues as I buy more devices."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great. Just as expected."}
{"Author": "Pierre S.", "Date": "on June 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy set up. Fast shipping. Great integration with Z-Wave and Nest, etc"}
{"Author": "Jack of all trades", "Date": "on June 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best hub for home automation", "Text": "I have been converting everything to a smart house and this hub makes it easy. I have no issues connecting devices or with mesh stability.\n\nI will say that the app can be a bit difficult to navigate at times.\n\nSupport is great and they respond quickly. There is a ton of information out there to help you customize your devices and add unsupported devices.\n\nMy biggest drawback is the unsupported devices. This is to be expected so I didn't take a star. As the company grows (now with the strength of Samsung behind it), more support will be added eliminating the need for ifttt and other third party services.\n\nMaking your house smart is addictive and expensive, but you will enjoy the simplicity it adds."}
{"Author": "Jonathan Guntert", "Date": "on June 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Thank you", "Text": "Love this thing, it has made my echo fun too"}
{"Author": "Chasjs", "Date": "on June 8, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Has a long way to go.", "Text": "Great idea but poor implementation. I purchased this along with a Gocontrol/linear garage door sensor so I could tell if the door was closed when I was away from home. I installed everything and it works - sometimes. There are many times it seems to lose connection to the opener but it does not indicate the connection has been lost. It will indicate the door is open when it is closed and vice-versa. I will use my phone to try to close it and it just says closing but nothing happens. So I still do not have piece of mind. I would think it should have a time out value if the device does not respond within a certain time - I have had it say for hours that the garage door is opening.\n\nThere is not user Interface on the device itself to be able to diagnosis issues - you have to log into your smartthings cloud account. The cloud pings your hub but the hub does not seem to actively ping the devices.\n\nSetting up alerts could be a lot simpler. You almost have to be a programmer to configure alerts.\n\nIt is nice when it works but the inconsistency and the lack of any feedback make it of minimal value."}
{"Author": "EmDee", "Date": "on June 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy set up and very easy to use.", "Text": "Our home came with zwave switches and other devices connected to Micasa verde's Vera1. While it was functional the interface felt very much like web 1.0 and while i am fairly technical the process of setting up routines wasn't very intuitive. So when I saw the smartthings on sale I jumped on it.\n\n1. Setting up the hub - The sole reason for taking a star away from the review. Not a whole lot of documentation comes with the device or is available online. When I initially set it up I had 3 green lights show up but the app would not connect and kept saying the hub was offline. Repeated attempts at rebooting it didn't help either. Tried opening up ports as per certain forum posts but to no avail. I did email customer service, but i noticed the device was near my audio receiver, though i doubt he magnetic interference caused the problem that seemed to do the trick and everything started working.\n\n2. Adding devices - As I mentioned the house came with most of the z wave switches and i was a bit worried about being able to add devices that had no identification marks (brand etc.). The documentation that comes with the device/app is also a bit lacking. Thanks to Google I was able to find out how to place the existing devices in an Exclusion mode in order to remove them from the current network. Adding these then on to smarthings was easy by just using the \"connect a thing\" feature. Once I got the hang of it I was able to reroute all the devices to the new network in no time\n3. Building routines - There are routines and then there are smart apps, I wanted to replicate the \"If then\" i hade on micasaverde and discovered that smartapps gave me the functionality I needed. Again building these in smartapps were very easy and intuitive.\n4. Alexa/Amazon Echo integration - My other reason for buying this hub. Setting up the integration was very easy and so far I have had no issues with using Alexa to turn things on and off as desired. (that said I haven't yet found a way to make Alexa trigger a routine)\n\nThings to improve upon\n1. Documentation - As good as non existent.\n2. IP Camera - Right now it supports a handful of DLink or Samsung cameras. I do not understand why I cannot specify the IP address of an existing camera and use it. Not asking for tilt/pan functionality"}
{"Author": "Tirso Cruise", "Date": "on June 7, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "faster but needs more refinement", "Text": "I upgraded for the original smartthings and it wasn't that easy. All your devices must be remove and the old system rather than transfer to new via software. So it means going to all the devices to remove using zwave utilities then when you remove all, you then have to connect all again to new and re-program all your routines etc, like starting all over again. Some devices like sirens are a pain if you have it installed on odd locations that requires ladder. Anyway, it's done. With more than 30+ devices, it's faster response from my old smartthings. Some of the devices flaws are same and contacted tech support to let them know (it takes a while for them to response, about 2 days average via email), by that time I figure some things out by trial and error. What I don't like is the external power supply. Before I'm able to power the hub via usb from my router but no more. You can't power this via USB. I don't get the battery backup since without a/c power, what's the point, my devices won't work anyways. It seems like the new software is so so. The older app seems easier to program with if then. The routines doesn't have much option as I would like. I had to create multiple routines as oppose to one from old app. I do like the integration with Echo, yet smartthings still don't have app for amazon tablet (boo!!!!)."}
{"Author": "Ilya", "Date": "on June 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very disappointed with this product", "Text": "Very disappointed with this product. After all the hype, I decided to upgrade from Vera Lite that I'm currently using. I have over 50 z-wave products in my house and setting them up from the phone is a nightmare. No desktop/web interface available. And even mobile UI is pretty horrible. No search available for the product name? I have to scroll through a huge list of categories and guess where my products might be. I don't care about security and fire production features, yet there's no way to customize landing screen of the application (Dashboard). Very limited APIs available in comparison to Vera. No custom UIs and mobile applications.\nNo official (or easily accessible unofficial) integration with Nest that had open APIs since day one. The only product that I have that has better integration with SmartThings then with Vera is Honeywell thermostat. And even that has an integration with Vera, it's just not very good.\nIn comparison with Vera, SmartThings requires Internet connection for more or less everything (except the simplest operation). Vera only needs internet connection for logging in and logs, everything else will work offline just fine.\nOverall feels like a major step down from Vera Lite, that's been on the market for three times as long as (not very) SmartThings."}
{"Author": "Garrett B Neuenkirchen", "Date": "on June 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Solid Product - Good Device Integration", "Text": "I think I have 20 various devices attached to this thing now. Seems very compatible with a wide variety of products. Been using it for some time and it's solid and seems to have good range."}
{"Author": "DS", "Date": "on June 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Setup was simple and app connects to give control of ...", "Text": "Setup was simple and app connects to give control of all devices. So far 3 updates from Samsung have automatically been applied with no impact to paired devices and app logic was maintained."}
{"Author": "Carl R. Fox", "Date": "on June 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "First rate customer service", "Text": "There was something wrong, so the hub didn't work. I wrote a strongly worded email, and got a response first thing in the morning. Jake and I emailed back and forth, and samsung did some tweak on there end, and the hub started working. Jake even sent me detailed instructions on how to set up my front door lock. My smoke detector synced on the first try."}
{"Author": "PWsFinest", "Date": "on June 3, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A little buggy, but getting there.", "Text": "I started home automation with Vera, moved to Vera 2, and then to VeraEdge. It was good to tinker with, but still had the \"made in someone's garage\" type feel. Once Samsung bought SmartThings and released this second generation hub, I made the switch. It was super simple to setup. The App is easy to use and has some nice features. If the Samsung app and official support doesn't have what you're looking for, you can go to the intranets and get code for many more smartapps. That part is for more advanced users, but it's not hard to learn how. I have Blink cameras and a MyQ garage door opener and everything integrates beautifully. Samsung just needs to devote a little more resources to this to make it great. There are a few features that have been requested over and over that haven't been implemented, but I prefer having the big name behind the product."}
{"Author": "Doc B", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Finally got it to work", "Text": "Initially had some problems as it the hub was showing up as inactive. Newer versions need a update pushed per customer service. After the update I can control some of my switches and lights."}
{"Author": "Fiftyohm", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good with the Exho", "Text": "Good compatibility with the Echo. So far, OK with a mix of Z-Wave devices."}
{"Author": "John D. Kelner", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "BUY THIS", "Text": "I love this and its interconnection with Alexa. Much better than Samsung SmartThings which I returned - did not work."}
{"Author": "Wesley T.", "Date": "on June 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "VERY EASY SETUP", "Text": "I love technology but HATE setup ... only because I can easily get confused and/or frustrated. This product is so easy to set up!! Connecting other devices to it was simple as well (I connected the Fibaro flood sensor). I'm very happy with this product and highly recommend it!"}
{"Author": "Tyler Forge", "Date": "on June 1, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not quite ready for prime time", "Text": "I gifted this to a friend for Christmas. The report back is luv-luv-luv-luv\n\nThat said, various articles report that SmartThings is suffering from its own success. People are plugging in more devices than the designers seem to have been prepared for. Or maybe they lost control of software quality. Dunno. My friend still loves his but he hasn't plugged much into it yet yet.\n\nAs of now, May of 2016, I wouldn't get a SmartThings hub. Maybe Samsung will have the issues worked out in a few months, but for now - no.\n\nI personally use the wink hub and have been happy with it for about a year."}
{"Author": "G T.", "Date": "on June 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not what I want at all....", "Text": "If you have days then this is your product. I have not been able to set it up. Every time it crashes you HAVE TO CONTACT customer support via email to reset the password code. this has taken hours each time. Bad planning and execution. Product is not easy to use, and customer support is slow."}
{"Author": "B.", "Date": "on June 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "EASIEST SET UP EVER!", "Text": "I have to say, this was the EASIEST set up of any network device I've ever done.\n\nI hook it up in literally 2 mins. That's counting opening the box, ok maybe not opening the box.\n\nDownloaded the app on my galaxy, entered my info and code provided, and it was working. Next step was to set up my Z Wave Lock and that was also an easy set up, just had to look it up in the App added it no problem.\n\nLooking to add more devices in the near future."}
{"Author": "George Kleczka", "Date": "on May 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Kind of a pain but worth it"}
{"Author": "ND", "Date": "on May 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it. Have a lot of stuff hooked to ...", "Text": "Love it. Have a lot of stuff hooked to this baby. Works great. Nice web application and great interconnection between all devices attached to this."}
{"Author": "Bobby R", "Date": "on May 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This was/is great. This is more for rule base house automation", "Text": "This was/is great. This is more for rule base house automation, not so much for security. Lowes is more security oriented but the free version of Sirus is limited and doesn't have the rule base in free version."}
{"Author": "Country Boy", "Date": "on May 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Support is not that good and doesn't work with my Schlage Connect Z-wave lock.", "Text": "I bought this solely to control my new Schlage Connect Touchscreen Deadbolt on my VRBO second home. I read that lock codes could be entered remotely with a hub. This hub was highly rated so I bought it. After several calls to support, one tech told me there was an unsupported app that would do this and directed me to the sight for it. After wasting about a day trying to get it working, I still was no where.\nIt's now 3 months later and it still isn't working.\nThey don't offer anything that works with windows but you can go online and work with it a little. Also, apparently they were going through some transition and I ended up with two different accounts in two places which is confusing to me and more confusing to them.\nThe only app Smartthings provides is one that tells you if the lock is locked and allows you to lock or unlock it. In other words it's strictly a toy.\nWhy not get the app working to handle the capabilities this lock offers???\nThis schlage lock is very nice but the idea is I need the ability to enter codes remotely for my renters.\nI believe it was Wink hub so I may end up replacing smartthings with something that will work.\nRecently I connected it to my Total Comfort thermostat but the app really doesn't come close to the free online app offered by Honeywell. About all you can do is set the temperature whereas Honeywell allows you to set up a 4 time 7 day schedule or to put on a temporary or permanent hold when you are away.\nSummary, Smartthings just doesn't have the programming up to speed so look elsewhere."}
{"Author": "apr", "Date": "on May 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I was sad to see a product that looks like it picks ...", "Text": "It will not pick up your products that you may already have. It works only with the products it sells you or on the list of approved products. Even if you have the right product but the wrong signal it still will not work. I was sad to see a product that looks like it picks up all signals did not work for any of my wifi items (camera) my lights (zigbee) or thermostat (radio/wifi). I would recommend this if you are starting new and have to buy everything. If you already have items and you see it on the list make sure it is the right model number because that will tell you if the right signal is in play if not your item will not work.\n\nSad to say we sent it back the good part Amazon was great about it."}
{"Author": "vj", "Date": "on May 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not good", "Text": "This hub is really funny, promising lot of stuff and not working anything properly. If someone serious about home automation/ smart home projects look something else"}
{"Author": "Toby Asplin", "Date": "on May 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lump Samsung in with the rest of the manufacturers who don't adequately test their products.", "Text": "So far, I'm not impressed. The setup process hung up and cycled for nearly an hour on two different mobile devices (Droid Turbo and iPad Mini). I finally had to force close the app, unplug the hub and start over again. While initial setup problems are not unique to Samsung's products, Samsung - like other \"smart\" product manufacturers - needs to realize that first impressions (setup) are lasting impressions. There are a few manufacturers whose setups run simply and flawlessly so it can be done. With a 30+ year background in technology, my guess is that Samsung is rushing products to market without adequate testing. Time to step up your game, Samsung."}
{"Author": "MrWizzerd", "Date": "on May 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I like Smartthings.", "Text": "I like Smartthings. Does what I need it to do, with very little hassle. Only drawback is that if it looses connection, you have to be there to reset it. Since I have this on a UPS, it does not loose connection, unless I do something to the network gear to cause it."}
{"Author": "David Burch", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't do it.", "Text": "Pure junk. Even the pre-installed programs won't run consistently, with only 5 things. The geofence 'sensor' fails almost daily. While I was on vacation, they pushed an update and froze my hub. There is no way I can find to control the updates. Asked for service help and days later got a 'form letter' type email assuring me I was a valued customer and thanking me for my patience. What makes these idiots think I'm patient? I'm looking for a replacement today."}
{"Author": "mdci", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "too bad that the bluetooth is not enables", "Text": "no bluetooth, the rest is fine"}
{"Author": "R Voorhees", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Avoid the SmartThing Hub - automation works inconsistently, or not at all", "Text": "I wanted so much to believe the good reviews of this product... surely the large fraction of 1- and 2-star reviews had to just be haters, right? Sadly, my own recent experience makes it impossible to give this product anything but 1 star. The only positive thing I can say is that installation and setup were very simple; my hub was up and running in 5-10 minutes, and my 2 GE Z-Wave Smart Switches were added shortly thereafter. (There was a bit of work involved, chatting with Support, because these devices had been part of a different Z-Wave network and had not been properly disconnected/removed from that network; but that process was to be expected, and fairly painless.)\n\nBeyond that, I have nothing good to say. Relative to other people with installations of scores or hundreds of Z-Wave devices, I only had 2 devices. Even without attempting automation, the results were inconsistent. I would \"turn on\" one of the lights via my iPhone app, then go to that room only to find that the light *wasn't* on... same thing trying to turn off a light that was on - the app would say it was off, but it was really still on. If the SmartThings hub can't correctly keep track of whether a device is on or off, what chance does it have to get any automation to work reliably?!\n\nFor automation, I tried installing the \"Smart Lights\" SmartApp that Samsung recommends. At about 5pm, I set it up to turn both lights on at 7pm, and to turn them off at 10pm - not a very challenging scenario. No dependencies on Home versus Away mode, or anything like that. I then went about my evening and forgot about things for a while. Only when it got to about 8:15pm, and I noticed that neither light had been turned on, did I really start to wonder if all of the negative reviews were true. Earlier today, I deleted the Smart Lights app and installed instead the \"Vacation Lighting Director\" app, since its intent matched pretty exactly what I wanted (randomly turning lights on and off in the evening, to simulate people in the house when everyone is really away). I had more success with this app; it randomly cycled power to the light in the room I was in a few times in the first 2 hours I had the scenario running. But I found once again that the iPhone app couldn't reliably show the actual state of the lights; it showed one light as \"off\" when it was really on, and vice versa for the other light. I suspect this is a problem of the iPhone app, rather than the Vacation Lighting Director smartapp - but in either case, the end result is a Z-Wave controller where I can't reliably count on the reported state of any of the controlled devices. That's a very, very bad thing for one of the supposed leaders in home automation..."}
{"Author": "UMPiloto", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Very buggy and unreliable."}
{"Author": "Ram", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "It works with Amazon echo"}
{"Author": "Mark H", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My Smart Home started with a SmartThings Hub. After adding an Echo, Envisalink, Harmony Hub & Rachio I truly have a smart home!", "Text": "I bought the Smartthings Hub last November with a few light switches to automate. I already had an Amazon Echo and quickly integrated it with the hub and switches. I loved being able to control the lights by voice. (Simple things like turn on the light above the kitchen sink via the Echo - handy when my hands are dirty).\n\nWithin a few months I added and integrated so much more. A Harmony Hub to control my TV/entertainment center (including a Fire TV and HTPC), an Envisalink (which through some programming connected my existing wired alarm to Smartthings), door locks, garage openers, connectivity and routines via IFTTT, a Rachio sprinkler/garden controller and more.\n\nWhen we want to watch TV I tell the echo to \"Turn on TV Time\" and my Family Room lights turn on, my first floor lights turn off and the TV turns on. When the last person goes to sleep he/she tells the echo to \"Turn on Sleepytime\" which turns on a hall light, then 30 seconds later turns off all lights, turns on the alarm system (via my Smartthings integration with Envisalink), locks the front door, and turns off the entertainment system (via Smartthings integration with Harmony). (\"Sleepytime\" would turn on by default at 12:30am if no one manually sets it). When anyone in the family comes home, the presence of their phone is detected which turns off the alarm system and unlocks the front door. And there is just so much more that I have Smartthings programmed to do.\n\nThe Envisalink and the HTPC integration requires code to be run on a computer. But almost everything else is done through Smartthings apps. Some tasks are simple, others more complicated. I also use IFTTT for a few tasks (like telling Siri to open or close my garage doors).\n\nUp until a few weeks ago I would have given the Smartthings Hub 5 stars. But I experienced two glitches recently. The first glitch was when my Family Room lights came on for no reason. The second glitch was an outage when nothing worked for about 15 minutes. Overall, I would have thought these to be minor annoyances as they are the only glitches I've had over a seven month span. But, when I looked into this more, I found that my issues are related to the Smartthings cloud (many Smartthings tasks run from the cloud using the Smartthings back end database that has had some issues and outages lately). Some other users have also experienced problems.\n\nEdit (6/9/16): I am downgrading my rating from 4 to 2 stars. Oh, how I want things to work smoothly again. I have had a number of issues over the past two weeks. Mainly there are the delays. Previously, commands executed within a few seconds. Now, while most commands execute quickly, some take 10-20 seconds. And there are times where commands execute after a significant delay. I've had a few delays in the range of 15 minutes to just over an hour. On 3 occasions I came home expecting my door to be unlocked and a light on (from a presence sensor), but that was not be the case. The command to unlock the door and turn on the light DID execute, but each time it was after I was in the house - with a delay as long as 20 minutes after entering. I do have many devices and from what I've read it appears that the more devices you have the more likely there will be issues like these. Another issue is that my My Amazon Echo stopped recognizing the 'Sleepytime' switch. If I remove/add the switch it works again, but the fix is only temporary. I don't know if this is an issue with Smartthings or the Echo.\n\nI have also removed my HTPC and replaced it with a FireTV. My initial thoughts are that I like the FireTV more - especially with it's easy integration into home automation (via the Harmony Hub).\n\nEdit (11/10/17): Upgrading this back to 4 stars. While there still are some delay issues - these are relatively minimal considering how much I use Smartthings every day. There is about 1 glitch or major delay per month."}
{"Author": "KBD", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It works for what I'm doing.", "Text": "It was easy to setup and does what I need. I only have my thermostat, 2 door dead bolts, a garage door, and an outlet on it, but they all work well. Really happy I went this route."}
{"Author": "Neil Delimont", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This product is so freaking awesome. I can now control my whole home with ...", "Text": "This product is so freaking awesome. I can now control my whole home with my smart phone anywhere in the world. I can also control it through voice with Amazon echo. All my devices, electronics, lights, security system, etc... All are automated. You can set up certain routines to happen based on certain parameters and it is also compatible with IFTTT to do even more. This is one of the best inventions ever! It has worked like a charm too. No complaints."}
{"Author": "Dan Rayburn", "Date": "on May 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a waste of time.", "Text": "I bought the hub and multiple peripherals. The app that supposedly works with it hangs up when during its initial step. The lights on the hub but the app won't advance so the peripherals can be configured. Tech support is a joke. You get emails every day asking about things you've already explained. It seems they are not concerned about fixing anything. I am returning the product."}
{"Author": "Dave", "Date": "on May 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Plain great! Yes as technology gets better, so will this....", "Text": "This is exactly what I wanted, I had another competitor for years, though home automation has come a long ways, this little device is great. Yes there are some things that could be added, yet it might just mean I need to search a way to do it. My entire house is z-wave, so I have about 30-40 devices, and this handles it smoother and quicker than my last device, plus added bonus this supports more than just z-wave.\n\nI strongly recommend looking at IFTTT with this device, it integrates wonderfully and helps me out a lot. I also am waiting on miss Alexa to get here to try the integration with that. It'll be fun to be able to tell SmartThings hub what to do via voice command."}
{"Author": "Desert Dweller", "Date": "on May 21, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An excellent way to quickly set up household security and automation", "Text": "This is my second Smart Things control unit. Frankly, I don't know the difference between my first generation unit and my second generation unit! They just work and are so easy to set up.\n\nMy purpose in getting them was mostly to have a system of some sort that would alert me when doors are opened. As a bonus, they also work with my Z wave door locks. Both units were used to monitor unoccupied homes that were going through remodeling efforts. The Smart Things hub is a very quick and inexpensive way to set up a perimeter around the house. I used the AEON recessed sensors in each door because they are SO unobtrusive. In addition, I used the units, in conjunction with Z wave light switches, to control exterior lights. I also had one interior light set up to come on at dusk.\n\nOnce I figured out how easy it is to configure things on this unit, I was very impressed. The instructions that come with the accessories are not always very complete, but the accessories are the same ones that are used with other z wave systems so it's a wash. Generally, you start with the Smart Things app on your phone, tell it to look for a new item, then press the button on the device you're adding to get it to connect.\n\nOne hard learned lesson was that once the Smart Things hub and the Z wave device connect, a screen will pop up in your Smart Things app, asking which other app you wish to control the item you just connected. You'd better do your homework ahead of time, because it is difficult to figure out how to control your \"thing\" you just added unless you pick an app as you initially install it.\n\nEventually, I figured out how to remove the device from Smart Things, then add it again so I could use the correct app. The technology works, but it has a little bit of a learning curve. Likewise, the Smart Things web site is not terribly supportive. You're better off using Google to ask your specific question than if you try to search the Smart Things support section.\n\nAmong the big pros for Smart Things:\n\n1. It uses Z wave - which is getting pretty universal. I believe it also uses Zigbee.\n2. It is inexpensive for a hub that can do so many things.\n3. There are NO monthly fees, even for advanced functions.\n4. Connecting new \"things\" to the hub is pretty painless\n5. Alerts can be emailed or texted very quickly\n\nI have a third Z wave hub that is much more powerful and not that much more expensive. It's just a bit too powerful for most folks to set up, but it's the unit I use at my home. It allows much more complex scenarios that you can set up yourself without an app. For most folks, I suggest starting with the Smart Things, then decide if you want something with more features.\n\nIn short - I don't hesitate to endorse the Smart Things hub as a good starting place for beginners who wish to quickly and inexpensively set up a home automation system."}
{"Author": "travelwise", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "dont buy it... it doesn't deliver as ...", "Text": "dont buy it...it doesn't deliver as promised. doesn't confirm if lights are on or off. sometimes they turn on sometimes not...you need a camera to actually see its doing what it is supposed to do."}
{"Author": "Matt", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overly Automated Home!", "Text": "I am using this with my Amazon alexa to control all my Z wave devices (Light switches), Nest and Logitech Hub (for contriving the TV). The marketplace is great for apps, you have endless possibility with this device!"}
{"Author": "Neverfast", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great and easy to use", "Text": "No issues with it at all. Super easy to set up and works great with my amazon echo products. No issues hooking up multiple devices of different brands would recommend."}
{"Author": "Dan", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No Regrets! I would buy again!", "Text": "If you like gadgets and home automation, buy this! I spent hours reading reviews and trying to decide if this was the right hub for me. I installed it a week ago and I love it. Some reviews talked about failures and glitches. I have not had any.\n\nAlexa is the perfect compliment to the system. It's nice to be able to control kitchen lights by voice when your hands are full or wet. It's also pretty handy to have Alexa adjust the temperature if you're busy in the kitchen. Combining this with Alexa has renewed my home automation bug.\n\nIt installed surprisingly easy. I was replacing an existing Nexia home automation system. In less than 2 hours I had unenrolled all of my devices (2 thermostats, 1 door lock, 8 dimmers/switches) from the Nexia bridge and enrolled them on the SmartThings hub. I had most of the automation programmed within that first two hours. Once everything was enrolled I spent several hours playing around and getting to know the app while watching TV. Over that course of time I learned to fine tune my events a bit more. Admittedly the user interface is not as friendly as Nexia, but the trade off is more capabilities and more integrated products. I particularly like that it uses our phones to know when we are home or away. I am able to trigger events based upon the coming and going of individual phones. The ultimate bonus is getting more functionality without the monthly subscription. I didn't give much thought to the $10 Nexia Subscription, but free is free!!\n\nFor those who are replacing a Nexia system, my tip is to pull the instructions and read how to unenroll your existing devices. This must be done physically using the Nexia bridge (hub). I had to carry my bridge around to each device and do a series of button pushing. Removing devices on the website does not unenroll them. THEY MUST BE UNENROLLED BEFORE YOU CAN ENROLL THEM ON A NEW DEVICE LIKE SMARTTHINGS.\n\nTrane Thrmostats:\nI can confirm that the Trane TZEMT500BB32 and Trane XL624 thermostats do work with the SmartThings hub. I have full functionality, including temperature control, fan control, and mode control from the app. I can manually change both thermostats from the app and I can program a temperature change at bedtime, morning and when we are away. That's plenty enough for me, but less options than Nexia provided. I am still looking for a way to program two thermostats at two different temperatures more effectively. I can only program one temperature at each mode change. I can choose to send the temperature to one or both thermostats, but I can not send a different temperature to each. Overall, I'm happy with how SmartThings controls the Thermostats.\n\nCameras:\nNexia camera's do not work with SmartThings. I chose t replace my cameras with D-Link cloud cameras using their free app with no monthly subscription. Smarthings gives you a list of compatible D-link cameras. You can integrate those cameras into your SmartThings app, but that will incur a monthly subscription at some point in the future. It's currently free as a beta program."}
{"Author": "Rita", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Looks good :)", "Text": "Have not used it yet. Once I try it, will update review accordingly."}
{"Author": "pinellasproofer", "Date": "on May 19, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "a bit frustrating with Echo", "Text": "I would have returned this if it wasn't the only hub that could easily connect my Harmony Hub to my Echo with normal voice control. The connection is not reliable.\n\nIt lost connection with my GE link light. Having to uninstall and reinstall with the horrible app was a pain.\n\nIt also has to plug directly into your router. The Wink does not.\n\nI'm giving it 3 stars since it can connect my Echo to more devices than the Wink."}
{"Author": "MV", "Date": "on May 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Work's very well with my zwave lock."}
{"Author": "Spencer", "Date": "on May 15, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I bought this to automate a lot of functions within ...", "Text": "I bought this to automate a lot of functions within my home. For some reason, the hub goes down every so often, and I have no idea why. The mobile app software is a little unpolished. It was able to successfully identify my Jasco ZWave lights. If they improved the stability and reliability of the hub, mobile app, and service, I'd improve my rating."}
{"Author": "Vlad", "Date": "on May 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The hub stopped working in 2 months - useless. During this period I locked/unlocked the door with ...", "Text": "The hub stopped working in 2 months - useless.\nDuring this period I locked/unlocked the door with my iphone about 30 times(including testing)\nI used only for a Schlage Connect Century Touchscreen Deadbolt door lock - not multiple devices.\nMy primary decision for SmartThings guh was based on Samsung's reputation - total disappointment now.."}
{"Author": "Joe R.", "Date": "on May 14, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Completely unreliable, unstable, even on my 4th replacement hub", "Text": "Not reliable, zero improvement in the past 12 months. The addition of \"local processing\" over cloud is a marketing gimmick. Only the glitchy smart lighting app is authorized to run locally. What's worse, when running locally its even more unreliable!\n\nCloud is completely unstable, gotten much worse in the past 12 months. They lose a star for creating a \"status\" web dashboard page that always indicates everything is running great, but regularly admit via support email that things aren't working for \"some customers\".\nForced Firmware updates have bricked 2 of my hubs. They do get a star for the hassle free warranty replacements. But they lose points for not having anyway to backup and restore. You must go through a 10 hour process to force delete items, unscrew them from the walls, hold them next to the hub, screw them back in, delete and recreate every simple automation you've made before.\n\nThey lose a star for marketing built in Bluetooth support, but customers are not able to access it.\n\nI should add this platform should never ever be used as a real alarm system. I discovered, as many others before me, that all you will get is false positives, and no way for you to fix anything without support email. In fact it didn't work at all when a neighbor did break into my house, the system had reset to disarmed for no reason. If you use a mobile device to automatically lock and unlock your doors, beware the geofence radius is huge. They do not use bluetooth or wifi assist to make it at least as small as wifi range. Instead, my geofence covers the next 27 houses, and the highway. Smart things says customers shouldn't use their phones, and should use the zigbee keychains. But as many other customers have found, that's even more unreliable. Smart things will disarm and unlock your doors for no reason, when the cloud says your dongle has arrived or departed when it hasn't or they just reset something on the cloud side. Apartment dwellers you have been warned.\n\nThey lose a star for not adapting their iOS app to iPad (which would take less than a few hours for them in Xcode by the way). They don't even have some form of web interface for a computer. The main concern here, is that you must register as a developer to even accomplish basic tasks like viewing the status of your devices. Did the device install local or cloud? What's my zigbee channel?\n\nThey get the second star for having some scripting access and being tinker friendly. The system is really locked down. It is not hacker friendly. You can't access the zwave or zigbee logs directly. You can't modify the radio channels, or add huge missing features like ota firmware updates to wireless devices, or even simple things like zwave device association.\n\nFrom what I have seen, Samsung bought smartthings to only integrate with the Samsung major home appliances. In fact new Samsung tv's will come out with \"smartthings\" integration, as long as you don't consider zwave, zigbee home automation to be part of it anymore. The future of this platform is uncertain."}
{"Author": "E. A. Herrera", "Date": "on May 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent", "Text": "Easy setup, works great with my Cree lights. Happy customer."}
{"Author": "gmau", "Date": "on May 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fun, works, smart home 2.0", "Text": "I haven't seen any of the issues that I've read here. As long as you have a decent zwave mesh network across your home I feel you won't have any issues with this hub. The community support is great and it has linked to 90% of my smarthome devices (more than initially I thought it was \"compatible\" with) So much better than using ADT pulse. Samsung are constantly improving the hub via firmware updates and the mobile apps are getting constant updates."}
{"Author": "MikeF", "Date": "on May 11, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I configured it with 5 smart locks, one motion detector", "Text": "I was able to get this set up and working in no time. I configured it with 5 smart locks, one motion detector, two wall switches (lights), and two iPhones. Adding devices was fairly easy though I had trouble with one of the smart locks. And I had trouble with the Ecolink motion detector. The Smartthings hub insisted on recognizing it as a door sensor. I found a work around on the SmartThings community forum. Lots of good info on the community forum.\n\nI've had it for a little over a month now and have had issues with the SmartApps working consistently. Sometimes the sensors trigger the corresponding Routine and sometimes not. I've had to delete just about all of the SmartApps I've setup and re-install them and so far they seem to be working more consistently. I'm wondering if a firmware update shortly after I installed the hub may have messed with the SmartApps. The user interface is okay but I see room for improvement in how it's laid out. It can be really easy to create and lose track of overlapping routines making it difficult to track why a light came on or went off at an unexpected time, for example. I'm giving this two stars based on my experience so far and the time I've wasted having to figure out why something didn't work as it was supposed to. If after having reinstalled the SmartApps and getting another firmware update the SmartApps start working consistently I'll change my rating."}
{"Author": "Me22", "Date": "on May 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it should be better.", "Text": "Neat but quirky. Worth the money though. As they develop it further, it should be better."}
{"Author": "C.J", "Date": "on May 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "How do you run a present day company like this. No phone only email", "Text": "TECH SUPPORT VIRTUALLY NON EXISTANT! How do you run a present day company like this. No phone only email. What? Yes. Unbelievable. Every time we want to add a device we have problems and have to write in and then wait days for a response. This should be illegal. Do not buy their products. Save yourself the frustration."}
{"Author": "Doug", "Date": "on May 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not reliable. Prepare to be frustrated and annoyed!", "Text": "Not reliable. Every few days it goes \"inactive\" and has to be unplugged to reset it. I have it plugged in out of sight next to my router so it's not the most accessible spot to unplug. It did connect with a GE light switch and lyric thermostat with no problem and works beautifully when it's not \"inactive\". Probably going to keep it but I'm not happy with it at all. I'll update further after working with customer service and connecting more devices."}
{"Author": "Amzilla", "Date": "on May 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Like it", "Text": "hooked up with a lot of Z-wave switches and Amazon Echo. Basically work good, but once a while the timer program won't work and need to re-installed to make it work again."}
