{"Author": "Keith Alan", "Date": "on May 9, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Going wireless", "Text": "I did my research and found this one to be my better option. for $99 it is worth it. I connected it to my router and downloaded the app as instructed. Setting up the Hub was pretty simple. Setting up devices to the hub is not as easy. Once I got them working it has worked well. My only real complaint is the app. It duplicates the name of the device. So I have two living room lights when in reality I only have one."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "does what it suppose to"}
{"Author": "Ray Detwiler", "Date": "on May 9, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, works well so far!", "Text": "7/11/2017\nI have been using this hub for over a year now, and until recently I was satisfied with it, with a few exceptions.\nCurrently I have a garage door opener, 3 motion sensors, 2 dimmers, 2 normal switches, a thermostat, 4 door sensors, and 6 osram light bulbs running.\nI had a security camera and some other lightbulbs that I had originally purchased, but SmartThings decided to stop supporting those, so even though I had shelled out $100 on the security camera, 3 months later it was no longer supported. I can still access it through the camera's own software/app but that kinda was the whole reason I purchased that specific camera so that was a bummer.\n\nLately my biggest complaint is that the hub will just randomly perform our \"i'm back\" routine in the middle of the night. This, of course, involves turning on lights, disarming the security, and opening the garage door. So at 3 am I'm waking up to all the lights on in the house, and an open garage. The GoControl garage door opener has not been working properly for the last 3-4 months (see review on that) so even though I tell it to close itself from the upstairs master, I have NO idea if is actually close unless I go downstairs and check on it in person.\n\nThe hub ran great when I first purchased it. However, over time, and with more and more updates, it has started acting differently and sometimes won't recognize that my wife or I are home. We will sit in the driveway and wait for it to open the house up (until we lose patience and do it ourselves), it has somehow lost connection with 2 of the 3 motion sensors (2 different brands) and just lists them as \"unavailable\" despite them having over 50% battery left. A hard reset will reconnect them, but only for a day or so max.\nEvery time Samsung releases updates for the hug I expect this stuff to go away, but it never does.\n\nAll in all, I'd still recommend this hub, but not to someone who isn't comfortable with technology and troubleshooting.\ndropping it to 3 stars as it is becoming more and more unreliable as time goes by.\nIf someone from Samsung is reading this, I'd love your advice on how to fix the random, middle of the night routines, despite it having performed the \"i'm back\" routine for me at 9pm when i actually did get home. It did it to me 3 times last night between 1 and 5 am. :(\n\n5/9/2016\nFirst attempt at any kind of home automation. Ordered this and a GE 12722 Z-wave switch. Received both overnight from Amazon despite choosing 2 day shipping (thanks Amazon!).\n\nSetting up the hub was super simple, and I was happy to see it was all able to be done with the smartphone app, as my computer was having some minor issues. Setup itself took about 10 minutes, during which the app just did its thing and no input was required from me.\n\nAfter that I set up the wall switch (which took longer than setting up the hub itself). Once both were set up, everything paired well and there were no issues.\nHoping to add a few more goodies over time, but starting small. Next are TCP Connect lights, a dimmer switch, some thermostats, and a garage door opener. Will try to keep this updated as I go."}
{"Author": "Chris E", "Date": "on May 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Compatible with Amazon Echo without the need of hub"}
{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good bye to the Old smart things hello Samsung", "Text": "Be Careful. I have both versions. Things that worked well with the older hub do not work correctly with the new one. New features not worth losing reliable operation and already security flaws have been found. Great support but unable to recover the same performance I have with the old one. They seem to be OK with saying that device is not really supported by smart things. No need to say you support a standard like Zwave if you are going to say in the end a Zwave device is not really supported."}
{"Author": "SeattleSwade", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No complaints about the hub...the app though...", "Text": "The product is sound, the app is quirky.\n\nWhile the app has been updated 2-3x since I bought my SmartThings hub, it's still a bit wonky, but when the app works, I see that the hub is doing exactly what it should do. So far, there are only a few sensors and a door lock connected, but I see myself adding many more as the years go by. I'll stick with this until something a whole lot better comes along."}
{"Author": "salih", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "perfect"}
{"Author": "Chad Moroni", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Its taken over my house and love how easy it is to use."}
{"Author": "Robert Stamps", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings Weak Point is nothing works if there is an internet outage", "Text": "The Smartthings works well and is easy to startup and to find new devices (things). It has a weak point however that anyone who buys the system should be aware. If the internet goes down nothing works at all. Samsung states that on the V2 some enabled apps should work locally. As a home security device the Smartthings needs to execute the routines regardless of power (battery backup) or internet availability at least until the internet and/or power outage is resolved."}
{"Author": "Tom Steele", "Date": "on May 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not readywork", "Text": "Matthew from Samsung has commented below. I thought that I would address a couple of those things here. First, I am aware that Smartthings and MyQue are not listed as compatible. They do work fairly well together though if you can navigate through copy-ninja's smart app and install it properly. Right now, after spending and hour or two at \"work\" with my co-worker trying to get things up and running, we were able to get Alexa, via Smartthings, to open my garage door. She won't close it back, but she will open it reliably. Which is not ideal, but a step in the right direction.\n\nI was NOT aware that smartthings and Hue didn't play well together. It is in your APP - so that is very confusing. I guess that I assumed Hue was sort of a standard in smart home functionality. Again, Wink works with BOTH of these things, very well. In fact, if it weren't for the unsupported ability to use Alexa and Smartthings together to use voice commands, I would find it very hard to see why I need the smartthings hub at all. The Wink hub is cheaper (even free I am told if you buy the right light kit) and hooks into a LOT of stuff natively.\n\nI will update soon when I get more functionality from the samsung smartthings hub. I believe Samsung will make this great eventually. But right now I've got customer service telling me that everything I'm trying to do is unsupported even though some of the things are in the app itself. That's a bad sign Matthew. When you have your app telling me to link up to the Hue lights but you are saying that I shouldn't expect it to work because it isn't supported - well, that's not good. And you mentioned that I should check the compatibility list as if that exonerates Samsung from not working with these things. Yeah, perhaps legally and financially. But from the perspective of a review of whether it is a good product, nope. It doesn't change at all that I - the customer - want it to work with these very popular products and it doesn't. Which is my point, I feel that smartthings is perhaps best left to those who want to use ONLY Samsung sensors with it, and Wink is better if you want to interact with other companies like Philips Hue, Chamberlain MyQ garage door openers, and others.\n\n---------Originally posted 5/4/16------------\n\nI really want this to work. I'm very frustrated that I cannot get it to work and I'm one of those people that reads other reviews and thinks, \"Ha, I wonder what they are doing wrong that they can't get it to work, I bet it will work fine for me.\" Except, it isn't.\n\nTo compound things, I have the Wink hub and it largely does work.\n\nThe reason I even bought this hub is that a co-worker has 75 connected devices, 4 Echo's, 2 Dot's and a very automated home. I am much more technologically oriented than most people I know, and even he and I have different areas of expertise where I outrank him in some areas and he outranks me in others. It is the ideal arrangement. Instead of the usual parasitic friendship where one person milks the other for help, we are able to help each other in different areas.\n\nHe convinced me to get the SmartThings hub because I already had one Amazon Echo and the Chamberlin MYQ garage door opener (much better than garageio at much lower cost IMHO) and several smart outlets and door locks and thermostat, etc... In his words, \"Alexa is much better than Siri, and SmartThings lets you use Alexa aka Amazon Echo).\n\nSo I ordered the hub and hooked it up. Things went smoothly. However, my app has remained largely unpopulated (except it knows that I have an iPhone - that is the only device it has registered yet.) in part because Samsung wants me to press the button on my Philips Hue Hub and it is upstairs in the Theater Equipment Room connected to the router and not wanting to exercise and go up and down stairs is the whole reason for getting smart home stuff, right? But today I decided to use my friend's expertise to get my garage door opener working with Alexa.\n\nApparently this requires a workaround because the various companies have decided that we are too stupid or they will be too liable if they let you open doors and/or locks with Alexa because someone might stand outside your house and yell at the top of their lungs to unlock the front door or the garage door and then have access to your home. A valid concern I suppose, but one that I should - as the user - be able to decide. Not them.\n\nSo apparently someone has written custom code in the smart things community to operate the MYQ garage door opener via Alexa. I want that. It is one of the PRIMARY reasons I have invested in smart home tech.\n\nI couldn't get that to work, in spite of carefully following my co-worker's instructions.\n\nNext I decided to take a step back towards simplicity and just have the app search for connected items in my home. I suspect that I have 20-25 things at this point. It didn't find one thing. It just sits and spins and says it is looking for things and it could take some time...\n\nSo, I decided to take another step backwards and just get the Hue lights up and running. I went to install the Hue hub and followed the instructions in the app. It discovers the Hue Hub which is hard wired into my router via a smart switch (something you will need once you have more than four things going to your router) and it works great with the Wink Hub and the Phillips App. SmartThings discovered the hub and then told me to press the button on the Philips Hue hub (this is required for ANYTHING you do with the Philips Hue Hub) and as soon as I pressed the button on the hub, the app started flickering rapidly and then crashed. I restarted the app and it told me that it had sent an error message to home (Samsung) and so I tried again. It is a VERY repeatable crash. I sent an error report to Samsung and am waiting for instructions on what to do next.\n\nSo right now, I have a $99 hub that news when my iPhone gets home and leaves my house. And an app that crashes a lot and a github account with a garage door opening smart app within the smart app that seems to go nowhere and Alexa doesn't know where it is and it doesn't work.\n\nHopefully I have provided enough details that will let you decide that I am clearly doing something different than you would be doing and it will work great for you and you can go ahead and order it anyway. ;-). I looked very seriously into smart home devices a couple of years ago when Casa Verde was about the only thing out there and I came to the conclusion that it wasn't quite ready for prime time.\n\nI'm still not sure if it is ready for prime time. Sure, if you want turn some pretty lights on and off, there are some neat gadgets out there. But I'm not convinced you can throw away your ADT subscription yet. Perhaps the most frustrating thing is the lack of information about what is going wrong and lack of plans to try and figure it out and fix it. Right now I just feel helpless and have to hope against hope that customer service will write back and say, \"Oh yeah, here's what's wrong and here's how you fix it.\" But more likely they will write back and tell me to reboot the hubs or something like that, which I have already done..."}
{"Author": "Adam Anderson", "Date": "on May 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good early adopter device", "Text": "The Samsung SmartThings hub was easy to install and easy to get working. It also has tons of apps and devices that work with it to make it better.\n\nThe thing that I don't like is the lack of documentation on how to do things. They let the community write forum posts on how to get things done and those are very hit or miss on their quality.\n\nOverall it is a great early adopter device that can do a ton of stuff, but it is still a toy at this point for people that want to play with home automation. It will be years before this stuff is easy enough for the masses to do... if ever."}
{"Author": "josh cummings", "Date": "on May 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Avoid", "Text": "Incredibly unstable and frustrating to troubleshoot and repair constant issues. Tech support is virtually non-existent."}
