{"Author": "PrimeGuy", "Date": "on April 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I wasn't able to get consistent results with any device ...", "Text": "I wasn't able to get consistent results with any device, whether Samsung branded or not. Interesting for tinkering, but not ready for prime time yet."}
{"Author": "Art L. Lawing", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SMART HUB A WINNER.", "Text": "Set it up programed it and it worked great"}
{"Author": "Mrfixit", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Better than Iris Smartthings is Smart", "Text": "Was a little tricky to pair my items but has worked great every time I use it. No issues at all."}
{"Author": "Collin", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Firmware updates seem to cause issues", "Text": "I got this for my birthday. During normal operation it works great.\n\nOccasionally Samsung now sends me an email alerting me about a firmware update push to the hub. After this update I have connectivity issues for WEEKS. Yes, I have gone through the connectivity trouble shooting but it only helps temporarily. No, its not my ethernet cable. Just not connecting to the Hub from my phone wouldn't be so bad but the internal systems no longer work either. Internal button pushes don't activate things per the setup I made.\n\nIf this issue could be resolved it would be a great product. Here's to hoping that Samsung gets it together on that.\n\nUpdate: I have not had this issue for some time and I believe it to be fixed. I have changed my review therefore to 4 stars up from 2."}
{"Author": "Edwin H.", "Date": "on April 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Be careful!", "Text": "Been on the fence for a Smart Home for a little while now. Looked at the Samsung SmartThings hub and about a month ago saw a significant price drop...which made me suspicious. I didn't fall for the temptation to buy and decided to wait and see as I have seen this many times before; companies are either about to introduce a next gen or just totally abandon a product and try to empty their warehouses. As for SmartThings...I read an article this morning about a total failure of the system on CNET. The recent reviews on Amazon confirm the article. SmartThings seems to hold a promise...just not at this time. You can read the article here:[...]"}
{"Author": "M. Whisman", "Date": "on April 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy with my SmartThings Hub", "Text": "Very happy with my SmartThings Hub. I have them monitoring security as well as watching for any possible water leaks. Easy to setup and maintain."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not compatible with z-wave products and no support at all...", "Text": "\u0644\u0627 \u062a\u0639\u0645\u0644 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u064a \u0634\u0631\u0643\u0647 \u0627\u062e\u0631\u064a."}
{"Author": "AKCh", "Date": "on April 23, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Meh.", "Text": "After several months of use, my conclusion is: Meh.\n\nI have several sites where I use Zwave and I have several Veras and still make use of this device. For basic functionality, I think this hub is sufficient. However to do anything interesting, you really need to be able to write code to the API.\n\nAs a software engineer in a past life, I really like the API. However, there are useful basic functionality I find in the Vera that just works out of the box (like scenes and deep device integration).\n\nI like the mobile UI better on ST, but am disappointed there's no web interface. I'm also disappointed that despite what they say, you are really tied to the cloud in order for this thing to work. Been having a helluva time trying to arm and disarm the security features recently, and ST this past week confirmed in an email to their users that they were having issues. I can't afford for my security system to be at the whim of \"their cloud.\" I just need the box to work, and work independently.\n\nAlso if you plan to use any device that has calibration features (like Aeon's Multisensor 6 to measure temp and humidity), you won't be able to calibrate it with ST. There's just no interface for the adjustment parameters.\n\nNot that Vera is perfect, but it solves most of the issues out of the box. Where it falls short, it also has a decent enough API to write code to. However I'll probably still use ST in some of my sites where its less mission critical."}
{"Author": "David P", "Date": "on April 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Voice Activated Through Amazon Alexa, Works Fine For Me.", "Text": "I have been using the Version 1 Hub for about a Year and a half now, afraid to move to Version 2 as \"whats not broke don't fix it?\" I have mine hooked up through Amazon Alexa, with many switches, dimmers, sockets all voice activated. Other than having a few switches that stopped communicating with the hub, which I assume is a switch problem, I have not had any other problems and it has worked fairly flawlessly for me. I am happy with the purchase, and the voice activation is awesome :)"}
{"Author": "Jesus G. Villafranca", "Date": "on April 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent product. My first smart home hub product was ...", "Text": "Excellent product. My first smart home hub product was the Wink. While I was able to pair it to my garage door sensor (zwave), front door lock (zwave), a couple of outside lights (zwave) and the nest thermostat. It had a huge DELAYED, the problem was that it was a wireless device only (it had no RJ45/ethernet data port). So whenever I send a command or request status update of a device, it would take up to 20 seconds to respond. I return it for a full refund.\nI got this one instead because it has a RJ45/Ethernet data port. It connects directly to my router. Also repairing the devices from the wink to the SmartThings Hub was no problem. All devices work perfectly. Also I am able to set specific tasks to perform whenever a device gives up a specific status (such as my own cellphone, when leaving the house, make sure the lock is set) and a bunch of other tasks. In addition, it is open source and there is a community that is growing and building custom tasks/apps that solve specific problems (wink doesn't have that). For example, Nest Thermostat support is not officially supported but through the community, you are easily able to add it. Great product, easy to use, lots of features, easy to configure, it had a RJ45 port and it has a compartment for backup with AA batteries which even comes included!"}
{"Author": "Amazon customer", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waste of time and money", "Text": "Update\n\nThis thing inexplicably just stopped working. I'm literally just using it to handle 7 or so light switches. Waste of time and money. Changing my review to one star. More trouble than it's worth. Have had enough.\n---------\nI'm going to start this review off by saying my bar is low. All I am looking to automate is 4 GE z-wave light switches and then I'd like to add my Sonos and Nest systems if possible. I had a Revolv hub that worked perfectly but that has service is being discontinued as of May 2016.\n\nFirst, I tried the Wink hub. It was cheaper and had slightly better reviews. No dice on this one. It didn't seem to have a way to reset my GE switches that had already been assigned to the Revolv hub. Really simple stuff but after a couple of hours of fiddling, I gave up.\n\nNext I ordered this one. Setup took about twenty minutes and then I spent an hour or so attempting to connect my switches. I needed to reset them which required a search of the original manuals and some internet searches as well. This was an unreliable process but I eventually got it to work. From there it was pretty seamless.\n\nOn the whole, this thing seems to work for me for the little I've given it to do. Quite a positive given the sorry state of home automation gear but I'll take it!\n\nPositives\n- seems to work with light switches\n- user friendly and easy to use app based interface\n- straightforward process to setup routines. No coding required.\n- Samsung seems to be making a decent effort to support this product via an investment of resources\n\nNegatives\n- setup took longer than it needs to. An hour and a half for what should take 10 minutes\n- the hub has to remain manually connected to a router ie no wifi limiting range\n- no Nest support yet! This is an obvious one"}
{"Author": "Scott Cherkauer", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So easy to get this up and running", "Text": "So easy to get this up and running. I'm only just starting with home automation, but this thing really shows you the potential."}
{"Author": "K. S.", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Used to be a great system... Now not so much.", "Text": "For the past few months the entire SmartThings system has become unreliable. We have been huge fans for the past year and even recommended the product to others. Now I retract those recommendations and would say stay away. The system is unstable and developers are slow to fix known issues. The last issue took over a month to solve and it is still not 100%. Reliability matters. Hopefully our sensors and switches work with another hub.. such as wink or Staples connect."}
{"Author": "Justin", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best purchase I have made for our new house", "Text": "Best purchase I have made for our new house. I have most of the light on smart switches, i have water leak sensors under every sink, in the laundry room, and basement and have a Zen Thermostat controlling the HVAC. It has already paid for itself when our Washing Machine popped a hose and water started to overwhelm the drain pan. If it wasn't for the Leak Sensor going off and notifying me, it could of caused several thousand dollars in damage, to our brand new home. The washing machine is on the second floor but because of the Smart Hub and Leak Sensors no damage was caused."}
{"Author": "D808", "Date": "on April 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "DO NOT BUY!!!!!!", "Text": "Avoid this product. It just doesn't work period. False promises from Samsung about fixes are all lies. Run run run from this product. If you were db like me and purchased it, return it now while you can. Seriously the worst product ever."}
{"Author": "Gabriel Compton", "Date": "on April 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very disappointed in this product", "Text": "Very disappointed in this product. I have successfully installed many different types of electronics systems from the simple to the very complex so I was pretty confident in my ability to get this hub set up and working. Boy was I mistaken. The hub and associated GE switches in my application simply do not want to work reliably. The hub goes off line randomly and often for no reason that I can figure out. The paired switches work sometimes or not at all and even when they do they respond very slowly. Reset the entire thing multiple times and tried many tweaks to no avail. I have only tried tech support a couple times which takes frustrating long since it is email based. When nearly 1/3 of the reviews are at one star its a solid indication of significant customer frustration over a product clearly not meeting expectations."}
{"Author": "Wesley Kramer-Jones", "Date": "on April 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Product for a Smart Home!", "Text": "What can you say about the Samsung SmartThings Hub except, \"This product has changed my life!\" This product has changed how I interact with my home. This product has changed how I interact with my everyday life. This product has changed me for the better.\n\nI use this product to connect everything together in my home. It works seamlessly with lighting, an array of different sensors and with Amazon Echo.\n\nOne of my favorite features is being able to connect to IFTTT and other apps. With IFTTT I am able to add items to control my house from anywhere. I should point out that you can do this without IFTTT through the Samsung SmartThings app as well.\n\nWhen I first seen the commercials, I thought that this was an amazing product. Little did I know how much I would actually use it. I now can't imagine my life without it!"}
{"Author": "RYAN K POWERS", "Date": "on April 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost as unreliable as IFTTT.", "Text": "Very unreliable. I have yet to see any sort of consistency. Some days my lights are on, but the wrong color. Other days, they didn't come on at all. I have to work around the problems with a Tasker script to toggle between the mode I want and another mode that does nothing. After about 5 to 10 toggles everything might be in the right state. Maybe... Maybe not. The only reason this gets 2 stars instead of 1 is because it's slightly better than IFTTT."}
{"Author": "dgberk", "Date": "on April 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Makes a great paper weight.", "Text": "I bought this on Ebay. It was new, in sealed packaging. I've ha it less than a week andit will not power on. I went to the support page, which is the only contact available and followed the instructions to reset. As of now, the only thing I can do with it is keep my papers from flying away when I open the window."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product", "Text": "Works great so far. Paired with Alexa beautifully. So far only have after devices but no issues to date"}
{"Author": "Chief Minnechuk", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A very \"Techy\" product...", "Text": "A very \"Techy\" product... If you are not interested in tweaking, experimenting, and cajoling this gadget into doing what you want, then it is not for you. I'm going to keep it because I'm a techno-geek. It seems to be evolving and improving over time, but it is NOT the complete, robust, home management solution I thought it was. I'm keeping mine in the hope that things will get better, but if your are not ready for a serious commitment to noodling with this thing a lot, then stay away."}
{"Author": "RDR", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it was easy to setup and the app is pretty nice", "Text": "I am giving this a 4, it was easy to setup and the app is pretty nice. I haven't connected anything to it yet"}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A marraige made in heaven", "Text": "The Smartthings Hub and Amazon's Echo work so great with each other. Add some Leviton or GE dimmers and switches and you are on your way to some nice home automation."}
{"Author": "Matthew M", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome when it works, dissapointing when it doesnt.", "Text": "I expected much better from Samsung. I was super exited when I got it all working then an hour later half my switches were non responsive, the app kept saying your not authorized, unexpected error, or network issues. It took a couple days of tinkering but it seems to be working pretty well now. Very convenient to use my Amazon Echo to turn on the patio lights etc. I researched a few different home automation websites and found that although it is glitchy, it is still the best controller out there. Hopefully Samsung will soon update the app and controller to fix the issues."}
{"Author": "Lynox", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Did exactly what they said, it was intended to do..."}
{"Author": "Freeman", "Date": "on April 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "the best smart hub I have owned", "Text": "So far, the best smart hub I have owned, and I have owned a few ( wink, iris, link... ). Interface is easy to use, a bit slow at times, but nice. I like the fact that there is and available SDK and dev portal. I've had no problems with devices disappearing ( unlike the other hubs )."}
{"Author": "Sglee", "Date": "on April 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing customer service!", "Text": "Little complicated to set up, but amazing customer service. When I had a problem, they walked me through the set up helped me trouble shoot some networking issues."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible", "Text": "Terrible. The app that you have to use is the basically unusable. This technology just isn't ready for the masses yet."}
{"Author": "Andy Greenwood", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "As described"}
{"Author": "oz", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it when it works!!!", "Text": "After i purchased this i started adding devices, loved it, worked great. My only complaint was every time they did an upgrade my system got messed up and i had to reboot. Then they did an upgrade in fall of 2015, took them over a month to get it fixed again, then everything worked flawless for months until they did another upgrade. It has now been 3 months i still get false alarms, missed notifications, unresponsiveness...appears many people are having the same issue and no response from them other than don't use the security and set up a custom security profile which does not seem to work either and is impossible to monitor. Like the fact it works with nearly everything out there and also like the fact they are constantly improving but please leave us the ability to take on the updates until we know they are stable! If you just want a cool devise to run lights this is for you, if you are going to trust it with security i would think twice. At this point it is just not reliable enough IMHO."}
{"Author": "J. Rose", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable", "Text": "Iv had it 24 hours and already having issues. I love technology and can figure out almost anything. This was absolutely totally non intuitive and I had to have tech support walk me through the whole process of connecting my zwave kwikset lock.\nI have tried to lock and unlock my door now 15 times. It has worked 2 times. I have no idea what's up and will give tech support a call but I will warn u that this is not a turn key solution like many of the new smarthome items.\n\nUpdate: I figured out the secret. Don't ask it to do much. I am only using the hub now to lock and unlock my front door. With that being the only task it's in charge of I have gotten it to be very reliable. Start adding thermostats, lights etc. and the thing starts messing up."}
{"Author": "egsleeve", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "the Hub hums along like my router without needing any attention to date", "Text": "So far, a reliable product that seems to always stay connected. Haven't had the connection issues that others have. The Smartthings App could use some finesse but, the Hub hums along like my router without needing any attention to date. Hub had no issues finding my Wemo and ZWave products.\n\nKnocking a star due to the App needing some attention in my opinion."}
{"Author": "Leo", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready yet for primetime. Only buy if you have a lot of patience.", "Text": "As I understand it, this is the best Z-Wave hub out there and it's pretty bad. The product size and features are good, however the software is just HORRIBLE. Everything from the website where you control devices and rooms to the iOS app just stink. You will be presented with a barrage of indecipherable error codes, a constantly spinning wheel while it waits for the network (50Mbps service not fast enough???), warnings that \"access is denied\" to your account which you are logged into and a handful of other garbage. If you are lucky enough to bind devices to it, have them show up as what they really are and actually associate them with room names in your home you are doing better than me."}
{"Author": "1ringo", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung says they are sorry", "Text": "Stay far away from this platform. 6 months and ST is still broken. Promised fixes and updates have made things worse. Check the community forums.\n\nSupport is so backed up I have dozens of unanswered open tickets. No answers no fixes. Just the same pablum, \"We are aware of the issue and are working on it.\" Months and months and every fix they deploy breaks somethings else. A total failure.\nHow does Samsung feel that only one third of there customers are happy with this product?"}
{"Author": "casco1632", "Date": "on April 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Gave it seven months, and it's been a frustrating waste of money", "Text": "I have been using the Samsung SmartThings 2nd generation hub for just under seven months now, along with two of the new versions of their Samsung SmartThings Motion Sensor and two of the Samsung SmartThings Arrival Sensor (the new versions as well). I've also been using the system with the following \"compatible\" devices:\n\n* TCP Connected Smart LED Light Bulb Starter Kit - Gateway plus 2 wireless A19 Soft White (2700K) LED Light Bulbs\n* GE Link Wireless PAR38 Smart Connected LED Light Bulb, Bright White (3000K), 90-Watt Equivalent, 1-Pack\n* Aeon Labs ZW080-A17 Z-Wave Gen 5 siren for indoors - US freq.\n* Kwikset 910 Signature Series Traditional Electronic Deadbolt with Z-Wave Wireless Remote Home Automation Compatibility, Satin Nickel\n* Securifi Key Fob AL-KFB01 - Programmable buttons to Arm/Disarm your Home Security System\n* SONOS PLAY:1 Compact Smart Speaker for Streaming Music (Black).\n\nI was really excited about having this smart home setup after reading about the different systems out there, and the positive reviews here on Amazon for SmartThings. And when it HAS worked, it can be great. But in the time I've had this setup, there have just been so many problems and malfunctions that it has definitely been much more of a headache than a pleasure. Sometimes the problems have (possibly) been related to another party, for example my TCP light bulbs have often been uncontrollable for short periods of time and that could be a problem at TCP. But most of the other issues I've had have been posted and discussed on SmartThings' community forum, so I know that many other people have experienced the same broken connections and malfunctions I have, and the company often takes weeks and weeks to find a solution (if ever). Customer support has been slow and flakey - one time I contacted the support staff and I eventually got a canned response that didn't even come close to answering my very clearly worded question, so I gave up on them and figured out the answer myself through much more trial and error. And you can never call someone at SmartThings for help - you can only email them. I didn't catch that before buying their products, and I think it's a major con. So now I've gotten used to searching for the problems I'm having on their community forum - that's how I figured out that when my motion sensors stop registering motion (which in turn prevents them from detecting an intruder or turning on lights on the room), I have to pry each of them open with a screwdriver without breaking them, struggle to remove the tightly-held battery inside, and re-insert the battery while holding down the reset button. I have had to do this many times now, and the backs of them are all scratched up where I have to pry them open. I'm surprised I haven't cracked them - the plastic seems very flimsy.\n\nI think the main problem here is smart home marketing that has gotten way ahead of the actual capabilities of the technologies at hand. And that goes for other companies selling these types of products as well. The videos on SmartThings website that demonstrate all of the capabilities of the setup are misleading: things rarely work consistently enough to \"automate your life.\" And I've read the same complaints about other platforms, like WeMo and Apple HomeKit.\n\nAs I am writing this, I cannot connect to my TCP light bulbs nor the GE link flood light bulbs on my garage (finally had to go out in the garage and just shut them off), I cannot lock the deadbolt on my door so I had to do it manually, and my SmartThings app. has said there is an \"Intruder detected\" for two whole weeks now after we had a false alarm. I have tried all of the tricks I've read about on the forums to clear this message, and nothing has worked, so I've given up.\n\nThe whole thing has been especially irritating to my husband who is not tech-savvy at all, and he thinks I'm crazy for all of the money I've spent buying the hub and all of the products to connect with it. Our siren went off (again) a few weeks ago even though the app. was registering us both as being \"home,\" and he just about popped a blood vessel! Being the techy one in the house, I feel like I'm always apologizing for things not working as they should and always saying \"okay, I have to figure out why that's happening.\" We were out to dinner one night when our phones notified us that an intruder had been detected and the siren had been activated. I just turned it off and we continued eating, and I still don't know whether someone actually entered the house or not. It malfunctions so often, that it's basically pointless to use it as a security system because you can never trust that it is accurate.\n\nSo needless to say, I am really regretting that I ever starting buying all of these \"smart\" devices, and now that I can't return them, they will probably end up in a box in the garage (unless I can try to sell some of the stuff on eBay or something). HUGE waste of time and money, and a significant stressor to be always troubleshooting the next problem that's come up. I really wanted to like it and give SmartThings some time to improve (which they are always promising on their website and forums), but I just hate it at this point and I'm ready to be done with it. I'm thinking I'll wait about ten years, and then see where this technology is at."}
{"Author": "TJ", "Date": "on April 12, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Upgrade Difficult", "Text": "May update the review at a later date, but this product has both good and bad points. Some devices which worked with my Gen 1 hub are not supported/recognized by this hub (eg. Aeon Labs Gen 5 door sensor). GE light bulbs eventually work, but you'll need to research the solution on your own as tech support was not able to provide a working solution (the bulbs need to be manually reset before they pair). Conversion from the Gen 1 hub was laborious. You have to deconstruct smartapps, exclude all devices, then rebuild everything ... hopefully you've saved all your device manuals as the SmartThings in app help tells you to go check the manufacturer's documentation. Once things are working the new software and capabilities are a step up from the Gen 1."}
{"Author": "John D.", "Date": "on April 12, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Customer Support not yet ready to support what can be an excellent product. (Update .. Improving support and reliability)", "Text": "product is good. It is much easier to setup and use for basic tasks compared to VeraLite. The ability to work with multiple communication formats (zigbee, zwave, wifi-hue, etc) is great. The integration with the Echo/Alexa is awesome. I would give it 5 stars except for a couple issues. The app is fair, it is not as intuitive as some and I find that it does not report the current status of devices accurately. Some devices that are locked appear unlocked, lights that are off appear on or vice-versa.\nMy biggest concern is that after growing the system gradually one device at a time up to almost 30 devices, I wanted to reconfigure/rename devices. It seemed the best option was to do a factory restore and start over. (I didn't integrate Alexa and the Hue bulbs the \"right\" way so things were a little messy) The only way to \"factory restore\" is to delete devices and what they call the \"Location\". I ran into a permissions error and contacted support via live chat. It only took 30 minutes or so to get an agent, but he was not able to help and needed to pass the issue to engineering. That was over a week ago and they have not addressed the issue. As a system that controls security and relied upon for basic functions, I don't feel they are capable to support this kind of system adequately. I will likely return to Vera until they can improve customer support response times.\n\nUpdate 4/13/2016\nI have submitted an email support request and will update if and when I get more information.\nI did not have a ticket number from the live chat, so I suspect I'm starting over.\nUPDATE 4/15/2016\nyesterday, I got an email that my hub was reset. I pulled out the card with the code that came in the original box and started over just like it was fresh out of the box. (Always keep that number)\n24 hrs later and everything is reloaded and so far it is running much better than before. I got an email explaining a server upgrade at smart things to improve reliability and so far it is better. I have a few smart apps to still set up.\nI have a mix of Jasco, GE, Aotec and Schlage z-wave - smart things zig bee - Hue - Sonos- Wemo - and an Echo Nd an Echo Dot. This is what I like about the Smartthings hub. I hope it continues to remain reliable... I will update again!"}
{"Author": "sdwyer1097", "Date": "on April 12, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Poor quality", "Text": "Poor quality - 50% of my purchases with these units don't even work for the get go.\n\nBut...for the ones that do work - They are fine."}
{"Author": "wireless", "Date": "on April 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This time it actually works!", "Text": "It works! I had previously purchased the GEN 1 product at had much trouble with it. The improvements in GEN 2 make sense and I'm looking forward to adding to the devices I connect to it. The app still needs to be made easier to use but they're on the right track."}
{"Author": "Pyro-C", "Date": "on April 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Thought I could make it work", "Text": "I really had high hopes for this hub. Currently own a Wink hub and decided to try LIFX lights, Wink does not support them. So I looked around at which home automation hub would and came across the SmartThings hub. I read all the reviews both positive and negative, even though there were a lot (and I mean a lot) of negative ones, I decided to try it out anyway. Assuming that most users either didn't know what they were doing or were expecting to much from the hub. I figured if I could get the hub to work, I could replace my Wink hub. Not that anything is wrong with my Wink hub, but I am a geek and I'm always looking for the latest and greatest. The SmartThings hub promises a lot it can do and I figured even if half of it worked, it would be worth the price. Well I was sorely mistaken, I ordered the hub from Amazon and the first thing I did was install it, connect it to my internet and it did a firmware update. Not a problem...yet, as I mentioned before, I solely brought the SmartThings hub to work with my LIFX lighting system. It locks up constantly, whether I'm creating a room, having it find the lights in my house, or when it does find the light, assigning them to a room.\n\nI can honestly say, I've never given a one star review as I'm always able to find something good about a product. But I just can't understand how a product could function so properly and be released to the public.\n\nAnother kick in the face, they don't even have support you can call. It's buy it and get help from other users if you can.\n\nI'm going to try a little more to see if it's anything I can possibly to make this thing work but if not, it's going back....FAST. If I can get anything to work, I'll post an update and the star rating."}
{"Author": "Gene Ussery", "Date": "on April 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "For me it works great! As others have said it allows you to ...", "Text": "I saw all of the negative reviews for this product and decided to write my own. For me it works great! As others have said it allows you to write custom interfaces to work with products that are not on the official compatible products list. There are a bunch of these on the community forum and are provided as is. Some work well and some not so much. You can get a pretty good idea of how well they work by reading the forums. You can't fault Samsung or the product for custom interfaces that have been written to support additional products.\nAs far as what Samsung says is supported I haven't experienced a single issue using these items. You can find the list of supported products here: [...] If you want a solution that works all of the time and don't want to write code you may want to use items on the official compatibility list.\nThe interface to Amazon echo is easy to work with and the number of items you can add to Smartthings is endless if you are willing to write interfaces. There is lots of community support for the product.\nI have only contacted technical support once and my experience was good. My question was not complicated so I don't have enough information to rate support.\nOverall Smartthings does what I need and more. After trying Hue, Wink, Insteon and others Smartthings has the most flexibility and is the most reliable."}
{"Author": "M. Davis", "Date": "on April 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It just isnt consistent enough to rely on."}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on April 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well for the most part but the app has bugs to be worked out.", "Text": "I like SmartThings and don't regret buying it but there are many bugs that Samsung needs to work out. This system is a server based system and if their servers go down, so does you home automation. For the most part, everything works well for the things I need. When I try to check recent history of devices or look at my notifications, I get constant messages that state, \"Sorry, but there was an unexpected error.\" Luckily, those pages don't control anything so I can wait for a solution from Samsung.\n\nAlthough there have been bugs with the system, Samsung has good customer service. They have a live chat to assist you with problems during business hours and email for after hours. They do not charge you to receive customer service. Each time I have contacted them about a problem, they have responded within a day."}
{"Author": "Scott March", "Date": "on April 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After lots of research I chose the SmartThings ecosystem for ...", "Text": "After lots of research I chose the SmartThings ecosystem for my home automation project. Biggest benefit for me is the close integration with the Harmony Elite hub-based remote control system. Now overhead lights & table lamps dim as the screen backlighting comes up. Home Theater starts up, TV comes on and opens right into Plex. Now if I can just figure out the activity to program for it to make me a sandwich I will be all set."}
{"Author": "Eric Tryon", "Date": "on April 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't waste your money", "Text": "$100 piece of junk. Worked halfway decent for about a month then stopped connecting with my lights. Samsung support is worthless, completely unresponsive. I'll look for a better option."}
{"Author": "Stephen G", "Date": "on April 8, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awful product, hopefully they will fix it so I can update this review.", "Text": "Disclaimer: This review is based on my personal experience, others may have different views.\n\nThis product is half baked, the app is extremely poorly laid out and makes absolutely no sense, I've worked in Software design for 20 years and I've honestly not seen anything this poor or confusing to try and set up. It constantly throws errors, very difficult and time consuming to pair with smart devices. There is virtually no explanation about any step on what to do and the worst part is to make use of devices you really need to log into a site [...] to be able to configure your devices if they are 3rd part or other tasks like setting up custom apps. They do not tell you this anywhere and the link on the Samsung Smartthings site is non existent. In otherwords if you go to the main Samsung Smartthings site, there is no where to log in. You have to go to the site I posted above. Whenever you are using the app it constantly throws errors and complains about network problems, it takes forever to refresh the dashboard screen. Honestly this product is 3 years in with a v2 hub and it looks and acts like a prototype. Samsung better fix this soon or their reputation is going down the tubes. A lot of people have invested a large amount in their smart systems and this system although it has a lot of possibilities is absolutely awful. The people in charge of the UX for this app should be fired immediately, the GUI designers should go next."}
{"Author": "F. E. Henry", "Date": "on April 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost caused a divorce", "Text": "This HA system looks great on paper but has almost caused a divorce dur to inconsistent performance, \"things\" frequently becoming unpaired from hub, and routines not being accomplished. I'm patient with some level of workarounds but this fails more often then it works. I'll try Ineston and see if any more reliable."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This product gives Amazon a bad name.", "Text": "Little to no support from manufacturer. Nothing but problems since installed. Sent of emails for support, have 2 tickets open. Have had one response from smartthings asking for screen shot, haven't heard back since, that was well over 24hrs ago."}
{"Author": "nolansc", "Date": "on April 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Resets, Disappointment performance for a year.", "Text": "Ive had nothing but the same problems over and over and over again with my smartthings and it's \"things.\" If I decide to make my alarm system automatic, arming at 11pm and disarming at 6am, it will work right for a half a week before it will stop disarming each morning. That requires a reset of my hub. Also, ive had an issue where the motion sensor will detect movement during the night but the siren won't trigger. I've woke up and checked my phone to see a missed alert. Scary thought. My wife's lamp doesn't turn off automatically at night like it should. It normally turns on at sunset, but after a week of perfection, it will stop turning off at 11pm. Lastly, the biggest issue i've had (because I can just arm and disarm the alarm myself) is with the door contact sensors. After about a week of resetting them, they no longer detect opening and closing. So my alarm system is basically functioning on my sole motion detector. I can reset the sensors, and they'll work right for about a week, then one day i'll notice that it says the sensor is open yet the door is closed. I'm sure i'm not the only one with these same problems. While I chose the smartthings system to be my choice for all things automated in my home. I regret the day I did. I've had nothing but poor performance, sleepless nights wondering if my system would work correctly throughout the night, and numerous days popping batteries out and in to reset sensors. Hope this helps someone else, because after last nights sensor reset, i've officially quitting smarttings and moving on."}
{"Author": "Bullphourg", "Date": "on April 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Too buggy", "Text": "I thought the Veras were horribly buggy but this is worse. With just a single GE switch paired I get extreme delays in turning the switch on and off. about 1/3 of the time it's instant. The other 2/3 of the time it takes several minutes to respond.\n\nThe user interface is so confusing. I'm a software developer that usually can make sense of confusing things. This one took about four hours to figure out how to install custom smart apps (scripts). As far as adding or deleting devices that's easy enough but that's not terribly useful by itself. They way they handle triggering events could be so much better."}
{"Author": "Pi", "Date": "on April 6, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Works most of the time, but way too unreliable."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on April 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Unreliable", "Text": "Without a doubt, this is the most unreliable product I have purchased in 5+ years. Nearly every time the app or hub is updated, a new bug is introduced/reintroduced and often goes unfixed for weeks at a time. I was very happy with the 1st generation hub and wish I never \"upgraded\". That said, I do have a very complex 30+ device setup. TIP: If you plan to automate lighting and have a technical background, check out Rule Machine smart app. Sadly, it is far more reliable than the smart lighting \"smart app\" from Smartthings."}
{"Author": "vagabonding", "Date": "on April 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Maybe version 3 will actually work?", "Text": "I so want automated house lighting. I had high hopes for the Samsung SmartThings Hub. However, so far been a disappointment. The device paired with GE zwave wall dimmers easily. Using the apple iOS SmartThings app, I can manually adjust the lighting fast and efficiently.\n\nWhere the device completely fails is in automation. The Hub is supposed to automatically turn on lights when I get close to home and turn them off when I leave the area. Despite all the appropriate settings on my phone being in place and speaking with Samsung support I still can't get the product to work appropriately. Even automation setting (such as the lights turning on or off at a set time everyday) continually fails to activate. For example, while on a recent vacation my downstairs and bedroom lights were to turn on at a certain time and go off - to help give the appearance someone was actually home. Checking my in-home security cameras (not linked to the SmartThings hub) I could confirm that the lights were not turning on. If Samsung can't get lights to automatically trigger with their system -- who in their right mind would trust them with the security systems that are linked to the SmartThings product? What is most telling is that even that Samsung representative said they had a bugs to work out. Buyer beware.\n\nUpdate: I have contacted Samsung support for a third time. They are only available over a chat function or email, which is very frustrating. Don't bother with email, as a rep will take forever to respond to your inquiry. The reps I have \"spoken with\" suggested I connect my system to another app called Life360 -- the provided instructions for integrating the two apps did not work (it looks like they are out of date). I'm waiting to hear back from them on corrected instructions. The second fix that was provided for automation involving the lights turning on at certain hours of the day was for Samsung to push an update to the hub. Again, this failed to fix the problem. I removed one star. Will update again in a week.\n\nUpdate Nov 2016\nI still have consistent issues with the hub's automation working. Every time I contact Samsung support I'm given a different answer why it's not working OR they blame it on an update that is to be made in the next couple of days. Support is polite but frankly they just don't seem to have real answers or fixes. I still regret this purchase."}
{"Author": "Seattle Hiker", "Date": "on April 5, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm not sure this is the best solution for smarthome stuff", "Text": "Doesn't always pick up new devices, and the iOS app is clunky. Once it's configured though it is convenient. I'm not sure this is the best solution for smarthome stuff, but it does work. I can only recommend this for power-users. Don't expect somebody without a lot of experience in computers to figure out this thing."}
{"Author": "Drew", "Date": "on April 4, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Design (Tough to Learn APP)", "Text": "Great product in theory. This hub appears to have the most flexibility only second to the staples connect (which is appears to be discontinued by staples). It has massive potential. The toughest part is the learning curve. It easily would earn five stars for reliability and flexibility but your only as good as your weakest link. The app has a great intent but the learning curve as to how to use it is pretty rough. If your interested in tinkering then this is the device for you. I am sticking with it because I will master the (very confusing and poorly laid out) app. I have extensive experience with the staples connect, the wink and now the Smartthings. If Samsung would have only spoofed the Staples Connect software then the Samsung would be king of the hill. One great feature is that if your Samsung Smartthings finds a device then you can most likely make it work with the Smartthings. Once the Samrtthings clears the horrible app hurtle then it will be worth slamming 5 stars."}
{"Author": "Aaron M. Webster", "Date": "on April 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was bad now great", "Text": "Has worked flawlessly for the last 6 months. New firmware is perfect and I have not had any issues. Now I have several more devices connected and the echo integration is also perfect. I highly recommend this product."}
{"Author": "MF", "Date": "on April 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great functionality", "Text": "Great functionality. Four stars because software has some glitches cousing misfunction couple times."}
{"Author": "Jacob", "Date": "on April 3, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but their software is amateur at best. Lots and lots of bugs", "Text": "SmartThings has a lot of promise, but their software is amateur at best. Lots and lots of bugs. Really helpful and responsive community."}
{"Author": "No41", "Date": "on April 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No support - Cannot register device", "Text": "So far - CRAP. I cannot even get past the initial registration - which should be pretty simple. You open the app, pick your region, and enter the registration code. However, after I enter the code - I get an error saying that I'm not authorized to complete this transaction. There is no phone number for support, only an email. No desktop or web option for setup either. I will wait 24 hours then either update this review with results or return the hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Perfect for my SCHLAGE lock! Easy setup."}
{"Author": "Tim Burt", "Date": "on April 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "so that kinda makes chat support useless. So I moved on to the forums", "Text": "I am not a typical user, I work as a DevOps engineer and I have been active with Unix/Linux for two decades and RPi and Arduino since their introduction. I purchased the SmartHub to interface with OpenHab to control several devices in my home. My unit arrived from Amazon on a Friday afternoon. I followed instructions, downloaded the app, activated the hub and tried to pair with a device. The hub is sitting 3 feet from the device, and I have confirmed that the hub has an IP and can access the internet.\n\nThe light on the hub blinks green, indicating it is trying to pair with a device. It never pairs, it just blinks. I reboot, I reset (inset red button) no change. It is now Saturday morning, and I thought to contact support. No phone support, email or chat only and Chat is only available during the same hours that I am working (9-5 PST), so that kinda makes chat support useless. So I moved on to the forums, and learned that Samsung is basically ignoring the consumers. I signed up for a forum login so that I could post my experience, and surprise, the activation email never comes. That surely put a stop to the negative posts that were coming from dissatisfied buyers.\n\nBefore investing in the Samsung Smart Things, be sure to read the forum posts at [...]. If you see only good posts, then Samsung has cleared out the forums of bad news. I expect this soon, following the \"no new logins\" policy they have implemented.\n\nIn short, if you like being frustrated and ignored, then by all means purchase a Samsung product. ( I got pretty much the same result on the Samsung Smart TV I own )\n\nMy advice, save yourself the return postage, learn from my mistake. This unit is going back on Monday.\n\nA little more detail for the techies...\n\nThe hub has no open ports, so it is secure to the extent that only Samsung can get to it. Upon boot, it communicates with AWS at 52.21.172.80 port 443 [...].\n\n10.1.1.244.39970 > 52.21.172.80.443: Flags [.], cksum 0xc7ce (correct), seq 1572915405, ack 1185738456, win 443, length 0\n\n80.172.21.52.in-addr.arpa name = ec2-52-21-172-80.compute-1.amazonaws.com.\n\nStraight to an ec-2 instance, these guys are not even using a load balancer and multi-AZ deployment. Really amateur.\n\nAll communications are encrypted, so just what Samsung is getting back is not known. They may have a map of your internal network and access to your open file shares, this is not hard to do.\n\nBad Bad Bad.. Samsung needs to fire their CTO."}
{"Author": "abba gail", "Date": "on April 2, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... hub works well and I have found it very easy to link all my devices", "Text": "The Smartthings hub works well and I have found it very easy to link all my devices, most of witch are not Samsung or Smartthins branded. I only have Z-wave devises so I have not tried anything else.\n\nMy complaint come from the lack of functionality between the Smartthings hub and my Schlage Camelot door lock. Both Smarthings and Schlage claim there product is compatible with the other but I expected more functionality. All you can do is check the status of the lock and open and close the lock. I contacted Samsung, they apologized and told me there was a work around but that it was not approved by Samsung due security reasons. I am not sure I want that in a door lock?\n\nSchlage clams increased functionality of secure system (I don't remember the exact wording) and I believe Smartthing claims to meet the requirment, so why only very limited functionality?\n\nThe hub works fime, the lock works fine, I am not sure I would purchase them together."}
{"Author": "Springfellow", "Date": "on April 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Addition of an Echo Dot was the final nail in the coffin. SmartThings hub is dead.", "Text": "I expect a device that controls my lighting, door locks, and alerts me to intruders to be 100% flawless. Actually I expect all products released to be flawless, or they shouldn't be released. SmartThings was about 15-30% functional for me while it lasted.\n\nMy home automation consists of a couple Echo's, Hue, locks, motion, open/close sensors, and outlets. It's only taken three months since setting up the system (and changing nothing since initial setup before today) for SmartThings to go haywire on it's own. Some of the hassles I've had to deal with include:\n\n-Inability to switch modes from armed to disarmed. Despite having ran the \"I'm home\" action, and it triggering the lights and door locks, it would not disarm the system and upon detecting a door open or motion, triggered the alarms and alerts which I was unable to turn off. I had to unplug the system and spend several days just resetting things and uninstalling/reinstalling the app. Switching phones had no effect.\n\n-Lights simply not responding, or some responding intermittently, and giving incorrect status in the app.\n\n-Door locks not responding and not updating to correct status, and taking minutes (sometimes up to a half hour) to respond to a single button press.\n\n-Motion sensors not working at all, or very selectively sometimes, despite working perfectly earlier in the day.\n\n-Multi purpose sensors constantly detecting knocks when there are none.\n\n-Never figured out how to get my existing cameras to work through the app. They just want you to buy one of their cameras with a monthly fee. I don't think so...\n\nNow SmartThings is dead. The only thing that's changed in my setup, is the addition of an Echo Dot today. I have no idea why it would affect anything, but SmartThings simply doesn't work anymore. At all. Even after unplugging the Dot. There are no issues with batteries in the sensors, I've reset, unplugged, reconnected, reinstalled everything multiple times. It just doesn't work anymore. My lights all still respond through the Hue app, but SmartThings does nothing. The motion sensors report no motion, no devices change status, I have no control over my locks.\n\nMaybe in 5-7 years someone will release a 100% functional and reliable smart home hub, but I've been messing around with this stuff for a while and it's just nowhere near ready for release."}
{"Author": "Michael Read", "Date": "on April 1, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "functional, but finicky"}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Decide whether to keep the Smartcam or hub", "Text": "So far two very important reasons to give two stars.\nFirst it is not really compatible with my \"Samsung\" Smartcam HD pro. I lose all features. Dumbs it down to a simple camera and I will be required to now pay for clips sent to the cloud. No motion sensing, no audio sensing, nothing but camera.\nSecond is the lack of UI for Windows desktop. This eliminates any control options without a cell phone as there are no real disarm methods w/o a cell phone. 30 seconds to search the house for a tablet, log in and disarm.\nKudos to Ben on the support team thoughts he was the best! He shared some great resources for working with device handlers. Too late to return camera so may need to lose the hub and sensors."}
{"Author": "James Mccarty", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good home automation hub with lots of device compatibility.", "Text": "So far I love it. Works with many devices. There is a hiccup now and then. But some of that is user error. I don't think its for the tech challenged. You have to know a thing or two if you want to use this to its full potential. The box is smaller then I thought. It was easy to get started. Plug it in and follow some simple instructions. Some devices are harder to pair then others. Works with the Echo to allow Echo to control more devices."}
{"Author": "Tapper", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... a shame - the possibilities for this hub are great BUT unfortunately", "Text": "What a shame - the possibilities for this hub are great BUT unfortunately, it is Internet based and the server is quite quirky. Many times I can't use things at all, and those that are supposed to happen automatically sometimes work, and sometimes don't. In a word, it's unreliable. And that just doesn't work for home automation - lights should come on when they're supposed to - not just sometimes, but all the time. I don't recommend and would love to return/sell mine - it's useless for me."}
{"Author": "Brandon J. Goulet", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Working pretty well so far. I've had it for about 2 months."}
{"Author": "JC From Texas", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome so far and have been expanding quickly! Alexa (Echo) makes things even better!", "Text": "Worked well right out of the box with a couple of light modules. Have been adding devices and controls every few weeks and making sure things work. No problems so far and have about 50% of the project done. I'm already purchasing water sensors, garage door modules, and an outdoor sprinkler upgrade to expand the system.\n\nThere are a few times you will need to google to find answers, but all in all things are pretty simple. The key thing to keep in mind is keeping your network expanding out from the hub and not placing items too far away without an extender. Every module with power (light switches, power outlets, etc) work as extenders and you can buy a plug in lamp module (versus a plain extender) to increase range while giving you one extra future control."}
{"Author": "CK.Step", "Date": "on March 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wasted my time. Probably going to try wink next.", "Text": "I am somewhat tech savy. Had no problem setting up my smart home additions with their designed apps. Trying to pull everything togther with this hub is way to difficult. I spent a significant amount of time to no avail. Worthless if the average tech person cannot get it up and running."}
{"Author": "B. Ruck", "Date": "on March 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Far from ready...", "Text": "After a few days of waiting for a reply from Samsung for my issue on how to get my hub to be recognized so I could finally begin the setup, I have now been told \"There is a slight platform issue (on our end) that is preventing you from being able to create a Location and add your new Hub. The good news is there is a fix...,\" followed by a - and I'm not kidding here - 24 step process to get this added to my network. I'm now looking into other options. I'm savvy enough that I could follow the 24 step manual process they emailed - but if I'm running into a problem like this at just the SETUP of the thing, I can't image the problems that will come in the future..."}
{"Author": "Roger A. Hermann", "Date": "on March 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time!", "Text": "Great idea but pair devices did not work. Also software app was poor."}
{"Author": "Iraj", "Date": "on March 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "STOP! Utterly Unreliable!", "Text": "So what is the point of SMART home? It is to make it easier for you to do some routine tasks, and for some of us, it's even more. I bought this partially for security reasons, and I was hoping I can rely on it. But it can not do simplest things:\n- It can not understand I am back home! Is it that hard? By my phone location which is always on, and always uses home wifi.\n- It can not disarm the security system and alarm, even when I try it manually! It just doesn't do it, and me my cats should freak out every time I come home until I can manually turn off the siren.\nBottom line: whether Smartthings suffers from mismanagement or whatever, I don't know. But you're not going to get what you're expecting. This system has so many bugs that you cannot trust it at all."}
{"Author": "Craig T.", "Date": "on March 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Very poor device...motion sensor never worked and the battery only lasted 1 month"}
{"Author": "Michele", "Date": "on March 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "AVOID THIS PRODUCT...it does NOT work!!!!", "Text": "Fancy packaging and glitzy marketing is about the best thing this product has to offer. You can only install the system via an app you install on your phone, and NOT from a home computer. The app you install is VERY buggy and VERY inconsistent - one minute it's detecting open/close doors/windows, the next it is not. Sometimes it sends an alert to you when a door is open, many times it does not. It even indicated someone had come home (via the fob I had installed with the system), even though that person was far from home. Also, this system relies on their cloud servers which are CONSTANTLY crashing. This entire system seems to be BETA version that was rolled out to the public months (if not a year) before it was ready for prime time. Now we the consumers are suffering with a VERY buggy product, helping Samsung debug what should NEVER have passed proper QA (at this point I am assuming they do not have a QA department). One last thing...their product support seems non-existent, especially nights and weekends. I wasted an entire weekend installing a systems full of bugs! Advice to Amazon...you may want to stop advertising plug and play between Smartthings and Echo (the main reason I purchased Smartthings) - you are misleading your Echo community, by leading them down a path to purchase an expensive system that is does not consistently work."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "so far SmartThings is working great with a couple light bulbs and a door lock", "Text": "I've started small with home automation, so far SmartThings is working great with a couple light bulbs and a door lock. I can't way to keep adding to the system, possibilities seem Limitless. One Smart Switch and Outlet at a time!"}
{"Author": "LarryM", "Date": "on March 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Potential - Be ready to tweak a bit", "Text": "SmartThings has a great deal of potential - but it isn't something that you can plug & go expecting it and the connected devices to work smoothly together. The SmartThings community forum ([...]) is the place to see both the potential as well as the struggle you will likely face as you begin your journey to a connected house.\n\nI started with several Osram Lightify lights (bought the Lightify gateway so I could update the firmware) for several rooms in the house. Then added Iris Smart Motion sensors (sold at a large box store) to trigger lights in our master bath area and on our front porch. Be advised, not all devices will be recognized out of the box by SmartThings. The community forum instructs you how to load specific device handlers which were developed by a great bunch of DIYers. The SmartThings app lets you set various conditions for the lights to include how long for the light to remain on after motion, etc. I love the fact that you can use Z-wave and Zigbee devices.\n\nYou can go simple or dive in. I'm trying to dive in so I bought the Amazon Echo. It (she) now controls the lights. When you add a user developed app (Alexa Helper) to SmartThings you'll discover ways to group lights and create routines. I added a number of contact sensors for exterior doors, windows, and an internal cabinet or two. Another SmartApp is SmartTiles which lets you create a web-based dashboard to control the devices & see the status of your sensors outside of the SmartThings App. I use an old Android phone as a controller in the family room. You can even mount a tablet on the wall as a control pad.\n\nRight now, I do not recommend SmartThings as a full fledged security system as the makers continue to refine (aka FIX) some scheduling and cloud issues.\n\nSo -- I say go for it!"}
{"Author": "FrDocOk", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't invest in z-wave quite yet...it's not smart enough", "Text": "It was fun while it lasted...one day. After getting my Scalage lock and my GE Link light bulb paired (which took quite a bit of tinkering), I tested both and they worked by evening. In the morning I even played with dimming the light bulb. And I had it all set up with Amazon Echo as well. Cool! Then, this evening, on my way out the door, I asked \"Alexa\" to turn on the light. She couldn't communicate with the hub. So I checked the app. It said the hum was online, but the app couldn't do anything with the light bulb or the lock. Bottom line: This device works inconsistently. And I agree with another reviewer (one of the many who has had the same inconsistencies)--we probably need to wait a few years before those who produce these \"smart\" products actually make them smart enough to work well.\nSo I'll return what I've got and wait."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy. Not reliable yet.", "Text": "It has gotten worse and worse. Nothing about Smartthings is easy or reliable. The fact that they sell this as a security product is a joke. The fact that it is still on sale at all is a bigger joke.\n\nI really want ST to succeed... But they're making it harder and harder to stick around."}
{"Author": "E. Okorie", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Zero star Crap!", "Text": "Crap, total crap! So do not buy!!!"}
{"Author": "Wes King", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If it wasn't for Samsung, this could be a 5 star product", "Text": "It is sad that I have to review this product so poorly because it is not the fault of the hardware. This software is the work of a disconnected, bigger than they need to be, company in Samsung. Like everything else they build, this app that accompanies the hardware is absolute garbage. The system works when it wants. It send intrusion detections when it is disarmed. It won't disarm on command or on rules for that matter. It is so sad because the regular automation features work wonderfully (most of the time). Samsung has once again ruined something that could be great. I'm going to have to send this hub back and try something else."}
{"Author": "neil wilkinson", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "this thing sucks!!!", "Text": "I had a choice of hubs to work with Alexa. i've had it about 4 days and THIS ONE SUCKS!. It is always dropping the internet connection--and we have a dedicated line for it. It is always saying that it has encountered a problem. I have tried moving it around the house. I'm getting tired of Alexa telling me it is not responding."}
{"Author": "dts", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One of the worst technology products I have ever encountered", "Text": "In cannot recommend SmartThings if you aren't interested in constantly fixing it.\n\nTL;DR: The platform stability is even for a consumer product extremely bad; It has more bugs than a cheap hostel; the app design is not intuitive and lacks basic design patterns; many popular devices like Nest or Ring are not supported (out of the box).\n\nThe SmartThings platform has constant outages where either their IDE cloud platform or their app are not working at all. This alone would be a reason to send it back right away, as you cannot control anything during that time. You are lucky if you have physical switches which still work while the hub is down. Otherwise you literally sit in the dark. The IDE has constant problems not showing your hub, devices or locations etc. - I can't count the bugs anymore I came across.\n\nThe only end-user facing interface available is the smartphone app. The app itself is awful. It lacks any kind of modern design patterns (it is ugly), logic and is slow as hell. To add devices and put automations in place it works reasonable well. However, for a daily usage it is simply unusable. The smartapps marketplace is a total mess which is hard to navigate and find the right application to make certain functions work.\n\nWe already have devices like Nest Thermostat, Nest Protect, Ring and Rachio at home - however these are all unsupported. A few devices like Nest you can make work through some 3rd party code in the IDE but there is no native integration. Some might work with very limited functionalities through an IFTTT channel.\n\nThe support is very unresponsive and could not solve any issues I came across in a reasonable time (3 working days).\n\nHowever, I was impressed by flexibility of the IDE and some user generated applications like the RuleMachine and some other integrations. Unfortunately, it seems that this flexibility comes with a high instability of the system.\n\nRecommendations for SmartThings/Samsung: 1) Fix your cloud system, right now your product is unusable. 2) Hire some good engineers and UX designers and fix your app, its UI is outdated and the stability is ridiculous. The functions are very setup driven and not use case driven 3) Partner with more major IoT/Smarthome manufacturers."}
{"Author": "Richard", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost built a great smart home system but, it seems they fired all the competent programmers.", "Text": "I bought into the SmartThings system because it was backed by Samsung and it seemed to work with a lot of different sensors, etc. I was looking to replace my Comcast security system with something I managed myself. ST seemed to fit the bill. First off none of the sensors that Comcast provided work with ST, even though they use a \"compatible\" protocol. I chalk that up to Comcast being d$%ks (no surprise there) to ensure people would not do what I am doing. Anyway, that issue is not Samsung's fault so I don't blame them for that. What I do blame them for is their horrible app, which by their own admission does not work correctly for home security (an issue that has lingered for more than a year as far as I can tell). If their Smart Home Monitor app worked it would display a nice arm home, arm away and disarm on the main dashboard of the ST app. The system is easy to add sensors, etc and seems at first glance to be great. Then, you know, you arm the system. Then you try to disarm the system, well that is where this product falls apart. You CAN'T disarm the alarm, so guess what you have to chat with tech support to turn it off!!! Think I am making this up go to status.smartings.com and see for yourself.\n\nOk, so after hours dealing with their tech support and revising their forums, other users said to use a 3rd party app call Smart Alarm. This app can be installed within the Samsung app (yes confusing) and actually is much better than the Samsung SHM app. Problem is Samsung, to be d's decided only their own apps can be on the dashboard so if you use a 3rd party app you are relegated to unnecessarily indirect ways of using them. So, after setting the SA app, everything seemed OK. At this point I would have just complained about how bad the SHM app is and gave this thing 3 stars but no it gets worse.\n\nYou see everything in SmartThings is not controlled on your hub, it is controlled in the cloud. Normally, this would be fine, I got a fast connection to internet, and I am used to Apple/Google \"it just works\" level of service. Nope, Samsung apparently cheaped out in the cloud, so this system is constantly going down or acting in funny ways. What prompted me to write this scathing review was that I armed the system, went to lunch and when I got home I could not disarm the system!! Yes, their servers are down, got a email from them telling me. That is great but when their servers are down I cannot disarm the system!! So I have to go into my house pull the siren and bury it under pillows (it is sealed with a internal battery and no off switch).\n\nSo here I am, I spent north of $600 on this crap and don't know what to do. I don't see another system that can do what this system does. I really wish Apple was further along with HomeKit or I would have never bought this stuff. I always stuck with Apple products because I always felt that the Samsung stuff was inferior, this experience has solidified my belief. I will NEVER buy a Samsung product again."}
{"Author": "Allison", "Date": "on March 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Most Unreliable Product Ever", "Text": "Worst product I have ever purchased. It's awesome when it works but, this company can't go two months without breaking something or having a major failure. I have been a SmartThings user for two years now and it is a constant effort to keep things working. I don't have the time or desire for it."}
{"Author": "J. S.", "Date": "on March 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I tried the VeraPlus... Went right back to SmartThings!", "Text": "I have tried quite a few hubs out there, and every time I come back to ST. Here's my experience of the good and the bad... However, the good heavily outweighs the bad, just as I recommend SmartThings over other hubs like vera or wink.\n\nI purchased my ST after initially purchased a VeraEdge controller and was disappointed in the slow interface, lack of zigbee support, and unreliable ui vera had. I ordered the SmartThings and with not really much of an idea how powerful it was... Initially I was impressed with the easy setup and compatibility, and since (with a little help from an amazing online community creating custom device types that the company supports) If it didn't natively work with ST, I could locate a custom device type quickly and get it installed. It's compatible with the 2nd gen Iris sensors which you can catch on sale for a good deal. Since purchasing, the integration and compatibility has become better and better!\n\nThe interface does have its drawbacks, as all hubs do i've found, and one of then is the UI. The device is designed to be home AUTOMATION not home control with a remote/mobile phone. Because it aids in true automation (where little interaction is required from the user) there's only an interface for android and iphone's designed to give you quick info and help you install devices. There's no ipad app and no a web ui (minus the IDE, for installing custom device types and apps). This makes it a little difficult for guest that come over. There are some 3rd party dashboards that I've integrated and have been fairly happy with such, but wish there was a native web ui. Also, the hub is pretty much rendered useless if your internet connection fails... This is an extreme rarity or myself with a backup internet connection, but could be problematic if you have internet that gets spotty. Lastly, like all the other hubs, a couple of the smartapps native to SmartThings are a little spotty, I occasionally. have issues with arrivals and departures (but not sure if that's an issue with Apple Location Services or the app itself)\n\nBecause of these problems, I decided to try the new VERAPLUS I've been seeing all over the internet... BIG MISTAKE! The only issue that wouldn't necessarily arise with Vera over ST is the internet connectivity but that was a minor improvement. Vera does not natively support near the number of devices nor have I found a simple way to \"add custom device types\" so to speak. The Zigbee integration is horribly unstable, rendering the device useless if it has issues configuring a zigbee device (which is frequent) The Web UI is a NIGHTMARE slow and unreliable and support is not prompt at all.\n\nI had an issues with my ST hub where the power wasn't working. I contacted support, and with a couple 3 emails back and forth and with some troubleshooting, I had a new hub express delivered to me no charge to replace it. They including a return label and told me to pack the old one in the box, slapped the label on and call UPS. The support request took about 6 hours to respond, and sent the replacement within 48 hours of the initial request. I contacted VERA support and it took them 8 days to respond to my support request, and after 2 weeks of trying to get a response by email, I gave up. They blamed they're tarty reply on a bug in they're filtering software (the reason why i was contacting them was because my garage door kept opening and closing in the night because of vera).\n\nOverall, in my opinion ST is an increasingly reliable, cost friendly/affordable, easy to install and configure, all in one Home Automation hub that I HIGHLY recommend to anyone wanting home automation. Each update brings better and better improvements, and an increasing number of happy home user's continue to help their online community grow stronger and stronger with new, innovative ways to incorporate home automation in your life. And that makes my life much simpler!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 23, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it worked fine. Then smoke detectors", "Text": "I have spent several hundred dollars on \"Smart Things\". At first I added a couple sensors, it worked fine. Then smoke detectors, it took me an hour to get 3 connected to the hub. After I got them all connected I pulled the batteries out of one, looked at the app and it stated that the detector was still active and was clear, not sure how that was possible. I then added 2 more sensors, another hour to pair. Next I ran into range issues with the 2 sensors so I purchased a switch so I would have a repeater, spent hours trying to get them connected and it never did. I then tried another switch, nope, won't connect. Finally I got the 3rd switch to pair, I installed it. Now the sensors that need the switch (repeater) as a \"parent\" in order to talk to the hub won't reconfigure. This system is a bust at this point. I was really excited to purchase this for our new home but after hours of devices not connecting properly, app failures, poor web site support articles, etc, I'm not so excited anymore."}
{"Author": "H", "Date": "on March 23, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable", "Text": "Works about 50% of the time. But often, the security system is going off and can't be disarmed from the app, which just hangs. Restarting the hub sometimes fixes the problem, but then you have to have physical access to the hub (can't be restarted remotely, to my knowledge). Really, really annoying. Not ready for prime time. Definitely do NOT replace your home security system with SmartThings!"}
{"Author": "Stubs", "Date": "on March 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Depends on cloud services. Consistency unable to connect. ...", "Text": "Depends on cloud services. Consistency unable to connect. Cant change status, Spent a week in Armed mode. Never ending errors on commands via android app. Slow event triggers. And there is always a preset block to doing what you want. (water leak detected can trigger turning a pump off without scripting for example)"}
{"Author": "Mihajlo", "Date": "on March 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy", "Text": "Installation was breeze. Integrating the z-wave devices no problem there too."}
{"Author": "flybird", "Date": "on March 22, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Sweet start with a big bump!", "Text": "We have been using the hub for 2 months until there was a recent version upgrade. Now the Samsung motion sensor and GE switch donot talk with the hub anymore. Due to mixed reviews, we were slowly automating room wise and thankfully have completed one room and in the process of second room when we hit a bump.\n\nSamsung support is currently helping us in resolving the problem. All in all, there is still so much room to develop. In an ideal world, a software version upgrade should not prevent us from using the sensors."}
{"Author": "Chris Weed", "Date": "on March 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Ignore the iOS ratings, great device!", "Text": "So far so good, and super easy to install. I was up and running in minutes. It's a shame the iOS app has such a bad rating, I haven't seen anything terrible about the app yet. I think people use the App Store feedback as a place to post user-error frustrations."}
{"Author": "Laura", "Date": "on March 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do not waste your time.", "Text": "I had been looking to buy a SmartThings Hub for a few months and jumped on the opportunity when it came up as a deal of the day on Amazon (as a combo with a smart things switch). I had selected it due to its compatibility with a number of devices that I already own: Ecobee3, wemo switches, netatmo weatherstation, sonos speaker. I thought that having a hub would make life simpler. It turns out this thing is junk. It has done nothing but frustrate me in the three weeks I have had it. Today I printed the return label and it is going back to Amazon. For those of you looking to buy one, I have listed out the specific issues I have had. My only advice: buyer beware!\n\n1. It is not actually compatible with Ecobee3. The website still says its compatible. As I was first setting up the device, Ecobee3 does not come up as a device I could connect to. When I google I find that there indeed isn't an app to connect it and I would have to \"donate\" to some random person on the internet to get code to connect it?! These didn't seem reasonable, so I emailed customer service. He told me to just select a different ecobee thermostat and that it would find it. I guess he was right, because it did connect, but it only stayed connected a couple days before it gave me an error that my credentials were incorrect - even though they hadn't changed. That is when I gave up on thermostat functionality.\n2. Then there was the lights. For the first week, there was a issue with the time. I had lights going on at all hours even though I only had a rule to turn them on at sunset, which at the time was ~5:45 here in CT. I had to delete all my rules and reinstall them before it would function as I wanted.\n3. Then my wemo switches lost connection. They worked fine for about a week and then they appeared offline. I could still go into the Wemo app to turn the lights on and off, so they are certainly \"online\". But I couldn't turn them on or off with the SmartThings app and they were not turning on and off with my scheduled routines. Again, I emailed customer support. After going back and forth twice with him and still not able to connect them I gave up. It just wasn't worth it!\n4. I had it connected to my sonos speakers. As part of my routines, it was supposed to read me the weather for the next day at bed time. This worked for the first week or so, but hasn't been working the last few days. I also mentioned this to customer support and his only suggestion was that they had to be on the same network to work. Well of course they are on the same network! When I mentioned this in my second email to him, he just ignored it.\n5. Then there was a few days in a row when I couldn't even open the app. It kept giving me an error message that there was an internet connection issue even though I still had complete functionality on other apps and other people in the house could open the app on their phone."}
{"Author": "jennie", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Integrates well with Amazon Echo and Schlage Smart Lovk"}
{"Author": "K. Pitchford", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good when it works", "Text": "It's great..... when it works. If there's any connection disruption whatsoever, it will remain unusable (along with all devices) until you take the batteries out, unplug it, and then reconnect it all. It won't reset the connection even when internet is restored. It just stays in a fault mode. I tried two of them; same problem. It's a firmware problem that's apparently been ongoing for 6mos or so given the reviews. I guess they don't care about addressing it."}
{"Author": "Rob Iceman", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't waste your money!", "Text": "You need the SmartThings app to control your devices, and that app is complete garbage. Samsung should be embarrassed to publish an app that is so full of bugs it is useless. Read the reviews at the App Store before buying this junk."}
{"Author": "Boomer", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Great!", "Text": "Works great....way better than Wemo without a hub....gives me so many more options for automation."}
{"Author": "R. K.", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Using smart phones as presence sensors is also flakey at times", "Text": "For the most part, this system has worked well. The biggest problem I've had is with a known issue with the built in scheduler. Time based events don't trigger sometimes such as turning on and off lights and executing automated routines which is the most basic job of a home automation system. Using smart phones as presence sensors is also flakey at times. These problems seem to come and go randomly. The system will be great when they gets these bugs worked out."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I do recommend this hub for your home automation!", "Text": "Excellent product!"}
{"Author": "Amazon customer", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SMART home up and running in 20 minutes- Purchased this ...", "Text": "SMART home up and running in 20 minutes- Purchased this after reading the CNET review calling it the most \"universal: of the SMART home controls. Within 20 minutes of taking t out of the Box all of my smart devices were up and running. Downloading the APP to my iPhone and going through the APP set up was the longest part. Great job Samsung"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Like it", "Text": "Works well little bit of lag time connecting with app and small learning curve pretty much plug and play support has been geat"}
{"Author": "B.T.", "Date": "on March 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Switched from Vera lite, helped make it easier on the non-techies in my family.", "Text": "Pros and cons discovered during my switch from Vera lite. Generally much easier to use, but a little more limiting in flexibility for creative configurations. Luup code in Vera is easier than Groovy scripting for SmartThings. Vera felt customizable by a hobbyist techie but very raw for the poor Luddites in my house that had to suffer through it. Smartthings is easy on the rest of my household, but I had to get a GitHub account and write real code for some things, which was a little more time and effort to learn than I was hoping for. Generally I recommend the switch."}
{"Author": "Prime Time", "Date": "on March 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub Offline", "Text": "Update: My SmartThings hub used to continually goes offline (every day) for no reason it also would lose the ability to control my HUE lights at least once or twice per week. Since the last big update both of these issues seem to be resolved. Hopefully I can now move on to playing with this device to see how else I can use it to integrate items in the house."}
{"Author": "T. Bruce", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fun hobby hub for home use", "Text": "Fun hobby hub for home use. Don't get this for Grandma. You need to be an engineer or at least highly techy to enjoy this. Concept is great. Execution is a little lacking."}
{"Author": "Drew", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'll be bringing the stupid wink hub piece of garbage back to home depot", "Text": "It works. It has a battery backup. It's wired. Thank God I bought this. I'll be bringing the stupid wink hub piece of garbage back to home depot"}
{"Author": "Jenna M Barefoot", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Run away from this product!", "Text": "Do not buy! System is unstable. When the alarm goes off you cannot dismiss. Most of the time when I want to arm the alarm that doesn't even work. Complete piece of junk. Support is terrible. I put in a ticket and got a reply almost a month later. Awful. Dreadful even."}
{"Author": "Freeze", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty good product", "Text": "I'm coming from staples connect, which was rock solid and all local processing BUT they stopped development and features are really lacking, so that is why i made the switch to ST v2. I've read the forums of smartthings for a long time now so I knew what i was getting into. This product is FAR from perfect but does provide very enhanced functionality with a lot of device support. The smartthings community is your best friend, that is where you'll get most of your help and smart apps. The app does give errors sometimes, but your exceptions just have to be set and you have to have patience. This is not a cheap system so I understand we all want it to be perfect, but it's not...but again this product can take your HA to a new level. Your home automation can really integrate to the extreme with this system. I'm looking forward to future updates to make it even better."}
{"Author": "Stoney Bubbles", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings would be great if it worked", "Text": "SmartThings would be great if it worked... I've been very disappointed. Routines often fail with no rhyme or reason. Things my be going fine for weeks then it decides to stop running a routine for a day or two, then start working again all on it's own. I've spent more time debugging this and trying to understand why routines fail and why it doesn't arm or disarm itself then it's worth. Would be easier for me turn the lights on and off myself. I've never seen such a buggy piece hardware/software in my life.\n\nThe sensors are great, it works with almost any sensor or light bulb, and I would change my rating to 5 stars if this hub worked reliably.. It doesn't.\n\nBe warned. This product is not even close to being ready for the consumer market."}
{"Author": "LDubya", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "HORRIBLE and USELESS support and can't view recorded camera footage.", "Text": "Where do I start? As a security system, its pretty much useless since you can't view any recorded footage. I contacted their support team and they confirmed it as a known issue and that they are working on it. So I have two dud cameras hanging from my ceiling right now and they don't know when the issue will be resolved. I also installed two motion sensors but for some reason they keep pairing with the Smartthings Hub as window and door open/close sensors. I contacted support and they were not helpful at all. Speaking of their support...\n\nTheir support is HORRIBLE. First of all, they don't offer phone support. On their website it states that they offer live chat support, but it turns out that due to the overwhelming demand for their support, they have disabled live chat support as well. So the only way to reach them is via email which typically takes them 2 days to get back to you and thats only if you are persistent with following up with them. On top of that, the actual support you receive will make you want to pull your hair out. I couldn't connect my cameras to my wifi signal so they gave me some bogus instructions on how to do it and after going back and forth for about a week, I gave up on Samsung's support and called D Link camera's support and they helped me figure it out on the spot. They also do not offer any support during the weekend so if you send an email on Friday you probably won't get a response till the following Tuesday. That's not acceptable IMO.\n\nI'm at my wit's end with the Smartthings Hub and their support. Their whole eco system is bug ridden and unreliable that you really can't depend on it as a security system. Do yourself a favor and stay AWAY from Smartthings!"}
{"Author": "Jeff Knight", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy Peasy home automation.", "Text": "This is my first foray into the home automation technologies. The smartThings hub is easy to hook up and simple to download apps for. It gets a little more difficult if you want to create your own apps, but there are people that are doing it for free or cheap. I have this paired with a Schlage lock, Liftmaster MyQ garage doors, and lutron Z-wave switches.\n\nI control my back door lock, outisde lights, and garage doors."}
{"Author": "Jeff K", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I can't recommend this product anymore", "Text": "I can't recommend this product anymore. I have purchased both the original V1 as well as the V2 hub. I have spent a ton of money on switches, sensors, etc. I LOVED SmartThings. However, for the past few months there have been COUNTLESS outages. \"SmartApps\" fail to run with increasing frequency. Sunday, I couldn't disarm the \"Smart\" Home Monitor. Thus every light in my house and a million notifications were sent every time a door opened or God forbid, I moved in my living room, bedroom or basement. Finally after hours of messing with it I found out it was an outage. I didn't find out from Samsung, I found out from other users in their forums. This outage is still happening, almost a week later. I have disabled all security features and now I have an expensive product that I can turn on lights with. Yay. Stay away, I feel SmartThings is a sinking ship, even with Samsung's backing."}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good idea, horrible implementation.", "Text": "I love this idea, but find it mind blowing how buggy and bad the app is. There are constant glitches with my system, resulting in false alarms all the time."}
{"Author": "Scott P.", "Date": "on March 17, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "not reliable - too many issues", "Text": "problems with smart home monitor app: recently became unable to \"arm\" from app though app shows armed. system basically stuck in disarm mode. automations related to disarm are working but cannot arm. emailed support but also seeing lots of posts on internet over same issue.\n\ni'm not convinced that these are technologically reliable yet. have also had a few false alarms on garage door sensor not showing closed when it is - requiring me to return home to check."}
{"Author": "Captain America", "Date": "on March 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Setup is chancy, operation is spotty, but still a nice luxury", "Text": "This whole ecosystem of devices is not perfect. Setting the stuff up is incredibly random and hinky, but once it works, it's nice."}
{"Author": "Byzantine Catholic", "Date": "on March 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Extremely unstable", "Text": "Extremely unstable\n\nMy alarm system keeps arming and disarming -- siren going off in the middle of the night\n\nGreat concept and I hope they work it out BUT it is PAINFUL"}
{"Author": "Jon", "Date": "on March 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "returned", "Text": "works well but lacks some of the integration i wanted. the whole market is in a mix atm trying to figure out what to buy for a smart home right now is a mess.i suggest waiting for a front runner or at least make sure you get one that integrate well with what you may already have. i returned."}
{"Author": "Matt D", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "OK as a toy and for non critical home automation", "Text": "But fails miserably as a security system. Constant false alarms. Have to re-initialize and add devices back after software updates. Devices periodically and arbitrarily get removed from hub. Got tired of having a science fair project for home automation/security and gave it to my kids as a toy."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "it's ok"}
{"Author": "M C Arnold", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings needs to get their act together", "Text": "This would be a good product if the Smartthings programmers could get their acts together. I have been dealing with a known issue where I have to uninstall security and reinstall and reconfigure frequently, a known issue that apparently they cannot fix. My presence sensors stopped working, and I frequently find the security has disarmed itself. Not trustworthy enough to be considered a security solution."}
{"Author": "Tom C", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works for Me!!", "Text": "Seems to work for me. I had the V2 since Dec 2015 it seemed to work fine up until the last firmware update. For some reason the antenna range dropped and it stopped communicating with 2 Z wave switches. I tried everything to connect to the HUB no dice. So I purchased Aeon range extenders from Amazon and reconnected the switches to the hub and all seems to be back in line and the routines are running with no issue. I had contacted SmartThings support and spoke to Jake several times thru email he was very helpful, and concerned that the system stopped working. He had given some advise on what to try and also helped on getting Echo to reconnect to the switches.\nI am very tech savvy and even have built interfaces for my alarm system to tie other peripherals to it. This is pretty much a no brainer and easy to setup. I had an X10 system is my home for 10 yrs and struggled from time to time to make certain peripherals to work, so pretty use to the hit or miss aspect of this technology."}
{"Author": "Cornerview", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as expected.", "Text": "This has worked well for me in the 3 months I have been using it. I've had no problems with it, and I have a number of devices linked to it.\nI've not had to reboot it. I've received one firmware update. Samsung notified me that the update would occur automatically on a certain date, and it did. The update installed without any assistance from me, and it works.\nI like that the hub works with both Zwave and Zigbee devices.\nI would recommend this to anyone who needs a hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't count on it.", "Text": "I can't count on it to do something as basic as turning a light on and off consistently. How could I possibly count on it to control a door lock or any other critical \"thing\""}
{"Author": "Informed Buyer", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A very powerful platform, much better user experience but a steep learning curve unless you know where to look", "Text": "I've been a user of SmartThing since the early days of the 1st Generation Hub. It's been one heck of a journey.\n\nQuick comparison, it's much easier to use than Vera, more powerful and flexible than Wink. Overall the possibilities with this hub is endless.\n\nThe best way to describe the experience with SmartThings is AWESOME! Awe as in the power of what it can do but at the same time it needs a lot of handholding. Think of it as building blocks to build your dream home and futuring experience. You can do a bunch of simple things like remotely locking your door, programming your thermostat, checking for open door/windows, water leaks etc. That's the basic stuff. However if you really want to excel at this you' can have an AWESOME experience but you'll need some hand holding and help to get there. Unfortunately while SmartThings is just the platform you can find a VERY active helpful community to help you get what you want from this.\n\nSo after tinkering with this for over two years a few of us decided to get together an create a bunch of Apps that allow you to extract the most out of this SmartThings hub. All you need a bunch of Z-Wave devices like Schlage Connect Camelot Touchscreen Deadbolt with Built-In Alarm, Satin Nickel, BE469 CAM 619, Garage Door Controller like GoControl/Linear GD00Z-4 Z-Wave Garage Door Opener Remote Controller, Small, Black Monoprice Z-Wave motion sensors for about 21 bucks, Ecolink Z-Wave Door/Window Sensor (DWZWAVE2-ECO) and maybe things like a Z-Wave Water Sensor or even WiFi Cameras like Foscam FI9821P Plug & Play Megapixel 1.0 Megapixel 1280 x 720 Wireless/Wired Pan/Tilt IP Camera with IR-Cut (Black) or the All New Fabulous Battery Operated Blink Camera (Blink Smart Home HD Monitor & Alert System, 100% Wire-Free - 1 Camera). Once you have these basics here are a few things you can do:\n1. When you and the family leave the house, the garage door closes, the doors lock up, the lights turn off, the thermostats change to eco settings and you get a confirmation that all doors/windows are closed and locked! It also arms the security system and turns on the camera to detect for motion.\n2. When a family member comes home, it disarms the security system, opens your garage door and unlocks your front door.\n3. If your family comes into town or you have a friend coming over, you can remotely create a lock code for them to use. When use it, the door unlocks, security system disarms, the audio system greets them by name, the camera takes a picture and send it to you to confirm they're arrived home safely.\n4. If there's a water leak in the house, it sets off the alarm, send you a message and turns off the mains to the house (yes it can do that!!) so there's no flodding\n5. If it's a cloudy day it can turn on the lights automatically inside the house, when the sun comes out it turns them off, in the evening it turns it on automatically and shuts everything down when you goto bed\n\nThese are some of the apps we have written to make the most out of this platform and hub. Overall it's a VERY powerful and flexible platform but if you aren't a programmer start with the community for help or visit the RBoy Apps website at www-rboyapps-com to see what you can get done to make your House Your Butler!\n\nEnjoy!!!\n\nPS - I've given it 4 stars, as much as we love this platform, is because you will need some help to make the most out of it, but truly once you're figure it out, Google NEST will look like a historical artifact!"}
{"Author": "Erik S.", "Date": "on March 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Started rough but has greatly improved", "Text": "This hub was my first HA hub so I don't have the frustrations that many Gen 1 owners have with trying to upgrade. Having said that, there were a lot of issues when I first purchased the Gen 2 hub (I preordered it from the ST website and received it shortly after release). The devices I bought with the hub paired fine and they functioned properly but I'd get random notifications that the hub was offline then back online a couple minutes later.\n\nST pushed out an update to the hub a couple months ago that has made the experience *vastly* better. The hub is no longer going offline randomly and everything seems to be working as it should.\n\nThe best part is easily the integration with the Amazon Echo. Being able to control my lights and devices with just my voice is not only cool but convenient as well. No more having to take out my phone and go into the app to manually change something that isn't set on a schedule. It also integrates well with the Harmony Hub, so I can turn my TV and other media devices on/off with just my voice.\n\nAs far as I can tell, everything still processes in the cloud, so I'm hoping that they open up the local processing to developers soon. I've got cellular backup on my primary internet, so I'm not too worried about the cloud integration now.\n\nOverall, things were initially a bit rough but after the major update a month or so ago things have been fantastic. It's not perfect, and anyone whose leery of the cloud should look elsewhere, but overall it's been a very good center for my home automation needs."}
{"Author": "Johnathan Mason", "Date": "on March 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "ugh.", "Text": "extremely unreliable. Works one minute, doesn't the next. If you like being continually frustrated, go for it."}
{"Author": "Sze Ching Mao", "Date": "on March 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible Experiences: - I purchased this item in NEW ...", "Text": "I have 3 brand new switches (Wemo, TP-Link and Ankuoo NEO), and none of them could be connected with the hub.\n\nTerrible Experiences:\n- I purchased this item in NEW condition (From amazon), the box was taped by some cheap tape. Maybe that's why I can't any app instruction.\n- The menu is terribly designed, it made me to read through the whole menu to find the download link for the apps\n- To activate the hub you need a code, but it took me 5+ attempts to get through (I emailed support and took them 2 days to email me just a case # (no solutions)\n\n- There are absolutely no instructions on how to use the app ( the menu that came with the box only shows you how to setup the hardware)\n- This hub only works specific brand and MODEL I guess. Make sure you buy the most expensive brand (specific Wemo) and check out their compatible list .. haha\n\nExtra info::\nWait for gen 3 or something, gen 2 is for lab rats!\n\nSwitches:\nSurprisingly, the cheapest brand ==> Ankuoo NEO works the best for me and their app load the fastest and response really quick but the draw back is, it doesn't work with Amazon Echo. Wemo is the worst and the most expensive, you can pour coffee or turn on and off 10 times physically while waiting (20s for single switch) for the app to load and scan for switches. TP-Link has reasonable price and the app has good response time (way better than Wemo) and it's compatible with Echo w/o hub.. Woohoo..! Not so fast, TP-link only makes \"smart plug\", they don't make switches. You can only buy TP for plug in devices, no ceiling lights or any appliance uses \"wall switch\"\n\n2016/03/19\nJust received my Wemo light switch which is on SmarThings' compatible list. Still no luck getting it to conncet to any of my smart plug/switches. I am returning it. Good luck!"}
{"Author": "clearwaterick", "Date": "on March 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love Samrtthings", "Text": "So far, I love my Smartthings hub and program. I look forward to their continuing to add additional items that will work with this hub. So far, no problems. Love it!!"}
{"Author": "Paul M. Sabatino", "Date": "on March 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... bulbs and GE ZWave lighting switches I quickly and easily transitioned from an intro WINK to this", "Text": "Using GE Link bulbs and GE ZWave lighting switches I quickly and easily transitioned from an intro WINK to this. The technical support, while only available by email was extremely helpful and always responded within 5 minutes of my email. I was very impressed with both the ease of use and the customer support."}
{"Author": "Robert DiLegge", "Date": "on March 12, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings is awesome. It's extremely responsive to both my Android phone ...", "Text": "SmartThings is awesome. It's extremely responsive to both my Android phone and my wife's iPhone. Had a few small issues setting it up but the SmartThings support team was very responsive. I'm happy to build our smart house around this platform!"}
{"Author": "Les236", "Date": "on March 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub!", "Text": "The included directions point you to a web site to download the app for either your smart phone or tablet. I used my tablet. I was presented with a video that walked me through the setup and it worked exactly as stated. My only hitch was it mentioned the one-time use code on the bottom of a card in the box. I couldn't find it at first, as it was the cardboard holder that the instructions came in. It took me a while until I found that and turned it over. I have integrated several devices and lights so far and it is great and works fine."}
{"Author": "Fisher900", "Date": "on March 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Top Hub Available", "Text": "I bought this to break into the home automation world and so far I really like it. I have it connected to 3 GE Link LED bulbs. It seems to have flawless control over them and they were easy to connect. The SmartThings app is intuitive and easy to use.\n\nI connected this to my Alexa and now I can control my lights with my voice! It was simple to setup. Rarely I will run into a problem where the hub simply doesn't respond to commands. This was particularly bad for 3 days. It was simply an inconvenience but it could have been worse had I owned the garage door opener, thermostat or door locks. I believe this is a server issue on Samsungs end and nothing I could do alleviated the problem. It only does this now during the occasional 10 minute maintenance update. These happen roughly once a month.\n\nI recommend this over every other home automation hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Everything works great for me", "Text": "Have had smartthings with multiple products connect to it including hue, wemo, etc for about a year. Everything works great for me, and when I do have a slight issue support has always answered me back within a couple\nHours for my issues. Top notch. And everything works nice. No big issues. Recommend to everyone."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Since I have owned the SmartThings Hub (got it in ...", "Text": "Since I have owned the SmartThings Hub (got it in December 2015) it has gone offline at least once a week. I haveto power it off and pull the batteries to reset it. Obviously this is a problem when you depend on this Hub to run automated patterns while you are away from home and not there to pull the batteries once a week. SmartThings support keeps telling me they are working on it and I get no resolution. I will be returning it, if Amazon will even take it back at this point. Don't buy this Hub, save yourself some greif."}
{"Author": "Scott D.", "Date": "on March 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "2) Samsung reboots your unit whenever they feel like it. 3) Samsung patches and makes changes to ...", "Text": "You\u2019re in for a real treat with this piece of work. What they don\u2019t tell you\u2026 1) Samsung controls your unit (from wherever they are located, Korea?). 2) Samsung reboots your unit whenever they feel like it. 3) Samsung patches and makes changes to your unit whenever they feel like it. 4) It never works right after they touch it, count on it being down every month. I\u2019ve had the pleasure of having my smart-home completely down from them making changes remotely. You\u2019ll become a master at repairing your Z-network, putting your devices in exclusion mode, putting your hub in exclusion mode, completely re-adding and configuring every device in your house to troubleshoot something Samsung broke. I\u2019ve had my system working 100% for weeks at a time, until Samsung touches it, then its broke and needs days of work to repair it, if it ever works again. I\u2019m currently stuck with all my thermostats down and Samsung can\u2019t do a thing to fix it because they don\u2019t know what they broke with the last update. You current customers know what I\u2019m talking about, the emails every month \u201cGood news we found something wrong with your smarthub, it only affects a few people (aka everyone) so we\u2019re going to apply a fix and reboot your unit this Wednesday\u201d.\nSo you want to put your faith in this unit for home security, flood protection, locking your doors, controlling temperature. You\u2019ll enjoy when your flood sensor says \u201ceverything is dry, battery 100%\u201d. And later you realize after water\u2019s on the floor, the batteries have been dead for weeks but Samsung still shows it as 100% functional. It\u2019s really become a joke in my house. Garage door up all the time, no problem come and enter my house because this unit will never trigger the alarm. Don\u2019t forget your keys because your automated door locks won\u2019t work when you need them to. I\u2019ve spent $1000\u2019s of dollars on devices that for all intense and purpose, I might as well throw in the garbage because Samsung smarthub makes them useless. I have cameras that will go offline in the smarthub, but will work perfectly with any other software tool, then magically work after a few days.\nThe support staff are nice, I know all them now very well, even what days and shifts they work. Unfortunately they all do the same thing over and over again without success, reboot, add, remove, zwave repair, etc. Nothing ever gets fixed until the next month\u2019s forced updates from Samsung (after they realized whatever mistakes they made with the previous update).\nThis was a great concept that has failed miserably in execution. I\u2019ll try any other vendor at this point.\n\n***Update 6/12/2016***\nI'm raising up to 4 stars from 1. Samsung has made alot of updates, almost monthly and my system is functioning about 100% of the time. I purchased some zwave repeaters and they solved alot of my issues. I have the smarthub in the basement, and it was acting sporadic with updating my devices. Once I installed the repeaters in the basement, 1st floor, and 2nd floor of my house, my sporadic issues went away. I've added more LED lights, fire alarms, motion detectors, and everything is working great to be honest, no complaints. I'll happily raise to 5-stars if this level maintains for a few more months. Thanks Samsung for making improvements."}
{"Author": "John Marshall", "Date": "on March 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Service Great Product", "Text": "I bought this specifically to provide abridge between Amazon Echo and my Logitech Harmony hub. At first I was a tad frustrated that I couldn't add my Harmony Hub activities as I kept getting an error \"Failed to Save Page Credentials\". Checked the smart things forums but nothing conclusive. I emailed smartthings support and very quickly was told there is a bug in the Echo interface but a work around was given to me. The work around worked a treat and am happy to wait for the new firmware update with the bug fixed shortly. Great service great product!"}
