{"Author": "Frank", "Date": "on February 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you can read and follow a recipe, there is no reason you can't make this work.", "Text": "I was interested in smart home items for a long long time, and read many reviews on hubs before deciding on this one. The open source apps and ability to add custom 'things' to your network along with no monthly fees is what made the sale. I also already had a foscam wireless camera and this hub had a community made app that allowed them to work together instead of me having to buy a new camera. Neat.\n\nAnyway~ I opened it up, followed the directions to a T, and everything worked instantly. Well, it took about 5 minutes to download a software update but when that was done, it worked instantly. From the gps phone locator that turns things on when I arrive or leave home, the messages and status about your 'things', the easy to follow app to set your 'routines'... simple. If you can read and follow a recipe, there is no reason you can't make this work. I figured out my old fridge is an energy hog, more so than the lights I always forget to turn off at night.\n\nMy only complaint is that I have an older iphone 4, and if I don't leave the app running sometimes it doesn't automatically know when I return 'home' and I have to click the routine manually. I think this is a problem with my phone and not the software though, and they do make little transponders that are supposed to be more accurate than the phone geolocator.\n\nRight now I just have the camera and some on/off switches for lights, and since it all works I will be adding in more soon. This is a great way to monitor the status of your home or business from your phone, and automatically turn on/off lights and security when you come and go.\n\nI don't think I would substitute this for a monthly-fee hard-wired security system that sounds an alarm and calls the cops or fire dept just yet, mainly because if your phone rings and you left it in the car or didn't notice it vibrate, and didn't check and notice it was going off until lunch time... it could be ineffective. I know I know, there are apps and services that let it do all that, but the main weakness in the system is actually your phone and your ability to instantly view notifications.\n\nI can see once they get this more... idiot proof... that insurance companies and fire departments would WANT people to include these in homes. Knowing when fire alarms and carbon monoxide detectors are going off can save lives, but because 90% of the time they are just false alarms that will be the part they need to work through next from their end.\n\nBasic home security, safety, energy monitoring, hvac control, and turning lights on/off when you come and go, and camera triggered photos and lights/alarms. I have mine set up as a wakeup alarm by turning on my lights when the sun comes up in the morning. Neat.\n\nLooking forward to seeing how these progress, and the open source nature of Samsung SmartThings makes it fun."}
{"Author": "KinkadeNeb", "Date": "on February 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Drops connected bulbs constantly....", "Text": "Had this hub for almost 2 months, and switched our entire house to Cree led connected bulbs. We have a whole house Sonos system and a few WeMo outlets as well. The Samsung hub would drop the entire network of bulbs about every day, rendering them all useless, on both the app and our Amazon Echo. Sent over 20 emails to 'support' with only 2 actual responses after 3 weeks..... They said it was my WiFi in my house, but my Sonos and WeMo had worked fine for years. I sent it back, purchased a Wink hub for $30 less, and all 28 bulbs have worked perfectly since, and have never dropped off once."}
{"Author": "sparkyjoe1", "Date": "on February 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't waste your money.......", "Text": "Doesn't work....iris hub from lowes works great!!!!! Go with it instead....I am a journeyman electrician......couldn't get it to work....."}
{"Author": "R. Restrepo", "Date": "on February 28, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love the fact that I am able to see the ...", "Text": "I love the fact that I am able to see the recent status of the individual things whenever i want."}
{"Author": "TriOptimum", "Date": "on February 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable, problematic platform", "Text": "My smart things system has not worked reliably since the v1 hub over a year ago. I upgraded to the new hub thinking it would be more reliable (they touted it as being more reliable due to having local network support instead of running everything through their unreliable servers).\n\nIt has not improved - reliability and function have gotten worse as they introduce new features tot the Samsung v2 hub without testing them well enough first. Constantly I have trouble with this or that. Sometimes certain devices or functions of the app become unresponsive, slow, or do not work. Sometimes notifications work, sometimes they don't, sometimes they send multiples over time.\n\nSince late February, I cannot disarm my security system through smart things reliably. Every time I open the door, the alarm goes off, and I have to wait for a call form the monitoring company so the police don't come. This is the result of a total outage from late February they claimed to have fixed but lots of users on the forums report different problems - inability to log in, disarm the alarm, and others. These problems have been persistent for almost a month now.\n\nThe platform is falling apart. The support staff are getting quiet and it seems like people there are giving up on fixing these problems."}
{"Author": "SignsTechGuru", "Date": "on February 27, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings, dumbthings, or Sungthings.", "Text": "Ok...I have had this device now since release and at 1st I was in love with it, but the longer I have owned it and the more devices I have added, the more issues that have arisen. I really want to love it, but since release, the promise to expand...not just to SAMSUNG devices...but to other popular devices has really not happened. They really lack support in the security camera realm...unless you are a fan of Dlink or Samsung cams. My father has the Samsung can and he has nothing but issues with it working correctly. With all this said, I will just do some Pros and Cons and be done with it. Oh...fyi, they sold out to the big home surveillance companies for that paid monitoring option...which I and many users feel they were not ready for.\n\nPros:\n-Price on the hub isn't too bad, but not as competitive as it should be.\n-ZigBee, Zwave adaptable\n-Battery backup\n-Compact\n-Works for the most part, but not fail safe when you need it.\n-SmartApps don't always work and same with Routines. Stuff doesn't turn off as scheduled...just afraid of failing when I need it to work right.\n\nCons:\n-Smartthings add-ons are always more expensive than other brands.\n-Bluetooth still not enabled by company\n-A lot of things that were advertised when they started to sell it still are not enabled.\n-Smartapps not always working right\n-Routines not always working right.\n-Not compatible with a lot of stuff, yet compatible with stuff I don't want or need. It's great it will work with home entertainment devices, but I didn't buy it for that. Home automation and security!\n\nI hope it gets better, but I can see them releasing another version before that happens."}
{"Author": "Ryan G", "Date": "on February 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This thing is AWESOME! I'm using it to control a bunch of ...", "Text": "This thing is AWESOME! I'm using it to control a bunch of Econet EV100 vents for bedrooms, so we only heat our living space during the day, and only the bedrooms at night. Love it!"}
{"Author": "Anonymous", "Date": "on February 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Unpleasant Home Automation", "Text": "This device requires cloud connectivity at all times. Remember: there's no cloud, it's just someone else's computer. And I'll tell you what, this thing loses connectivity with those other computers all the time.\n\nIn the last month, my routines have failed to run on dozens of occasions. The integrations I have built with my Amazon Echo and Harmony Hub have been broken numerous times. Just check out [...] for a list of all the times your hub will break. I've worked hard to get buy-in from my wife for having a smart home, and this thing is dumb as a doorknob. It's not helping the cause.\n\nThis is not a pleasant HA experience, and I would highly advise people to not use this product."}
{"Author": "NM", "Date": "on February 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Could not get working right not sure if it was used but looked open."}
{"Author": "Jonathan", "Date": "on February 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Keep your search going. Don't settle for this", "Text": "I give it 2 stars because it functions but honestly it's junk. It has 20 errors I see routinely and the app is terrible. It stands a great chance of being returned"}
{"Author": "ChrisO", "Date": "on February 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I think it's the best hub around", "Text": "I like open source and this platform is the best to work with. You can add unlimited and deal with any changes. My only issue is they are slow at adding new products and the hub tends to go offline from time to time. Other than that it is the best smart home hub around."}
{"Author": "W. Henry", "Date": "on February 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung SmartHub is dumb as they come.", "Text": "SmartThings Hub is completely unreliable. Don't buy under any circumstances. Once you get it online it works great. The only problem is that it stays online for less than a day. It's time for this hub to take a trip to the garbage can. Unreliable and it looks as if Samsung will not fix their problem. This has been going on for over a month."}
{"Author": "GroovyGeek", "Date": "on February 24, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just a toy, not suitable for security", "Text": "I am finding the ST hub to be completely unreliable for anything \"serious\". As I am writing this the status of my phone shown under \"Things\" is \"Away\". Same for my wife's phone. Despite this the \"Goodbye\" routine has not executed for 5 hrs despite it having a trigger to execute when \"Everyone leaves\" and the definition of \"everyone\" is mine and my wife's phones. On some days it executes, on others it does not. Nothing is changing in the setup and the connectivity of the ST hub, it just seems to have a mind of its own. Door sensor status sometimes is updated correctly and sometimes not. I bought a panic button to mount on my wife's night stand so she has some way of triggering a siren at night when I am away in the unlikely event of an intrusion. When I test the button sometimes it triggers an even and sometimes it does not. And that is with the button less than 10 ft from the hub and the router that the hub is connected to. In other words the system is completely unsuitable to manage a DYI security setup in your home. I cannot trust it to automatically trigger a siren because I can't trust it to trigger when it has to, and equally importantly I cannot trust it to NOT trigger when it should not. The ONLY thing the system is good for at this time is \"for fun\" applications, such as sending out an \"alarm\" when my wife's phone returns within the geofencing range, speaking \"hello gorgeous\" through the Sonos when the front door opens, turn lights on/off when we are away, or control the garden fountain. For anything else where frequent failure is not an option look elsewhere. So far I have about $200 invested in the setup and am still debating whether to write it off as a total loss or hope for the best over time. Based on my experience so far I sure am not buying any more z-wave devices. These things are still fairly pricey, and if they don't work properly what is the point?"}
{"Author": "Josh Kramer", "Date": "on February 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup for Smart Home Noobs", "Text": "works great for all my home smart automation but for my Zwave switches ran through my harmony remotes is a bit slow."}
{"Author": "Craig K. Cozze", "Date": "on February 24, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was good, but is quickly declining", "Text": "I have had SmartThings since the beginning with v1 hub, when Samsung had nothing to do with them. I have to say, ever since Samsung has taken control of the product it has been extremely unreliable. I maybe switching over to wink which now has true local control of lights"}
{"Author": "Zachary G", "Date": "on February 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect system. Horrible app and lack of web GUI", "Text": "Perfect system. Horrible app and lack of web GUI. Somewhat reliable. Perk is that you can add almost anything."}
{"Author": "Amaizing Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 23, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Class action lawsuit? Where is it? NEVER works", "Text": "I have a version 1 hub from before they were bought by samsung. It worked great at first. Found out that when the internet is out it doesn't work so after recieving an email from them about moving my extremely complicated setup for me, I bought the hub version 2. They have now informed me that they can't move me over to the new hub. The only option is to start over from scratch after reseting every single device. Every door sensor, every window sensor, motion sensor, vibration sensors, tempature sensors, garage door sensor, etc. Stay far away. Go with another company who doesn't force you to wipe out everything and start over every time you want to upgrade.\n\nUpdate: Purchased in February. I've been working with support and have found their product to be horribly buggy and their support nonexistent. They have email and chat support. Their phone support hung up on me after waiting for 15 minutes. They tell me to take the batteries out and unplug the power. This has to be done about once a week if not more. There are NO automated functions except horribly limited things like turning a light on or off on a schedule. If you have no internet you have no lights or door locks. I've reported many issues to them only to receive a response of \"It's a bug and we are working on it.\"\n\nSave your money and your sanity and buy anything else.\n\nUpdate: It still hasn't been a year and it doesn't work. I've opened at least 17 support tickets with them ending with \"We updated your firmware\" and yet it still happens. I have to do everything smart things is supposed to do manually. I'm wondering why there isn't a class action with these people. It can't do a basic schedule. That's it's function, to turn lights on and off on a schedule. I can now do that with the hue system and it works on time like it should."}
{"Author": "Trevor", "Date": "on February 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A+", "Text": "I couldn't be happier with my Hub. It works great with my Echo and SmartThings is a great platform for customization. I like their commitment to an open platform and allowing developers to create their own content. Any issues that I've had have been quickly solved by their support team. Keep up the great work."}
{"Author": "Jonathan", "Date": "on February 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far no issues. I have it paired with ...", "Text": "So far no issues. I have it paired with my locks for now. I wanted to add nest but haven't had the chance yet."}
{"Author": "STEVE CANNON", "Date": "on February 21, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not what I expected", "Text": "So far I have been very unsuccessful in connecting to my Kwikset 916. Which is the sole purpose I bought this hub. I own a Samsung smart thing hub and it works great with lights. But so far I'm disappointed with this product. If some listening can give me feedback on pairing the talked about hub (Samsung) to the Kwikset door knob please contact me telegodjr@gmail.com"}
{"Author": "Nick A Hippe", "Date": "on February 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Everything was great but then with no devices added or changes that ...", "Text": "I purchased a Smartthings hub a while back. Everything was great but then with no devices added or changes that I know of (there might have been a software update to the hub that I was unaware of) the problems started to show up. First the modes stopped working, I confirmed that this is a known issue with support. Then I was unable to control certain switches. I contacted support and worked with them for some time. I was told to exclude the problem devices and then run network repairs. I did this over and over. Every time I excluded one device another device started to have problems. Support was not able to provide any useful information and the information that they did provide turned out to be either wrong or useless. As an example I was told that when a mode failed that I needed to log into the web application and update the mode. I did that a couple of times but then decided to see what would happen if I did not update. The answer is nothing. It would still fail intermittently, updating did nothing."}
{"Author": "CRogers", "Date": "on February 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Expandable", "Text": "I bought the hub and water sensor for the basement sump pump and water heater. I set it up to get a text message if any water shows up. You can also check the status through the iOS App"}
{"Author": "Spencer K.", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If I could give it zero stars I would.", "Text": "If I could give it zero stars I would. Product didn't work, was unreliable, buggy, slow, and worthless. A waste of time and money, they tried sending me a replacement and that didn't work either. Tried using it with Schlage lock and Samsung smart outlets, all failed. Contacted Schlage and they recommended using the Wink hub instead. Returning this useless piece of garbage and moving onto something that actually works."}
{"Author": "George Fallar", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings just works without any painful fiddling", "Text": "We initially tried Belkin WeMo gear here and failed miserably, it simply wouldn't work correctly with our network in the house and I have 30+ years of networking experience.\n\nWe plugged the SmartThings hub into the network, and it worked. It has continued working form months now, it just sits there quietly next to the ASUS RT-AC68U router and does it's job.\n\nWe started slowly with a front porch light switch, a ceiling fan \"dimmer\", and an outlet (all from GE). We programmed the hub to turn on the porch light and the living room lamp 15 minutes before sundown every day. It just works.\n\nWe can also control all the SmartThings connected gear with Alexa and a Harmony hub, again after painless setup. We have since added a couple Cree programmable LED bulbs that also connected very easily and work flawlessly.\n\nThere have been a couple times after a router reboot or a SmartThings hub firmware update that the schedule for the lights has stopped working, requiring a five minute reprogramming effort. But that hasn't happened in some time now, so I am assuming Samsung has made some software revision to resolve those issues."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings app leaves a lot to be desired", "Text": "I had great hopes for the SmartThings hub, but it hasn't performed as I expected. Initial setup was easy, but using the hub has not been a good experience. The worst aspect of SmartThings is the terrible smartphone app that controls the hub. The app is confusing, cumbersome, and crashes often. Mine has crashed in the middle of an operation leaving garbage and errors every time is use it. The app wouldn't be as big a deal except that its the only way to control devices with SmartThings. There is no PC app or web app that can control devices, so you are stuck with the phone app."}
{"Author": "Jim Bryan", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best device of its kind on the market", "Text": "I've been using the SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation for several weeks now and love it. I live in a smart house which was built with a Nexia Z-wave system installed on locks and some light switches. The Nexia hub required a monthly service fee for access. I bought the SmartThings hub because I wanted to avoid monthly fees for my home automation, but it has given me so much more functionality than I had with my Nexia system. Setting it up was mostly effortless. The hub discovered most of my switches, locks, and thermostats with no problem. It discovered the one sensor that it initially couldn't find when I varied the timing of when I pushed the discover button on the sensor in the discovery process. The hub was compatible with all the devices in my home, and it has easily discovered new devices I have purchased since I learned about the increased functionality of the hub. I especially appreciate that SmartThings has it's own IFTTT channel for very specific automation menus, as well as compatibility with Amazon's Echo device. Teaming the SmartThings hub with Echo makes the whole home voice actuated. Very cool! The hub is also compatible with my Harmony Ultimate remote hub, so I can even control my audio/video system with voice commands using the Echo to direct the SmartThings hub to direct the Harmony remote. The cool thing is that everything is accessible from the single SmartThings app on my phone. I do not have to constantly switch between apps like I used to. No more switching between the Philips Hue Light app, Harmony, and Nexia the way I used to.\n\nWhat I am trying to say is that the SmartThings hub has truly integrated all the smart devices in my home as none other I know of could. One reason is that Samsung has a very enthusiastic SmartThings development team who is developing new uses and expanding compatible devices each month. I learn about the new features through a newsletter they send monthly. My only disappointment is that the hub is only compatible with one Samsung model of security cam. I have two Samsung cams that are not compatible and hope that the development team will write compatibility for my models into the software soon. In summary, I think this hub is the best on the market, requires no monthly service fee, and is getting better each month."}
{"Author": "David Budman", "Date": "on February 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Connectivity and UI was no bueno.,...returned it..."}
{"Author": "Steve", "Date": "on February 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The SmartThings is not very smart. It could not connect to the internet which ...", "Text": "The SmartThings is not very smart. It could not connect to the internet which is essential for doing its job. Technical support from Samsung is weak and involves a one or two delay email exchange. Even then the support team was unable to suggest any way to get the Hub to connect other than send it back to Amazon for a replacement. I did that but the replacement Hub was just as uncommunicative as the old one. Perhaps the Hub does work in other configurations. My configuration is a Comcast router and an Apple iPhone."}
{"Author": "Spoony920", "Date": "on February 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very close", "Text": "Been waiting a while since purchasing and using the ST hub before writing this review. I will try to summarize as best as possible. I think the product does work very well, but it's not quite perfect. If the hub were just a little more reliable I would say 5 stars for sure.\n\nI'm using the hub for home security/monitoring.\nHave about 10 devices on the hub: Door/Window sensors, motion sensors, alarm, water leak sensor\n\nSetup: I found the hub very easy to setup and configure, this was something I was very pleased with. Reading different reviews it sounded like people were having major issues with the hub and the smartphone application to configure/run it. I didn't have any of these experiences. I thought everything was very easy to get up and running for my purpose, and adding new sensors was painless. 5 stars for that\n\nFeatures: I think out of the box the hub does have most of the standard features/programs built in that someone would need. Obviously if you wanted to get more in depth with your automation some custom scripting will be necessary. Overall the smart phone application allowed me to easily configure everything that I wanted from the system so far.\n\nOperation: Overall I think it runs very well. I had one update pushed from Samsung that required a reboot, that was all. Otherwise I haven't had to try and reset/reboot the hub at all. I have sensors all over different levels of my house, attached garage, and an out building. The outbuilding is probably 100' from the hub or more and no issues seeing my sensors.\n\nReliability: This is the one spot where ST just isn't quite there yet. Randomly things just don't quite work, like my daily routines. I've reached out to Samsung on those, and they responded promptly but don't have the problems fixed yet. I've had a few devices give me false positives, and my alarm got stuck on at one point briefly. These are more issues with the devices themselves, and not so much the hub. I think if they can get the features within the hub to run just a little more consistently this will be the perfect solution.\n\nOverall: Very happy with this setup. I use it for home security/monitoring and it works very well. For the cost to setup, and the fact I have no monthly monitoring fees makes this a great value to me. I will continue to add a few more sensors over time, and hopefully it continues to be a success."}
{"Author": "nicholas-karl clement", "Date": "on February 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works as expected"}
{"Author": "Terry G.", "Date": "on February 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay Away!", "Text": "Run don't walk away from this product. It's a great idea but lacks on delivery. Cloud-based home automation is a great concept but Smart Things lacks in delivery. I've using version 1 since July 2015 and things started out ok but have their services have degraded in recent months. The simplest processes are simply put \"broken\". All timed events are NOT reliable and have not been for months. In addition I have a new version 2 hub still in the box because when I decided to order it I was not aware that they had not developed a migration tool, which they continue to promise they will have, but we are still waiting.\n\nI had so much hope for this to be a better experience but it's sad they can't seem to deliver on what I think are the simplest of tasks."}
{"Author": "Joseph M. Clemente", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can be USB powered!", "Text": "The Samsung SmartThings Hub 2nd Generation runs on 5V and can be USB powered thanks to a USB to Type M converter cable. I am using a multi-port USB \"charger\" to power this and other 5V devices, eliminating the clutter of power bricks."}
{"Author": "eric mathieu", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as described", "Text": "Works as described"}
{"Author": "Derek", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works Great"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After some difficulty, it worked for a day.", "Text": "I have a gen 1 hub. It wouldn't connect to anything, even supported devices. I only have 3 devices to connect. Customer support managed to help me get it working with an e-mail. Then the software crashed and nothing works again. It sent a \"crash\" report to wherever, but customer support isn't responding to me anymore. It was great when it worked, which was for about a day. Not recommended!"}
{"Author": "Dennis", "Date": "on February 16, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product, when it works. Unfortunately, that is not often enough", "Text": "I bought the Smartthings hub to replace a Revolv hub that google/nest had discontinued support for. So I had to find a replacement, and Smartthings seemed to have a good community and lots of supporters. I also had a bunch of Insteon switches and plugs (and previously an insteon hub). I replaced the insteon end points with Z-Wave at the same time as the hub upgrade.\n\nAfter having the new setup for two weeks, here is my take:\nThe good:\nThe hub is easy to set up, The app seems pretty good to me compared to Insteon, just OK compared to Revolv (Damn you Nest!). Lots of options for time based and sunup/sundown. Good support for a wide variety of devices (though not insteon...). Easy to set up devices when they are in range.\n\nThe bad:\nPerformance on certain routines seems to be optional. I set up the lights to go off at 11:30. Sometimes they do, sometimes, the hub forgets. Coffee on in the morning. Maybe, if it feels like it today. Seriously? My $10 alarm clock goes off EVERY day. No fail. But this thing can't even get basic time-based routines to execute with regularity. It works, maybe 50% of the time. I've been working with ST support - which to their credit, seems like they try hard. But no real explanation for why simple things don't work, or effective fixes. Seems like the problem is storing all the routines in the cloud. They just don't have it down.\n\nSeriously considering returning this - just don't know what to replace it with."}
{"Author": "Uncle Bob", "Date": "on February 16, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Things not smart", "Text": "Why is it we can have all makes and models of wireless alarm systems that work very well, but cannot have a ST system that works?"}
{"Author": "Rob J.", "Date": "on February 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wrong Z-Wave frequency band", "Text": "Actually I made a mistake with it. I needed a hub with as much different protocols as possible and the Samsung was a good candidate. Z-Wave, Zigbee and others. I was in the process of buying the hub in the UK but found out i could not have it shipped to Euro maninland. Still dont know why. So I switched to Amazon US and with some addition shipping funds i received the goods exceptionally fast . So far so good. But, at the end of the day, the US hub was obviously operating with another Zwave frequency band so the hub was quite useless here in Europe. I should have checked taht but I foolishly enough I didn't. If you are European, don't buy it. Get a UK or better a real Euro version. Meanwhile competitors with similar options pop up so i might switch to another brand completely."}
{"Author": "Justin E.", "Date": "on February 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Only for hobbyists with a lot of time on their hands", "Text": "I really want to love this platform, but the company has made it impossible. The community is so great, and there's so much good code out there that's free-to-use, but the platform is so completely unstable that it makes it impossible to rely upon. Scheduling and events are the top two requirements of any HA platform, and SmartThings scheduling is utterly and completely broken now, and has only become worse since I bought it 6 months ago. Want something to happen at sunrise everyday? You'll be lucky if it happens once a week. If you don't have reliability in your automations, then you've created *more* work for yourself instead of less."}
{"Author": "Kevin", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable $200 replacement for $20 timers", "Text": "I purchased the hub as part of a kit from Smart Things directly and added on switches from Amazon. Initially, the system worked mostly well with my programmed schedules automatically turning my lights in my house on and off.\n\nHowever, after less than 8 months of using the system, Smart Things completely screwed up their services so now my lights may or may not turn on/off according to their schedules. Contacting Smart Things results in canned responses along the lines of \"we know there is something wrong and we are working to fix it\". In the mean time, just reprogram your system over and over again every few days.\n\nLook elsewhere unless you have a ton of time to fiddle with this system.\n\nTwo stars because at least I can still turn the lights on and off from my phone."}
{"Author": "Bob Anderson", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is such a potentially great product, that it's really disappointing how badly it's ...", "Text": "This is such a potentially great product, that it's really disappointing how badly it's been botched. Repeatedly.\n\nI've had my hub for over a year, and today my porch lights did not turn off on sunup as they're correctly programmed to do. Now, a glitch here and there is maybe expected. But this happens more often than not. Is my hub broken? No. Is my setup flawed? No. What's happened is that the back end servers are overwhelmed with traffic causing scheduled events to not happen about as often as they happen.\n\nThis is all the result of a boneheaded (or worse, malicious) decision to make all scheduling require use of a centralized server. That's right, every time ANY SmartThings user *all over the world* has a desire to schedule an event as simple as turning on a light, this requires communicating with a centralized server for it to work. Now, why would they do something so stupid? Was it so they could charge subscription fees down the road once a bunch of people were \"hooked\"? Was it to datamine people's habits for profit? Who knows, one thing we do know is that such a system is unreliable and has remained unreliable for a very long time.\n\nMaybe someday this product will get its stuff together and be what it says it is. Right now, it is not. At all. Don't buy it."}
{"Author": "Eric", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works better than I thought it would.", "Text": "Works better than I thought it would. I was skeptical about some of the reviews, but this thing works great."}
{"Author": "texas_mike", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The number of devices that are supported and the community forums are fantastic. Response time is much much", "Text": "I am a Vera convert to Wink to SmartThings convert. Now I am a SmartThings apostle. The number of devices that are supported and the community forums are fantastic. Response time is much much quicker"}
{"Author": "walter", "Date": "on February 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "three Star", "Text": "Promises so much, achieves so little...\n\nUpdate: I was a bit harsh. It promises alot, it achieves alot, but falls short at times which can be especially frustrating since it has the potential to be a great product. i use it to control at least 30 lights. 8 motion detectors, and 4 outlets. it doesn't control the Hue lights as well as android/ios based hue apps that i've used, but the integrated motion detectors and cooperation with amazon echo make it indispensible.... if it could reduce the error rate in controlling the lights it could easily be a 5 star product\n\nUpdate: Integration with HUE bridge completely failed. Support suggested I disconnect the HUE bridge. Controlling lights is about 80% of what this thing is supposed to do, so if it can't do that right, its next to useless."}
{"Author": "Ski Bum", "Date": "on February 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Choice", "Text": "Fantastic, Good range, easy to set up. Using the SmartThings android App with this hub is intuitive and very functional."}
{"Author": "Gary shelton", "Date": "on February 14, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointed", "Text": "Works sometimes, not always. A device that is supposed to streamline and make things easier seems to only be causing headaches. Hopefully future updates will remove glitches."}
{"Author": "Sean Todd", "Date": "on February 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent platform to use as a foundation for your home automation.", "Text": "I originally purchased this as a start to automating my home. I'm a technology geek to start so I figured I could figure this thing out and make it do the things I wanted. It was so easy my parents can do it! I did look a few different brands but landed on Samsung because about every large electronic in our house is Samsung as well as our smartphones. I figure may as well keep it in the \"family\".\n\nSet up was extremely easy. I've been slowly adding sensors as time goes on so I don't need to put up the capital investment right away. Have even been able to add IRIS sensors from Lowe's successfully. I know it says they're not compatible, but with the help of some smart people in the SmartThings community I was able to grab the code and put it in the SmartThings portal as a custom device which works flawlessly.\n\nThe 2 biggest reasons for installing this are 1) we have a young child who likes to open outside doors so we want to know if they get opened unexpectedly to be able to make sure someone isn't making a break for it, and 2) ensure if someone breaks into our home we're aware of it. We've tested it a few times just to make sure it works and thus far it has, but thankfully we've not yet had a \"real\" test."}
{"Author": "Daniel P. Boyd", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Zero stars if possible!! Absolutely the worst controller I have used", "Text": "This is by far the worst possible controller for your smart home. The web based software is completely unreliable and it had nothing to do with internet connection. My family is cold and I can't change it. Going back to Vera I wish I never left."}
{"Author": "Joel", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm not so satisfied with the \"cloud\" aspect of it", "Text": "The hub itself is OK. I'm not so satisfied with the \"cloud\" aspect of it. The reliability of the cloud service is not as good as I had hoped. There are latencies that cause delays turning things on and off. There are also problems with scheduled events not occurring. On the plus side it is very flexible if you happen to have some programming expertise. There is an active community of developers who have done wonders making this a more reliable system. I highly recommend the \"rule-maker\" smartapp. This application has kept me from tossing the system."}
{"Author": "Justthefacts", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not so smart", "Text": "It's very difficult to pair compatible devices with and some just don't pair at all even if they are on the list. Software is limited. You can't reprogram door lock codes. All you can really do in turn lights on and off, lock and unlock doors."}
{"Author": "Jess Wright", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "limited control of features, they want you to use limited function macros"}
{"Author": "Kevin", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy this if you want your smart home to work right", "Text": "Don't buy this if you want your smart home to work right. Lot's of bugs and half the time routines don't execute."}
{"Author": "SWhite2010", "Date": "on February 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great price point to get into home automation!"}
{"Author": "Denver P. Lancaster", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings is a dumb choice.", "Text": "I purchased this hoping to connect 2 Wemo switches, a wireless net cam, and 3 lightbulb.\n\n2 light bulbs connected just fine. Third bulb connected a week later for no reason.\n\nNOTHING ELSE HAS WORKED, PERIOD.\n\nWill not connect to wemo switches regardless of steps taken as per instructions from wemo and from smartthings. I'll add photos. In-app instructions do not even describe menu options that EXIST. The switches do not even show up in the app. They connect to the native wemo app workout a problem.\n\nThe camera connects to other apps fine. Not smartthings.\n\nDon't even get me started on my Nest. There ate community solutions to set it up. No success.\n\nAbsolutely AWFUL costume support. Don't even bother calling. And still waiting for an email."}
{"Author": "xpda", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Needs to be reset occasionally."}
{"Author": "Prime Customer", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'd Like All My Money Back ~ About $1000", "Text": "I've been a fan of ST for years...back when there was real live chat and a few of the customer service people would call me on the phone to troubleshoot if I promised to keep their number private (and I never broke that promise). I must have about $1000 worth of ST products here and the functionality has gotten progressively worse. Routines don't fire up when they should which affects lighting, security and all the routines that follow afterward. I'm spending a lot of time babysitting this system to make sure it does what it is supposed to do. I'm afraid to purchase any more peripheral components like dimmer modules and cameras. If the routines don't come on when they are supposed to then what is the sense? I communicated with ST customer service and the generic response seems to be \"we're working on it\". Geez, if someone offered me all my money back I would jump on it in a second. Maybe there needs to be a class action lawsuit because although their intentions seem to be genuinely good this stuff is basically useless."}
{"Author": "CH", "Date": "on February 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub and Platform, Careful of Bad MAC Address Problems", "Text": "Some ship with mismatching MAC address and can't be setup. Mine was purchased in December 2015, could be just a bad batch from then.\n\nI'm new to the smart home and finally ended up with Smartthings as the way to go and purchased the Hub 2. Setup was a problem, ended up calling support and there was a mismatch between the MAC address of the unit and the MAC of what Smartthings associated in their records. They shipped out a replacement via 2 day air. That as a bummer.\n\nEveryone else goes into the details of setting them up. Setting up the replacement was easy. Adding the \"things\" was also easy. Haven't had any issues.\n\nThe only hard part was learning that if you want special or finer control over your things, you have to visit GitHub and figure out how to download them to your hub to get the functionality. Once you find the instructions and do it, you learn, but it's not going to happen right out of the box.\n\nI love all the z-wave stuff, Amazon Echo, and my Harmony Elite remote with Smartthings. Once you set it up, you will be hooked and quickly replacing all of your switches!"}
{"Author": "Robert K.", "Date": "on February 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung needs to get it together...", "Text": "I'm not sure how the community at large is supposed to get Samsung's attention except by impacting sales of these things. If they focused as much engineering effort on the V2 hub as they have sexy marketing, packaging, etc. then they could have an awesome product. But as it is it is horribly unreliable. Setting it up over the weekend, Android app outputs numerous \"encountered an error\" messages while going through the configuration wizard. After setting up two lights and routines to turn them on and off based on time of day, I find that sometimes the routines execute, sometimes they don't. I find numerous day old threads complaining about this. Here is the best quote \"This has been a constant issue for me over the last week. I'm so tired of this platform failing that I haven't even bothered to report it.\"\n\nI want to like this thing!!! I have a home grown solution using Raspberry Pi and Aeon Zwave USB stick that took me a long time to get working, but it's reliable. But until they get their house in order, Samsung should stop selling more of these things. I suppose I should send mine back to Amazon just to make a statement."}
{"Author": "Danno", "Date": "on February 8, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If not for the Amazon Echo integration I'd be returning to Vera platform.", "Text": "My review of the V2 hub is from the perspective of having come from years of Vera3 experience. The V2 offers promise but only time will tell if they can remain a player in this popular techy space. My basic characterization of the V2 is that is an immature product but they did get some things right.\nLikes: My main reason for moving from a stable Vera3 platform was the Smartthings integration with Amazon Echo. It works really well and for the most part I'm happy I made the switch. Once I learned to disassociate my devices from the Vera3 hub during migration I found the migration to be a piece of cake for standard switches, plugs etc.. Price is reasonable compared with competitive products and Samsung's names suggests innovation and integration into more of their suite of products.\nDislikes: Immature & not reliable. My Vera 3 was bulletproof in comparison. I got so frustrated with having to reboot the ST V2 hub to address the \"Hub is offline\" problems that I re-commissioned the Vera3 to control the power to the V2 so I could remotely reboot it. The battery backup is useless to me because of this reliability problem. The apps environment is oriented towards programmers and so far there isn't a very solid base of solutions. Most of the basic functionality like thermostat controls and door lock access management requires searching for other people's custom scripts and learning the Software Development Environment in order to access the apps. Lack of PC (Windows for me) control interface is bothersome. If not for the Amazon Echo I'd have to reach for my phone to control everything which is annoying given that I have a laptop in front of me most of the time.\n\nSummary: The main reason for me to stay on the Smartthings platform is for the Amazon Echo integration. Time will tell whether or not I stay with this platform. If Samsung can improve the Smartthings reliability and applications/solutions platform before Vera Control has a robust integration with Echo then I'll probably leave things the way they are but Vera's platform and solutions suite is much more mature."}
{"Author": "M.E. Dad", "Date": "on February 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do Not Buy. The hype from V1 does not follow V2", "Text": "Garbage. V2 is unreliable. End of story. For home automation this is paramount.\n\nExpanding and giving details/specifics on why unreliable:\nNov 24, Delays and app not functioning\nDec 11, Hard reset of hub. Had to do this twice in one week. Jus glad I was not away from home on business or vacation.\nDec 24, Security would not clear. Ended up removing it.\nDec 31, Had to reset smarttings motion sensor\nOn going, Routines run sporadically. This is my biggest pain point as that I bought the hub to just be a little smarter than multiple switches on timers. It is a basic task and all I want is for my lights to turn on and off at a specified time. One routine to turn them on, one routine to turn them off. I would like to do more but since it can't do that reliably, I am just not bothering to do anything more at this point.\n\nI would have changed back to Vera but I bought these cool outdoor LED garden lights which were not cheap and of course will not work with Vera since OSRAM does not have an API."}
{"Author": "Kris", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works better than expected", "Text": "I have been waiting years until i felt the home automation market is maturing.\n\nWell its not mature, but defimitely much better than ever before. The Smartthings hub v2 works well. I have actually attached 2 thermastates, 6 light circuits, outside led landscape lights, schlage door locks and next is garage door.\n\nI was suprised at how the network relay of zwave works really well. Also, with minimal technology knowledge i could setup apps and devices from the smartthings forum.\n\nDefinitely still on the cutting edge, but not bleeding edge of maturity."}
{"Author": "Darrell Deaton", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to hook up and works great with the Echo...."}
{"Author": "Nix36", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great buy", "Text": "Works really well and wish we got one ages ago. It is easy to install and set up and use."}
{"Author": "Timothy Ward", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for mainstream - SmartThings platform infrastructure constantly fails or experiences issues", "Text": "The SmartThings hub is a nice product - but the company has SERIOUS issues with their infrastructure and the therefore the product can not be trusted to function properly. Your home setup is hosted on the SmartThings infrastructure to some extent, and they have constant issues. Often scheduled tasks don't run rendering your setup useless. The integration with light switches and moisture alarms seems to work well, and now I have it working with a smart deadbolt - but my integration with my Ecobee3 thermostats is lack luster and very unreliable. The scheduler required to pool Ecobee servers fails constantly and the SmartThings cloud-to-cloud integration is full of issues."}
{"Author": "Raj", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Highly Recommend!", "Text": "I bought this to automate our bedroom lights and for our kids. I couldn't be happier, the hub was super easy to set up and I installed 5 dimmer switches in a few hours and had them all connected. I even put one in my kids rooms so I can automatically make their lights come on in the morning to wake them up!\n\nI've also connected a few water sensors to it, and they hooked up easily."}
{"Author": "Will", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best IOT hub available", "Text": "New hub is an improvement on the old one. There are a lot of as yet unrealized promises in the new hub vs the old one but it definitely is a lot faster and more responsive. I love that it has no problem integrating with generic z-wave sensors and lights instead of being locked down to just smartthings branded ones. Smartthings+hue+amazon echo is the easiest and most complete smart home system currently available.\n\nThe only con is that the smartthings app needs a lot of work to make it easier to use and it doesn't have a desktop windows/osx app. But at least it is really open and has IFTT and other third party app integration"}
{"Author": "Marti Hidden", "Date": "on February 5, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great features but falls short where it counts...", "Text": "Been using the SmartThings hub V2 for a few months now - time for a review: There are some great features offered by this device - smart apps, compatibility with an array of devices, programmable routines etc. Unfortunately, it falls short in the routines department. It intermittently chooses to skip routines leaving you either in the dark, or freezing when you get out of bed because it didn't run the thermostat routine. I had hoped to add security features and I really wanted to like this device, and if they can work out the bugs I still might like it, but sadly it's just not ready for prime time so I won't be expanding it's use. Sorry SmartThings, you gotta do better..."}
{"Author": "Kaz", "Date": "on February 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay away - far far away. Not worth the hassle", "Text": "Software is simply not ready for consumers. Sensors are 3rd rate. Bought 3 door sensors - 1 died after a week - the next one died now.\n\nIs NOT compatible with a LOT of Z-Wave devices without \"hacking\" and applying a lot of code\n\nIs NOT compatible with 100's of devices - only 56 on the list so far - and they are more or less 15 device groups with \"lots of sub products in it\"\n\nI simply can not recommend them"}
{"Author": "Clint", "Date": "on February 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home automation is fantastic!", "Text": "This is my first crack at home automation and I absolutely love it! Obviously I can't compare to any other products or the previous version so purely based off of a first time owner this is clearly a 5 star product. Although I can completely understand the lower ratings by other people that had the first gen and upgraded and had to update ALL the sensors to the new device. That would be a time consuming pain.\n\nI started off with just the door sensors and a motion for the living room. Quickly I added the multi sensor to the garage and now I get alerts when the door is left open for more than 7 minutes and can close it if I'm already gone. That's already saved me a few times. Plus I added a motion to the garage and the lights come on whenever it is tripped and same thing in the living room whenever the device is armed. I never have to reach for the lights when coming or going in the garage when typically it could be very dark. Overall it just makes life a little more convenient. Haven't had to use the water sensor yet, but it's in place so the condenser won't flood the house as bad again."}
{"Author": "Philip L. Gastaldo", "Date": "on February 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works like a charm", "Text": "Simple to set up and integrate. Works like a charm. I would definitely recommend this product."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The hub works great once I had support explain a few issues on ...", "Text": "The hub works great once I had support explain a few issues on setup. Support was very helpful as the directions were not as clear as they should have been."}
{"Author": "AC be me.", "Date": "on February 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works fine for a couple days then something breaks.", "Text": "Over the last couple months I have had countless issues with my hub and seems to be getting worse. I've gotten to the point i'm surprised when it actually works.\n\nIssue #1: SmartThings lost the IP address of the Philips Hue and I had to remove all smartapps, bulbs and hue TWICE IN 10 DAYS. As a noted, nothing changed with Phillips and no other apps or connections broke to Philips. The IP address of the Phillips Hub was static and didn't change.\n\nIssue 2: I have had numerous intrusion alerts because I arrive and notes I'm home and does all other commands except disarm. I had to remove everything tied to arming and disarming, arriving and leaving.\n\nIssue 3: This has been going on forever. I can be hundreds of miles away and Smartthings thinks I arrive at home. My GPS in my phone is working fine in all aspects and other apps. It bounces back and forth home and away until I end up rebooting the phone to fix it. I would understand if I'm a few miles and the GPS accuracy or phone tower or wifi is near by. Or if I recently arrived or left and had not refreshed but in some cases it starts after being away from home for a week.\n\nIssue 4: Simple Timers based on time for lights to come on and off randomly stop working and have to be recreated them in order to work.\n\nIssue 5: I got notification my garage door was open when I look in the app at the device activate, there is nothing indicating the door was open. It freaked me out when I was 40 mins away and thinking someone is breaking in.\n\nI have no faith in notifications or SmartThings controlling things like door locks anything that controls security or safety.\n\nI've contact support via email and it took a week to get an unprofessionally written message to remove evenything you configured and start from scratch."}
{"Author": "Kevin H.", "Date": "on February 4, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "less than reliable for alarm and takes a long time to load all the things when I start the app.", "Text": "Some down time, which isn't really acceptable. Biggest issue is that it takes forever to load my \"things\" into the app when I click on a new page. I have approx 60 things (all on the compatible list) so maybe this is too much for it."}
{"Author": "Joe Miller", "Date": "on February 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very unreliable. It's nothing more than a toy!", "Text": "This hub is very unreliable. Things will get turn on/off by themselves and alarm went off randomly. I have to reboot this hub every weeks because it randomly went offline. The app used to control this device is full of bugs and has only 2 star ratings on iTune."}
{"Author": "Marcus Busbee", "Date": "on February 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Don't waste your money. Works maybe half the time."}
{"Author": "dgs", "Date": "on February 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't waste your money", "Text": "Don't waste your money. Works only intermittently for me and will not reboot on its own. Works only one or a few days without dying."}
{"Author": "GG", "Date": "on February 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not an improvement over a non-automated house", "Text": "This device uses the 'cloud' for about everything. If you turn a light on your phone app has to send a request to a server somewhere that then instructs this device to send a wireless command to the device to turn on. By the time this happens 30 seconds have gone by. Or nothing happens and your phone is showing an error message.\n\nI don't see how this is an improvement over a simple remote control, or over an old-fashioned wall switch.\n\nOn top of that: if the internet goes out you're in the dark (or you have to crawl behind the couch in the dark to hit the little button on the physical switching device). Having to rely on the Internet and your Wi-Fi to all work for basic things like turning your lights on is a silly idea."}
{"Author": "Sooner613", "Date": "on February 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good...", "Text": "While the SmartThings hub does take some work to set-up (where it is positioned, can the hub \"see\" all of the devices, etc...), I have had little to no problems with the system. I have three Aeon recessed door sensors, a Utilitech strobe / siren, an Iris leakSMART valve, an ST multi-sensor, three ST leak sensors, an Iris outlet, and a Z-wave outlet all working well. I have been using it for ~6 weeks."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't work", "Text": "Bought this for my Yale lock. I tells me the door is unlocked when it is locked. I've deleted and re-synced 3 times and still the same issue."}
{"Author": "da burg", "Date": "on February 2, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best consumer option in a sea of bad options. Needs a lot of interface work!", "Text": "Kudos to Samsung for attempting to deliver home automation to the masses. Now it\u2019s time to get out continuous beta mode and actually build something that actually enables the consumer to solve their problems. The primary problems with Smartthings can be summed up pretty easily. In summary: (1) The phone interface needs a lot of user experience work. (2) The website controller interface is not easy to navigate and doesn\u2019t add a lot of additional features. (3) Buying a new device to solve a problem is not straightforward (#1 question on Amazon: Does this work with SmartThings?) (4) There is no way to update device firmware via SmartThings that I can find. That\u2019s a security issue. (5) Changing simple device parameters to allow you to customize basic things (like increase/decrease a dimmer rate, turn off or on a load sensing feature on a plug-in) require programming skills. (6) There needs to be far better if/then functionality. (Example: if sensor B is tripped, then X, Y and Z.) IFTTT is not the way to do this elegantly, it simply should not be that hard to integrate this kind of functionality directly into the Samsung interface.\n\nIn short, the system is kind of stuck between two worlds: it is marketed as a consumer product but requires hacking/programming skills to make it indispensable or in some cases, useful. One thing Samsung seems to have missed: I live in a house with a wife and a child. I wanted the system. I set it up. I like it and know its quirks and shortcomings. My wife, on the other hand, wants to throw it in the trash. Why? Because she does not want to learn how to operate a light switch on SmartThings, she wants the darn light to turn on and off (you know, like it always did before SmartThings).\n\nThere are two other worlds that SmartThings is stuck in as well. On one hand, it\u2019s this great multi-protocol, multi-platform, bring your own device kind of solution that would be awesome if they actually leaned into that with consumer-centric,intuitive interfaces. On the other hand, it is kind of a Samsung Zigbee solution marketed with this pathetically small collection of Samsung devices that happens to sort of support a ton of Z-Wave and compatible 3rd party Zigbee devices. Samsung needs to decide \u2013 do they want to give the user a consumer-centric closed system that simply works out of the box, or an open system that is relatively easy to troubleshoot and customize, because right now it is sort of neither for the average consumer. I'd gladly pay triple the current SmartThings retail price for either of these. To draw an analogy, it\u2019s like the worst of Apple, the worst of Microsoft, plus the ability to code Linux (if you can code) to make it stink less in one bundle.\n\nHopefully Hub 3.0 solves some of these problems, because if it does not, a better solution from another company cannot be that far off."}
{"Author": "Bill", "Date": "on February 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Forget any type of service", "Text": "I bought this and tried to install a device. Got one of three to connect.. Followed all directions and can't make it work.\nWent to the website for help.. No phone ot call and the site says live chat.. BUT NO WHERE TO CHAT.\nFor a new company of young people, you would think customer service and word of mouth would be important to them;.\nGuess not\nUPDATE: been emailing support and they tell me I have to REMOVE the locks from the doors and get them close to the hub, then REINSTALL the lock . Are you kidding me!! I\"m 20 feet from the lock to the hub"}
{"Author": "Gordon Small", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I just can't give this hub the praise it deserves ...", "Text": "I just can't give this hub the praise it deserves. That's because one star is the lowest rating available. Just read all the other one star reviews and run away.\n\nSeriously! On my network I have a Hue Hub with 10 bulbs, 3 desktops, a laptop 2 iPhones, 2 iPads, a Blu-Ray Player, A TiVo Roamio and a TiVo Roamio Mini, a 5 camera security system with DVR several WeMo devices and a Smartthings hub that controls several devices. I've been losing internet a couple times a week for several weeks and sometimes 2-3 times in a day. EVERY one of my devices comes back online without human intervention EXCEPT the Smartthings hub. Every time I have an internet problem I have to physically reset the Smartthings hub before it starts working again. There's no way of resetting it remotely. It requires a button to be pushed at the hub. So once it's down you have to make a trip to wherever your hub is to do the reset before it starts working again. Everything else on my network runs flawlessly. Wehn the internet has a hiccup everything else just comes up without any problems. I suggest doing a google search on \"Smartthings V2 unreliability\" and see whet pops up. Many other users are having reliability issues."}
{"Author": "2treeline", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time. Or any other time, for that matter.", "Text": "This hub, despite claims that it does local processing, relies almost entirely on the Samsung/Smartthings cloud platform. Over the last six months or so, the processing platform has become increasingly unstable leading to intermittent and unreliable performance. If you enjoy your thermostat not changing temps and leaving the house cold in the morning, being able to access the mobile app on an entirely random basis or having your door locks left open at night - buy this device. Otherwise, try something else."}
{"Author": "Charlie", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Broken Promises", "Text": "I really get frustrated seeing all the plugs for Smartthings, frankly it doesn't live up to all the hype. I initially purchased the Smartthings system with included motion detectors and sensors. I also bought some TCP lightbulbs and a couple of G.E. wall switches, however Smartthings is so buggy and unreliable that it fails to even consistently change modes from dusk to dawn, literally leaving me sitting in the dark. I'd recommend that this product not be taken seriously until Samsung can deliver the fully developed product that can deliver on it's promises."}
{"Author": "Travis S. Box", "Date": "on January 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Huge Disappointment", "Text": "This controller was a huge disappointment! We had been using the VeraLite for about a year before purchasing the Samsung Smartthings. The VeraLite seemed a little slow, and there was always a delay if you would send commands through the app. Our house has about 25 Leviton switches and dimmers and three Leviton VRCS4-M0Z Vizia RF + 4-Button Remote Scene Controller. These scene controllers are key to the entire operation. My wife is never going to use a phone to turn lights off, and as I said, we have a lot of lights in the system. With theses controllers, she can hit one button and every light that she needs to cook dinner is suddenly lit. The VeraLite worked very well with these controllers; it was just a little slow through the app.\n\nThe Samsung Smartthings controller cannot operate or, more importantly, program these or ANY scene controller. The only way to turn on multiple lights at one time is to go through the app. There are no scene controllers on the market that will work with ST. I contacted support, and they told me to check out the Smartthings community. They were basically telling me that they didn't know and didn't care. I had already looked at the community postings (obviously), and I had even installed an app that was supposed to work with these scene controllers. The app did work some, but the button pushes would have to send a message back to the controller, and then the controller would send messages to all of the lights. This would take about 1 minute. With the Vera, the button push sends the message straight from the scene controller to all of the lights, so the scene changes happen instantaneously.\n\nMaybe my unhappiness with this lack of scene controller functionality seems nit picky, but this is a core function of many automation systems. You should not buy this thinking that the home brewed app available on the Smartthings Community forum is going to work the way you want. It absolutely will not work the way you are thinking!!!\n\nAll that aside, the main reason we were shopping around was that the VeraLite seemed a little slow. After you use the Smartthings for a month, the VeraLite will feel like a supercomputer. The problem is that so many of the commands just fail. Sometimes you can't tell if it is just taking so long because it is thinking or because it just gave up. The last straw was our outdoor lights. With the Vera and Smartthings, they were set to come on every night at sunset. In about 25 attempts, the Smartthings only turned the lights on about 20 times. This is a very simple operation, that never failed even once with the Vera.\n\nSo ultimately, we returned the Smartthings and we replaced it with a VeraEdge. It works just like the VeraLite but is noticeably faster. I wasted so much time un-pairing and re-pairing, then un-pairing and re-pairing all of my lights and controllers (literally 3 full days). I made a terrible mistake! Please don't make the same mistake."}
{"Author": "Mark Twain IV", "Date": "on January 28, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dead in 3 days. Seriously?!", "Text": "Dead in less than 3 days. No lights after I spent a day tinkering to get the AEON energy monitor connected and now it's a dead unit. WTF. Thinking going Vera now or Wink, I don't have time for good looking items that power off for no good reason in a couple days. No longer trust it. A hundred bucks of nothing."}
{"Author": "Fernando C.", "Date": "on January 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... had bought the first version and I did not liked it because it was completely cloud dependent", "Text": "I had bought the first version and I did not liked it because it was completely cloud dependent. Which means that it must be connected to the internet at all times for your automation to work. For instance you have lights that need to turn on at dusk and turn off at down... Well if the internet goes out ( And where I'm at it happens very frequently ) the lights would not turn on at all at night or worst if it happen in the morning the lights would stay on all day.\nThen I went to CES 2015 and talked to the Smart People and they said that the problem was solved on the V2 HUB, so I went and bought a V2 HUB but to my surprise it still misses the simple light On/Off automation. I reached to Tech Support which it is e-mail only by the way but I have not hear from them.\nI have used Vera for years now and I have no problems. It simple works. Save yourself some ulcers if you want to automate your house."}
{"Author": "Motion Man", "Date": "on January 28, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth It", "Text": "Very Buggy. Menu and instruction are hideous. My 5 year old grandson could write better instruction."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wicked support from Smart Things. A Big shout out to Eric", "Text": "Wicked support from Smart Things. A Big shout out to Eric, Quick Response, Accurate, Friendly, and most of all Helpful...I am rare if ever to write customer reviews even if its a real crappy product. I take the time because they took the time to respond so effectively. Thanks Tim Slagle, Thanks Eric M from support."}
{"Author": "Laura A Templin", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great so far!"}
{"Author": "jerry", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No telephon or chat support", "Text": "Had configuration question and no telephone support\nReturned thr item and purchased another brand"}
{"Author": "Me", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Trying hard to love this, but.....", "Text": "So I got this and some door sensors. I wanted it mainly to monitor an apartment that's 4 hours away from where I live. If it worked ok I would get the water sensors and thermostat a/c control. Let me first say I'm not a tech person, I know enough to plug stuff in and follow basic directions though. Set up was very easy. I've read a lot of complaints here about set up but I experienced no issues and it went quickly. The app does suck though, it's not hard to use but it's not good, can't explain it, just not smooth.... The system works perfectly for me until smart things updates the hub. I found this out because I checked it in the app and it said it was not working. I looked on a forum online and they said the hub was just updated and many others were having the same issue. When updates come from smart things the hub needs to be reset and restarted at the hub, it doesn't restart automatically apparently. Im not sure why they would design it like this. For someone like me who uses this remotely it makes it basically useless. On the forum some gurus where saying this could be solved by having another brands hub control the smart things hub. Then use the other brands hub to restart the smart things hub. Are you kidding me? Really? This is just not acceptable. Btw I made the 4 hour trip cause I needed to go anyway. I reset the hub and it worked perfectly again for a month, the next update killed it again. So like I said I really want to love it but I just cant. As updates keep coming it will continue to stop working. If it were where I live I might have no issues but since I can't drive 4 hours each way to turn it on its an expensive paperweight. It's difficult because I would like to invest in more \"things\" but won't waste the money on an unreliable technology."}
{"Author": "Benito Huerta", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty good, promising but they have a long way to go.", "Text": "This HUB is pretty good and works as described however it only gets 3 stars because of software. Samsung has a chance to corner this new market and they dont seem to be paying too much attention. They better hope Apple doesn't get into this too soon.\n\nGetting around the application is at times non-intuitive. In most screens you literally have to click the back button 5 times to get back to the home screen. This wouldn't be too bad on a desktop but on a cell phone it gets old pretty quick. I also expected more functionality and for it to be easier to add rules. Things like - \"If my outside light get's turned on and it's day turn it off after 5 minutes\". There are ways to do this but again, it's pretty cumbersome."}
{"Author": "Einstein", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I Pretty happy with the ST hub", "Text": "I Pretty happy with the ST hub. It is is very easy to setup. The support is very good. Very professional."}
{"Author": "Jason", "Date": "on January 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for home automation", "Text": "It takes a little getting used to, but now that I've gotten accustom to the interface, it works pretty well. The first one I got was defective, but Amazon exchanged quickly. I'm slowly adding more lights and sensors to this, and it's great. Much better than the Vera I had previously."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "you like paying full price for a product that is still ...", "Text": "Purchase only if all of the following are true; you like paying full price for a product that is still in beta test, you think $100 is not too much to pay for a novelty piece of junk that rarely works, you have no real use for reliable home automation, and you love technical support that is absolutely non-existent. It's a great idea whose time has come, however, the this implementation is flakey and inconsistent, and that's the best and most generous possible review I could give the 2nd generation Smartthings hub and app."}
{"Author": "BJC", "Date": "on January 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I read all the reviews on several different home automation products and chose smartthings because everyone seemed to like it an", "Text": "This hub will give you the power to do extraordinary things. If you haven't gotten into the home automation world yet, its time. I read all the reviews on several different home automation products and chose smartthings because everyone seemed to like it and the fact it has an open platform. An open platform is very important though you may never understand why. It allows companies, people and devices of all kind to work with and integrate with the smartthings hub and applications. With this hub, you can choose from a huge variety of different companies and devices to meet the automation needs of your specific home needs/wants. https://www.smartthings.com/compatible-products Everything from turning things on/off our up/down to securing your home to making sure there are no leaks or fires detected to measuring your overall home watt usage. There is almost nothing you cant do even at this point and realistically we are at the \"Motorola Razor\" phase of what will soon become an iphone 12......... an Atari version of what will soon become a Playstation 37 meaning its only going to get better and better and I cant wait. Only drawbacks is that there is no number to call to trouble shoot any problems you may have. I have sent a few emails for help which was answered in a responsible amount of time and asked Mr. Google who showed me several forums of information that helped me work through the few minor problems ive had."}
{"Author": "William Pierskalla", "Date": "on January 26, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beta product, maybe even alpha. Unreliable for everyday use. Read the forums prior to purchasing", "Text": "Unfortunately this product is unreliable for everyday use. There is a seemingly constant \" oops we are down again\" or \"update failed, please reset your hub\" series of problems. Wait until the reviews are better or they allow us to disconnect from their servers to avoid updates if everything is working as needed in your home. Google the forums for details of problems."}
{"Author": "Joe C.", "Date": "on January 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good with the smart things I have not experienced any ...", "Text": "So far so good with the smart things I have not experienced any issues, I don't have many devices yet. I have just the front door lock looking to add more devices in the future and will update this review at that point."}
{"Author": "Charles Murphy", "Date": "on January 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Cannot connect to any items in my house."}
{"Author": "Aboynamedpoo", "Date": "on January 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Flexible and reliable", "Text": "Great product. Easy to use and build up an entire system. SmartThings is very flexible in that you can connect a wide array of devices, including cheap off-brand items for simple tasks. I have it running my home alarm system and I keep adding various functions with time. Great support online and many apps for ios and Android."}
{"Author": "Rodolfo", "Date": "on January 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You NEED to be willing to do frequent fixes", "Text": "*** UPDATE 01/25/2016 ****\nI am downgrading my review to two stars. Ever since I got this system, there's always something to fix. It is not only me, the whole SmartThings community gets these \"outages\" as well. Staff recognizes there is some problem and then they try to fix it and sometimes it may last for days or even weeks. Last thing that made me decide to throw this away was that I reached out to support for help on my schedules not working, and I ended up getting three different e-mails, at three different times that said the SAME thing. It was so clear that it was a template because on one of the e-mails, the support guy didn't even bother to change the name to whom it was addressed.\n\nIf you want automation from time to time, and have enough time to tinker with in a weekly or so basis, go for this. If you are thinking of getting a Plug and Play and Forget device, move along.\n\n*** UPDATE 03/23/2016 ***\nOkay, so now I have decided to lower my rating to 1 star. This is just something that I can neither justify nor recommend to anyone. After the last problems 2 months ago, things eventually got \"fixed\", and I say \"fixed\" because it started to behave stable-ish, but at the cost of much of the platform's power. For example, the Smart Home Monitor, which is Samsung's idea of monetizing SmartThings by partnering with security systems like Scout, has never worked perfectly. I had about two months of my lights and rest of my setup giving me little to no trouble, but there was nothing complex running.\n\nThis was until a week ago. SmartThings has had an outage of its platform, degrading the performance of it and rendering you unable to control devices through the app. As of the moment of this writing, the SmartThings platform has been having problems for over 12 days, without a fix in sight. People in the community forum are outraged by this, and some have even sent e-mails to Samsung's CEO, which eventually led to SmartThing's CEO to show his face on the forum to communicate with the users.\nIt is unacceptable for a company that promotes this item as a security monitoring device, which actually earns money by monthly subscriptions with security companies, to have an outage of more than a day. Before you even think of purchasing this hub, think if you would like your security company to go deaf to your house for 12 days.\n\nThis is just a toy. A very expensive one, for that matter, because by itself it does nothing. You need to start buying other stuff, which will quickly start to add up to the thousands of dollars. STAY AWAY FROM THIS."}
{"Author": "E. Vela", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best thing since sliced bread.", "Text": "Being used with my GE Z-Wave devices (switches/outlets), Hue, and Minimotes. Samsung stays on top of technical issues. Great product."}
{"Author": "Hoku Kaauwai", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Things Rocks!", "Text": "The potential is super for this. there are many glitches but the Smartthings team works through them. If you purchase this product, then you need to be patient and expect growing pains. I love the idea of this and the products are getting better and better"}
{"Author": "Bob Jackson", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "and initially was very pleased. The pairing has some potential", "Text": "I have put a few weeks into this device. Support is unresponsive, unit has wonder potential; however is is buggy and extremely unreliable; I purchase this to pair with the Echo unit, and initially was very pleased. The pairing has some potential, but the smartthings portion has not work for more than 1 day without issue. I like playing with things; however when other family members abandon these devices then their value is severely diminished. I am looking for another home automation device which can pair well with Echo. Samsung's name on this device is not a mark of quality."}
{"Author": "RoyL", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not Reliable", "Text": "If you're looking for a reliable Home Automation System, This ain't it. It's a shiny product with great Prospects, and a nice app. For the first few weeks, it worked well and replaced my older Insteon System. I then started noticing that reboots were required on increasingly frequent intervals for it to work. At first, it would stay up for two weeks before failing to transmit over Z-Wave. Now it won't even stay up for 24 hours. I'm forced to remove the batteries and pull power from it once a day using a old mechanical timer outlet.\n\nThe Smarthings Website offers chat to talk to the Support personal, but this seems disabled at their side - nothing will happen. Emails can take up to weeks to respond. Their staff are nice to talk with, but the problems remain unresolved."}
{"Author": "Kerry Brown", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't plan on support", "Text": "The way this is designed you need intervention from Samsung support just to set it up in some situations. I've had my hub for several days and I'm still waiting for Samsung to reset it so I can use it. I don't like products that are so locked down you can end up unable to access an otherwise working device without the manufacturer's say so. When they move on to other products, leave the business, or otherwise decide it's okay to ignore customer requests for help, you're out of luck. It's an architecture that's designed to fail."}
{"Author": "Big John", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Liked the SmartThings very much at first....now nothing but headaches", "Text": "I purchased the original hub from Amazon and it has been routinely updated to the newest software releases. Originally, I was very pleased with unit. I use it to monitor my second home in another state and use smart switches, smoke/fire detectors and temp/humidity sensors. It seems that since the acquisition of SmarThings by Samsung, the quality of the releases and the support have suffered badly. Late last year, I found a problem where the time of day to activate a device command was off by two hours on some of the devices. I first emailed SmartThings support on December 4th. The issue was not closed until mid-January, with no real resolution, just a workaround. Turns out the hub cannot figure out time zone differences if the mobile app is used in a different time zone, even when you program the location into the hub. I would wait between 3-4 days up to over 10 days to get a response from their technical support team. A couple of days ago, I checked in with the mobile app and found that none of lights were turning on at the programmed time. I went into the online app and, after routing around, found that the devices were hung waiting for an event trigger that was three days in the past. I ended up reprogramming all the switches to clear the issue. And to add insult to injury, I got a smoke detected alarm last weekend. I immediately sent my neighbor over to check the house....no smoke. All day long, I kept getting reminders about the event with no obvious way the clear the condition. Once again, I logged into my account online and found no events related to the alarm in any of the event logs and the status of the device was \"clear.\" So, I got a false alarm...grateful I didn't call the fire department and get socked with a false alarm fee.\n\nI am pretty much out of patience with the unreliability of this product and the now continual issues. Time to start looking for an alternative and wish SmartThings Adieu."}
{"Author": "AT", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product!", "Text": "Great product! The motion sensors and multipurpose sensors are very susceptible to interference. My car alarm system causes them to go offline. The hub doesn't allow you to change channels. Maybe if I could then that might help me resolve this issue. Smartthings has come a long ways over the past few years. It was painful but now things seem pretty stable finally."}
{"Author": "Oleg Butov", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a letdown! Used to be ok, but getting worse and worse...", "Text": "I've been dreading the upgrade from v1 hub to v2 for a while now. I had read some complains that there was no easy way to migrate all of the things from one hub to another, and I'd basically have to remove everything from hub v1 and then re-add to hub v2. Well, I finally decided to bite a bullet and just do it, since I wanted to add video capabilities to my home security setup and I could only do it with v2 hub. That was a huge mistake! It took nearly 8 hours to migrate everything (close to 15 devices). The worst performers were the actual SmartThings sensors, as it took close to 10 minutes to identify each sensor. It used to be a breeze with the old hub. But re-adding the devices was just a beginning.\nExperience of reprogramming all of the routines and smart apps was even worse. First of all, I couldn't save any smart apps with sunrise/sunset offset in it. Then, I discovered I couldn't use sunrise/sunset in automatic mode switch configuration. I relied on that functionality extensively in my previous setup. Finally, even when I was able to configure to use sunset/sunrise in automation - it was not working at all, as nothing would trigger. Extremely frustrating experience.\nMoreover, video capability is very buggy and un-reliable, and the only way to use it in any automation is through their \"premium\" service (free till February). Such a disappointment!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Huge disappointment!", "Text": "I can't say how extremely disappointed I am with this product. The ST platform is so unstable that even simple home automation tasks such as tuning on lights at sunset routinely fail. These platform issues have been known to the ST staff for many months now and things have not only not improved, but the reliability has gotten much worse. If you're considering buying this hub please read the ST support forums first, there are literally hundreds of user complaints about poor reliability. Very disappointed."}
{"Author": "D. Kennel", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Too unreliable, poor support", "Text": "Very disappointed. I have used the first hub for over a year. I had a couple of issues, but nothing too serious. Things started to get buggy with the new app that was released last year. Tech support has gotten really bad to where you can only email them. It seems things got bad with the Samsung takeover. I hoped the v2 hub would make things better, but it is a bigger nightmare! To \"upgrade\" I had to uninstall all devices on the network and then reinstall them on a new network. One week later I am still trying to reconnect some sensors. Today the hub crashed and I cannot connect to it even with the status light on green. Without 24/7 tech support this has become a useless system. I see similar comments on the smartthings user forums. This is very disappointing. The soft and hardware upgrades have not improved this system. I wanted it to simplify life not CREATE problems. At this point I wish I had not started this mess...."}
{"Author": "J. Hess", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Would not recommend to my worst enemy.", "Text": "A year ago I would give this 4 or 5 stars. It was a great addition to the home. It had its flaws but they were working on them and the customer service was pretty good at helping you.\n\nNow I wouldnt suggest this to ANYONE. I have has so many issues with my new hub its made me give up on the whole smartthings hub. I would read reviews everywhere and check the message boards on their website. Half the time nothing works right and or part of their opperation is not working. When you contact customer service it takes them over a week sometimes a month to respond and if they need more information from you and you submit it then it takes that much longer to get things resolved."}
{"Author": "Lana", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay away", "Text": "Could not find any of my in wall dimmers and switches from GE."}
{"Author": "Erica Ardian", "Date": "on January 21, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not really worth it after all", "Text": "So here's the thing, I love Samsung, I love tech, I wanted to love this. Unfortunately, I'm regretting this purchase and may still return this. This does seem like a great idea but isn't implementable, unless you're willing to shell out tons of money on compatible products you're screwed. Since I've had this I haven't had a great user experience, first it is buggy, meaning sometimes it works, sometimes it tells you it's offline while one of the sensors sends you a message that something is open when it's not. I can't integrate this with my august smart lock, arlo can, or the garage door opener that I got so it's pointless. I will agree with people who say this is a great hobby, if by hobby you like wasting money, oh and I forgot, this isn't compatible with nest either so unless you like the products that are compatible with this again, screwed. I was hoping with newer iterations there would be both forward and backward capability with zwave/ZigBee and no luck on that either."}
{"Author": "tall-latte", "Date": "on January 21, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fun hobby project when it works, consistently not reliable", "Text": "SmartThings provides a fun hobby project but absolutely should not be relied on as a security system or automated lock/unlock system. The version 1 hub is mostly stable but does not work during an Internet outage. The version 2 hub was updated to allow for offline functionality, but it is highly unreliable and frequently does not work as expected. That said, it is still a fun hobby product, as long as you understand up front that it frequently does not work correctly, does not work as advertised, and absolutely should not be used with an automated siren or home monitoring company. When it does work, it is great. Sadly, the problems have been ongoing for many months, and because of this, Product Support takes many days to get back with you. They are friendly and apologetic, but in the end they do not solve your problem, since the problem is typically not your fault anyway; it is due to a poorly architected backend system, at least in my opinion. I sincerely hope that one day they get the platform stabilized and working properly, so that it may one day be able to be used as intended and as advertised. In the meantime, it can again serve as a fun - yet frustrating - hobby project. One tip: for devices you really do need to work correctly, such as smoke alarms and perhaps security cameras, keep those separate from SmartThings. Use SmartThings as your sometimes functioning door/window/motion alerts, but use something more reliable for your smoke detectors and security cameras."}
{"Author": "ab33b3", "Date": "on January 21, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does not work reliably or consistently", "Text": "I was very excited about the potential of the smarthub, but have been disappointed with it's poor reliability. I wanted a relatively simple switch to turn lights and electrical switches on and off at certain times or when the sun rises and sets. While I have been mostly able to set these things up, they don't *stay* set up. I would find that I would have to delete and re-add devices on a weekly basis to get them to keep doing what they were set up to do. I have gotten really tired of waking up in the morning to find lights that were supposed to turn themselves off were, in fact, still on. At the same time, the set up is complicated and time-consuming enough that resetting everything on a bi-weekly basis is a pain in the butt.\n\nWhile many people seem happy with the ability to extend the way the hub works with custom code from the online community, that is a level beyond where I wanted to go to get things to work. I found the 'macro' language to be kludgey and inefficient. For example to turn a light on at Sunset, and then turn it off the same night at 11:30, the user has to set up two 'rules'\n\nThe device does enough of what it is supposed to do that I did not return it before the 30 days was up, but I do not think it is ready for prime time. At this point, I would absolutely NOT count on the hub to do anything more important than fiddling with lights. Based on the lack of reliability and consistancy I have experienced, I think anyone expecting it to alert you to a leaking hot water heater or broken pipe might be very disappointed."}
{"Author": "Vincent J Romeo", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it! Connected to my Amazon Echo and it is truly like living in the future."}
{"Author": "george", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub, excellent tech", "Text": "Great Hub ,excellent tech. Support"}
{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome", "Text": "Living in my house is like being on the star trek but more comfortable. Entirely thanks to smartthings. They have had bugs like every other available hub but the versatility and potential of this hub far exceeds its price point. At the time of this writing, there is occasional unreliability so I wont rely on it for security just yet, but for monitoring/automating my house (thermostat, lights, detectors/sensors, power, etc) it does that great. I've linked it with IFTTT, and amazon Echo. The community development is really the best part. Smarttiles.click is one really cool advantage. Rule Machine is another. When you compare it to other systems out there, you can do more with smartthings at the best price point. If you want cheaper/easier, look at wink. If you want more expensive/harder theres lots of options. But despite its drawbacks, the winner of the homeautomation hubs is currently Smartthings."}
{"Author": "Mr. A.", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "set up was super easy - price is good - shipping was fast"}
{"Author": "Mark Twain", "Date": "on January 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simply unreliable", "Text": "Not reliable at all, maybe 25% of scheduled tasks work when they are supposed to. Nice idea, really bad product."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Garbage. Works about 20% of the time.", "Text": "I have just two devices scheduled to turn on and off daily at certain times of the day. It works just 20% of the time.\n\nBeen four months of patience on my end with no improvement from Samsung.\n\nIt's unplugged and tossed in trash can."}
{"Author": "rick wilkes", "Date": "on January 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "It's amazing!!!"}
{"Author": "Sammy", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Only a Hobby Item at This Stage", "Text": "First, This review is not version specific. I have the SmartThings Hub v1and 20 devices connected to it. I purchased it shortly before SmartThings v2 was quietly released. At this point in time, both of these hubs are strictly for the hobbyist and should not be relied on for any real security. That being said, I love the idea of the SmartThings and Z-Wave technology.\n\nThe Hub: Now on version 2, neither one of these hubs is beyond beta. In other words, they rushed these things out and neither of them is complete. Most people on V1 as I am have invested hours in setting devices up just to find out they released a V2. However, there is no way to migrate to V2. In fact, moving from v1 to v2 requires much more work than the original setup because you have to remove every SmartApp and every device from the old hub before they will join the new one. The only comparison I can make to this is, let\u2019s say you accidently delete a document like the one I am typing here. Instead of having to retype it again, you would have to un-type it first. Meaning you would first have to type the document backwards, letter by letter and then type it forward again. It is the most ridiculous migration of anything I have ever seen and I have been in the IT world for a very long time. Other small issues are; it often requires a power reset to make it do something simple like add or delete a device or change a value.\n\nThe App: Nothing can be done on the SmartThings platform without either an iOS or Android app. Note, as of today these are only mobile phone apps. There is no iPad, Tablet, Web, Windows or Mac apps. If you don\u2019t have a smart phone you cannot use this product. While there is a web GUI for some backend programming features, all of the functionality including adding and deleting devices, creating system events, controlling devices and monitoring security are all done through the phone app. The completely unintuitive app has gone through several major updates, all of which are confusing and sometimes confounding. There seems to be no logic to most of the functions. Even though SmartThings is owned by Samsung, it seems like they have a 17-year-old kid programming the app and writing code as he figures out something was missing. I picture this kids room with clothes piled up high on the floor and candy wrappers under the covers. I say this because there is no sense of order or reason in this application.\n\nYou eventually figure things out after a lot of tapping through various screens. But to give you an example, if you don\u2019t link a SmartApp function to a device when you join it for the first time, there is absolutely no documentation or help on how to do it after the fact. It can be done, but not until you go through a half dozen unnecessary screen to find it. So what\u2019s a SmartApp? It is what is needed to do any automation or monitoring for the devices you install. Without them, you simply have a very expensive way to remotely control your lights and monitor the temperature in your house.\n\nDevices: It seems a few companies have really jumped into this technology in a big way. Schlagle, Kwickset, GE, Aeotec, Samsung, Next, Honeywell, are just a few that have incorporated z-wave technology into their devices. None of them are cheap. A regular non-zwave wall switch at Home Depot is about $4.00. A GE z-wave switch will set you back at least $40.00. Motion sensors, sirens, are 50.00 or more. The high end Schlagle locks are going for $300.00. The problem is compatibility and drivers. Just like devices you plug into your PC, every one of these devices needs a driver that the SmartThings hub can understand. SmartThings will list a device as compatible even if there is minimal support for the item. For instance, I purchased an Aeotec Multi sensor 6, the newest sensor out there for motion, temperature humidity, light levels etc. Sure enough, it joined the network in the usual 4 tries. But it didn\u2019t support all of the functions. Nether SmartThings or Aeotech have a driver that supports all the functions, yet both claim compatibility with each other. Also it was grossly inaccurate. But that\u2019s another review. The solution was finding a thread on some obscure forum pointing to a driver written by a very smart person that can be installed though the web GUI. Imagine buying a $50.00 computer mouse that only goes up and down and you had to find a driver written by a third party to make it go in every direction.\n\nSupport: Nonexistent! Both SmartThings and the manufactures of most of the devices have no phone support. You have to email them and they may get back to you in a few days with a canned response that may offer no help, but a promise of a fix in \u201cthe future\u201d.\n\nThe Community: Exceptional! SmartThings has an all volunteer community of very intelligent and helpful people both on SmartThings forum and some others on the internet. Right now this is the sole source of real support for SmartThings and pretty much anything z-wave.\n\nOverall Impression: I love the concept, but all the players have a long way to go. As a hobby I have invested a lot of time and money in SmartThings but it cannot be relied upon for real home security because of 4 things. It relies on an internet connect, electric power, your phone and luck. If you lose any of them, you have also lost all your security. The luck comes in because sometimes SmartThings just isn\u2019t so smart. It doesn\u2019t always do what you want it to do. But I still have hope that Samsung will at some point take this seriously and dedicate a team of real programmers to this technology. I think my investment in the devices is a good one. At only $100.00, the SmartThings hub is not very expensive when you figure in the investment of time and money you put into the devices. If they get their act together, great. If not, I will eventually switch to a different hub that is released by another company that is serious about making this system work. In the meantime, I am amusing myself and frustrating my wife with automating my lights and devices. What\u2019s more fun than that?\n\n2/18/2016 - Update\n\nI still use Smartthings every day for automation and routines and continue to add devices. It seems there are periods of time for hours or days where system performance degrades significantly. Automation of timed actions fail partiality or entirely. You can set 3 lights to come on at sunset. Perhaps 1, 2 or all 3 will fail to come on. If you have an automation that fails for more than a few days, you have to delete it and re add it in the app. I am convinced their servers are overloaded and as more people join the platform and add more devices, their servers get bogged down exponentially.\n\nI think ST has two options. Stop selling any more hubs until they can accommodate the load they already have, or make significant and expeditious growth to their infrastructure. If they don\u2019t do something quick, they are going to continue to get horrific reviews and force users to abandoned ST for the next player to come along who is ready for the challenge. They sorely need a migration tool for upgrades that has been promised for many months. They keep telling people it is coming, but there is no ETA, Their support still stinks! If they can't fix these things, I am ready to jump ship the minute I hear of a viable alternative. Logitech, Microsoft, Apple, anyone, you listening?"}
{"Author": "The Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Ordered item to Israel but still received US and not EU plug, and no adapter."}
{"Author": "FXFD", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product. Little to none issues .. compare to Vera, it is very responsive and reliable."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great now and constantly improving and growing!", "Text": "I have had Smartthings monitoring and automating several things in my home for a while now. At first there were some bugs. Between updates and one note to support everything works great now. I rely on my Smartthings automation I'm not sure what I would do without it. I recently was trying to automate a camera in my garage and having problems figuring it out. I contacted Smartthings support. I asked the question over the weekend and hoped for a reply on monday. I got a reply helping me completely within hours....on a weekend! Thank you very much to Eric M. for the quick helpful reply! In the very small business I work for we do the same thing and it's VERY impressive to see a large company doing the same! My Smartthings works great now and is continually improving. More automation apps and more devices are added all the time. Love the way it's going and you can't beat their fantastic support. 4 stars instead of 5 because there are a lot more devices to add yet!"}
{"Author": "Tim", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't work dependably", "Text": "As a novelty, it is pretty neat. As a security system, it simply isn't dependable enough. I would never recommend it for home security."}
{"Author": "smarter than average guy", "Date": "on January 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Compared to the Revolv Smart Hub, this is not worth the money", "Text": "This has been a very disappointing device. It does not work well with WeMo switches and only works with Zigbee and Zwave. Compared to the Revolv Smart Hub, this is not worth the money."}
{"Author": "Rey", "Date": "on January 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great! Programming function and look could be better.", "Text": "Has been working great! I do recommend Samsung release a software update that is easier to use and looks better but I'm satisfied as is! :)"}
{"Author": "DH in California", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Danger Will Robinson!", "Text": "Worked for 2 days then stopped working. No documentation. Reset has no effect. Zwave devices now inert. A very damaging device. Interface is pathetic."}
{"Author": "BilLowry", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Trust the bad reviews. Can't believe Samsung would put their name ...", "Text": "Truly a time wasting joke. Trust the bad reviews. Can't believe Samsung would put their name on this. The iOS crashes constantly. Be warned."}
{"Author": "EKanas", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best home automation out there", "Text": "I have been a gen 1 customer from the beginning, upgraded to gen 2 and still love the product several years later. The flexibility and integration possibilities are endless. This will turn into more than just another product in your home, it will become a hobby. One thing to keep in mind, if you purchase this hub, keep at as far away as possible from your wireless router (especially if you have an AirPort Extreme) the signal from the extreme will interfere with the hub causing connection issues with the Zwave signal. I connected mine to my airport express extender and it's flawless."}
{"Author": "gear41", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I got into the home automation scene by purchasing a ...", "Text": "I got into the home automation scene by purchasing a Phillips hue starter kit. After doing a lot more research, I decided to return the Hue set and invest in Smarthings, as it is much more expandable and can control many more devices (not just lights, as with Hue). Connecting to the CREE Connected bulbs I purchased was a breeze.\n\nThe only con is that there seems to be a slight delay when turning on and off lights, something that was not the case with Hue."}
{"Author": "Alex", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fine to use but a pain to setup", "Text": "I honestly expected a lot more from a major brand like Samsung and was really disappointed by the very awkward interface options for this device. The biggest problem I have with the SmartThings Hub is not being able access it from a computer. The only way to control the SmartThings Hub is to use a smartphone compatible with their app. This phone app is fine but I'm baffled why Samsung would force everyone to configure their Hub this way. I genuinely like the app (now that everything is working) but using a phone touchscreen keyboard to enter in all of the codes and to configure everything for first-time use added a ton of frustration for seemingly no apparent reason.\n\nI was able to connect all of my devices to the hub, but again, it would have been much easier had I not been forced to do this on a phone. The app seems like it's fairly capable, and I eventually got it configured and could group devices into rooms or toggle things like light switches all from one screen, but since there was no instructions and you can only see what will fit on a small phone screen, getting to this point was quite a chore and really took all the fun out of this process.\n\nPerhaps there is hope that some of this can be addressed with software updates - it's a real shame the way the GUI is ruining the experience because the hardware is actually quite good. The hub is pretty much compatible with all major connection technologies, including ZigBee D-Wave, and WiFi, and despite there being some lag on occasion, it's always eventually responded to commands or updated with the correct information."}
{"Author": "Gadget Nut", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Big name company with no Support", "Text": "So after returning Samsung smart hub and trying others I have gone back to SmartThings. Been in use for about 2 years, only a few minor issues. Has work as a great device to turn lights on/off as planned in my smart apps timers. I love this unit lots of options."}
{"Author": "Stilton23", "Date": "on January 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Quirky Installation, But Mostly Positive", "Text": "Just purchased this and installed to get better control over a Wemo light switch that was not being detected by the Wemo app. Installation was a little problematic, as the lights hung up for more than 30 minutes without indicating a link. I powered down and rebooted and it came online after about 5 minutes. It quickly detected the Wemo switch and linking to Amazon Echo was painless. Initial impressions are very positive, though the iPhone app could use some design help - not very intuitive. This is developing technology and I look forward to delving more into the SmartThings community and their SmartApps. I will update this review as I bring more switches, outlets and detectors online. At this early stage, though, and having done a lot of research, I believe this is the best automation integration system available - just don't expect it to be perfect."}
{"Author": "E. Sharp", "Date": "on January 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So Far So Good", "Text": "Just installed the SmartThings Hub 2nd Generation and have connected a GE Smart Switch, Smart Bulb, and Sonos Speoker.. So far so good. Love being able to set up \"routines\" so that lights and things come on and off at certain times. Will update the review as I continue to add and work with new accessories."}
{"Author": "K. Halgerson", "Date": "on January 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent for power users", "Text": "After trying out a couple other solutions, this is my favorite ('cause it actually works). It is widely supported by lots of other solutions. The most important for me is that it can be plugged into the Android program Tasker (which I use to automate the rest of my life) via SharpTools. It is also compatible with IFTTT and Logitech Harmony, so this is truly the bridge connects everything in my home.\n\nI'm sure you could get the same results for less money, but it would be a lot of work and headache. With the SmartThings hub and a few other tools, anyone can do it in a few hours."}
{"Author": "OldRick", "Date": "on January 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable and suited only for hobbyists with lots of time to waste. Not recommended for humans.", "Text": "This is the most unreliable piece of over-hyped technology I have ever seen. No part of it works reliably. It is not suitable for security applications, HVAC, or even lighting control.\nI have wasted dozens of hours trying to do simple things like control lights and heating, only to find that nothing works reliably, i.e., at least once each week, programmed \"automated\" actions don't happen.\nYou would waste far more seconds of your life on SmartThings than on flipping light switches, and there is no way on earth that you would ever get back your investment in this technology when you sell a house with this impenetrable junk installed."}
{"Author": "Mikeazon", "Date": "on January 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bittersweet Review", "Text": "Product worked well when I tested it. I then moved it to a remote location where I own a cabin and rigged up a router and MIFi for cameras. Problem is since its s new network name it won't work. Tried deleting my previous Location but all I get are error notes. No one to call so tried the chat box on my app, it was during operation hours but Chat was down. Sent email but no response. Probably a good item unless you need ANY support."}
{"Author": "Christine", "Date": "on January 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Would not buy this again", "Text": "After three calls to tech support and having to hire someone to come and set this up to our network, it's finally working. It's gone offline once (which could have been due to wifi). I would never buy this product again. It's way too complicated to set up and was nearly impossible (and we ARE computer savvy), the interface is quite confusing on their Apple app and the tech support is via email only.\n\nOnce it's working, it does the job. But to get there there is nearly impossible and trying to figure out how to program it on their very complex app proved to be a challenge to which I almost succumbed !"}
{"Author": "siliconvallaeys", "Date": "on January 12, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I tried this and also Wink and the Wink has ...", "Text": "I tried this and also Wink and the Wink has an easier to use app and also seems to work with more of the devices I want to use. A lot of SmartThings integrations seem to be experimental and complicated to get working."}
{"Author": "C. A. Thompson", "Date": "on January 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You're not allowed to reset it yourself. Not easy to use.", "Text": "I returned this after days of frustration. Aside from being somewhat difficult to use, the worst thing about it to me is that you can't reset the device without involving customer support. I never thought I'd need to reset the hub but after fruitlessly trying to configure several devices, I thought I'd reset it and start over. Then I found out the hard way that you can't just reset it. That's ridiculous to me. If I pay $100 for the hub, it's mine and I should be able to program it as I want to, and that includes resetting it. Customer service is only over email (the chat window on the support site is never available) and when they told me after two attempts that engineers might need to get involved just to do a reset, I gave up."}
{"Author": "Nikita S.", "Date": "on January 12, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as expected.", "Text": "UPDATED: 1/26/2016\nFinally got reply from customer support and my issue was resolved. Hub and devices work good so far.\n\nPREVIOUSLY:\nMy hub stopped sending alerts after 2 months. Android app doesnt let me set system to Home or Arm state anymore, same applies to iOS. Customer support is useless. Forums are good but not much help.\n\nThey must clearly state that this product is for hobbiest."}
{"Author": "Casey Hill", "Date": "on January 12, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Its an improvement and recommended", "Text": "I have to say the overall potential (let me stress the potential part again) for the Hub v2 is fantastic. We are all paitently awaiting for the new features to come in. Essentially you are getting everything the version one hub has so there is no reason to consider it (likely can't get it anyway).\n\nAre you looking for something that is simple, turn key, easy to understand - then you've likely come to the wrong place. However, the other home automation systems out there are even worse so I would still recommend smartthings.\n\nI've been doing these home installations for 9 months now and every installation is unique. Each customers needs are quick to implement but require extensive knowledge. Yes, the community forums are the best place to get started with advanced features and functions. Be warned, you better be willing to invest 100+ hours ...\n\nThis is true from the previous review:\nHere's an example: SmartThings sells Kwikset locks through their marketplace. They also list it as a supported device. What they don't say is that you won't be able to use ALL of the features the lock is capable of, primarily PIN code management, which is a basic feature on pretty much every other competitor. You can only view the status of the lock and lock/unlock the device. Luckily the community comes to the rescue here and a custom application is available to \"unlock\" these features.\n\nI would also agree the app has gotten more complicated to understand especially if you used it in a previous version."}
{"Author": "rtloeffler", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "love the hub style, api - its easy.", "Text": "Its buggy but the potential and the amount of control you get. There is nothing else that compares, and for the price its great! However the app itself needs to be rebuilt from the ground up. Its horrible at time and can get stuck loading. plus the layout is confusing for awhile, but you eventually get used to it."}
{"Author": "Juan C. Villa", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best hub in the market and decent application", "Text": "Awesome device. Has great potential, but I feel it's only at 80% of what it could be. It has two USB ports that have no practical functionality yet. I wish those USB ports support 3G/4G USB modems as a backup or primary connection to the cloud (think security applications with Scout). The mobile application is alright, but not great. The app is very buggy and hangs occasionally, which after a restart requires me to log in again. Nevertheless, this is by far the best and most customizable smart home hub and solution on the market. Can't wait to see what Smart Things will accomplish under Samsung's umbrella."}
{"Author": "Mark Budz", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They claim they are Z-wave Certified but unit dons support basic", "Text": "They claim they are Z-wave Certified but unit dons support basic functions to be z-wave certified .I was not able to add 2 older z-wave devices, I could not do primal shift or add secondary from homeseer or leviton controller"}
{"Author": "Timothy Cook", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love Smartthings so much more", "Text": "Switched to Smartthings from Lowes' Iris system. I love Smartthings so much more!!! It is so much more customizable than the Lowe's system and can use a lot more devices. The Smartthings community and forums are also so great!! A lot of great developers and help there that can get done just about anything you want!!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "STAY AWAY!!", "Text": "Brand new V2 hub won't connect. Known problem, that Smartthings has yet to address. 4 e-mails to support, and 7 days later, still no response. \"Live chat\" is actually never online, although advertised to be 9am-5pm Mon-Fri. I was super excited about this product, but definitely STAY AWAY!!"}
{"Author": "Karen R", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "while the hub seems fine have connections issues that they probably could solve in ...", "Text": "while the hub seems fine have connections issues that they probably could solve in two minutes but their support section is non existent they don't answer emails (automated response, received your email,l does't count) and their chat line is permanently offline. will be returning this for that reason, several other hub out there to do the same thing with better support"}
{"Author": "Christopher Pratt", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Occasional app glitches like logging out unexpectedly", "Text": "I have about 15 switches/outlets and a door lock linked and all connected through my Echo. Everything works perfectly. Occasional app glitches like logging out unexpectedly, but nothing serious or constant. Many reviewers complaining of communication problems may need to relocate the hub...it does not like being close to the router. Use this every day and is amazing...love it!"}
{"Author": "Lem", "Date": "on January 10, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Underwhelmed", "Text": "Installation and use was pretty simple. Hardware is solid. The software seriously blows. It is complicated, but as an engineer, I had not problem navigating. The worst part is the software crashes regularly. Not a biggie, but in this day and age. It blows. There are lots of small things to customize but the developers cut corners. LIke taking a picture of your house as your stock photo. You have to use their stupid images."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung Smart Hub V2... No Phone Support, Case Closed!", "Text": "Samsung Support is Dismal. First this device took overnight to connect originally. OVERNIGHT! Then you can't call Samsung for an answer, only EMAIL... an email that was answered 17 hours later asking me what colored lights I was getting on the front of the hub when I told them in my support question what color lights I had. Been there, Done That like, 12 hours ago! I'm not a typical computer user that doesn't know anything. I'm a power user and the only reason I contact any support is because I can't figure it out after hours in the first place. What would the common internet user do?\n\nI think you really need to ask yourself, Do you really need this in your home? Even if its Version 2... I think it's too early to really be what you hope it would be. Ask the V1 Hub users how they feel now that V2 has arrived? I have an Amazon Echo and I think it does everything I need it to do and with software updates it continually does more. I have the Philips Hue System, and it works along with the Echo. I also have D-link system that has motion detector, cameras, and everything I need, and it worked from the start... WITH TELEPHONE SUPPORT!\n\nMy advice.. Don't be a 2nd Adopter to this system. Give it more time. You hear all these \"Rants & Raves\" from CES2016 about what's coming. I think, wait till CES 2017 and then consider what new things this device can be useful for. If people are getting so lazy that they can't get up and turn off a light, and then waste time \"fingering\" through an app on their cellphones... well, I guess you are the person that needs this device!\n\nCase Closed!"}
{"Author": "Bobby", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very good system, while not much in life is perfect ...", "Text": "Very good system, while not much in life is perfect this system is the best I have found with out breaking the bank I am very please.\nI have had this for many months now and think it's really great, I have programed it to turn lights on at 6:45am and can easily change it to anything else you can imagine. When I go on vacation I set it for on one hour before dawn and off at dusk for my birds. I have connected it to Amazon's Alexa and can now voice control my whole house. The best NEW thing I can say Alexa \"lights off\" it will then ask what and I say \"Good Night\" and the whole house turns off! I can say \"Good Morning\" and I'm set to entertain. I have managed to learn this all on my own by just playing with it and trying new things and these devices HAVE had software updates too. I Love it!"}
{"Author": "Mark", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great concept that simply doesn't work", "Text": "I've been a user for a year and my initial enthusiasm has turned to anger and disappointment. What was once a promising product is now unreliable, unsupported, and nothing more than an expensive toy. SmartThings has acknowledged things have gone South (which is commendable on their part) but they are unwilling or unable to fix the myriad of problems they've introduced. These problems cause the entire SmartThings platform to be unreliable and/or completely non-functional, leaving you, your family, and your home unprotected. This would be a great home automation product if it worked reliably. Go to the SmartThings Community Forum and read posts from other users before spending a penny on SmartThings products."}
{"Author": "LCOC", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "worked right away", "Text": "this linked up quickly with the ge outdoor outlets and the smart things iPhone app. no complaints here:)"}
{"Author": "shawn steadman", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "As wxpected"}
{"Author": "Mark Nassab", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They do a great job marketing", "Text": "Unfortunately I have to give these guys a low score. They don't have any support system at all. Your only option is to email them and it takes more than a week for them to respond and they are clueless. I have been using them for few months and have installed over 40 devices to it and nothing works as it should. They do a great job marketing, but fail miserably in their products. Don't buy this product and waste your time and money."}
{"Author": "Trenda", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Software update broke it", "Text": "Hub setup was easy and quick. My camera, a Samsung SmartCam HD Pro was running great via Ethernet and the hub easily connected to it. A few hours later the hub got a software update which caused the hub to go offline. I had to get tech support to help me get it back online but it never would find the camera again (still connected via Ethernet) even after additional help from tech support. I returned hub for a refund. It's pretty sad that a Samsung product can't play nice with another Samsung product. I can only assume there would be more endless problems every time there is a software update with this product in the future. The main reason I bought this hub was to work with my camera.\nThe camera continues to work just fine with my Galaxy phone and Samsung SmartCam HD app."}
{"Author": "Thrifty", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Small with a very far reach", "Text": "Very versatile little machine for the price. I was really surprised just how small it actually is. It can fit anywhere, just as long as it's close to your WIFI router.\nThe app for Smartthings also wasn't very complicated at all. It was very straightforward and logically setup up by rooms or as a list of smart things you have installed. Connecting it to an Amazon Echo is also very easy, and this needs to be done via the Alexa app first.\nThe range is also quite nice. I was worried it wouldn't reach a switch behind a night table in my bedroom, at the end of a hallway, about 60 ft from the hub. So far no issues.\nLooking forward to integrating more things, and turning my apartment as smart as possible."}
{"Author": "Susan", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung support for this is bad....", "Text": "UPDATED AGAIN: Ok, as we have learned more about the quirks/bugs of this hub, I've upgraded it again. I guess it's just a learning curve figuring out how this thing thinks. I think we have. We like it now!\n\nHowever, I will say this - don't expect any support from Smartthings. If you post a bad review here, in a couple of days they will leave a nice comment saying sorry. But that doesn't really count as support now does it? If Smartthings is to be affiliated with Samsung, they will need to step up their customer service by 100 fold.\n\nUPDATE: I have updated my rating to a three-star rating. I will probably keep learning how this thing works and keep upgrading my rating. First up, the problem we had with our light switch not working -- here's a hint. If you swap out a 3 way switch, (like in our kitchen we have two switches on either side of the room that both turn on the light) you can't use the switch that isn't zwave or you throw the thing out of sync. Got it figured out!\n\nSecond, it seems as though to get the hub to see the Linear garage door opener, we had to sit it next to the hub and push the button that's on the Linear. It worked! Tricky, took a couple of times pushing that button before the hub finally saw it, but it finally did. At this point, I'm really hoping that it's just a matter of learning all the quirks of this system. FINGERS CROSSED!\n_____________________________________________________\n\nIf you look at all my reviews, I rarely, if ever, leave a 1-star review. And granted, I am new to Smartthings. I understand there is a learning curve. It's not like you need to be a rocket scientist to get this hub and the various devices to up and running. It's pretty straight forward as to how you set it up. That's the point. I feel like even a rocket scientist would be pulling their hair out at this point! After reading the rave reviews of how well this works, my hubby and I dove right in. Felt totally confident that it would be a great product....it's a Samsung after all.\n\nHere's what we've seen so far in the first three days: Day one we installed a light switch in the kitchen. It paired right up with the hub. Yay! \"Alexa, turn on the kitchen light.\" And she did! Woo hoo! So we set up a routine \"Good morning\" and tell it to turn the lights on at 6:00 a.m. And we tell it to turn off the lights when everyone is gone. Tried to get the Linear garage door hooked up, never could pair it up. We are sending it back for a new unit to see if that one will work.\n\nDay two: Kitchen light was on. Yay! Went to work, came home, light was still on. What the heck?! \"Alexa, turn off the lights.\" And she did. Tried to use the app (just to see if it would work) to turn it back on again, nothing happened. Lights only came on when I clicked the wall switch.\n\nDay three: Woke up to a dark house. The only things working were the ones on timers that aren't connected to Smartthings. WTH?!\n\nCustomer support is basically non-existent. I emailed them since they don't have a phone number. And their \"chat now\" is NEVER available. Ever. Got one vague email back and nothing since. That is so not like Samsung!\n\nI promise that if we get all this straightened out, things up and running correctly, I will revise and update this rating. But for now, it's staying."}
{"Author": "Brett M. Williams", "Date": "on January 8, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hopefully things get better with this before I decide to return it", "Text": "Hopefully things get better with this before I decide to return it. Spend some time checking out the SmartThings Community. If you are going to be using this device, you will be spending some time there.\n\nEverything arrived on time and I was excited to get this plugged in, setup the app, and start tinkering with all the various devices that I had ordered for the project I had in mind. The device seemed to do its part to login and register itself, but shortly after I started using the app I got an error \"You are not authorized to perform the requested operation.\" OK, minor setup back, let me go scan the forums and see what I can find to remedy the situation.\n\nUpdated a week later:\nI finally got a response from the support team, took about 24 hours. The problem was on their backend and there was nothing I was going to be able to do about it. They resolved it fairly quickly and I was on my way. Once this was cleared up, everything else was fine. I am optimistic now about seeing what I can do with this.\n\nEvery indication pointed to having to get in touch with support. So I tried the Online Chat with support, that appears to still be on their website, but is never actually manned. There is no phone number to call for support, even for first time users just unboxing their device. That leaves one option, sending a request in via e-mail/website form. I did that and got an auto-response that my e-mail was received.\n\nFlash to the next day and no further response. I have had some communication with others that when they finally got in touch with support they were able to get this problem resolved (it appears to be something on the back-end and is not resolvable on the consumer side), however it took upwards of a week to get a response back from Support. I just can't see having this new device sitting here for a week waiting to hear back from support. I spent almost $400 on the hub and all the devices I need for my project, and can't do a single thing. Very frustrating."}
{"Author": "Murr Clurr", "Date": "on January 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Working great!", "Text": "Love this hub! Currently I have a motion sensor and five different lights running and everything is working flawlessly. Had the Vera Lite controller before this and sent it back as the UI was clunky and a bit cumbersome. The Smart Things app and hub have worked great and I haven't had any issues."}
{"Author": "J. Urschel", "Date": "on January 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings really does ROCK!", "Text": "I got my wife a smart door lock for christmas and we wanted to automate some functions of the lock. I did my investigations and found SmartThings to be the best bet for that task. I came to Amazon and read these reviews on the device. Obviously, it worried me. There are what seem to be two camps. You either love the hub or hate it. Given the mixed reviews on Amazon I decided not to purchase from Amazon and instead buy locally at BB with the warranty so I could/can just return it easily if something happens. I have to say this device just works. In about 2 minutes I had my door lock added as a device and was locking and unlocking it. After some forum searching I quickly discovered that there's a team of people who have spent a lot of time making custom apps for the hub located here http://smartthings.ramitbhalla.com/ . So I spent another 10$ in donation money and now I can do some ridiculous things with my door lock. I have since in about the span of 2 weeks added a smoke alarm and a thermostat which both easily added themselves to the hub and are both now managed. It honestly might have taken 1-2 hours to get everything added and customized using the open API of smartthings and the apps above. I love this device and am so glad I didn't buy into the FUD that some people are spreading about it on this listing. If your new to HA this device will do just fine for you!"}
{"Author": "Rory", "Date": "on January 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My life without a smart home would be terrible", "Text": "My life without a smart home would be terrible. I had Wink and Smartthings, but I am now 100% Smartthings."}
{"Author": "CAH", "Date": "on January 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent Home Automation Hub", "Text": "Graduating from the old X10 products to the new Smart Things Hub with Z-wave capability and Amazon Echo voice control of devices. My first device was a Fibaro Flood sensor that once connected to the Smart Things Hub alerts you to a moisture condition and the hub is able to text my cell phone with the alarm. It also re-sends the text every hour until the alarm is acknowledged or reset. I also have it turn on a light in my home so we have a physical alarm also when we are home."}
{"Author": "Patricia A. Slaughter", "Date": "on January 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings V2 Hub is Great!!", "Text": "Others have reported problems with the 2nd generation Hub, but I've had no problems. Many device will pair anywhere in the house, but some require that they are near the Hub to pair properly. The devices that are required to be near the Hub to pair, are not Smart\u02c7hings devices, but from other manufacturers. This works well with the Amazon Echo & was very easy to setup. So far I use Aeon Labs and GE devices and they all work well!! I really like this product."}
{"Author": "G. McGowan", "Date": "on January 4, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This product does not deliver what it advertises.", "Text": "Great potential, lots of vision on the part of SmartThings. Unfortunately the quality assurance and execution has missed the mark by a long shot.\n\nThis device is a cloud connected device. It's means that it's \"brains\" reside on a server somewhere. SmartThings continually introduces bugs into their platform which seems to break functionality with every new release.\n\nThis hub will appear to work fine with a small number of devices. How as you add more devices with different function you begin to discover half baked attempts to support these solutions.\n\n."}
{"Author": "D Art", "Date": "on January 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am happy with the hub and all the listed devices", "Text": "Smarthings Hub 2.0 review\n\nWorking well now, but had two service outages that required reset. I have this linked to 4 multipurpose sensors (2 as magnetic door switches and 2 as tilt sensors for garage door), one motion sensor.\n\nNon-Samsung devices:\n\n1) GE12722 Z-Wave Wireless Lighting Control\n2) Enerwave ZWN-333 Z-Wave Wireless Plug-In Appliance On / Off Switch\n3) MIMOLite - Z-wave Mulit-Input/Output Dry Contact Bridge\n4) Three Cree LED light bulbs (dimmable)\n4) Amazon Echo\n\nGripes:\n1) iOS app logs me out so I have to periodically log in again\n2) Always shows iPhones as \"present\" even when I am away from home. (app issue?)\n3)Hub does not have WiFi, so it requires hardwired Ethernet connection. This is a pain as I was not able to locate it where I wanted.\n4) Not able to query state of sensors with Amazon Echo, but controls lamps ok. This is probably a limitation of the Echo, not the hub. I expect this functionality will be added in the future.\n\nAll in all, I am happy with the hub and all the listed devices. I would recommend it."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best in breed despite being a work in progress", "Text": "A number of people have dinged the SmartThings Hub for its clumsy software, but the latest version isn't too bad. There are just a lot of options which eventually you may find useful. From what I can tell, it's the only smart hub that handles lighting control properly. Turn on for motion, turn off some minutes after the motion stops, and do this from sunset to sunrise plus or minus a specified offset. The motion sensor itself is tiny, battery operated, and reliable.\n\nDirect Ethernet connection is more reliable and avoids a power hungry WiFi radio. Battery backup and local smarts allow basic functions to work without power or Internet (like any decent home security system). It's an open platform that supports plug-in applications. It includes visual instructions, recommendations, a store, and let's you organize your SmartThings by Devices, Rooms, or Applications. It reminds me a little of iTunes.\n\nIt has built-in radios for Z-Wave, Zigbee, and Bluetooth (not enabled yet). That so many of the basics work reliably is a big plus. Enjoy!"}
{"Author": "M. R. Lee", "Date": "on January 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Update: It's gotten better", "Text": "Update 7/13/2016: After a recent backend software update, most of my performance related issues have gone. I also replaced my TCP Connected lights (which no longer support cloud-connected bulb functionality) with Cree Smart Bulbs and now my lights all work as they should. SmartThings still needs to figure out how to do proper customer support, but at the least, it no longer is a daily chore to diagnose and fix.\n\nSmartThings is a very smart idea. Unfortunately, execution and support is TERRIBLE. For example, my lights constantly disconnect from the SmartThings hub, requiring me to reauthorize my lights every day or every other day. The app constantly tells me that there is some sort of unexpected error with no indication of what the error might be. Attempts to contact Samsung Support has come to naught. Samsung does not provide you with a telephone number to call. All support must be done through emails (but there is nobody to respond to your support emails) and the live support (which apparently doesn't work either).\n\nAll in all, a terrible device for my purposes. This device is supposed to be the second generation, but it feels like a first-gen product. Myriads of bugs and barely-functional capabilities at all. It's hilarious that Samsung actually advertises this as a home monitoring device, because, quite frankly, I hope you have nothing valuable in your homes."}
{"Author": "Skyhawk", "Date": "on January 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Flawlessly with iPhone. I Have Many Things Connected. A FEW Software Shortcomings Prevents Total Perfection.", "Text": "Works Flawlessly with iPhone. I Have Many Things Connected. A FEW Software Shortcomings Prevents Total Perfection.\n\nSo glad that I switched to iPhone. The iPhone app is 4.83 stars\n\nWhen shopping for a Z-Wave / Zigbee Hub the popularity of that hub is an important consideration. It does appear that the SmartThings Hub is now number one. I think the much loved Revolv Hub WAS #1 until it was purchased by The Evil Empire (aka, Google), and dismantled.\n\nSmartThings has an active user forum where you can get help and suggestions from other users like you. I have read some criticisms of SmartThings support. I had occasion to write them about an issue and I received a reply in about 24 hours. On another occasion, it took about 3 days to get an answer. I'm disappointed in the timeline, but I did receive good and helpful answers. I suspect, (but do not know) that the support is coming from free Korea.\n\nPrimarily, I am using the SmartThings hub to control Aeon Labs DSC24-ZWUS Smart Switchs, (5-stars also). One merely has to press the button on the switch several times rapidly in order to pair it with the SmartThings hub.\n\nA few observations are:\n\n1) Take the batteries that come with the SmartThings hub and throw them away. Replace them with lithium batteries. Lithium batteries last about four times longer, and I have never seen them leak.\n\n2) When I first installed the app, I found that I had to enter my user name and password repeatedly. This annoying problem was addressed by support and the problem has almost gone away.\n\n3) If controlling things during a power failure is important. Consider plugging this unit into a Sine Wave output, Uninterruptible Power Supply.\n\n4) Regarding the range of Z-Wave / Zigbee devices. Each Z-Wave / Zigbee device acts as a repeater. So start using devices that are closer to the SmartThings hub and move outwards. The nearby devices will repeat the signal to the ones further away. If you have no nearby devices, Z-Wave / Zigbee signal repeaters are available.\n\n5) Thermostats: When shopping for thermostats I strongly prefer ones that have an LED indicator light. My house has 11 thermostats, (large house with zones). With an LED indicator light you can tell at a 20'-50' distance whether the thermostat is calling for heat or air conditioning. Red = Heat, Green = A.C. Very nice when lying in bed, or other situations when you don't want to get up and look at your thermostat.\n\nRegarding the SmartThings program (app).\n\nIT WORKS! Performs very solidly. When at home, it utilizes my Wi-Fi network. Response times are virtually instantaneous when I tap on a switch using the iPhone app. The device operates with about a 1/4 second delay. This is about as good as it can get. From 1000 miles away, using the SmartThings network. The delay is a couple of seconds.\n\nThings that could be better in the SmartThings program (app), (Warning, I spent many years designing, and approving software interfaces.)\n\n1) All of your devices can be found under a category they call, \"Things\". This list is alphabetized. There should be an option to reorder this list.\n\n2) There is a category called, \"SmartApps\". Under this category I can only find an item called, \"Smart Lighting\". Why they use the word \"Lighting\" I do not understand. Most of the things I am controlling are not lights at all. I might call this category simply, \"Programming\". Under \"Smart Lighting\" you will find any programming you have done, for example, turn off switch 3 at 9:30 PM. This list cannot be reordered. It should be.\n\n3) ALL lists should have the ability to be reordered.\n\n4) In order to help organize things they have a heading called, \"Rooms\". Perhaps that's the way most people will use this. In my case under, \"Rooms\" I have things like. First-floor cameras, Second-floor cameras, Christmas lights. As you can see, I'm not using the rooms, as rooms simply a way to categorize different things.\n\n5) I find no way to copy my programming in one SmartThings Hub and transfer it to another one. I would like to have the ability to make a backup of my programming should my hub ever fail.\n\nMany people will use SmartThings to increase the security of their home. Many experts now recommend AGAINST continuous outdoor lighting. It turns out, that in many cases outdoor lighting is simply illuminating the criminals work area. It also turns out that many criminals are afraid of the dark! You are probably better off to have outdoor security lights on motion sensors. That way, when a bad guy is walking nearby, the lights snap on and startles them. Burglars don't like changing environments. Moreover, remember this. Most burglaries happen during the daytime.\n\nSmartThings is still relatively new. I suspect that the few glitches that they have will be ironed out over time. SmartThings appears to be making a solid commitment to home automation, this is probably a product you can grow with.\n\nAnd finally, many of us have learned to avoid any product with the name, \"Smart\" or the name, \"Green\" in the product name or description. SmartThings is an exception to this usually good rule."}
{"Author": "Raoul Picante", "Date": "on January 3, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good system design. Software and interface needs improvement", "Text": "I've just installed and started testing with a SmartThings Multipurpose Sensor (open/close and temperature).\n\nThe Android app running on a Samsung 3 indicates intermittent failures. I'm not sure whether this is caused by the app or the hub.\n\nHeads Up on installation: You get to an app screen that says it will take 5-10 minutes to download the firmware -- don't turn off hub. When the screen confirms, then tap Next. After waiting an eternity, I never saw any clear confirmation. However, almost instantaneously a green circle with check mark appeared. I wasn't sure whether or not that was confirmation. I tried powering down everything and redid the process. Same thing. Then I went to the room with the hub and observed as steady green LED -- on the FRONT of the hub. So I proceeded, and was able to complete the hub setup.\n\nSee also my review on the Multipurpose Sensor."}
{"Author": "MCE LLC", "Date": "on January 2, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What you deserve to know before buying this product", "Text": "Fourth update: Rating increase to three stars from one star.\nI've had this for over a year now. Much of what I've written below still applies with one exception. Samsung appears to have gotten on top of the service reliability issues. In fact, I was so frustrated, I stopped caring about it. All of a sudden I realized that it had become much more reliable. This has worked with minimal intervention from me for at least six months. The most common problem I have is that the sunrise/sunset routine doesn't run which maybe occurs once a month.There are more HA options today than just a year ago so you should shop around. Like all things wireless and internet, some tech skills are required.\n---------------------------\nThis is the third time I'm writing this review. Each time my product rating gets lower and lower. This is based on my expectations and how well it fit my needs. I want you to know what you are buying so you won't be disappointed if you expected something different.\n\nWhat you deserve to know:\n1 - You are depending on the reliability of a service provided by Samsung. Most of the rules you write will be stored and run on Samsung's servers. They may say that some apps are run locally, most are not.\n2 - Server problems are a common event. Sometimes it is a bad cluster or they are upgrading the servers. Sometimes, it's just because...\n3 - You must visit the community forum if you want to get anywhere. That is where you can find out about all the problems and solutions. It is also where you can see that this is very open source and Samsung is looking for the community to mature the product.\n4 - You must treat this like a hobby. Ever thought about getting a Raspberry Pi? This product is for you. If want nothing more complicated than buying a smart TV and connecting it to the internet, this product is not for you.\n5 - This product is not suitable for anything critical like safety, security, or health. If you have serious needs and want something more turn key. Look elsewhere.\n6 -There is no phone support. Email or forum help only.\n\nOn the other hand:\n7 - You can have fun with this as a hobby if that's what you're looking for. Many of the negatives listed above are positives when treated as a hobby.\n8 - This is about as good a product you can buy at this price point. Face it, home automation has been around for decades. Getting hardware with internet connectivity and a phone app for $99 is pretty good. Just know what you are getting.\n\nIf I didn't hate to give up on things, I would have trashed my hub by now. My like for the product exceeds my contempt for its unreliablity...just barely. This may change anytime now."}
{"Author": "Unwound", "Date": "on January 1, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice universal smart device controller", "Text": "The SmartThings hub itself works very well but some of the device apps software is a bit buggy. I bought this hub because of its universal nature and ability to control wi-fi, z-wave and zigbee devices. In addition to the natively supported smart devices there is a whole community dedicated to developing device types and apps many many more smart devices at GitHub.com."}
{"Author": "Rob", "Date": "on December 31, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Compared this vs Wink. SmartThings won by a long shot.", "Text": "Compared this vs Wink. Almost went with the Wink since it was about 70% less in cost but this thing is amazing. It integrates with GIT so people can post code and automation and you can pull from their reports. It's little more difficult to setup than Wink but well worth it. Also, I noticed it powers items on/off 1000% faster than Wink."}
{"Author": "CHAO C HUANG", "Date": "on December 31, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Upgraded from v1 hub for better response time and more reliable performance", "Text": "Upgraded from v1 hub for better response time and more reliable performance. Kind of worry about transfer my 40+ devices over v2 hub before purchase this thing, but it turns out much easier than I thought. I have transferred SmartSense Multi Sensor, SmartSense Motion Sensor, Smart Power outlet, Fibaro Motion Sensor, Ecolink Motion Sensor, CT100 Thermostat, Schlage Connect Touchscreen Deadbolt, Linear Garage Door Opener, First Alert Z-Wave Smoke Alarm, and Utilitech Water Leak Detector without any issue. All devices are working correctly and the v2 hub does provides more reliable automation than v1 hub."}
{"Author": "E-Man", "Date": "on December 30, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good on the hardware side", "Text": "So far so good on the hardware side, only issues are the hub seems to disconnect at times and since I bought it I had to reset it a few times. The app is hit and miss and could use some work, for instance if I try to unlock my Kwikset 910 Z-wave lock and if the lock is out of range of the hub, it will say that it is unlocked even though the lock didn't open. When I check the Activity Log it doesn't show as unlocked but on the device screen it shows it as unlocked. Then I close the app and go back in, it shows that the lock is still locked, so it's like a false positive initally. This is the only gripe I have, and hopefully if I buy a range extender it will solve the issue. I wish there was some way it let me know that the device isn't responding instead of saying the command executed when it didn't."}
{"Author": "Drue", "Date": "on December 30, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home AutoMation at its best.", "Text": "I think the whole home automation thing is fairly new, but I have looked at all the different options and SmartThings by far is superior. Currently I have setup cam's, openers, switches and more and they all work great..\n\nSome bit of a learning curve is necessary here, but it's well worth it."}
{"Author": "Evan H.", "Date": "on December 29, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good for basic/starter home automation users", "Text": "I am new to the HA scene and consider myself a technical person. After several hours spent researching which hub to purchase (Smartthings, Homeseer, Vera Edge, etc), I decided on this device for my parents home for many reasons:\n1. Multiprotocol support (Zwave, Zigbee, Wifi, and Bluetooth). This thing can control pretty much anything (given the device is supported either by ST or the ST Community).\n2. The Community. Even before buying, I was searching the forums and quickly found out that other ST users are willing to help with any issue. Also there is usually a user developed custom device type or smart app to help integrate any device that is not \"officially\" supported by ST. (for instance, my MyQ garage door openers are now controlled by ST thanks to a community member creating a custom Smart App and Device Type.\n3. Samsung recently bought SmartThings. I love Samsung and I expect great things to come from this acquisition.\n4. The app is user friendly (once configured) so my non-tech savvy parents can utilize the home automation system for monitoring and controlling their house.\n\nThere are some things that are keeping me from giving this a 5 star rating:\n1. Must be connected via ethernet. Basically have to have this next to your router/switch (or buy a longer ethernet cord).\n2. You are pretty much SOL if the internet goes out.\n3. Configuration is done through the App. I move quicker on a laptop/pc and I think it'd be easier to set up rules and devices via a web portal."}
{"Author": "Krishnan Subramanian", "Date": "on December 29, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product But", "Text": "I am a Smartthings user from their early days. I love this product and still do. But my experience with Ver 2 of the Hub has been pathetic compared to Ver 1. The routines will stop working regularly, app experience is sub-optimal compared to my experience with Ver 1 and I would have to reboot the hub to get the routines working again. Has happened 3-4 times in the last 3+ months of using Hub Ver 2. The support has been more than awesome and pro-active. They have reached out to me based on my complaints on Twitter. Their CEO responds to questions and complaints on Twitter. So I can claim that I am a satisfied customer as far as their support is concerned. But the annoyance with the routines from not working properly and the need to reboot/reset is a pain. Not sure if I got a bad piece but this is annoying. In my opinion, a good smart hub product should be boring. Once it is set up you shouldn't be worrying about it. However, my experience with Smartthings Ver 2 is sub optimal. In short, bet on Smartthings but stick to Hub Ver 1, if possible."}
{"Author": "Rick Schleicher", "Date": "on December 29, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "We love Samsung products but this app seems to have missed ...", "Text": "So far it's working well. Took some time to figure out the interface but things are smoothing out now. The 2 things that concern me are, can't send text alerts to multiple phones and can't seem to get routines vs the dashboard figured out and the community boards haven't provided much info. We love Samsung products but this app seems to have missed the high marks Samsung usually gets"}
{"Author": "Earnest K", "Date": "on December 28, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Brought it back and I was dumb enough to purchase yet another from an electronics store", "Text": "Purchased one from a well known department store. It would NOT recognized any sensors. Brought it back and I was dumb enough to purchase yet another from an electronics store. Again, the PROGRAMING IS VERY BUGGY. It will shut down over and over and over, til your cellphone battery dies. False call after false call after false call til your cellphone battery dies. When it is turned off, the alarm activates while you are walking around the house...Yes, until your cellphone battery dies. For days on end, I spent every free hour I had to get this piece of junk to stop sending false alarms, let me walk around the house without tripping...UGGGGG.\nDo yourself a favor, JUST DON'T PURCHASE THIS GARBAGE. If you did purchase this, PLUG IN YOUR CELLPHONE BECAUSE YOU WILL BE WORKING WITH THIS BUGGY PROGRAM FOR DAYS ON END!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 28, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings - Promising product that does NOT deliver. Not ready for production, too many design flaws...", "Text": "ST hubs are not ready for \"prime time\" (Production) and the v2 hub is worse than the v1 hub. Was starting to move devices over from v1 to v2 hub but have stopped due to very poor reliability, i.e. my Jasco outdoor appliance module would only respond 25% of the time on the v2 hub vs the v1 hub. And the v2 hub is still _very_ smartthings-cloud dependant despite the added battery. i.e. your home automation is down when your Internet connection is down. Living 9mile from town in Alaska, this is too often a problem. I'm seriously considering moving back to the MiCasaVera products which do not suffer this serious flaw. Yes, they have their own problems (less critical mass, smaller support base, etc...) but do not suffer this design flaw of cloud dependance. Other problems is poor support for security devices like deadbolts with keypads (No individual PINs, etc...). In general, I'm very disappointed with the ST environment and think that it will set back the IOT market acceptance due to their lack of insight."}
{"Author": "Sal Bashi", "Date": "on December 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect for home automation", "Text": "Worked well now after new updates. Waiting for more products to be added."}
{"Author": "H Winter", "Date": "on December 26, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Can be slow at times."}
{"Author": "K. Fagan", "Date": "on December 25, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect Control for Home Automation", "Text": "I've been on the home automation kick for a few years now, started with WeMo switches, added Philips Hue, added Amazon Echo and then got one of these. This is the one that controls them all.\n\nSo far the Smart Things hub and interface has been the perfect compliment to roping all of those together and making them talk to each other. The phone app is pretty easy to use, adds everything pretty seamlessly, letting you search for compatible devices by brand / name, so it's easy to find my philips / wemo devices.\n\nWith the hub, I've added motion sensors, and a few open/close sensors and they all work very well together. The app allows you to configure \"routines\" that allow the devices to interact with each other - example, turn on Philips Hue hallway lights when front door opens/closes.\n\nI feel like I'm only 20% into the capabilities of the Smart Things interface (haven't even touched creating \"modes\").\n\nUpon connection of my first device, I had a problem connecting to the hub, but Smart Things customer service was pretty quick in responding to me and it turns out that my device had been connected the whole time (I just never saw the confirmation).\n\nHighly recommend."}
{"Author": "AlohaCPU", "Date": "on December 24, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Potential, But its a no-go implimentation.", "Text": "I started off as a big believer with endless uses for this system. Setting up is a lot work if you have many devices, but I enjoy that sort of tinkering. When the system is working, you will have true home automation. Unfortunately the system is very unreliable, and it all stems from the hub. I have had the system for over 6 months now, it has worked reliably for less than half that time. One or all devices will fail to turn on or off at the appropriate times. I've followed all the manufacturers recommendations to no avail. The online forums have basically given up, the device is not reliable. Hopefully now that Samsung has bought the company, their engineering expertise will solve these problems. I've invested in a dozen devices (Switches and outlets), so the system isn't to large. Good luck if you invest in this product. Go read the forums before buying."}
{"Author": "SincLabs", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "UPDATED! - Garbage - This is not ready for prime time...", "Text": "I just had to update this review: This product not only doesn't work reliably, but it is also dangerous. I was very concerned originally with the way Samsung implemented their battery backup solution (rechargeable AA batteries). I still had my SmartThings hub plugged in, although I rarely use it anymore as I have and moved most of my smart home gear away from it. Last night at 2AM I heard this zapping/crackling sound. I just happened to have the SmartThings hub in my master bedroom where I had been testing it. Not the normal spot (closet). I got out of bed and immediately noticed the sound was coming from the SmartThings hub. I picked the hub up and turned it over only to find the rechargeable batteries leaking badly. This is supposed to be a product you setup and forget. This was not good. I removed the batteries and re-installed the battery cover. I left the hub plugged in as I was still testing it. About a half hour later I again heard the zapping/crackling sounds. I went back to the hub and unplugged it as it smelled and apparently had started smoking. I mean seriously folks... unplug this thing and throw it out. OLD REVIEW: Okay so let me just say that I was a big fan of the SmartThings platform. A huge fan prior to Samsung acquiring SmartThings. Sense Samsung has taken over the company I have had numerous issues that all started when I upgraded to the V2 hub from the V1 hub. The upgrade itself was actually more painful than it should have been. Sense this new hub has been online it has gone offline numerous times, mainly when I have been away. So with the hub offline and me away it is basically worthless. The entire reason I got this hub was to keep an eye on things when I am out. So its pointless at this point. I have to reboot it regularly. Now it rarely turns on the lights when it is supposed to. Presence sensing is also awful. Sense the device works off presence detection, again its got issues. I am really bummed about it and I am sad that I spent money on this. I was concerned once Samsung took over and my concerns have been validated. This is not ready for prime time."}
{"Author": "Brian J Lambert", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best home automation hub for the price, but still a work-in-progress", "Text": "The best hub on the market for its price range, but is still a work in progress. Great for automating simple home controls. This hub is a modest improvement over the 1st generation hub, but it makes it (relatively) simple to connect compatible devices and control them and get alerts.\n\nDIFFERENCE BETWEEN V1 & V2:\nThe design for V2 is slightly more boxy, but they are very similar in appearance. The new design allows it to hold 4 AA batteries for backup when power goes out (great for a security alarm, but most things that it connects to requires power, so this isn't a huge deal). The new hub is slightly faster, but more importantly, allows for [some] offline processing of events. The new hub also allows it to connect to some networked cameras, but I do not have any that are compatible, so I'll have to take their word on it.\n\nSETUP:\nSetup was simple enough with the free app on the App Store (works with iPhone and Android only, though. no iPad app or Windows app). Connect power & a wired network connection (no wifi). I plugged it in, it updated for about 5-10 minutes, and I could immediately start adding devices. When you add a device it brings some options to make them \"smart\", such as lighting controls to turn on lights when motion is detected or a door is opened.\n\nAPP & USE:\nThe SmartThings app is way over-complicated. It's been refined in the last year, but it needs another makeover to help simplify some things. I primarily use the Smart Lighting app to control lights. It works locally with supported devices, so it responds fast and will still turn on lights with motion even if the internet goes down. The SmartThings servers sometimes act up, but this hub helps keeps things running through minor hiccups. It also can push notifications when there is unexpected activity when away from home. The app breaks these different functions up to add clarity, but things get complicated really fast.\n\nDEVICES:\nI highly recommend investing in a few door contact sensors and a few motion sensors. In addition, add some compatible light bulbs or switches.\nBefore purchasing any devices, make sure they are listed on the SmartThings website as certified. You can also browse recommended devices from the app. There are a lot of great devices out there, and most (but not all) Z-wave and Zigbee devices will work, but just make sure. I use several zigbee lightbulbs (Osram, etc.), Z-wave motion and contact sensors, and a few Z-wave outlets in addition to a LIFX multi-color light bulb.\n\nSmartThings just added a 3rd party monitoring service that can call the police if there are intrusions detected by the hub. It's $20/month and could be handy if you use SmartThings as an alarm system. The service isn't necessary, but does help if you travel a lot and can't contact the police yourself. It doesn't cover fire alarms, but maybe they can add that in the future.\n\nPROS: Works with many devices. Performs some basic functions offline. Continual updates to add devices & features. Great online community resources.\n\nCONS: Complicated App. Expect some outages. Still overly-reliant on the cloud. Only works on iPhone (not iPad) and Android.\n\nBOTTOM LINE: I recommend this hub if you want to start automating your home and aren't afraid to tinker with devices and routines. It's pretty amazing when it works! You can have lights come on when you come home, walk into a room, or open a door. You'll get alerts when there's home activity when you're away and keep an eye on things at home."}
{"Author": "troymantha", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I still installed the backup batteries in the Smart Things Hub", "Text": "I ordered a brand new SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation and when it arrived I noticed that the 4 batteries that came with the unit were not sealed/packed. Anyway, I still installed the backup batteries in the Smart Things Hub, connected the power supply and hooked up the hub to my router.\nI then downloaded the Smart Things up in my mobile phone, created an account and continued to the setup. It then ask for a code which can easily be found inside the box. But when I type in the code, there was an error message \" code has been previously used \".\nIt just confirm my initial assumption that the unit that I paid for as new is actually a used one when I saw the battery not being sealed or packed. I decided to return it the next day."}
{"Author": "Genesys", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I Really, Really wanted to like this, but ....", "Text": "I Really, Really wanted to like this, but I've had some disappointments. First, this is a Samsung product now as apposed to a small startup company and I really expect more from Samsung.\n\nFirst, when you open the box, there is almost no documentation - barely enough to get it connected. After that, you have to figure out everything else on your own. The Menu is not intuitive. I've spent A LOT OF TIME trying to figure out where I need to go to get something done and then when I think I've got it, I'm still wrong. I have a Master's in Computer Science - it shouldn't be this hard to understand. Minimally, they should provide a template that shows you how to maneuver through the menu.\n\nYes, there is Support - sort of. If you go to their support page, they make you believe that there is Chat Support available - I've tried many times to have a \"CHAT\", but not a single time was I able to connect - always get a \"no one available\" message and now they are closed for the holidays. So you have to send them an email - response takes 2-???? days - I've had response in 2 days, but I have had some in for over 7 days and still no response. Not what I call good support.\n\nI've tried using my phone (Samsung Galaxy S4) and my wife's phone (Samsung Galaxy S3) as presence devices. All I can say, is that using your phone as a presence device is totally unreliable. It seems worse with my wife's phone than mine, but still not good. I get notified that I or my wife have arrived home when we're more than three miles away. You don't want to be turning on your lights, opening your garage, and unlocking your doors when your shopping at the grocery store or still at work. We have done everything that has been recommended by Support, but nothing really helps. I've checked our phone's gps and it sees us where we are, so I don't know how it could be reporting us home. Last week, we were 1200 miles away and it reported us as arriving home. I have not tried to use the Samsung Presence device yet to see if that works any better.\n\nOn the positive side, lighting using switches, remotes, and scenes work well. This was the primary purpose for us, so we are not too unhappy with this. We will be getting additional devices for motion and temperature sensing and I will provide updates as we go."}
{"Author": "Baka Woodworker", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "1st gen hub and SmartThings worked great. Very stable", "Text": "1st gen hub and SmartThings worked great. Very stable. 2nd gen (mostly ST, not the hub) is much less stable. Lights fail constantly and little, to no resolutions from SmartThing support (have a list of items that used to work, but no longer, including light switches...weeks of asking ST on status and no resolution or response). Would I still use/get ST? yes. Am I as happy with them as I was with 1st gen? NO"}
{"Author": "Eric Fishon", "Date": "on December 22, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wish I could give more stars", "Text": "I'm a total home gadget geek. Probably only time I will ever say geek. This assisted me in bringing home automation to its fullest potential. I'm able to use this for my wemo lights, lightifly, switches, and more. The price was about $99 when I purchased. Also another added benefit is their customer service. When you email them they get back to you quickly. There is also an entire online community to assist as well."}
{"Author": "alfleagle", "Date": "on December 20, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Run from this!!!!!", "Text": "When the system fails (and it will fail almost immediately), you can only email support; there is no one to talk to. Regardless of your problem they will tell you again and again, unplug, press the button, reattach. Of course when that hasn't worked for the last several weeks and they're still telling you to do it again and again and again and again... Well you get a little frustrated. I've spent over $600 on this system and I'm seriously considering throwing it all in the trash. The forums are full of people having the same problems and getting no technical support.\n\nActual email response:\n\nThis email is to notify you that we have created a support ticket for your request. We're very sorry but we may be a bit slower than usual getting back to you. We have a number of new and old users alike that have contacted us with questions. Between our new Hub, new mobile experience, and the tremendous excitement around what SmartThings is doing, we have a sizable backlog of requests. Our support team will do our best to get back to you as soon as possible but we humbly ask for your patience. If you have anything else you'd like to tell us, you can reply to this email. Otherwise, we'll be in touch as soon as we're able."}
{"Author": "bceddie", "Date": "on December 19, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time.", "Text": "Just an expensive toy. Purchased this to monitor a vacation home but the hub keeps turning off and there is no way to remotely reset. Without the hub communication it is worthless."}
{"Author": "Robert Hopkins", "Date": "on December 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buy! Buy! Buy! Home Automation made easy!!!", "Text": "Use smartthings for my home automation and it works like an absolute charm. I am fairly \"techie\" but would certainly not consider myself a tech guy by any means. Regardless, the setup through the app and pairing of devises has been extremely user friendly. I am learning new uses for this hub every single day. Samsung has provided an extremely helpful and supportive community to work on projects and ideas together. This thing just keeps on getting \"smarter\". If you are looking to dive into the world of home automation this is the hub for you. I just purchased an amazon echo which now has integration through ST and I can't wait to use them together."}
{"Author": "Christian", "Date": "on December 17, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You will eventually be disappointed", "Text": "At first this was incredible and it really made setting up a smart home very easy. Then the problems. At first the app would only work sporadically and had the inability to add my wife as a user. After a month or so that (included) feature finally started working. She (we) then started buying and adding new devices, switches and the like. Everything was fine until two days ago when all my wall switches stopped working with the hub. They are still connected to the hub and are visible in the app but they do not respond to input. I will also mention that they DO work when physically pressed on the wall. After two days of removing the switches, resetting the hub, adding the switches back, leaving the breaker switch off all night (as per a recommendation in their support forums), I can no longer add the switches back easily or at all and when they do reconnect they will not respond to any app commands.\n\nMy next step was to use the built in \"Support Chat\" feature in the app. As soon as I tapped on the chat link I got a message saying the chat is not available and I should email support. Why the heck in that in your app if it is not usable? So I went online to the chat feature that imposes itself on you whenever you go to the forums. I open it up and I am able to enter my question. I do. I got the same \"chat support is not available\" message as soon as I hit send. Again, why have that feature if it is not usable.\n\nSo now, frustrated beyod belief, I email support with my questions. I get this response:\n\n\"We're very sorry but we may be a bit slower than usual getting back to you. We have a number of new and old users alike that have contacted us with questions. Between our new Hub, new mobile experience, and the tremendous excitement around what SmartThings is doing, we have a sizable backlog of requests. Our support team will do our best to get back to you as soon as possible but we humbly ask for your patience. If you have anything else you'd like to tell us, you can reply to this email. Otherwise, we'll be in touch as soon as we're able.\"\n\nSo my product that this company says does \"x\" no longer does \"x\", and after my due diligence to restore \"x\" they are unable to help me fix it. I can still open my garage door and turn on my lights and all the other things this product was supposed to handle for me, but I have spent several hundreds of dollars and am beyond frustrated just to be where I started before I got this product.\n\nIt is a rushed product that seems not ready to be in the market and it does not have the support infrastructure to handle the issues caused by early release."}
{"Author": "Mark D.", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pro-level automation at a 'starter' price", "Text": "WHOA! This thing is great! I work for a high-end home automation company so I'm pretty well versed in the Home Automation category. Been using Philips Hue with Echo for a quick and dirty HA solution in an apartment. (Our 'pro-level' gear requires installation so it's not really apartment-friendly.) Well while I thought the future was great using Echo to say 'Alexa, turn on my bedroom lights' and it worked, no phone app required, adding in the SmartThings hub opened up custom programming and even more device capability! This kit can do some *real* home automation! Not just simple on/off or basic rules, but you can actually write small programs (called SmartApps) in the Groovy programming language (think a subset of Java) and do some really crazy stuff! Out of the box it's great. Add in the custom programming and it's amazing. (I just wish their phone app was better, but considering I only use it to configure my system, then use my voice with the Echo to actually control it, I don't mind.\n\nBuy this. You won't regret it!"}
{"Author": "Aerin", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It is easy to use and in general works great", "Text": "I purchased this from Samsung directly because amazon was out of stock. It is easy to use and in general works great. The android app could be laid out a bit better but isn't bad. My only serious complaint so far is that whenever you connect a new device it asks if you would like to also install a related smartapp. Installing the smartapp almost always crashes the program and sometimes you have to add the new device again. If they were third party apps I would be a bit more forgiving, but they are apps written by Smartthings."}
{"Author": "Jim C", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Returned it. Doesn't work with the products I was led to believe without solid programming skills."}
{"Author": "C H H Family", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for making the house more \"user\" friendly", "Text": "Great for making the house more \"user\" friendly. We were able to set up several lights on this system and plan to had our garage door opener to it. It was easy to install and the app on the phone is super easy to use."}
{"Author": "S.B.", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great purchase. It has its issues but the overall ...", "Text": "Great purchase. It has its issues but the overall functionality of the hub is better than my previous automation hubs. Support is very responsive and the ST community is full of great information."}
{"Author": "Stewart H", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's nice when it works but too many bugs and issues", "Text": "It's nice when it works but too many bugs and issues. Given it's lake of stability, I'd consider the current software, particularly Samsung's own SmartApps to be a Beta at best. The automations don't always work. It frequently complains that I'm having network issues when everything else is fine. I haven't tried writing my own IFFT scripts yet but I may have to given the unreliability of Samsung's. Give it a year to mature (hopefully.)"}
{"Author": "Jesus Caraballo", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "ST-Samsung Review/Opinion", "Text": "Since this product came out to the market I never thought the possibilities to have it. Thinking on home automation to make our lives more simple and very easy in some many aspects (Because time is money and life) I tried to look into the different solutions to give more sense to our new home. When compare this hub with many other is obvious that the cloud was a big issue and still is when you check the reviews everywhere over the internet, too many problems associated to this system is making my mind change over the opinion I had in the beginning.\n\nI recently acquired three Lifx Light Bulbs which are very smart and well done product in my personal opinion, these smart bulbs have the capability to be integrated to the smarting hub, however I have not seen any reaction since my hub controlling at all these devices and when compare with the Vera controller or in major scale the Fibaro Controller the ST hub never made react my devices as programmed with the iPhone app. I have gone through the ST help and support, blog, Developer community and so on.\n\nIf you are thinking more about autonomy then I think is better get the Vera controller for the same price or Fibaro controller as a very expensive option, thats the Ferrari of the Home Automation Controller."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Set-up was fairly easy and took 30min", "Text": "Set-up was fairly easy and took 30min. The app could really be improved - it is not very clear or friendly to use. To unleash the full potential of this system you need to invest in quite a lot of different 'things'. The starter kit is extensive.\nI have set-up an open/close and motion sensor , which should call/text me when intrusion is detected, but this never worked unfortunately."}
{"Author": "J. Overton", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My experience with Smart Things overall has been dismal", "Text": "My experience with Smart Things overall has been dismal, depressing and extremely frustrating. Smart Things continues to suffer from a confusing user interface, timeout issues, cloud connection outages and in a word a \"buggy\" solution.\n\nIt just does not seem to be ready for prime time, don't get me wrong I REALLY wanted to like Smart Things and as much as I tried I just couldn't. While it does have potential and at times can work well, it's really hard to have any confidence in a product that seems to work on a part time basis.\n\nOh and let's talk about support ... not sure what their issue is, however Smart things support is poor to marginal and at times very unresponsive, As I write this review (12/14/15) I am still awaiting a response from Smart Things support on a number of issues that I continue to experience (it has been a week and a half). I find the lack of responsiveness and unanswered emails unacceptable and has forced me to return the Smart Things hub to Amazon before I exceed the return window.\n\nSmart Things may be fine if you don't mind writing scripts in \"Groovy\", tinkering with device settings and dealing with a questionable cloud interface, however if you're looking for more of a reliable platform with a simple user interface and responsive technical support then you may want to wait until this solution matures."}
{"Author": "Michael McGrath", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Has potential but it has become completely unreliable lately", "Text": "I can't go a day anymore without something failing to turn on or turn off which completely defeats the purpose of home automation. My setup isn't even all that complicated either. The company has been releasing patches regularly to combat this instability but so far nothing has helped. Save your money and some frustration and look elsewhere for now."}
{"Author": "Prime", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Awesome"}
{"Author": "hazim JA Batwah", "Date": "on December 13, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "the best in the market but need to improove compatibilty with things."}
{"Author": "J. Meran", "Date": "on December 13, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far it seems to work just fine. Their tech support is great", "Text": "I went with SmartThings because of the Samsung affiliation. So far it seems to work just fine. Their tech support is great. The internet of Things will get a lot better but it still has a loooong way to go. IoT seems to be where PC's were in 1990. I think Samsung/SmartThings will be the leader."}
{"Author": "Nexus Nerd", "Date": "on December 13, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Would be just ok if not for the developer option", "Text": "There app and open development is what sells this for me. I currently have this integrated with my Nest thermostat and Protect and hopefully soon with my Nest Cam. Along with my Nest products I am running My Q garage door, light switches and a Z wave deadbolt. A little pain to integrate everything but follow the tutorials and you will be fine. Would be five stars if it was s little easier to integrate everything."}
{"Author": "DFS3", "Date": "on December 13, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Clunky UI, Poor Connectivity.", "Text": "I really wanted to like this unit. I pre ordered it and waited patiently for it. I found it to be extremely buggy and had issues connecting to some of my devices. I ended up having to ship it back and I'm still waiting for some sort of solution that is all encompassing but lacks many of the bugs that this unit had. I'm keeping an eye on some of the nest thermostat compatibility that's coming out with some of the devices later on this year or next year. I was really hoping when Samsung bought this company that it would breathe some new life into it and fix many of the issues but it looks like maybe they tried too hard and failed miserably. The interface for the app on your phone is terrible clunky and really not very intuitive."}
{"Author": "Steve B", "Date": "on December 12, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A great idea that\u2019s just not ready for prime time", "Text": "A great idea that\u2019s just not ready for prime time. On December 11th there was a widespread issue that made hubs lock-up, requiring a manual push-the-little-recessed button kind of reset. After this reset, several of my devices (temp and water leak sensor, outlets) are no longer working. ST support has yet to offer a solution.\n\nIf you like to tinker with stuff or you live alone, maybe this kind of failure is tolerable. However, when your spouse has to pull the couch out just to manually push a little button on a so-called \u201csmart outlet\u201d to turn the lights on, it doesn\u2019t bode well.\n\nAbsent some major upgrade, I very strongly suggest that this hub shouldn\u2019t be used in a remote vacation house, in any security application, at an elderly parent\u2019s house, or in any situation where there isn\u2019t a technically-inclined person available.\n\nMobile apps and cloud are great things, but until the web & computer folks learn a lesson from old-school HVAC and hard-wire electrical folks about reliability,, IoT and home automation will be stuck in the realm of the tinkerers."}
{"Author": "D. Weeks", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Without reliability, it is only useful as a toy or hobby", "Text": "Sadly, at the time of this review (Dec '15), this isn't a reliable system for home automation -- yet. A system like this needs to be stable and resilient enough to be left alone for extended periods of time without physical intervention. Especially if you are using it for security or as an alarm system (they just announced an add-on for alarm monitoring service). Well, a few days ago, SmartThings had a problem that caused many user hubs, including mine, to go offline. A hard reboot by pressing a button on the hub is the only way to bring it back online. Unfortunately, I'm away from home for another month and will be unable to do that reset so I am assuming all my \"things\" are stuck in the state they were in at the time of the problem. My outdoor lights are on 24x7, I have no ability to monitor the security and conditions of my building, nor do I have the ability to operate door locks remotely for visitors. Customer service says they are working on a firmware for the unit that might have a watchdog or other abilities to reboot to get back online so I may wait to fully implement my system until that is available. Because really... this type of system is only a toy if you can't rely on using it remotely as it was designed."}
{"Author": "Andrew W", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great idea, Great user community, Poor reliability and Tech Support", "Text": "I purchased this direct from SmartThings (ST) in August '15, and received September '15. I felt it necessary to leave a review of my experiences so far as a warning to others looking for an automation solution.\n\nI am currently using this with a ST motion sensor, a Cree Connected bulb, and a Schlage deadbolt. I've held off in investing in more devices until I know for sure the hub works reliably. For me, it is installed in my home, but I would warn on setting up somewhere remote or a vacation home as it sometimes goes offline and needs to be manually reset. When it works, it works great, there are built in apps and routines to create many automated processes. There is also a great deal of community lead support with custom apps, device types not officially supported yet, and troubleshooting. Without the community support, this item would be very difficult to use. ST/Samsung tech support on this product has been very slow, and difficult to get answers to issues.\n\nAll in all, it is a fun product, but I don't personally feel comfortable relying on it for anything beyond \"fun\" automation. I also can't justify the cost of adding to the system a great deal until it more reliable."}
{"Author": "lgkahn", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub is good when it works", "Text": "Hub is good when it works.\nGoes offline, no remote reboot in certain cases. will need wifi switch or to goto remote location.\nMuch power and flexibility.\nNot yet stable.. HAve to muck with it daily to get reliable routines etc.\nCannot in good faith recommend yet as it is just not stable enough.\nA shame really, as it has a lot of possibilities."}
{"Author": "Samuel H.", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Are you tech savvy? Do you hate Bluetooth?", "Text": "Unless you're pretty tech savvy, I wouldn't recommend getting this hub...yet. If you are capable of basic troubleshooting and willing to put some time in, this will work out great for you. Issues are being dealt with a little slow from the manufacturer's support team, but this hub has come a long way since the release date. I expect even more big changes soon as Samsung has announced that they are planning on shipping new tv sets with an integrated smartthings hub. Hopefully that will push them to put additional support and programming resources on the smartthings team. I love my hub and what it's capable of, however I wouldn't give one to my parents or expect my non techie wife to be able to set it up.\n\n*****Update 11/17*****\nIn spite of many updates and overall better reliability and usability, I'm going to reduce my rating from 4 stars to 3 due to lack of support from smartthings one of the promised features. Still no Bluetooth and it's \"not a priority\"? Wtf?! This thing is advertised as having a Bluetooth radio...and technically it does, but it has not activated literally YEARS after launch. Imagine buying a truck with an advertised 4wd system except there is no way to activate it. Great, the system is there but now I'm stuck in the mud because you won't turn the feature on and support it. So frustrating. Smartthings needs to hire more support or at least make good on their promised features. To be honest, I wouldn't be surprised if someone filed a lawsuit in the future."}
{"Author": "Scott", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Conceptually this is a good product, but.....", "Text": "Samsung is trying to drive cell phone revenue by only allowing it to be configured from a cell phone. I hate to be forced to upgrade my cell phone to the latest release of Android or iOS just because of home automation. There are no certified IP66 outside cameras available for this product either. There are allot of choices in Home Automation that allow flexibility in setting up the system without having the latest cell phone."}
{"Author": "Robert Teichman", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lots of fun automating my house with this", "Text": "Lots of fun automating my house with this. Very flexible in that you can program it to do just about anything."}
{"Author": "Doug W", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not reliable enough to use an alarm", "Text": "I read a whole lot of reviews before settling on the SmartThings 2nd Gen Hub. I wanted something that would provide a basic alarm system and do some home automation. I think I got it about half right.\n\nI'm new to home automation, but I've been playing with this for about two months now. I've got four door sensors, a motion detector, a switch, and an alarm.\n\nIf you want an alarm system that you can depend on, this isn't it. Today is a case in point. I forgot to disarm off the alarm when I came home. I didn't get a blaring alarm, I got total silence. It was a few minutes before this clicked. I checked, and the alarm was still \"armed.\"\n\nThe hub has done this several times since I've had it. It just seems to lose touch with sensors, but it isn't aware that it has done so. My entry door was still showing that it was \"closed\" while I held it wide open. I checked and found that another one of my four doors was also just lost. (I can tell that our primary door was connected earlier today, but the other door may have been down for quite some time.)\n\nWhen the hub has lost its way before, I've taken out the batteries and unplugged it, and it has reconnected with the sensors. That didn't work today. No, its not that they are too far from the hub (or it shouldn't be). One of the lost doors is about 10 feet away. So, I can google this and hunt around ... that isn't how I'd like to spend my time.\n\nIn addition to losing contact with sensors, the hub has just plain lost its way. We got a 4:00 am text last week telling us the hub was offline -- our Internet connection wasn't.\n\nIf the light that we have hooked up to our motion sensor doesn't click on, we just walk over and flip the switch. (That does work most of the time and is nice.) If your alarm doesn't come on when someone breaks into your house while you're asleep in your room, that's another story. That, unfortunately, is the SmartThings story.\n\nI'd like to say that I have a better recommendation, but I don't. All I have right now is this system that I really wish I could recommend, but I can't. My advice is to keep looking. Let me know what you find."}
{"Author": "Jarrod", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A DumbThing thats full of bugs", "Text": "So many bugs...\n\nI just picked this thing up a few weeks ago and could not be more disappointed. Out of the box things barely work. You have to fiddle with the scripts online to get simple automation going. If your not a programmer then you don't have a prayer at getting any of this working. After I got things setup the way I wanted them using 7 Z Wave devices things would go to crap. First devices would stop sending statuses (I am trying to monitor power usage), the door sensors would register as never being closed, and then last but not least the dumbthing would go offline even though the internet is up.\n\nThe last straw was with the presence features. You can only add ONE iphone. I went to add my wifes tonight and the app kept saying this phone was already added. The only phone in the system is mine and not hers.\n\nI really wanted this thing to work and really had hopes for it but alas its going back to Amazon. Thank god for their great return policy!"}
{"Author": "spouse of knitter", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unable to conect to the hub on 2 of the 3 days I've owned the hub.", "Text": "I've had the hub three days. On two of those days the hub spent most of the evening \"offline\" due to smartthings server issues. The first time I had to 'press the red button' to reboot the hub, tonight it is once again not responding.\n\nWhen it is up - I've been able to easily connect several z wave outlets, and GE smart bulb and the Android app is good. But all this is moot if I can't connect to my hub.\n\nI'll update this review if things get any better - but for now I assume that \"smart things\" refers only to their hardware."}
{"Author": "Matt K Atlanta", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Updates have dramatically improved hub", "Text": "Worked for two months now shows as offline. Tried to contact support via email and chat no response. I'd recommend waiting for a more reliable option before building out your iot network.\n\n***update*** Updates have significantly improved the reliability and overall performance of the Hub. Different product (much better) at this point than what was originally purchased."}
{"Author": "C. Kelly", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Things kit working great", "Text": "Just got the Smart Things kit. Very easy to power up, link the various devices and get it all going. Day 2 and everything is working just as expected. Set up some text alerts to go my cell. Very effective when combined with custom audio alerts on my cell. Started to get into some more advanced logic and got speedy and great online IM support from Eric."}
{"Author": "Ted M.", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This device is life-changing! It makes daily routines much ...", "Text": "This device is life-changing! It makes daily routines much simpler, and just feels all-around magical."}
{"Author": "Gretchen Helterhoff", "Date": "on December 10, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't Waste Your Money or Your Time, Doesn't Work Consistently !", "Text": "Purchased on September 14th, and already the unit is nonfunctional. As of three days ago, none of the automations function, whether triggered manually or via triggers. Even the individual devices will no longer function unless I press the physical On/Off button on the device itself. Statuses no longer update in the app, and logging is constantly inaccurate. Reboot of the device, rebuilding of devices/automations, and other troubleshooting merely results in a few days of functionality followed by repeated failures. Add to all this, Smartthings will take the unit/app down (without prior notice) for upgrade and break my devices/automations, and during which time the hub is down and does not function at all (read: no security, no logging, huge gap!).\n\nNote that all I'm using this for currently is to monitor departure/arrival of an iPhone, and turning on/off two plug-in modules to control Christmas lights. Since nothing works consistently, I'm terrified for the people who might rely on this for door locks, smoke alarms, cameras, motion, or other true-security-system functions.\n\nI'm very upset that this is clearly a manufacturer defect, but I'm not eligible for a return beyond 30 days (?). I guess I'll be selling this for a loss, and going back to my previous Z-Wave hub. I hated the other interface worse than Smartthings' app, but at least there was a corresponding website interface, and nothing *ever* broke or stopped working.\n\nUpdate 12/10/2015\nSent in Support ticket to request refund. I can buy multiple (working) light-timers with all that money!\n\nUpdate 12/15/2015\nOn my sixth day of having an open ticket with Support, and I've received no response beyond the automated \"we're too busy\" email back on the 10th."}
{"Author": "Marshall M", "Date": "on December 9, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Finally, everything is working", "Text": "Updated 12/22/15 - looked on the forums and saw it was finally working for some people - maybe it got an update or something and suddenly I could add all Z wave devices and all was right in the world. But the lack of customer response is the reason for 3 stars - at least let the people who own the products know what's going on.\n\nUpdated: 12/20/15 - After leaving this review the company promptly got back to me and went though some trouble shooting. Was told there may be issues with customers with Verizon FIOS with the router/hub. I was able to get into my firewall and open the ports. After not getting it to work the company sent me a new hub to ensure it I didn't get a bad hub. I got a package with a few smartthings 2 sensors, 1 motion sensor and an outlet. I was able to get the hub up and running and even got the outlets and sensors working - the motion sensor was broken in the package (the piece to connect to the battery had fallen off (not a good soldering job). I found out that these are not Z-wave devices, but Zee-bee or something different. So I guess its kind of working but not for what I need it for. I bought this and the light switches because it said it would work together and I wanted my lights automated for when I leave to visit family for the holidays - guess that won't be happening.\n\nOriginal review: It is currently a white brick with a green light. I bought the hub and 7 GE smart on/off paddle switches (zwave) to work with the hub. Got them all installed to automate my outdoor lights from sunset to sunrise (nothing crazy), so now I have expensive manual switches since the hub refuses to work. I emailed customer support 2 days ago and got an automated response. I have spent the past 2 days researching and trying to get it to work, not exactly how I would like to spend my time off. BEWARE!"}
{"Author": "Brad RV", "Date": "on December 9, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Have not had any issues pairing any devices so far ...", "Text": "Have not had any issues pairing any devices so far. I did need to reset the hub once but has been working flawlessness every sense. I am currently using it with Schlage locks and GE switches."}
{"Author": "David Tr", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "New Single Feature welcome between v1 and v2 hub, but migration process from a V1 hub is worse than non-existant", "Text": "Converting from V1 hub to V2 hub process doesn't exist. No, let me correct that...the process is delete every automation, task, location, device and other configuration from your account. Delete the old hub. Then start like you're a new Smartthings user.\n\nUSB ports, non-functional at launch\nBluetooth, non-functional at launch\nVideo capabilities, non-functional at launch\nIPv6, No.\nRead about all the other things you can't do right now with the \"new\" stuff: http://docs.smartthings.com/en/latest/sept-2015-faq.html\n\nBasically the only thing you get right now from a v1 to v2 hub upgrade is a working smarthome when the internet is out.\n\nPossibilities look promising, I guess only the future will tell if anything will come of it."}
{"Author": "Grizzly", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Complete waste of money", "Text": "Here is my experience with the Smart Things Hub over the past 6 months. I'll also note that I have only used devices that are on their website as approved so they should be expected to work properly.\n\nIf you are buying this for anything that needs to be reliable like controlling water, controlling temperature, security system, or anything that needs to work reliably while you are on vacation - DON'T. Here is why:\n\nThe hub itself has had issues which require a physical reset. There was not way to access the hub remotely so I had to physically disconnect the power to reset it. This would be impossible if you are trusting this system to work while you are away traveling.\n\nThe motion sensor did not trigger all the time so there was a good chance someone could go by it and it wouldn't trip the security alert. I got rid of that sensor.\n\nThe lights have worked pretty well from what I know. The major problem is that the way the system meshes together, if one of the light switches goes down, other devices stop working too. Even if those devices should be able to see the hub directly without using the other device as a repeater. This wouldn't be as bad if the app actually showed the correct status. It seems that with the app, it sends the command to turn a light on, changes the displayed status to \"on\", but never verifies if the switch actually turned on. The app can't be relied on to tell you the actual status of your devices. I'm still having this problem to this day.\n\nThese issues do seem to pretty common after reading through the forums. For the price it probably isn't bad. It does work decent for doing some basic things if you can accept they may not always work as expected.\n\nI needed to move my hub to a different room, which is actually much closer to my existing devices. Of course everything stopped working when I did this. I tried to do the z-wave network repair to get things working again and all my devices are still completely unresponsive."}
{"Author": "Randy Webb", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing Security System and Home Automation Hub", "Text": "I searched for a year for the right home security system and this is it. It does everything and more than any other system if you are tech savvy. The potential of this hub is almost unlimited. I armed my entire house with it and I haven't even scratched the surface of what this hub is capable of. So happy with it. What's amazing about it is how compatible it is with other manufacturer's items. So awesome. I'd recommend this to anyone who understands electronics and computers."}
{"Author": "Chris C.", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love having a smart house.", "Text": "I was on the Lowes Iris system but they have gotten all crazy with fees. You have to pay in order to be able to smart schedule anything with Iris now. SO I jumped ship the the smartthings platform. The Iris specific devises dont work with the smartthings hub but it is compatible with so much more sensors and switches.\n\nSmartthings has some work to do on user permissions and hopefully a web interface but it works well. You must have a smart phone or tablet in order to configure the hub and add new devices right now. There are some smart apps that will allow you to control your house over a web browser though so make sure to look into those. The best one so far is called Smart Tiles. Have fun and happy automating."}
{"Author": "dcengr", "Date": "on December 7, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great way to gain security and peace of mind", "Text": "I purchased this hub after reading about smart smoke detectors that can warn me when I'm away. I have two cats and when I leave them for a few days, I want to make sure they are protected. I have a few foscams, but I can't stare at them 24/7! Smartthings found the smoke detector right away and I had no problems pairing with it. The door sensor I purchased also paired seamlessly. I had some problems getting 2 GE link bulbs to work, but after browsing the forums, it turned out to be a WIFI interference from my router. After I shut off the 2.4 GHz signal and turned off remaining WIFI devices in the room, the light bulbs paired immediately. I have now moved the hub away from the router and so far so good. It was pretty simple to program my hub to turn the lights on at sunset, turn them off at a set time when I'm away. It arms itself when I leave, and disarms when I arrive home via my smart phone. I now get a door open signal when the cat sitter arrives when I am on vacation so that I can use my foscam to view them playing with the cats. I plan on hooking up my automated irrigation system with a remote outlet so that I can not only program the watering schedule, but activate it remotely on demand. I also have a 3D printer that I leave unattended, which is considered somewhat dangerous because of the nozzle temperature being 250C. But with the smoke detector and remote power switch, I can program the hub to turn the power off on the 3D printer if it detects smoke or if the print job goes bad so I don't waste more filament (I also have an IP camera staring at the print job).\n\nFor what it costs, with no monthly fees, this device is on my list as one of the most useful gadgets to come to market."}
{"Author": "Mark L.", "Date": "on December 7, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Previous VeraLite User", "Text": "I've only installed the SmartThings Hub for 1 day and I'm very impressed. I've had the VeraLite for the past couple of years. It's been rock solid, but I've always felt like the mobile app was clunky. ST was built with mobile users in mind. I was actually surprised when I found out that the majority of the configuration was done on the mobile phone.\n\nI had several Z-Wave devices already installed for use with my Vera system. I had to remove the devices from my Vera and then install to the ST system. It was so much nicer not having to carry around the Vera hub and just use my Samsubg cell phone to add devices. The ST paired with all of my Z-Wave devices.\n\nI was able to get all of my previous scenes in place except for a couple which are a bit more complex. The great thing is that the developer community is just as strong for ST as Vera.\n\nOne of the things that pushed me to get the SmartThings hub was the ability to integrate it with Amazon Echo. I'm looking forward to do that as soon as I get it."}
{"Author": "TobycW", "Date": "on December 7, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great", "Text": "The Samsung SmartThings Hub was easy to setup and functions like I want it to. I bought Jasco/GE Z-wave wall switches and a dimmer to control overhead ceiling lights, the ceiling fan and my fireplace. Very easy to setup and works great with the Samsung SmartThings app on my Iphone. Additionally, communication is excellent with Harmony Elite remote/hub. Looks like you can do a lot with this Hub.\n\nRecommended."}
{"Author": "Derek R Getsla", "Date": "on December 6, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Support is very slow if you need them.", "Text": "Update: After about 2 weeks, support finally got the update to my hub to make it functional.\n\nGot this as a gift, so I was unable to personally return it. My hub would not pair with any device. I tried several SmartThings branded devices and WeMo devices. I contacted support and they assured me it was just a firmware update that needed to be sent to the unit by them. After about 3 emails (they have no phone number) they stopped writing. I have a hub that is defective and support is just ignoring me. Just something to think about if you have any issues with this product."}
{"Author": "Luy", "Date": "on December 4, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so great. I'm moving over from a VeraLite and am ...", "Text": "So far so great. I'm moving over from a VeraLite and am instantly impressed.\n\nAll of the gear i had already purchased worked out of the box. The interface is much much simpler to use than the Vera and the app is pretty stable.\n\nOne of my favorite things about this was the amazon echo integration, there's something extra nerdy about telling alexa to turn on the christmas tree before she reads the news :)\n\nOverall I'm impressed but will be returning here to write a more in depth review as i've used the system for a little bit longer."}
{"Author": "Kevin Zimmerman", "Date": "on December 4, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An Expensive Trap Designed for Those with Disposable Income and Disposable Time.", "Text": "The Samsung SmartThings Hub is a terrible product. However, the Samsung SmartThings Hub is one of those very SPECIAL terrible products, that manages to make me feel as furious and disgusted with myself as I am with it. I knew when I ordered it that it was just a stupid, douche-ey toy, designed for nerdy types with disposable income and a certain amount of patience for fiddling with settings and macros and apps, etc.\n\nBut it is SO flakey, peripherals are SO difficult to get to work properly, the app is SO poorly designed, and \"customer support\" from Samsung is a giant brick wall. No phone number. No chat. Just an email address with an automated reply that goes unanswered.\n\nIt makes me feel dirty that I even considered spending $100 on this in the first place. The whole idea was to have all my holiday lights tied together, interior and exterior, and how that would be fun and my kids would be enthralled, and then after the holidays I'd come up with more fun things to automate, etc. But it just. Doesn't. Work.\n\nSo, like my father, and his father before him, I shall turn on my lights with an old-fashioned mechanical timer. And instead of pounding away at some stupid app, I shall use that extra time to play with my children, and enjoy looking at our twinkly lights."}
{"Author": "SMO", "Date": "on December 4, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Reliable and responsive.", "Text": "I started off with a Wink hub and wasn't happy with the lack of reliability. At least weekly my GE Link lights would unpair and I had to go through a tiresome routine to get them paired again.\n\nDecided to dump the Wink and migrate everything over to SmartThings and I'm happy that I did. No problem whatsoever keeping everything paired and the response time for lights to switch on/off is much improved. Integrates seamlessly with the Amazon Echo.\n\nThe app seems fairly well organized and easy to navigate. Really looking forward to building my system using this hub."}
{"Author": "steven caudill", "Date": "on December 4, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great", "Text": "only had a issue with it once but has been working sence."}
{"Author": "Vay Vong", "Date": "on December 3, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Having been on the smartthings system for awhile now, ...", "Text": "Having been on the smartthings system for awhile now, I am ready to cancel my ATT Digital Life subscription. I started with other products at first where capabilities and integration was limited. I actually could have saved some money if I started with smartthings system first. It offers so much flexibility on the range of product that can work with the HUB. I am looking forward to deeper integration with Nest as the company does have plan to improve on that. Even with that, I would still choose this product over and over again.\n\nOn top of that , their support team would go above and beyond for you. True story with my recent request to their support team."}
{"Author": "Renata", "Date": "on December 3, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Create scheduled smart apps that turn every light off", "Text": "Works as advertised and more. Only thing to have in mind if you live in a place that suffers power blackouts and use add-ons such as bulbs, when power comes back the bulb will lit and system will have it registered as off. Quick fix: Create scheduled smart apps that turn every light off."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Our \"Smart Home\" is Getting D\u0336u\u0336m\u0336b\u0336e\u0336r\u0336 Smarter by the Day", "Text": "UPDATED (June 21, 2016) REVIEW:\nAfter much frustration in late 2015 and early 2016, I have to update my review again (I've gone from 1 star to 3 stars, and now to 5 stars).\n\nOver the past few months, our entire SmartThings hub and ecosystem has been performing nearly-flawlessly. Kudos to the SmartThings team for all of the firmware updates and capacity upgrades. They are obviously improving the system dramatically. Things just work now and I don't have to even think about it. I've got my fingers crossed that these improvements will last.\n\nORIGINAL REVIEW:\nAfter a few months of successful testing with the v1 hub, I decided to go all-in with Smartthings over the past few months. I've now invested over $1800 in devices and migrated everything to the v2 hub. Everything seemed to begin going downhill once I switched to the 2nd gen. hub.\n\nSmartthings has always had its quirks, but over the past few weeks it has gotten so bad that it has become a complete nuisance. The biggest issue by far is that routines are failing constantly. We woke up this morning to a cold house (the thermostat failed to trigger), a dark house (all the lights failed to trigger), and a blaring alarm when opening the door (the alarm failed to disarm). When we arrived home, I hit the \"I'm Home\" routine and again the alarms sounded upon entering for reasons unknown and the house was dark.\n\nAt this point I'm ready to find our 20 year-old Honeywell programable thermostat, go back to timers with dials on the lights, and fire up the ancient ADT alarm system again. Things were much easier and worked much better the good old-fashioned way. I've actually managed to dumb-down our house with Smartthings.\n\nSmartthings would be great if things worked as they're supposed to work, but I'm finding myself spending hours in the forums each day and reprogramming routines trying to troubleshoot all the issues. It's cause for great celebration if a day without problems. It's just not worth it anymore. Time to pull the plug on Smartthings and hope some other miracle hub comes along to take advantage of all the Zigbee and Z-wave devices we've accumulated."}
{"Author": "Derreck Albers", "Date": "on December 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Mandatory for Everyone!", "Text": "I feel like they should mandate the installation of the SmartThings hub in every home purchase, or just make it mandatory like ObamaCare, the world would be a better place!"}
{"Author": "Craig Robson", "Date": "on December 2, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "It works"}
{"Author": "SB", "Date": "on December 2, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A neat toy with great potential.", "Text": "I have been using SmartThings for nearly two years. I own both the original hub and the new hub. This is one of the most flexible platforms on the market today. It can do a lot of tricks with your lights, AV equipment and security of your home. You can basically transform your home into a database and run macros to perform desired actions, from turning lights on, when certain events happen in or around your home, to changing the temperatures on your thermostats when it gets too cold or too hot. It can open the garage door as you approach your home, it can unlock the doors when you arrive. The things you can have this little box do, are limited only by your imagination!"}
{"Author": "mike", "Date": "on December 1, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great light and appliance controller.", "Text": "Works great after following instructions to activate with outlets. Have in house in the Catskills and I control lights and appliances from my house in NJ. Very easy to set up and has worked well.\nUPDATE 4/6/2018--Samsung fixing things that aren't broken and causing issues, like they have done with the SmartCam software. After using two installations for a few years, they updated the software that has resulted in more outages and a change in the software to not notify you when the HUB is back on. You will be told it is off. Customer service is responsive, but the system engineers are totally disconnected from customer focused needs. ."}
{"Author": "Logan D.", "Date": "on December 1, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Product was useless to me due to the extremely slow poll times(Displaying ...", "Text": "Product was useless to me due to the extremely slow poll times(Displaying whether device on or off), also there was huge delays at times when turning lights on or off, sometimes up to 5 minutes; obviously this makes the system pointless.\n\nSmartthings uses their own servers to control devices in your home that is why there is lag, basically if their servers get busy your product doesn't work.\n\nI have switched to Homeseer which I highly recommend, everything runs locally and the granular configurations available are leaps and bounds above smartthings."}
{"Author": "Mark", "Date": "on November 29, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works perfectly and set up was fast.", "Text": "After seeing what my cousin did with his Echo and SmartThings I had to follow his lead. Had Echo up and running a month ago and now added the Smart Thing hub and a couple of switches. Since I already have a network hub in the family room, connecting the network port was quick and easy. Getting my Android phone to configure the SmartThings hub was also very easy. I then added the switches and the only glitch was I forgot to tap the first switch paddle to let the hub find it. Once I did that it was up and running. You do have to remember to export devices to Amazon Echo. I guess that's a security feature to let you restrict Echo's access to some devices. Now adding a Z-Wave switch to control the front door lights and a Z-Wave light bulb to allow remote control over at least one light in the living room.\n\nAs I wasn't coming from the 1st generation hub I did not experience the deregistration problems that others have."}
{"Author": "Michael Burnstein", "Date": "on November 29, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm a fan", "Text": "I started with a Z-wave lock for my front door (Schlage). From there I bought a Nexia bridge. I would not get the bridge to pair with the door. I talked to the Nexia customer service and they let me know my unit was defective and they sent me a new one. That one would not work either. So I looked for alternatives. The samsung smarthub had the best reviews and so I bought it. It was ridiculously easy to set up, especially compared to the Nexia bridge. Download the app (I have an iPhone), follow the instructions, done. I liked it so much that I ordered another samsung device -- the door sensor. It attaches to the door and if someone opens it while you are away. Again, super easy to set up and configure. Took literally 3 minutes. As you can see, I'm a fan. My understanding is that this is the most future-proof of the current options too."}
{"Author": "Jeff W.", "Date": "on November 29, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome!", "Text": "This thing is great! It controls my lights and works like a champ. SmartThings is great about providing information and updates."}
{"Author": "Justin", "Date": "on November 28, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Had a hard time connecting any of my connect locks ...", "Text": "Had a hard time connecting any of my connect locks and smoke alarms. Mine worked for a week until it would randomly disconnect from my network. Then one night it just stopped working, checked the power supply and it has power so the unit is dead. No help from support at all, sending this back and going to buy a hub from another company"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 27, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product!!", "Text": "So far the product has been pretty good. And the community that goes with it have produced some pretty good applications to extend its functionality. Very pleased."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 27, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A refection of the modern times where sort of working seems to be good", "Text": "Flakey for a consumer product. Some of the so called compatible products require some mucking around to work. I have a motion sensor and a Nest protect device that will no peer. A refection of the modern times where sort of working seems to be good enough"}
{"Author": "Chuck", "Date": "on November 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "lighting automation", "Text": "When i set up a lighting automation i set it to come on at 8pm and go off at 8am.sometimes it would work and sometimes not.what i did was change my automation to on at 7:55 pm off at 8am.that 5min offset worked wonders.hope this is helpful."}
{"Author": "Chris and Tara Barr", "Date": "on November 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "although it came with the batteries and that was nice.", "Text": "Simple to install and able to control everything well.\nWe couldn't care less about the battery option since ours in plugged into an APC battery backup; although it came with the batteries and that was nice."}
{"Author": "texbuck", "Date": "on November 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Impressive, Responsive, And Powerful Product. Baffled At Some Of the Negative Reviews", "Text": "I love this hub and It perfectly connects all my home devices. Ignore the negative reviews. They really baffle me because this thing is responsive, accurate, and even turns off my coffee maker that doesn't have an auto shut off. The support is great and any issue I have had, mostly with small set up issues, are addressed quickly by a great staff at Smart Things. They warn you that it may take a bit to get to your question, but within minutes or a couple hours I will get a response and my question is answered. They have always even followed up to make sure I am still not having issues. Love That!!!!\n\nThe Smart Things Hub works great with the Amazon Echo too. Many products that I couldn't control with the Echo before, I can control with ease now. Either through voice prompts with Echo or through the Smart Things app, your products snap to attention by turning off, on, up,down, locked, or unlocked etc. all very quickly. The responsiveness is impressive. I really like how this hub pulls all my other hubs and products together.\n\nAs I said before, the set up is easy but has some awkward moments. I think that's true for every smart product that I have bought. I am somewhat tech savvy but I'm certainly not a professional and this is NOT a hard set up. And as I said before, Smart Things support is first class!\n\nI am so happy with my purchase and I can say that it is so wonderful having all my smart gadgets in one place with one great hub. If you don't believe me, PC Magazine gave this product an Editor's Choice. I truly can not relate to some of the negative user reviews here because my experience has HONESTLY been nothing but positive. The few snags I have had were quickly resolved. I can't ask for any more. Thank you Smart Things for making my smart gadgets, and some pretty dumb ones too, so much better!"}
{"Author": "R", "Date": "on November 25, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product and great product support", "Text": "Great product and great product support. I sent an email to Smartthings support and got a response within minutes. Thanks Eric M. From Smartthings support!"}
{"Author": "R. Pearson", "Date": "on November 25, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "May turn out to be better than Wink", "Text": "Still experimenting with the hub. May turn out to be better than Wink. I like the battery backup."}
{"Author": "Wayne S.", "Date": "on November 25, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Okay...", "Text": "I am semi-satisfied with this product as it requires an Ethernet connection instead of a WiFi connection. Otherwise it performs as advertised."}
{"Author": "Sean M Holbert", "Date": "on November 25, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works... Most of the Time", "Text": "I like this home automation solution... when it works. To be fair, it does work most of the time, but it has also let me down a few times. Now, because of that, I don't fully trust the system and I'm constantly checking up on it. That's not really an ideal situation. The biggest issue with this product, is that it's 100% cloud based, so if the could goes down, you lose a lot of the hub's functionality. Now, most manual routines and actions will work if the cloud goes down, but any automatic ones won't work. I've had my thermostat stay at the daytime temp all night, lights not come on in the morning, outside lights stay on all night. Again, these aren't every day or even every week occurrences, but they have lowered my confidence in the system, especially now that's it's heating season and that I have all of my Christmas lights controlled by SmartThings.\n\nWhen the system is working (which again is most of the time) it is fantastic. Being able to set up routines that turn on lights, lock doors, and raise the thermostat all with one trigger is nice. One of the best routines I have, is that when I come home after sunset and unlock my door, the lights in my house come on and my thermostat raises to the desires temp. That's pretty convenient.\n\nSo again, if you are a patient person who loves to tinker, this product is right for you. If you want a system that is hands off and worry-free... well, I don't think SmartThings is quite there yet."}
{"Author": "Apple Guru", "Date": "on November 24, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Too bad it has to be hard wired in a world of wireless", "Text": "The one draw back is that it has to be connected to the router. If you have a bigger house or if you use it for door locks, it will be too far from them to reliably operate. If you put it next to your door then it is far from your water sensors etc. so in short, WiFi plus router is the way to go"}
{"Author": "Mktexpress", "Date": "on November 24, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do not buy refurbished UPDATED***", "Text": "Be wary of buying a refurbished one. Smartthings uses an activation code specific for each device. Once it is used, it can not be used again. I've tried contacting smart things but I have not had a response yet. This is frustrating as this means it is technically not refurbished, Amazon or whoever should have cleaned up activation so that it can be re-activated before selling the product back.\n\nUPDATED: I contacted Smarthings and they requested I send a picture of the bottom of the device. I sent it over and within about 5 minutes they fixed the issue."}
{"Author": "whtzom6", "Date": "on November 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fantastic Product!", "Text": "Best home automation hub currently on the market!"}
{"Author": "John M Dunn", "Date": "on November 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They all connect to a remote control I have and they work fine. However", "Text": "This hub doesn't work with any of my ZWave devices. I have multiple light switches, wall units, and lamp modules. They all connect to a remote control I have and they work fine. However, the SmartThings hub was completely unable to connect to any of them. Samsung's website suggested I chat with customer service, but no one was available. Emailed customer service, no response. I was excited about trying this but unfortunately its just a $100 paperweight. I'm returning it. :("}
{"Author": "Zach", "Date": "on November 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great hub, love it!", "Text": "I bought this as my first home automation hub, and have to say that I'm very happy with it! Currently i only have a Cree smart led bulb that i am using as a porch light and a 2gig CT100 thermostat. Both have paired with no issues and work great. What i like the most about the Smartthings hub is the ability to create profiles, i really feel that the possibilities are endless. My porch light comes on automatically every night and shuts off in the morning, and i can control my thermostat from anywhere. I recently traveled abroad and was still able to check and adjust the temperature. There's also the fact that you are able to further integrate your devices with IFTTT, though i have to say that i have not yet played around with it. The android app has been under fire by some other reviewers, but i actually happen to find it pretty straightforward, though a bit cluttered. I would highly recommend this hub for anyone that wants to get into home automation!"}
{"Author": "Katniss", "Date": "on November 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy to set up", "Text": "Very easy to set up, and the phone app looks great and is intuitive. Connected 3 smoke detectors and 2 light switches without any trouble. Looking forward to getting more devices."}
{"Author": "Alpine Trekker", "Date": "on November 22, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cutting edge product with a promising future that is useful today...", "Text": "I am pleased with this device. I started fresh with version2 and no legacy devices. Everything set up easily and works fine. I took a couple of hours to really play with and learn the app, which saved me a lot of aggravation later. Some of the poor reviews are clearly from folks to think this should be plug and play intuitive and don't have a knack for tech. It's close, but there are really too many variables to expect that level of simplicity in the setup stage. The operation stage is another matter - it's extremely easy to use once it's configured properly. There are a number of features on my wish list, such as over/under temperature alerts, which I expect to be forthcoming via updates. All in all, this is a cutting edge product with a promising future that is useful today."}
{"Author": "Parag", "Date": "on November 21, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great system", "Text": "I am using open close sensor on garage & motion sensor.. I will be adding water sensor soon.\nThe product setup was very easy. The app might take some time to understand but it's easy.\nThe sms & app alerts are instantaneous. Hope Samsung continues to maintain/support this product."}
{"Author": "Scott Payne", "Date": "on November 20, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't live up to advertised claims and actually requires extensive configuration and community-provided support to be useful.", "Text": "Doesn't live up to advertised claims and actually requires extensive configuration and community-provided support to be at all useful. Unless you already have substantial experience with this product, don't expect to solve any problem out of the box. If I did not enjoy the more esoteric aspects of home automation, I would have returned this product. Yet, I do enjoy this, more or less, as a toy with interesting capabilities. The hardware and associated software are not ahead of their time, they are just a terribly clumsy and incomplete implementation of home automation."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 20, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Really? You can't program a door unlock code? ...", "Text": "[Update]\nFinally had the time to follow the instructions provided in the comment and it is working - I can now use this for what I bought I for - setting a lock code remotely. Thanks!\n\n[Original Review - 1 start]\n\nReally? You can't program a door unlock code?\n\nIf you are getting this to remotely control a door lock, don't. It \"doesn't yet support setting a code\". Give me a break. I wish they made this much clearer & were honest and upfront. A $100 mistake."}
{"Author": "Noon MD", "Date": "on November 20, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not good!", "Text": "Bad! It doesn't work, kept going offline. Also, I wanted to be notified if someone opens my door, equipped with zwave Schlage lock, you need additional equipment in-order to set that up. I returned it."}
{"Author": "Naughty Garfield", "Date": "on November 19, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... few features and isn't compatible with most of my smart home items", "Text": "So few features and isn't compatible with most of my smart home items. Such as my Lutron Cassta Dimmers, Wemo Light Switches, Nest Thermostat and few other items that I have.."}
{"Author": "Hector Diaz", "Date": "on November 19, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent Hub", "Text": "Love the Smartthing hub because make my life easier. It is compatible with almost any smart product."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 19, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... choice other products to link with smartthing hub just like cameras only Samsung and d-link I think it will ...", "Text": "Very very limited to choice other products to link with smartthing hub just like cameras only Samsung and d-link I think it will open to link with every zigbee and z wave devices"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 19, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Flawless, app hard to navigate tho."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on November 18, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No support with a beta level product", "Text": "Disappointment. Support does not respond ( you can only send emails) and hub has multiple issues related to z-wave devices.\n\nSo much potential, such a horable experience."}
{"Author": "TornadoTJ", "Date": "on November 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works with everything I've thrown at it", "Text": "I am pretty impressed. It even works with items it \"doesn't work\" with, because of the community involvement and open nature of the box. I had a couple of Z-Wave issues with one light switch, but the online chat support was able to assist me in resolving the issues very quickly. It doesn't have the best Wemo integration, but I know this to be a Wemo issue, not something Samsung can probably resolve on their own."}
{"Author": "cpIdaho", "Date": "on November 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This one was the winner and for good reason. The base unit was a very simple ...", "Text": "I was torn between this the two others. I researched for a very long time and ended up waiting for the 2nd generation hub to come out. This one was the winner and for good reason.\nThe base unit was a very simple setup and the app that goes with this it is crazy simple and dynamic. you can basically do anything you want with it as well as write your own code if someone hasn't already done it."}
{"Author": "Charlie Foxtrot", "Date": "on November 18, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Needed improvement, seems to have gotten it!", "Text": "Updating my original review to reflect the progress that the platform has made since my initial install. Smartthings has gotten the attention that could make it a killer product. My first pass review was after a few months of best effort trying to make things work, and it was pretty harsh. Then again, the android UI really was quite bad. A few things have happened since then:\n\n-Smartthings did reach out to me to collect some more data and offer support\n-Numerous firmware upgrades were made to the hub\n-A major overhaul of the mobile app occurred\n-Google has discovered my Wifi radius\n\nThere are still some outstanding issues with integration of other vendors' stuff, specifically GE Link bulbs, but those aren't really officially supported afaik. When you make a hub that talks to other stuff, you need to rely on them to be standards compliant, or write to their standard yourselves. No small task. However, they seem to have righted the ship. I've done 4 installs of the smartthings ecosystem and various goodies in rental properties. Despite the few remaining quirks, the big rocks are out of the way.\n\nIt's been helpful to keep an eye on properties from afar, specifically temps and CO/smoke/leak detection, as well as keeping an eye on unit thermostat settings to ensure tenants don't crank it up to 95 degrees all the time."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 17, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to use and setup. Makes life much easier with home automation"}
{"Author": "JanD", "Date": "on November 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An excellent HOME AUTOMATION choice", "Text": "This is the BEST Zwave controller I have ever worked with. It is amazing that is has paired so easily with everything I have been connecting it to. There is also no monthly fee - and so far as I can tell it is imminently reliable. The new model has batteries so that your automations will keep working if the Internet service is down. If you buy the right devices - you can easily see all kinds of details through the app (relative humidity, temperature, electricity usage, motion, dampness, etc). The alerts work well.\n\nWe are waiting for improvements to be made to the ADD ANOTHER USER feature. Those should come any time now.\n\n-----\n\nI am adding to my review. It has been a few months now - I am still very pleased with SmartThings v2. I now have fourteen devices connected - and will soon add four more. My thermostats (2) are connected, and I have leak detection, Motion/Temperature/earthquake detection, and other awesome devices. SmartThings has very good customer service - and the only issue I have had so far is when our internet carrier went down for days - I had to reset the SmartThings controller. Otherwise, they let you know if they are to send an update or if they are working on an issue. I am still hoping they will improve the user administration feature - but everything else works great. The device compatibility is really good - and I do not have issues that friends with other systems have. I am glad I banked on Z-Wave...it really outperforms my neighbor's wifi systems...."}
{"Author": "AJ", "Date": "on November 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worked for few months. Now dead.", "Text": "I have smartthings hub V2. Worked well for while but stopped working from Nov, 2015. I contacted support but seems they are slow to Respond."}
{"Author": "ZIAD E.", "Date": "on November 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 14, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Awesome hub...easy to install and app is excellent."}
{"Author": "Cedric Collins", "Date": "on November 14, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Things Hub v2", "Text": "I had the first version of the Hub and I did not have any issues connecting my things. I upgraded to the Hub v2 and I could not get my things to connect. I worked with Eric W. and he was great. He responded to all of my emails and even walked me through the process on the phone. We discovered that I had a bad Hub. Eric W. was quick to ship me out a new Hub. He walked me through the process again, just to make sure that I was doing everything correctly. I was able to get my things connected with this new Hub.\n\nOnce again Eric. W. was very patience with me and he made me feel like my issue was important to him."}
{"Author": "Jake L", "Date": "on November 13, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Although it does not allow the same level of programming and control that I liked with the Vera", "Text": "Used this unit to replace my existing Vera Edge. Although it does not allow the same level of programming and control that I liked with the Vera, my z-wave network has not gone down with the SmartThings hub. This was a constant problem with the Vera and I had nearly all but given up on trying my home automation. As far as programming and control goes It is just a very simplified interface, you can go tho the SmartThings website and use the API interface to control from there as well."}
{"Author": "W. Todd", "Date": "on November 12, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Really good product, wide range of compatible add-on; takes a little more learning than some other hubs.", "Text": "While it takes a little more learning than the Staples Connect hub i am replacing this has a much longer list of supported add-on devices. the iOS app also is a little faster to load/connect then the Connect app. Had this for about a month now and don't have any negative issues to report. As with every home automation hub out on the market now the biggest issue is device compatibility. If you are just starting I definitely recommend this hub since it supports a very large list of devices. If you are thinking of switching from another hub you will want to double check the compatibility of any devices you already have (but that's the same with switching to any other hub). Case in point, my SC hub supports Lutron Pico remotes and this one doesn't. I currently have my SC hub connected only those devices I an using my pico remotes for, once I have time to figure out if combining my ST hub and my SC hub will work for me I think I will be all set. Otherwise I will have to decide on if I want to keep things as they are or replace my pico remotes with z-wave remotes and totally remove my SC hub from my setup."}
{"Author": "Dj Jablon", "Date": "on November 11, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Could not pair with anything"}
{"Author": "@nJ!0", "Date": "on November 11, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... Not Buy 1) made cheap not click and play like they make it seem", "Text": "Do Not Buy\n1) made cheap not click and play like they make it seem. Comcast gateway routers do not support this.\n2) terrible customer service. you have to jump thru hoops because no one is familiar with the product and returns are nightmare\n3) only way get support is via email or instant message. They provide limited support with troubleshooting\n\nThis is the 2nd Samsung item (hub and frig) I've purchased with same result unhappy with quality and support. Samsung hub sucks plain and simple."}
{"Author": "curtis terry", "Date": "on November 10, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love how I communicate with all my devices"}
{"Author": "Michael J. Casey", "Date": "on November 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great device and very easy to set up!"}
{"Author": "gary heer", "Date": "on November 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "excellent product and delivered as promised"}
{"Author": "HappyDad", "Date": "on November 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works", "Text": "Works like a charm for me so far. I own both v1 and v2 and both work fine. Like v2 better because of battery backup, but normal operation they are perfect for my needs."}
{"Author": "JB", "Date": "on November 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seams to work fine. I didn't have as much settings as my ...", "Text": "Seams to work fine. I didn't have as much settings as my Vera so I returned and kept using my Vera."}
{"Author": "Frazzxr", "Date": "on November 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The installation was easy. A couple minor bugs with the phone app", "Text": "We had a water heater leak a while back, I am mainly using this as a leak detector and a way to shut off the main supply to the house if a leak is detected in the future. I do not have any other automation components setup. The installation was easy. A couple minor bugs with the phone app, were known by the company and the next update had solved them."}
{"Author": "Mmm", "Date": "on November 7, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Averages out to four stars...", "Text": "Three stars if you have very little technical prowess. The system is very easy to get hooked up on your network and identify Smart bulbs, etc. at a very basic level. I've accumulated several Wemo items, and the Hue system through the years. As I've upgraded my network, and dealing with increasingly complex passwords, I stopped using the Wemo integration devices and just used the bulbs as normal bulbs. Same thing with the Hue system. When I got the Smartthings hub for my birthday, I decided to get things going again. Smartthings immediately found all of the Wemo devices, even though the interface systems of the Wemo were no longer part of the network. Nice! The Hue did require me to configure the bridge and then add it into the Smartthings system.\n\nBut this is where the love affair ended. While it is easy to turn the bulbs on/off and adjust the brightness, doing the simple tasks like building schedules isn't the most intuitive process. I can't just go somewhere and build a schedule. You have to build that schedule, and then apply it to a mode for the hub. You then have to mark your mode within the hub when you've left for vacation, or whatever.\n\nFive stars if you're technical and willing to accept the learning curve. The hub is super powerful if you're willing to learn and dig into the system. Github brings in all kinds of \"Apps\" which are lacking out of the box. As I mentioned above, the Vacation Lights solved this problem. You still need to make yourself away, however this can be accomplished by utilizing the geofence, and linking that to your phone. Once outside of a radius, change mode to <whatever>. I'd like to see something of once xx miles outside of the geofence, set mode to vacation, or something like that. It's probably out there, but I'm very early in the learning curve.\n\nIn summary, I would say, if you're willing to get both hands dirty and spend a fair amount of time, this is a great system. If not, look to the functions within the more consumer driven products. At that level, the Wemo and Hue offer great interfaces, but must be programmed individually, unless you buy into one system."}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on November 6, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waste of time and money to upgrade if you currently have a 1st gen SmartThings hub.", "Text": "I help fund the Kickstarter for the first hub. I was excited about some of the advertised features with this v2 hub. But after having it for a day, I'm not excited anymore. if you already own v1 and plan on upgrading to this one, then get ready to sink a ton of time into moving all of your devices over. SmartThings has no easy way to move existing configuration to the new hub. I had to exclude and re-add all 45 of my devices. Im actually still working on getting a handful of devices over that don't want to corporate. The worst part is that some features that were supported on the v1 hub do not work on the new v2 hub. Namely, my garage door controller. I used to have the ability to see when my garage was open or closed with a sensor and have it work in conjunction with a z-wave switch that allowed me to open or close the door, always seeing the current state of the door. Not possible (at this point) with the v2 hub. Really not happy about this. So no I'm at a point where I am seriously considering putting my old v1 hub back in service and spending another 12 hours moving my devices back to it and returning the v2. When I think about it, the only thing I gain with the v2 hub is battery backup, local processing for network failures, and video support that will cost $5 a month after 2015. In addition, I haven't really seen a big difference in latency from the local processing on the v2.\n\nBOTTOM LINE: If you are new to home automation, IFTTT, and like tinkering then SmartThings is great. If you already own a v1 SmartThings hub and are thinking about upgrading, then I would hold off."}
{"Author": "Jason Edwards", "Date": "on November 6, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. The whole system so far has been very ...", "Text": "Works great. The whole system so far has been very easy to use and works as advertised. Very little if any delay at all in getting notifications. Great product."}
{"Author": "Cw", "Date": "on November 6, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fantastic product! Review from Australia", "Text": "Worked right out of the box. I am based in Australia and works perfectly. I do note that the compatibility of ecobee3 despite listed as a compatible product is still not available to use. App works great and once learn how to use it, can do smart things like schedule your away schedules and randomly switch on lights as if someone is home! It's pretty awesome! (Note that this uses USA wave frequency so will need zwave USA products)"}
{"Author": "Bradley", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Device setup took about 10-15 mins. Was able to add multiple sensors and lights with no issue."}
{"Author": "Marlo Joseph Mendoza", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good z-wave hub", "Text": "The device works great for z-wave products. Connected this on my logitech harmony hub and it works ok. The only issue I had was the app. It crashes sometimes."}
{"Author": "Scott Miller", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but overall it's been a good experience so", "Text": "The software could use a lot of work, but overall it's been a good experience so far"}
{"Author": "ssingh200", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great home automation hub.", "Text": "Works as expected. the app is good."}
{"Author": "Dan Parker", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I really wanted to like this hub...", "Text": "...as the hardware (and firmware) itself appears to be a decent product, though it's near impossible to know for sure. The app that you have to use in order to configure and maintain it is so poorly designed and executed that it borders on being utterly unusable. I had hoped that over a year after acquiring SmartThings that Samsung would have addressed at least some, if not most of the major issues that the user community has been so loudly (and justifiably) complaining about for a long time now...but such is not the case. Sadly the company is exhibiting little-to-no evidence of any serious commitment to making the product live up to its promises and/or potential, or even providing minimally acceptable customer support. This is a major disappointment given the number of Samsung products that I have owned and been quite happy with over the years. I expect more from them."}
{"Author": "Dan D", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Version 1 Better, Too Many Bugs", "Text": "I researched before buying my first home automation hub. Through all the cost-benefit analysis, I went with the first-generation, publically available product. I quickly got the v1 hub to work, and was able to integrate my Hue kit along with many third-party sensors. I wired my garage with a Z-Wave controller in a test of DIY affordability. There was an occasional issue and the v1 application on iOS took some time to understand the GUI. Overall, the SmartThings Support team was always available and the quality was perfect.\nI recommended the product to colleagues who were using Wink. They often complained of processing lag time, of which I had none with SmartThings. I was excited about the next generation. I was also able to integrate more products of different kinds with the help of the developer forum (still fantastic!).\nThen v2 came out.\nWhile my application\u2019s dashboard was still functional, I was able to work around some gaps to add users (I can still do that because my dashboard is intact from V1). I can also still use my garage door functionality. My colleague who started with V2 cannot do either of those things.\nV2 was a clear step backward. The concept of MVP (e.g. Agile development) should be incremental improvements and steps forward. V2 hardly meets \u201cminimally viable\u201d and it should hardly be considered a sellable \u201cproduct.\u201d There are no discernable, practical improvements from V1.\nThen the bugs started and continued.\nSince migrating to V2, I\u2019ve had consistent downtime when I previously had none. I\u2019ve had all my ZigBee-based devices lose their connection to the hub (taking out the battery and reinserting after two minutes solved). I\u2019ve had multiple GE Link Bulbs lose their connections multiple times, and it has gotten worse since the end of October. Nothing has changed on my end.\nI\u2019ve argued with tech-support about some logic gaps (e.g. the initial removal of \u2018light power allowance\u2019 that ultimately was added back). I\u2019ve also had to argue about \u201clight turn on\u201d not sending the \u201csetlevel\u201d command. That was ultimately corrected with a program update, but not until after multiple weeks of correspondence and repeated instances of \u201cIT\u2019S NOT WORKING!\u201d\nI\u2019ve now had delays in processing that were never there. I\u2014luckily\u2014have more app functionality because my dashboard remains useful and intact. Had I lost my dashboard or the ability to add family members to the account, I would\u2019ve returned v2 over a month ago.\nHere is what SmartThings needs to do:\n\u2022 Take ownership. Recognize that selling the product as it is described, at best, constitutes deception. Offer discounts to current users who have placed their faith in all that was advertised.\n\u2022 Communicate. Many of us who are in the developer community or on this board are prepared to tinker. We understand \u201cstuff happens\u201d and coding takes time; however, at this point we need constant updates.\n\u2022 Invest in support. I used to get a quick email reply from SmartThings Support, now there are multiple day-long delays. Given all the issues, SmartThings needs to prioritize this for its legions of unsatisfied customers.\n\u2022 Reconsider the Dashboard. Bring that back. The functionality that was there in v1, while not perfect is more of a minimally viable product than the current iteration.\n\u2022 Delay future product releases until more testing can be done. There\u2019s a difference between MVP and a pile of garbage.\nI hope to stay with SmartThings; however, it is becoming less likely given the issues, lack of communication, and overall slow resolution.\n\nBased on the above I'm at 2 stars."}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on November 4, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great piece of hardware. Terrible support ecosystem and communication from the manufacturer.", "Text": "I really fantastic product, with horrific execution. Don't buy this if you aren't willing to tinker and if you are going to depend fully on it's features. Multiple user support broke at launch 2 months ago, and still hasn't been fixed, while other useless features, like some weird weatherbug integration took priority. At one point, a change on their end resulted in all of my time-based automations no longer working. I needed to go into each one and re-save them to make that work. This happened system wide for all users, yet I only found a resolution from a their community forums and a third party website. Support is a joke. Chat support is often disabled if their request volume is too high, there's no phone number to call, and they may or may not reply to your emails. SmartThings staff on the community problems don't say much other then tell you \"soon\" or \"stay on topic\" or \"we're working on it\" when issues like multiple user support come up. This company is suffering some serious growing pains.\n\nOn the other hand, it's the only hub I know of that combines ZigBee and Z-Wave, with a handy app, amazon echo support, local execution of many commands with a 'cloud' based back-end, built-in battery backup along with maintaining some basic functionality when the internet is down - all in a $99 package. It has so much going for it, but the support or lack thereof and the broken/breaking features are likely a dealbreaker for some."}
{"Author": "douglas c meng", "Date": "on November 4, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Finally, a good home automation system", "Text": "Was looking to get a programmable thermostat for the house but didn't like the prices for the Wi-Fi units, I found a Z-Wave thermostat on Amazon and started looking a SmartThings. The hub and thermostat were almost the same price as a good single unit, and then I could play with smart home stuff. Now I have 5 light bulbs and a smart switch and motion detector and I love it! Looking forward to growing with this product."}
{"Author": "J Fred Bob", "Date": "on November 4, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is a very good device, so far", "Text": "This is a very good device, so far, but a little light on large amount of product support. However, Samsung support, on-line and email, was fantastic and was able to help me with three different issues in a matter of hours."}
{"Author": "Bob Smith", "Date": "on November 4, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time, company seems as though run by a bunch of college kids", "Text": "As of this review (and hopefully it'll change), this product is not ready for prime time. Several have commented that this product is more like a v1 than a v2, and I'd go so far as to say this product is more like a v0.5. The automation features are buggy, and the company seems underwater in addressing them. Go read the community forums, and they're replete with stories of substantial bugs that impact the usability of the device and that have gone unfixed for months.\n\n[11/11/2015 Update] - Added two stars - one because Smartthings has shown it is customer service focused (see below) and one because the product, though still buggy, is progressing\n\n[11/29/2016 Update] - Dropping a star. I'm moving on and am going to buy a different home automation system. Smartthings hasn't gotten their act together. While it is less buggy, and their support team earnest, the product is still not there despite a year of development. It doesn't live up the quality of any of my other Samsung products. For example, over Thanksgiving, my hub glitched and forgot all of its devices and routines. Starting from scratch to re-add the devices and re-program the automation is a many hour process I'm going to reinvest in this hub. I'm going to move to a different product, preferably one that is entirely local and not reliant on a web based server for its automation. Not only will this put me in full control, the system will be more secure and I'll have confidence enough in it to add in home security and smart locks."}
{"Author": "PurelyNicole", "Date": "on November 2, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice upgrade, needs migration feature", "Text": "The new SmartThings hub is a nice step forward. It now has battery backup and can work offline with some devices. However, if you're an existing user be prepared for a lengthy migration process. You will have to unpair all of your devices with the V1 hub, re-pair them with V2, and re-add all your SmartApps."}
{"Author": "DrE", "Date": "on October 31, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good hub, and a lot cheaper than Apples limited ...", "Text": "Good hub, and a lot cheaper than Apples limited offering. If you are a nerd, there are endless programming possibilities. There is lots of documentation, but whats really needed is a better how-to for each accessory. Great for a DIY security system."}
{"Author": "Janna", "Date": "on October 31, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub 2.0 is not Ready", "Text": "Not sure how all the 5 star ratings are going on here. We ordered the hub 2.0 with high hopes back in August... Since then, we cannot share the account. Despite broken promises from ST, my husband and i need to log into the same account to use the app. This means we cannot use our phones to let ST know when we arrive or leave the house. No automatic turning off lights and no automatic closing garage door. The hub also has a mind of its own. Lights turn off and on at random. Motion sensors send security alerts at random. This thing was released too early and is not ready. My husband says the company is amateur at best and run by kids, not by Samsung...do not buy this product yet"}
{"Author": "Daniel T.", "Date": "on October 30, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "To everyone who has trouble connecting things from previous device - PLEASE READ!", "Text": "I had the first version of the hub and decided to use that for my office and get this new version for my home. I was really mad because I had the trouble connecting ANY of my light switches that had been connected before. I read here on Amazon that a lot of people have trouble connecting.\n\nI FOUND THE SOLUTION!\n\nAll the Z-Wave things need to be disconnected before reconnecting. They need to be excluded in the app and then can be reconnected. That helped me with my problems.\n\nRead here:\nhttps://support.smartthings.com/hc/en-us/articles/200878314-How-to-exclude-Z-Wave-devices\n\nI still think that the Smartthings app is very complicated to understand and is not self explanatory. Also what I don't like is that it doesn't seem to have a function of \"Random On/Off\" to use when away on vacation."}
{"Author": "Mike in Maryland", "Date": "on October 30, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings Hub V2 is great and fairly easy to use", "Text": "I have had this for about one month and it has had a few issues but I have resolved them with a chat session. I have had a home automation system in my house for several years it probably had more capability that this but it was much harder to use and it didn't have some of the smart phone capabilities. I have several dimmer light switches, a couple of motion detectors, door sensors, a smoke/carbon monoxide detector and one smart bulb. They are all working and they were very easy to connect to the system. I have lights on timers using sunrise and sunset triggers and then motion detectors to turn lights on in the middle of the night. I have the armed mode deactivate automatically when my wife and I are both away and it disarms the alarm when either one of us returns home so I don't have to worry about setting the alarm or turning it off when I get home. It is nice that I will know if the smoke detector goes off when I am away. I am going to get a water detector for the laundry room soon in case the water heater leaks or the washing machine spills. I also want to put in a deadbolt but I am waiting to see if the new zigbee door locks are good and reliable. What is nice about this system is that you can expand it slowly over time. I have three grown kids and they all want a hub for Christmas. I amd getting them one so I will have three more people people to help me figure out cool things to do with this setup. One of them is a programmer and the other two have technical backgrounds."}
{"Author": "StevieG", "Date": "on October 30, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product Not so Great Tech Support", "Text": "This is an excellent hub and Samsung has baked in and continues to add a lot of supported devices. The camera support is a welcome addition although cam models are limited. The user interface offers a high degree of logic control possibility but the configuration pages are heavily layered and can be confusing. This can be overcome if one takes the time to navigate and understand the correlation between the pages and how they can relate to your custom automation schemes. I would have given a full 5 star rating if it wasn't for the seemingly invisible technical support on the Smart Things website. Although there are a lot of subjects covered onine there appears to be no recourse for issues that are not. For example I added my Samsung S6 edge as a presence device and it continually yields a refrush error and even if you remove the device or re-add it the refresh error nag screen persists with no method of stopping it short of uninstalling the software entirely and reconfiguring your devices from scratch. The latest over the air update from SmartThings didn't even solve the issue."}
{"Author": "Wolfgang Schobel", "Date": "on October 29, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent product"}
{"Author": "dmreviews", "Date": "on October 29, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This thing is amazing! Home automation has become an addiction!"}
{"Author": "Manoj Pandya", "Date": "on October 29, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm so far very pleased with it", "Text": "After reviewing many hubs i decided to go for STs. I'm so far very pleased with it. I have connected a couple of GS Zwave switches (indoors), some Zigbee light bulbs (outdoors) and my Ecobee3 thermostat. All work fine and took my a couple of hours to setup.\n\nMy next project is to hook it up with my Amazon Echo and I plan to purchase some water/flood detection Zwave monitors.\n\nI gave this a four instead of a 5 for a couple of main reasons 1) The app needs a lot of work. I can see what it is rated low. It is not user friendly. 2) The hub feels like it is still in development missing Bluetooth connectivity and the ability to setup multiple accounts for example."}
{"Author": "Tyler", "Date": "on October 28, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Satisfaction", "Text": "I've had the SmartThings V2 Hub for about a month now. The biggest thing I can say about the product is I feel it is still in a beta stage at this time, which is not necessarily a good or bad thing but should be taken as an indicator to others that the software side of this product is in a constant state of changing/morphing. Hopefully changing for the better and not going towards a \"dead end\" growth. (Along the lines of, how much \"health improvement\" has there been in the fast food industry?). I have not tested the hub to its limits yet but what I can say is that any SmartApps that were working may not work with a SmartThings after an update.\n\nOn the brighter side of things, Cree Connected lightbulbs work amazingly well with the V2 hub. I also use the Aeotec Smart Strip with it. I leave the house, it turns off EVERYTHING. When I come home, it turns on the lights to allows me to walk into a cheerful lit room and my computer has started up. In the process, I learned that I can turn on my computer with a power switch (Aeotec Smart Strip) using boot bios after \"power failure\". It's saved me time and ergonomics from having to reach down to knee/shin length to turn on my computer, redundant walking to turn on lights and allows me to wake up to a room that gradually brightens allowing my eyes to adjust comfortably.\n\nThe next step would be to find motion/occupancy sensors for my closets to trigger lights when entering. Another goal I have in mind is getting the Amazon Echo and integrating it with this. I definitely feel I am starting to develop a relationship with my house, speaking as a single, nerdy male. She comforts me when I'm home, turns on the lights for me and makes sure the lights are off when I leave and texts me that the lights are off.\n\nIn short, great product. FYI to others, it is a double-edged sword like most things in life, so take it with a grain of salt and a cracked pepper. It's definitely a useful tool for convenience, comfort and health. Though, I cannot speak for security or safety and its reliability. I would recommend this product to others and thinking about purchasing another one as a gift."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 28, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I tried someone's custom code to support the ecobee three that worked great for about 8 hours", "Text": "Received my new \"Smarthings\" hub and so far thoroughly unimpressed. Apparently we are still years away from a home automation platform that is worth investing in. I have an Ecobee3 thermostat that smarthings doesn't support. I tried someone's custom code to support the ecobee three that worked great for about 8 hours. Awoke at 5 am to API error notifications on my phone every 10 minutes. No simple way to just remove the thermostat from Smartthings need to do an exclusion on the device itself. What if a device becomes defective? How can it be excluded? Maybe I'm just new to this and missing something but this has been painful. I can manage to turn a light on and off and sunset and sunrise. Also have a Schlage camelot door lock. Only thing I can do with it is lock and unlock the door. No remote access code changes. Not much advantage over punching in my code and opening the door."}
{"Author": "Francis Gari\u00e9py", "Date": "on October 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent!", "Text": "Very simple to install and works flawless!"}
{"Author": "Rafael Nieves", "Date": "on October 27, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Activation is a chore and support is non-existent.", "Text": "Received unit and attempted to install. Activation code got registered into the system but could not locate the device then the app crashed. Restarted the app, activation code was already used and was instructed to contact support website. Support supposedly had chat support M-F 9-5 PST but there was no option for chat. I sent several e-mails requesting support with my \"activated\" device and received none. I'm sending it back today. Maybe it's awesome if you can actually get it activated but support for this device absolutely sucks."}
{"Author": "LucasChristian", "Date": "on October 26, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Keep V1 for now, but don't hesitate to get V2 either!", "Text": "Im still transitioning from V1 to V2...I might have waited till they got more bugs cleared out...but I'm an ST loyalist, so I know they will. They're still the best option out there. And you can always integrate it with other HA systems...I'm still learning, but it's getting easier."}
{"Author": "mypointofview", "Date": "on October 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I've been very pleased with this system", "Text": "I've been very pleased with this system. It doesn't seem the rules based system I'm used to but I've found it rapid to deploy and nothing has acted up since install. The integration with Amazon Echo is very cool."}
{"Author": "Tony", "Date": "on October 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works as expected. No issues."}
{"Author": "B. Born", "Date": "on October 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "Deanne C. Tracy", "Date": "on October 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to use system", "Text": "The hub detects the devices and has an easy to use app. It does not require monitoring of a service and it sends me a text when it detects motion etc"}
{"Author": "bladerunnerrocks", "Date": "on October 25, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay away!!!", "Text": "I bought the V1 hub and a small system no more than 6 months ago. The company kept promising they will integrate a camera into the system. Many believed it would the Foscam HD. But since the company was bought by Samsung, it is not surprising that they integrated the Samsung camera instead. What is surprising it is they basically threw their old customers under the bus with this new V2 hub. There is no plan to work on or improve the V1 hub whatsoever. The Samsung camera is not compatible with V1, and I suspect anything they welcome into the family won't be either. They want you fork over another $100 to buy a new hub. And believe what everyone has said. This is not an easy turn-key system. It is designed for developers who want to write their own codes and integrate different things into the system. No way am I upgrading to V2 and spending any more money on this."}
{"Author": "GadgetGuy", "Date": "on October 25, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do not buy until iOS software bugs are fixed", "Text": "I recently bought the hub v2. I have a strong IT background so I am confident that these problems are not my fault. Here is a concrete list of bugs in the software :\n1) unable to add additional users. You get an error message saying feature coming soon. This prevents you from using multiple iPhone as presence sensors\n2) the built in routines (Away, home, etc) don't auto switch appropriately. I set it to change to home or away based on if my phone was home. The application clearly marks my coming and going, but does not switch the mode.\n3) the software GUI is confusing and not intuitive\n\nUpdate: 1 month in. Tons of posts on support site. No resolution to issues. Stay away till software fixed."}
{"Author": "E. Tucker", "Date": "on October 25, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does not work offline", "Text": "Sending it back.\n\nI've tried the Phillips, Wemo, Wink hubs. This one was in the running but Wink is better. If Wink ever goes local control it will be perfect....for me.\n\nI just want to control a few lights/outlets. In some cases using sunset/sunup timing. For the latter the Smarthings app made me download a Smartapp called Smartlights. That's an app within an app. If the second app is Smart, what does that make the first one.\n\nCompared to the Wink system/app the Smarthings system/app is touch-techie.Yes that makes the Wink system touchy-feely. Guess it all depends on how you want to spend your time.\n\nThe Smarthings app is \"open source\". There is no question they want people to write their own programs (apps). That may explain why the tech support is slower for Smarthings than for Wink. Perhaps because they are busy dealing with \"developer\" issues.\n\nI will be returning this at my expense. Not amazon's fault. I'll also post this on my Wink review as an update.\n\nUpdate 11/24/2015\n\nI came back to this system. Because it was supposed to work if no internet access was available.\nTheir propaganda says it will work offline with zigbee and z wave devices. No way\n\nI've had 2 instances in the last 4 days when for whatever reason the Internet modem went down. Hub did NOT control via the smart apps or by individual on/off via the app. Hub was powered up with a solid blue light.\n\nI have a request in process with smarthings. FYI their support is very slow relative to Wink."}
{"Author": "Andrew", "Date": "on October 25, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Prefer Over the Wink Hub.", "Text": "Previously purchased a Wink hub before picking up up the SmartThings Hub. The Wink hub after set-up would take 5-10 seconds to turn on/off items such as my Schlage lock and some Aeon switches.\n\nAfter pairing all of my items to the SmartThings Hub (Not as hard as many have made it out to be), I found this hub completed its tasks much faster and with less errors. I'm still in the testing phase of using it, but so far I like it quite a bit."}
{"Author": "Oldman", "Date": "on October 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very reliable. A pleasure to work with it.", "Text": "I bought the ST hub 2.0 and am thoroughly satisfied with it and also with the support.\nI have a ton of devices and 2 houses. One house has an ST v1 hub and the other a ST v2\nThe newer hub is vastly faster and has been working flawlessly. The SmartApps always work on the newer hub and rarely work on the older one.\nRemoving Zwave devices is a pain but removing Zigbee devices is a breeze. I'd recommend buying Zigbee devices. The removal is not due to the hub but due to the design of Zwave. So if you're having problems with Zwave devices don't blame the ST hub rather blame Zwave.\nThe app is a bit complicated but the last two releases have been awesome. It seems to get significantly better with each release.\nI am very pleased with ST HUB 2.0. Buy one!"}
{"Author": "Steven Hasting", "Date": "on October 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, i love it!", "Text": "Just got it. Works great with the schlage deadbolt and the Arial FOB. Nice to have the door lock and unlock automatically."}
{"Author": "John Nicoletti", "Date": "on October 24, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well but unable to track who comes and goes ...", "Text": "Works well but unable to track who comes and goes. They claim it's being worked on. We shall see."}
{"Author": "diane coston", "Date": "on October 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "False advertising by supplier.", "Text": "This product was sold to me as a new item. I was excited to receive it in the mail and begin automating my home. The first step in the set up process is to enter the welcome code from the hub. When I entered the 6 digit code I was informed that this code had been used before and could not be used again. That's right this was a used hub and now I'm forced to go through Samsung to try and reset the welcome code. We'll see how long this takes, but I'm not opptomistic at this point. I've had good dealings with Amazon in the past but this purchase has certainly given them a black eye in my view. Amazon needs to be careful about what they mark as new and used. I certainly paid the new price but received used goods."}
{"Author": "Floyd the Barber", "Date": "on October 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to set up. Great interface. First time user and migrating from Homeseer. So much more intuitive..."}
{"Author": "Joshwa R Rock", "Date": "on October 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "I love how this integrates with so many devices!"}
{"Author": "AWV", "Date": "on October 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Tons of software issues", "Text": "Very disappointing. Samsung software is loaded with errors from account regestration screens notworking to bugs in the Smartthings hub to errors on the device screen. this is sad i have multiple samsung products several cphones, tv, mpplayers andctheir new watch and circule headphone which all work perfectly. Sorry samsung you only get 1 star."}
{"Author": "Ed lover", "Date": "on October 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Constantly improving product and great customer service.", "Text": "Love Smartthings. I'm coming from a Staples connect hub, which wasn't bad, but didn't offer everything I needed. I ordered a Smartthings 2.0 starter pack and love it...so flexible and easy to use. Love the community and apps. Nice work to the Smartthings devs! there were some early issues that they've been working through. I had my first hub swapped out, and since then it's been great. Looking forward to watching the product grow. I've read about some of the frustration others have felt...I just see some people working hard at helping customers and improving their product. With a tad bit of patience on my part, I've been happy. Nice work to the customer service folks and developers.\nKind of a pain switching hubs, but was able to get through it quickly. I use a mix of Aoetch, Monoprice, and Smarthings sensors. All work well!"}
{"Author": "Bran32209", "Date": "on October 22, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Full of bugs", "Text": "Seems like it was released to soon. Alot of issues dont even think the camera thing is cool. It is not still in beta testing and it really does suck with the dlink. Every time they up date you will need to reconnect any ge light bulbs. There some great features with the hub being open source. But bring some raid because it is buggy."}
{"Author": "D. Hansel", "Date": "on October 22, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far, so good. Great platform, and tons of support from community", "Text": "It's early days on the IoT frontier, but I choose SmartThings after careful research. I'm sure Apple, Google, and maybe even Amazon will eventually join the race for home automation, but I liked the openness (something Apple purposefully restricts, with best intentions) as I like to explore, learn, and experiment with possibilities. For that, it's proving to be a perfect \"platform\" for me to grow with. I started with security and smoke/CO, then music (Sonos), and starting to do lights. It's not only useful, but fun too. Another plus is the fantastic community of users and people creating custom programs and apps based on whatever need arises. Only negative, you've got to have a solid internet connection, as currently there is very little \"local\" control."}
{"Author": "gb_ott", "Date": "on October 21, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simple but poor dev support. - Revised review - up a star.", "Text": "I'll keep this short and sweet pending more testing.\nSetup 5/5. - incredibly easy using lock lamps so far. App is easy on Android.\nSupport 1/5 - I ran into a well documented snag almost immediately. Can't add another user ( my wife). This apparent priority 1 bug has been open over a month. Sammy has 1 week to solve this bug or it goes back.\n\n10/29 - It is pretty clear that Samsung has either left SmartThings to operate like a startup (or just stuck with taking over manufacturing) because the development and stability of this product is atrocious. The essential add users feature (so more than 1 family member can use this) is still broken and in the past week, basic previously functioning scripts are NOT working. Simply turning my living room lamps on and off suddenly kicked off a door lock access sms everytime.\n\nIf you are looking for a toy, this is great. If you are looking for a RELIABLE home security and automation system, this is not the answer. I will be deciding if this goes back next week.\n\n11/15/2015 Update\nIt's been over a week since the patch came down that allowed multiple users to use the system. Seems to stable and running. I have not experienced any corruption or screw-ups in the system in the past week either. Things are getting promising.\n\n12/25/2015 - Last night we inadvertent tripped the alarm while doing the Santa stuff. We had set the alarm to away so that motions were active. This set off notifications to every phone in the house..Great right? WRONG! The ST decided to keep notifying us every hours since..it is now close to 18 hours. I cannot get support and there are no forum admin's to assist either. I am back to considering this a steaming pile again for both the ongoing KickStart attitude of this garbage company and the apparent lack of investment in support by Samsung. If I could return this unit today, I would. But, it is obviously too long.. I strongly recommend staying completely away from home automation or considering these units anywhere near ready for primetime security monitoring.\n\n1/8/16 - After having the Smart Home Monitor scripts deleted by support, I took the advice from a helpful person in the ST communities and went with a 3rd party security script ONLY. I have had zero issues since. In fact, my siren actually works with the script flawlessly now. I am receiving both app and sms updates for the family as intended. The system is...working? I will continue to update as time go on.\n1/12/16- infinite triggers repeating AGAIN for absolutely no reason this time. Support chat down, no response on email and forums has been no value. I cannot stop sms'ing to our phones even with unit unplugged. Fed up with this garbage..looking for an alternative solution.\n\n11/17/17 - Complete turnaround ..Things have stabilized and improved over the past year. I have had very few incidents outside the app seems a bit slower after recent update. Integration with Google Home is great for device control."}
{"Author": "IGP2016", "Date": "on October 21, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It nails the basics and has potential, but just doesn't work like it should for advanced functions right now", "Text": "The basic functions works, but you can quickly run into issues and waste a lot of tie trying to program it to do anything other than simple on/off of devices. It has problems with just able any multi-step task (or If-Then commands) you program it to do. Tried to get it to turn off lights after 2 hours (for example) t it always shuts them off within 30 seconds. Other times devices randomly aren't recognized. It reads the temperature from my multi-sensor but is very unreliable with turning on or off my portable AC unit when \"trigger\" temps are reached as another example. It has potential, but right now is a bit of a headache :)."}
{"Author": "Richard Walsh", "Date": "on October 21, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Coolest thing ever! Along with Alexa, Sonos, and Hue, I shall rule the world...... well at least my home."}
{"Author": "Yong Choon Keat", "Date": "on October 20, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Frequent crashes on the Android app. Interface needs further ...", "Text": "Frequent crashes on the Android app. Interface needs further polishing - For example, the tile screen uses half of the screen for showing a static picture, and left with the remainder of the screen for scrolling the list of smartapps (which can grow quite a bit). And the gigantic font size doesn't help.\nThe smartapp for Harmony Home Control does not update nor refresh the list of activities available for triggering. Email to support gets a cryptic message to retry it, and their support online chat is not available currently.\n\nMysterious disconnection of the hub itself from the cloud and requires a power cycle."}
{"Author": "Parker Harvey", "Date": "on October 20, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, and works with everything!", "Text": "Easy setup, works great and with A LOT of devices. Works great with Amazon Echo too!"}
{"Author": "Michael M.", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A \"MUST HAVE\" for home automation!!!", "Text": "I have been a Smartthings customer from the onset....before IFTTT, before Samsung purchased them. I had \"Hub V1\", then upgraded recently to \"Hub V2\". I have approx. 18 items connected to my Smartthings, including motion sensors, open/close sensors, light switches, moisture detection, and am adding new things all of the time. So...if there is someone qualified to speak on the product, I'm pretty sure I'm the guy.\n\nSimply put, this product is awesome! I have a large home (6000+ sq ft), and everything communicates with the hub seamlessly. If you don't know anything about home automation, it can be a bit of a challenge if you aren't good at following instructions, but Smartthings has a bunch of how-to videos to get you through just about any issue you may come across.\n\nThe only thing better than this product, is their customer service. I can't say enough about these guys! So I was hooking up my V2 hub, and was having some connectivity issues (later discovered it was my fault, not the product)...I emailed customer support, got a response within a few hours, and the tech asked if he could call me to help walk me through the issue. He called me...from his home (kids in the background), to help me with my issues. I'll say that again...FROM HIS HOME!!! Did I mention this is a Samsung owned company?!?! Unheard of!!! Listen, I can't say enough about these guys...they are awesome. Either go with them and be happy about your choice, or, drop $50-$75K on a high end system that does the same thing, but doesn't have the open source expandability. For me, and my money, it was a no-brainer, and I'm extremely happy I did."}
{"Author": "Derek B. Rosen", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Run like Hell.", "Text": "You have been warned."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The App is intuitive and easy to set", "Text": "Connected with the devices seamlessly. The App is intuitive and easy to set.\nAdds a great deal of peace of mind for a modest cost and no additional monthly expenses.\nNo cons so far."}
{"Author": "Sina Hakami", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A Great Start", "Text": "I've had this for a short while now, and so far so good. I haven't yet installed any sensors, and use it only with my cell phone and a bunch of smart switches. The variety of devices that work with it is pretty good. The software has issues. Sometimes I've had to remove a bunch of devices to add one, and then add the rest back, which is annoying. Specially the phone presence (which tells the system whether you're home or away based on your phones GPS location) is buggy, both to set up, and to use.\nThe customer service is OK. I've had emailed them several times about different issues, and they always get back to me, but also the message always says \"we're very busy and this might take a while to resolve, but we promise we do our best to resolve your issue.\" In the end, I've always worked around my problems with things such as removing devices and adding them back on, before I get a really helpful assistance from the customer service."}
{"Author": "Geno", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product, so far had no problem with this Hub... works well with Z-wave products"}
{"Author": "Grenik", "Date": "on October 19, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good idea, but execution still needs work, particularly the app", "Text": "EDIT: I received a lot of technical support from SmartThings and the system is working better now than it was in the past. The app is more stable and I received help getting more of my devices to operate locally instead of back to ST's servers. The technical support was particularly good from my perspective. Never once did I get an email that said something like \"sorry you have a problem, here is a link to a stock solution or FAQ\". It was individualized to my issues. It was definitely 5-star service and support.\n\nIn light of the excellent service, I wish I could rate the system higher. The app, while more stable now, is still poor and interferes with the experience instead of enhancing it. There is no landscape mode for tablets. There is no summary screen where I can set up the devices that I use the most for quick access. On the surface, the app seems logical and well laid out, but that is only if you do not actually have to use it much. If everything is automated and you use the app once to set up your automation, then it is fine. Everything in a room and all that. But if you want to turn on a couple lights in different rooms and dim them (like I wanted to do for Halloween), then it is drill into each room, each light, set the dim level, back out screen-by-screen, then into another room, into each light, etc.\n\nCompared to the easy and intuitive apps like Phillips Hue, the SmartThings experience is very lacking. I did increase the overall rating because of the excellent support and the improved app stability and would be more willing to recommend it to others. Hopefully development will continue and I am looking forward to a 5-star product!\n\nEND EDIT\n\nI was able to migrate from the original SmartThings hub to the new SmartThings hub, so I guess that is some level of success. The process was very painful and in hindsight, I wish that I would have just stayed on the original hub. In fact, in hindsight, I would not install the system at all. However, with the number of devices I now have, I am not willing to toss the whole system in the trash, but I am getting close.\n\nI had hoped that Samsung ownership would bring some stability along with thoughtful designs from the user standpoint. I have their 12.2 Note tablet and a Galaxy S5 phone. I enjoy their products. However, I do not see any of their \u201ctouch\u201d in this system.\n\nI had read the migration instructions prior to purchasing the new hub and knew that the process involved deleting and removing my old setup and starting over with the new hub. I knew that going into this and planned a full day for migration. I have approximately 50 items connected to my system. Having to go through this process was disappointing, but I knew that up front, so I am not taking off any rating due to having to go through this process.\n\nI experienced two issues which I considered significant and are the reasons for the low rating. First, the app crashes all the time. I could only delete three devices from my system without the app crashing. I tried the app on my Samsung tablet and on my Samsung phone. Both behaved the same way. The previous app seemed to work OK, but this one is terrible. It does not seem to crash as mush in normal use, but every three devices the app would freeze, go black, or pop up a message that there was an error. It also crashed several times as I was adding devices to the new hub. My Galaxy S5 phone is new and almost completely stock. I set it up two days prior to working on the SmartThings system. I had to wait 30-45 seconds after killing the app to re-launch it and do three more items. After doing that a couple times, I had to reboot the device. This added a significant amount of time to the transition process. I wonder how they could release an app that works performs that poorly on Samsung devices?\n\nSecondly, there appears to be no thought put into the migration process to make it easier for the user. I wonder if anyone actually migrated a house full of items before releasing the new app and hub. A couple examples:\n\nEach and every device has to be removed from the old hub. However, to remove the item, it cannot have any Smart Apps associated with it. It would have made the process much easier if I could have put the app in \u201cmigrate mode\u201d and it would have removed the Smart App and the device at the same time. Both needed to be removed, why the multiple steps? Even better would be the ability to remove all the smart apps associated with devices at one time. Some devices need special steps to remove, so I understand not being able to bulk remove the devices. But the Smart App is just the code that is in the SmartThings system. All that could have been deleted at one time.\n\nEvery device has to be added to the new hub once the old hub is removed. When you discover new devices there are likely to be multiple devices that need to be set up. From the \u201cMarketplace\u201d tab, you see the items that need to be set up. You select one, set it up, make a Smart App if needed, and hit done. The program returns you to the Dashboard. Why not back to the Marketplace and the list of items that need to be set up? How about an option to go to the next item to be set up? Again, it would be easy to put a toggle into the app to indicate if you are migrating if the developers did not want to have this be the normal way the app performs.\n\nAll of this may seem minor, but after going through the process, I felt that the developers did not about users that already had a system. It was like they went out of their way to make it more difficult than it needed to be.\n\nThe crashing app and the lack of thought and care for people migrating left me very frustrated. The system has been running now for a full day and I have not noticed any performance improvements. Lights do not turn on faster when tripping the motion sensor for example."}
{"Author": "4acae86", "Date": "on October 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a difference!", "Text": "I switched to this hub from the GE wink hub. This thing works fast and always works. My GE would constantly disconnect from my Wifi no matter where I put it. I do wish the app had the routines in the first screen on the app, but past that so far so good!"}
{"Author": "BuckeyeJohn", "Date": "on October 17, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung V2 is still a move in the right direction, just need to ensure development continues.", "Text": "The application has taken \"ease of use\" step backwards. Need to streamline the interface. The smartapps don't seem to be working properly yet. It almost seems like the cloud interface confuses time zones or something. Amazon Echo integration is fun, works surprisingly well. Multi-user (More than 3 people in the family need access to the app that controls things) isn't working yet. The upgrade path required me to unregister multiple devices and completely re-connect."}
{"Author": "III", "Date": "on October 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A's a first time smart things owner this thing is a beast", "Text": "Not sure why everyone is in such a negative uproar. A's a first time smart things owner this thing is a beast. I'm new to home automation and this puppy has made it a breeze for me. Purchased in a bundle with door sensors and motion sensors. Yeah just like any app there are glitches from time to time, but this thing will just get better as time passes. Beware, home automation is addicting. The possiblities are endless."}
{"Author": "Patenaudeted", "Date": "on October 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The unit works well. It could use added. ...", "Text": "The unit works well. It could use added. Instructions,but figured it in a relatively short time."}
{"Author": "Mareng", "Date": "on October 15, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "actually not sure who is worse. I am giving this three stars and maybe ...", "Text": "This review is for the Samsung SmartThings hub. I have been using this for only a month and a half. Having problems with my Yale lock not being recognized by the hub. This particular lock is Zwave. Also have Hue, Osram and Lifx lighting products. The main selling point for this hub are the different protocol's that are supported, with hopefully more in the next firmware version. Previous to thus I was using a Mi casa Verde hub which is only Zwave. The hub can be quirky at times along with the app, actually not sure who is worse. I am giving this three stars and maybe come back in another month or so with an update. Be prepared to do resets when you make changes or add devices so the hub picks up existing things on the network, again... Had to extend the signal of my home network due to the location of where I placed the hub. Samsung should have used a better receiver in this unit, just saying. One last observation having issues with the Lifx bulbs being recognized by the hub, unfortunate as the Hue requires it's own hub but adds additional congestion to my network. Not sure if I will invest in Lifx. One last, last plug for Keen Home, can't wait for my smart vents they work with my Nest. Check them out, they're not cheap. That's all for now."}
{"Author": "Erin", "Date": "on October 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you have version 1 don't buy or upgrade the app.", "Text": "Currently the dashboard only shows the security, you can no longer turn groups of lights off with one switch and it's like they thought it would be a good idea to burry things under layers. So a a previously two swipe has become 4 to 5 menus to get where your going. Also a response from a co founder about all the issues was basically I don't care my conscious is clear."}
{"Author": "Richard Caldwell", "Date": "on October 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Meh", "Text": "Takes a little kicking. But it's cool"}
{"Author": "Steve G.", "Date": "on October 14, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "New to SmartThings very happy with the ease of use, more importantly usefulness", "Text": "We're currently just into the first week of setting up the house to become a Smart Home. As a result I'll probably update this review in a few months.\n\nAnd we are new to SmartThings so people who have owned the v1 Hub will probably not find any of this important, whereas newbies to SmartThings may (hopefully will) find this more valuable than the reviews of people who have migrated from v1 to v2 Hubs. I also should point out that I've used Wemos for a couple of years so automating lights and such is not completely a new experience for me.\n\nSetup of the Hub\nThe Quick Start guide is well done and easy to follow. There's a bit that talks about how setting this thing up is...\"Easy peasy\" and I have to agree. I suggest getting the app onto your iPhone, Android, or Windows phone (do people actually have those? sorry, just a joke). Then plug in the hub and follow the instructions on your phone. It took quite a bit of time to go thru the setup (maybe I was just being anxious). I thought it was having issues so I went to the SmartThings website, looked in Support and found out what the different lights blinking in the front meant. Perhaps they should have added those to the Quick Start Guide, but it wasn't a big deal for me to look it up. I think it downloaded an update and after that..boom! I was done and everything was working.\n\nThe setup continues by you selecting your location which it needs for \"geofencing\" which enables your phone to let your home know that you are...well at home. You can also take a picture of your home and also give it a name. Basically it's a super simple setup.\n\nAdding Things\nYep, it's the new buzzword...Internet of Things. So the next step was adding \"things\". I did this ultra slowly by first installing a light switch GE12722 Z-Wave Wireless Lighting Control On/Off Switch (I'm a decent handyman so this was easy for me but you may want an electrician if this is out of your comfort zone). Once installed and flipping the breakers back on I tested the light switch using the manual on/off and then attempted to add it using the SmartThings app on my phone. It was both simple and seamless as it connected and I was able to turn it on and off remotely.\n\nMore adds\nI continued to add more devices around the house and worked thru setting up the home. The app uses rooms (even has you take pictures if you like) and then add devices to those rooms. Overall the process was very easy to follow and my variety of light switches, outlets, door/window sensors and even a motion sensor all connected. The motion sensor was the only one where I had to do two attempts but on the second it too connected fine. And I did not use any of the SmartThings branded devices, instead using GE and Ecolink brands.\n\nUsing SmartApps\nSmartApps are how you automate the devices you have added to the hub. Personally I think it's a very odd choice of words, they say you use apps to control the devices but to me that's more like \"rules\" or \"instructions\". SmartApps just doesn't sound right, SmartRules does, but I don't know, maybe it's because I've used Wemos in the past. I should say at this point that the SmartThings stuff is WAY!!! better than using Wemo. I had 4 Wemo switches in use over the past couple of years and only 1 of them still works. And that one got tossed right into trash as soon as I connected up a few of my devices and started to really use SmartThings.\n\nBut I digress.\n\nSo SmartApps you in essence download and then set up to use with your devices. I've only downloaded one so far (don't worry I said I'd update this review as I got into things more). The one I've got is Smart Lighting which is made by SmartThings. Oh, did I forget to mention that one of the main reasons I went with SmartThings is it's incredibly active and strong community? Yes, SmartApps can be (and most are) made by users of SmartThings Hubs. I trolled around their community site for months (community.smartthings.com) and found oodles of good info and suggest you do as well. But back to the Apps, the lighting one from the company is okay, a few things seem odd to me, but again I'm coming from setting up rules on the Wemo.\n\nBut overall it was pretty easy to setup my son's lights to go on at sunset and turn off at his bedtime. I did different rules for our master bedroom lights and did one for turning off our kitchen lights when the motion sensor no longer showed motion in that room. Still playing with it and adjusting things. Deleting rules is easy and redoing them a different way is painless. I also set up a door/window sensor connected to our garage door to let us know if we forgot to close it. My next thing is to download a SmartApp that will send us a text letting us know it's open. Again, a strong user community with plenty of cool SmartApps makes this Hub extremely useful.\n\nAnd although I do give the Hub 5 stars, it's not perfect and some of the UI is not very good. As mentioned some of the jargon is not very intuitive. The App itself also didn't work once to add a new automation (again I've been playing with those a lot and have added, deleted, re-added, re-deleted, etc.) so I wasn't too upset it gave me the hated spinning wheel. But I merely shut the app off on my phone and re-lauched it and everything was fine.\n\nAnd the Smart Lighting app which is from SmartThings does have some very odd UI quirks as well as some things you think should be in there (rules and such) that you can't do. But again, the community is there with replacement Apps or even code snippets that allow you to create your own SmartApps to do whatever you want. And this was a major reason I went with their ecosystem rather than Wink or waiting for Apple to get HomeKit correct and I'm a Mac guy and even worked at Apple way back in the 1990's (wow I sound old). I also like how much more open SmartThings is and the breadth of devices that they support.\n\nAfter a few months I'll update this and I'm sure will have a few more things to pick at, but hopefully also more admiration to the ease of use and the usefulness of the platform."}
{"Author": "BC Alaska", "Date": "on October 14, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good idea, bad implementation", "Text": "It's a great little hub for connecting all of our smart compatible devices together at our office. Unfortunately, multiple users are not allowed which, as a business, we find less than desirable.\n\nAlso unfortunate is the lack of power over your own device. It seems you cannot do anything without a support technician's help. I could not put another person on to the smart hub and could not even change the email address linked to it myself, because a technician has to do it for you, so I eventually turned to Samsung SmartThings customer service.\n\nNo phone customer service is available at ALL, which is ridiculous for those of us who want something fixed in a timely manner and wish to not have it drag out over a period of days. Instead they have live chat, which would be as good were it ever actually working. This left me with only an email option.\nThe support for email takes days to get through, as Samsung seems to only reply when you are asleep, and is never online during normal waking hours, and is also probably VERY overworked, considering it is everyone's only option.\n\nAll in all, this product would be great were it not impossible to do anything without a customer service person, or if the customer service was at least reachable in a timely fashion."}
{"Author": "jkizer82", "Date": "on October 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I wish I could actually test the product with what ...", "Text": "I wish I could actually test the product with what looked to be a normal unit so I could give a fair review, but the first order arrived with a shifted electrical board, making it impossible to plug anything into it and the \"replacement\" item had a broken battery door and would not connect to any of our devices. Amazon says they were both \"new\" and unused; if that's actually true, it would seem the product quality is VERY low."}
{"Author": "Mark", "Date": "on October 13, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Previously had wink which would constantly forget or lose devices ...", "Text": "Previously had wink which would constantly forget or lose devices requiring me to re-pair. Drove me nuts taking down lights and doing a reset to pair them again. This has been much more reliable."}
{"Author": "Sorin Lazarescu", "Date": "on October 13, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "because these smartthings devices are so horrible their customer support is overloaded", "Text": "this product is not ready to be sold. takes forever to detect new devices, sometimes it doesnt detect devices from its own range (smartthings devices) such as the samsung motion sensors.\n\ntechnical support is non existant. because these smartthings devices are so horrible their customer support is overloaded. look what they say!!!\n\nSmartThings Support: Due to increased ticket volume, live chat is currently unavailable. In the meantime, please email support@smartthings.com with any issues you may be having and we'll get back to you right away.\n\nI have been waiting for at least 30 minutes for a reposnse. i got nothing but a canned response that didnt help me at all.\n\nDO NOT BUY ANY SMARTTHINGS DEVICES!!! THEY DO NOT WORK!!!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 13, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Must be willing to tinker", "Text": "I have to say the overall potential for the Hub v2 is fantastic. Unfortunately, this is not a turn key solution. You won't be able to make use of that potential in the state that this device has been released, you need to be willing to go into the Community forums and find what you are looking for.\n\nHere's an example: SmartThings sells Kwikset locks through their marketplace. They also list it as a supported device. What they don't say is that you won't be able to use ALL of the features the lock is capable of, primarily PIN code management, which is a basic feature on pretty much every other competitor. You can only view the status of the lock and lock/unlock the device. Luckily the community comes to the rescue here and a custom application is available to \"unlock\" these features.\n\nNext there's the issue of device support. I was actually surprised that not all US based Z-Wave devices were supported. I thought that was a requirement to get certified, but it looks like I was wrong. One of my temperature sensors was not supported out of box, but again, thanks to the Community, I was able to find the custom device code to get things working.\n\nFinally, there's the app. It's pretty obvious this was released under the gun. The user experience is confusing at best. I'm sure it will get better, but there hasn't been a lot of movement in the past month since release. It comes off as more of a gen 1 product, not a gen 2. There are even features that were available in gen 1 that are not yet available, such as multiple user support. Want to give someone else access to control your devices? You've also got to either sign them in manually or give them your account password...\n\nA lot of this can easily be fixed through updates. Hopefully, Samsung is working to stabilize the platform and build out its gaps. If you have a working setup today, I would hold off on migrating. If you're looking for a home automation solution and are willing to roll up your sleeves and search for solutions to things that should be native, then this is one of the most powerful platforms on the market."}
{"Author": "Paul Q", "Date": "on October 11, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice device, not-so-nice app", "Text": "I've been using the hub in my home for a little over a month. Speaking only of the hub itself, it seems well built and the battery back-up is a plus. I've been able to pair various z-wave devices to it although sometimes it takes a bit of fiddling.\n\nThe downfall of this product is the app which is not intuitive. It needs work. I've read that the old app was better but I never used it. There seem to be quite a few complaints about the new app. The app opens to a \"dashboard\" with only \"smart home monitor\" (aka a security system) which is useless if you aren't using the hub for that purpose. Why can't you put the rooms or something else right on the dashboard? Once you set up a device, it's a bit of a pain to change the way you set something up. It's just not very user friendly. Luckily, I'm pretty tech savvy so I've (almost) been able to wrap my brain around how the app works. I saw almost because I still run into puzzling aspects of the app.\n\nMy brief experience with customer service was positive. I have no complaints there.\n\nI'm giving it 4 stars (aka \"I like it\") because it is doing what it is advertising it will do. It would get 5 stars if the app that makes it work was more intuitive. They may need to sit down and rewrite the app from the ground up (again). I can see less tech savvy people getting very frustrated."}
{"Author": "KeithF", "Date": "on October 11, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice Security/Automation Solution", "Text": "So far, so good. I connected several Z-Wave devices to the hub and everything is working well."}
{"Author": "yandreev3", "Date": "on October 11, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good, but not for everyone.", "Text": "EDIT : After taking to support, I had a replacement sent. It had the same issue but after resetting it and my app, it l worked and I'm up l and running. Great support. Now that I've been using it for a bit, I like it but some basic things are missing. For example, to make a light time out after turning it on manually, I had to sign up as a developer and write my own code to do something so simple. Otherwise I like that you can do a lot with it and make it your own.\n\nI got this today to replace my Wink system and right out of the box, it does not work. I put in the batteries and hooked it up to my first floor switch and gave it power. The status light came on and I went to add it in the app and it asked for my welcome code. I typed it in only to get a message that said hub update failed. I even tried resetting the hub and my app and still nothing. Mildly disappointed. Will be returning it."}
{"Author": "Average Joe", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lousy app, lousy support. Won't respond to user community.", "Text": "Stay away people. This might be ready in a year but right now it's worse than nothing at all.\nST won't communicate. Support is useless. They've totally screwed over V1 users.\nThey have taken away necessary functions, and removed the ability to add extra users. You can only control things from one smart phone.\nAlso check out the number of 5 star reviews cropping up lately. Go take a look at some of those users, and you'll find that they've only ever reviewed ST hardware. Funny how that works.\n\nOh and Riley from tech support, don't bother commenting. I've talked to support until I'm blue in the face.\nI want my money back."}
{"Author": "Mathew m", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't buy used one big pain in the ass can't reuse code...", "Text": "star sating don't count but dont buy used the one i got was used and the code that comes with it can only be used once wast of time for me have to send it back thanks guys for wasting my time"}
{"Author": "Jay", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "V2 is huge disappointment due to", "Text": "Ive been long time smartthings user since v1.\n\nV2 is huge disappointment due to..\n\n1.they removed lots of useful apps in newer app from the old version.\n\n2. Only few app runs locally.\n\n3. Still no support for Lutron caseta.\n\n4. App is getting worse. Grouping is alsmost non existance. Confusing layout.\n\nNext gen will be nice if it gets apple homekit and lutron support."}
{"Author": "Tim", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well - app could be better - good choice", "Text": "Spent a lot of time looking at different home automation solutions & even had a few Wemo devices before buying this. It work well. I did have to move it to a more central location so it could communicate well with my outdoor sensor but that is not unreasonable.\nThe app that runs this if fine, but has room for improvement (as of 10/10/15). It has all the functions I need, but it takes some extra steps to program some functions as compared to the Wemo app.\nBy the way... this found and operates my Wemo switches & outlets without any trouble (but no support yet for Wemo Maker)"}
{"Author": "Ryan Boone", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable with poor support.", "Text": "Has to be reset about every six hours to control my z wave Kwikset 910 lock. Works perfectly after a reset and then stops working several hours later.\n\nThe only support is via email. How can one effectively trouble shoot and fix when it takes 24-48 hours between email responses.\n\nDon't purchase unless you have a lot of extra free time and know how to code.\n\nI bought this hub to automate and simplify my life, not complicate and frustrate it."}
{"Author": "just me", "Date": "on October 9, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works better than anything else I've tried. Currently using over 30 devices and switched."}
{"Author": "Barbara", "Date": "on October 9, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable. Support is useless. App keeps getting worse. Still no tiled things page and lots of vaporware/broken promises.", "Text": "UPDATE April 2017. ST is now harassing customers regarding negative reviews online. Things continue to degrade and ST is less functional now than it was 2 years ago.\n\nOriginal review.\nWhen you read this review, keep in mind I've been buying things from Amazon for years and this is the only the second one star review I've ever given.\n\nThis thing keeps getting worse. It's unreliable and the company that sells it, couldn't possibly care less. The only way to get a response out of them is to post a negative review. Not that getting a response does any good."}
{"Author": "Ben Bullitt", "Date": "on October 9, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... my first time with a SmartThings hub and I love it. It's allowed me to automate a lot ...", "Text": "This is my first time with a SmartThings hub and I love it. It's allowed me to automate a lot of things in my home in a really nice way. Looking forward to adding new products to my smart home so I can make it even smarter."}
{"Author": "Tech guy in CO", "Date": "on October 8, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Tech support is horrible and occurs totally by email", "Text": "Brand new hub quit working after less than 10 days. Tech support is horrible and occurs totally by email. They even state that they have no phone number (huh?). I would not buy this product again!"}
{"Author": "Some guy at a keyboard", "Date": "on October 7, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Sad and disappointed", "Text": "So much potential, so much disappointment. I had read up on smart home systems and z-wave devices for several months prior to purchasing this hub. I decided to go with SmartThings based on the history and active community. Once I heard a newer version was coming out, I decided to wait for it. After setting it up with some sensors, thermostat, door lock, etc., I have come to realize that the user interface via the Android app is very poor. I was really hoping for a very customized experience, but instead got a very rigid gui with limited functionality for displaying information. In addition, there are SO MANY bugs. Basic functionality is missing in several places. The dev team and support are so backlogged that it is taking a surprising amount of time for these bugs to get fixed. I'm seriously wondering if I should have gone with another platform.\n\nUpdate 10/25/2015:\n\nDropping my review to 1 start - the problems continue...\n\n1) I am not able to modify my dashboard. I don't see the plus sign described in the online help.\n2) Smart Home Monitor shows unconfigured, even after configuring all available settings.\n3) Scheduled routines are not automatically running (not late, not ever). I have to manually kick off the routine for my thermostat - not cool.\n4) I cannot add my wife as a user to the Smartthings account - she needs to be able to use her phone too. I am not able to log into her phone as me either, because it generates errors from me being logged into two devices.\n5) I cannot change the icon for devices, how should this be done on Android?\n6) When I click on the configure button for my basement flood sensor, nothing happens.\n7) The button tiles on the screen for the garage door opener are all duplicated, two of each tile."}
{"Author": "Brandon M", "Date": "on October 7, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Needs some work so much possibilities!", "Text": "Good day my peoples! As many of you know, I am somewhat obsessed with technology and gadgetry ( and have been since I was a lil kid). I am pretty sure that I drive my wife crazy with all the gadgets and gizmos I have but she loves me still #Blessed . I remember watching the Jetsons as a kid or Lost in Space and thinking , \"How cool would it be to actually have the ability to control things in my home remotely and automatically ?\" Well, this has actually been a \"reality\" for many years but up until recently, has not been connected in ways that we all have wanted. Such as the ability to remotely lock you door (from your phone or internet ) , turn on/off your lights if you forgot to , close your garage for you automatically when you leave the neighborhood and endless other things. But NOW we have come into this age of \"the internet of THINGS\" which is essentially many different \"things\" that all communicate together to allow for the above mentioned actions to take place. I did a brief review previously on the Wink Connected Hub so forgive me if some of this is similar. I liked the Wink but it was almost too simple for what I wanted the potential for . So I bit the bullet and jumped on the SmartThings bandwagon for a nice price of $99.\n\nI already had bulbs, siren, motion sensors and door sensors from my wink and was told that they \"should\" all work with the SmartThings hub. I received my hub next day (Via Amazon ) and ripped the box open to check it all out. I knew that since I had an existing Smart Home network (via Wink) that I would need to disassociate all my devices from that hub before they would connect so I went about my way to Exclude all items from my Wink hub (this is somewhat time consuming since , at least for me , I had to actually \"exclude\" each device 1 by 1 from the wink hub) Once I did this , I shut off my Wink hub and then put in my batteries in the SmartThings hub v2 , hooked it up to power and plugged it in to power and Ethernet (there is NO WIFI ) . I downloaded the iOS app and went through the setup process , well attempted to . My first try was a no go, the app just kept sitting there on the Waiting screen while it looked for the hub . I power cycled it and it came right up after that (I was worried because I had read that several people had the same issue and it had ended up being bad units that were sent out) . I did open a ticket with Samsung in the meantime but figured it out in minutes. (Another note is that they have no phone support and the Tech Support is anything but speedy...took a day to get any response and another few days after that for another response so be prepared to read a lot of forums if you are lost on anything) . I was able to enroll all my devices, Schlage Connect Door lock, my GE z-wave Dimmers, All my GE Link Bulbs, My TCPConnected Bulbs, door sensors and motion sensors (Re-branded 2gig z-wave units), and rebranded 2gig Siren (although it showed up as a switch only) fairly simply. Everything seemed to pair quickly and showed up on the app. At this point, I had all my items on the app and was ready to start the Automation part. This is where things get \"sticky\". The possibilities are endless or seemingly with the Samsung Smart things, but the execution is a bit overwhelming and can be confusing. An example would be setting something up to turn on lights automatically when walking into the room. The initial setup of this is pretty simple via something called \"smart app\" (their way of calling an automation rule ) There are ones that are created by Samsung SmartThings team and ones that the \"community\" creates. The thing with these are that every persons situation and setup is different so it is not always a cut and dry setup. Sometimes you will have to create an SmartApp for 1 set of lights to turn on , then create another one to turn off but again its really difficult even here to try and explain it. My biggest issue I kept running into was that my lights would turn off while I was still in the room (even though I had it set to turn off automatically 15 min after motion stopped) What I didn't realize was that the way it is currently setup is that ,this particular \"App\" starts that 15 min timer after motion stops but doesn't start over if it senses motion in between so imagine you sit down on the couch for a few min and lay there for only 2-3 min, at that point the app thinks no one is there ,so it starts the 15 min countdown to turn the lights off so even if you get up and move, it doesn't register that and then ends up turning the lights off. I realized this after a while of tinkering and reading online that this is an issue with the current software and they are working to resolve it. The cool thing though is that these devices actually have the ability to have programs written for them and \"coded\" so if you are good at Coding , these are quite the amazing little tool. They have an open API that lets the user configure all types of settings . The thing is , they don't really directly tell you about this and you have to do a lot of reading and understanding before you can jump into it (I am a techy person and even for me it confused me ) I eventually was able to run a custom \" Smart App\" and get the lights working for me but even then with the only 2 sensors I have for motion, I am limited as to what I can do. This has a ton of potential but is not generally \"consumer friendly\" in that I can't imagine most people picking one up and making \"just work\" which is why things like Wink, ADT Pulse and IRIS exist and do quite well. For the price , this has some really cool features and the future is looking bright, See below for a brief list of Pros and Cons and some pictures of the HUB itself.\n\nPros:\n\n-Fairly reasonably priced at $99\n-Seemingly Endless possibilities of things to control\n-Works with ALOT of different \"Smart Things\" such as z-wave , zigabee and potentially others down the road.\n-The fact that it works with different \"things\" means you don't have to purchase the \"Samsung\" branded \"things\"\n-Version 2 has Battery backup so it will still communicate with your battery powered items in case of power outage\n-Has the ability to work \"offline\" meaning that if you lose internet , it will still function locally (most others like Wink , will not work at all if no internet)\n-Has ethernet connection\n-Has a large community online of willing users and tons of apps and info\n\nCons:\n\n-App is too confusing to navigate ( I really preferred the Wink one to this as of now) Also no support for multiple users which defeats many of the built in options\n-No wifi which means you have to have it plugged in to Ethernet to communicate so if you want to connect new devices , the unit itself needs to be close to that item while doing the initial \"inclusion\" (there are ways around it such as long Ethernet cable or putting it in inclusion mode then disconnecting Ethernet but it is still a pain)\n-To have your house running properly , you will need to spend a considerable amount of money on devices to make it work as you like ...primarily sensors which are average of 40-50$ each and you will need one in every room or hallway and/or every windows. Then you still need to get things like door lock (200+), Thermostat (120+), garage opener (100+) and so on and so forth.\n-Support sucks and is pretty much non existent but they do try the best they can.\n-The whole process can become overwhelming and confusing (even for a seasoned tech person)"}
{"Author": "Gcat", "Date": "on October 7, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hard to use but it works. Comparison to Wink.", "Text": "I used Wink for a few months and grew frustrated with it's lagginess, unreliable execution of commands, and poor range. News of its bankruptcy gave me little hope for the future so I looked for other options. Enter SmartThings which I have used for about 2 weeks. Here is a brief comparison:\n\nHARDWARE\n-SmartThings is much more compact and easy to hide. The Wink hub is really big and stands vertically.\n\nCONNECTIVITY\n-SmartThings requires a hard ethernet connection while Wink is all wifi. For most people, this means Wink is much easier to place anywhere in the house.\n-SmartThings will need to be hardwired in order to pair with devices. Unless you have jacks all over the house, you will need a really long ethernet cable so your hub can travel to each device. Wink just needs an outlet.\n\nAPP\n-SmartThings app is pretty bad. It is not intuitive and can be tough to navigate. It can take multiple taps to execute a simple command. Categorization is not good either. For example, I found out that I can use the \"Rooms\" tab to compartmentalize my locks, outlets, and switches because it doesn't automatically do that for you.\n-Wink app is much easier to navigate and far more intuitive. Fewer taps are required.\n-Wink widgets are more customizable and sleek than the SmartThings.\n\nRELIABILITY\n-Here is where Wink was becoming a problem and it was mainly with the Schlage Century locks. Too often, it would not lock/unlock the door. The widget shortcut would not work reliably.\n-So far, SmartThings commands have been working at about 95% reliability. While not perfect, it is more reliable and executes lock commands faster than the Wink.\n\nRANGE\n-About the same but my SmartThings is able to reach a distant lock than my Wink couldn't.\n\nOVERALL\nI've been slightly happier so far with the SmartThings hub because it is able to perform it's functions more reliably and with less lag. That's the whole point after all. Once you go through the learning curve of using the SmartThings app, it's acceptable. The Wink is far better in terms of ease of use and intuitiveness but I'm concerned about its long-term support given the recent bankruptcy.\n\nUPDATE Jan 2016: I am still content with this SmartThings hub. I have experienced no major problems. It is not 100% reliable as far as executing the scheduled \"routines\" but it's been good enough."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on October 6, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "pretty sad for a newly launched product", "Text": "Lots of broken features, lots of missing features. It is very obvious this was rushed out and not ready yet... Major basic features such as changing icons hasn't worked yet, pretty sad for a newly launched product. More bugs than should ever be in a new major release like this. Really lost confidence in SmartThings going forward. Add to all of the issues horrible customer support with basic canned troubleshooting responses and no real fixes."}
{"Author": "Brandon", "Date": "on October 5, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't work well in offline mode. AKA you can't ...", "Text": "Doesn't work well in offline mode. AKA you can't set it up until you get internet service at your house."}
{"Author": "Juan Pablo Risso", "Date": "on October 5, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Engineer must have", "Text": "As a developer I love this hub. It enables me to customize and add a software layer to my whole house. This defensively changed my life. Recently I moved to a new house and before I set SmartThings up it was clear that it was missing and how much I enjoy having it taking care of simple things like tuning off lights if nobody is in the room."}
{"Author": "Jimmy Lin", "Date": "on October 4, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Setup takes longer than I expect but everything works fine. It automatically finds my dimmer switch", "Text": "Setup takes longer than I expect but everything works fine. It automatically finds my dimmer switch. Easy to setup. The only drawback is that it doesn't support wifi. I have to put it close to my router."}
{"Author": "Jack Merritt", "Date": "on October 4, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Junk", "Text": "This is my second smartthings hub. I bought the original model and there was nothing but problems using my iPhone according to their customer service they were experiencing problems with apple. Hours later I was able to control a single switch and a single outlet in my office. I can not change the icons for the outlet with my iphones and have to get someone with a Samsung to change them. So when the new model was coming out I got on the list thinking surely these problems were resolved. I was wrong. I am returning the unit and modules because I do not have the energy to spend hours on the phone with their customer service. The instructions are extremely brief, which is great if the product works but not in this case. This is NOT plug and play by any means. Whoever approved this model should be fired today! I was lured by the promise of connecting to many different items but they can not even connect to their own items. shame on you."}
{"Author": "E. Latkowsky", "Date": "on October 4, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Died in a week", "Text": "Worked for a week then it died"}
{"Author": "Bob", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it!", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "Mr. Ashley Stevens", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much easier than Vera, once set up correctly", "Text": "I'm increasing this to four stars from two as it's now working thanks to some help from Riley at SmartThings customer service, which is really good by the way. In my case the hub kept going offline and then attempting to update and then fail, and then coming back online, repeat forever. My hub was plugged into a switch. Rlley suggested plugging directly into the modem which didn't work but then I tried directly into the router and that did work. The hub was able to update itself and then worked properly and is not stable. So it appears this hub really does need to be plugged directly into the router. I can't understand why it doesn't like being plugged into a switch but it doesn't. Having to locate the hub physically close to the router is not always ideal and may result in needing some Z-Wave repeaters. An improvement would have been wifi in the hub so that it could be placed anywhere. That would also aid pairing since you could take the hub to the device to be paired on battery power and see the result on the app.\n\nI had to unpair a couple of devices that had partially paired the first time around when the hub was unstable. I had to exclude them and then re-include them, meaning the device though it was paired but the hub didn't (but the hub didn't say they were unknown devices, so it sort of did know they were paired, but not properly).\n\nI still have several more devices to pair but it's looking good, easier to use and better Z-Wave range than Vera. Certain aspects of the UI do seem odd but you can tell that it's because it's designed for multiple locations and when you have only one location then some of the UI is a bit superfluous. It's also a pity there's only a phone app and no iPad/tablet app. The phone app looks a bit naff when scaled on a tablet.\n\nAs well as pairing with Z-Wave devices I use the MyQ app to pair with my LiftMaster garage door. https://community.smartthings.com/t/release-myq-liftmaster-chamberlain/8939\n\nOne site that may be of use to others is RBoy's apps page. I intend to use the Foscam camera device and camera motion alarm. http://smartthings.ramitbhalla.com\n\nPreviously:\nMine appears to be defective. Most of the time it's offline and inactive, then it tells me it's updating and just occasionally it works, but less than 20% of the time. It's up and down more than a whore's draws! Most of the time it won't pair, but just occasionally, as if to give you hope and not send it back it succeeds in pairing. I'm going to send this one back but I'll try a second to see if I just got a defective unit. I still have hope that this thing might work properly, we'll see when the replacement comes (but they're out of stock at the moment)."}
{"Author": "C. Gibson", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't bother with this half-baked hub.", "Text": "This device can be summed up as half-baked garbage. Simple functionality like grouping lights together so a room can be turned on, off, or dimmed at the same time doesn't exist. I don't mind waiting for advanced features, in fact, I expect it with a product like this. Home automation with Z-Wave and Zigbee devices is a work in progress and I accept that. But when basic functions do not exist I cannot accept that.\n\nMy hope is that Amazon pulls this product until SmartThings delivers on what they promise."}
{"Author": "-jim", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seems like Samsung's own products will not connect even to one another.", "Text": "Although I have great hope for the product, I am very concerned. Recently downsized recently moved to a new apartment. Before we had a large 100+ device automated home and after down-sizing, decided to protect the apartment. I have a Samsung TV, Smart Phone and UHD monitor all good products.\n\nI have owned a Samsung SmartCam HD Pro 1080p Full-HD Wi-Fi Camera for a while. The SmarcamPro was setup with the SMarCam app and working fine. Ordered the Samsung SmartThings Hub v2 and can not get it to connect wirelessly to the SMarCam. Opened a case with Support and only had an email from them saying they had to speak with another person who knew more about it.\nAlso, my Samsung UN55JU7500 Curved 55-Inch 4K Ultra HD 3D Smart LED TV (2015 Model) to the SmartHub with the builtin SmartHome App. Seems like Samsung's own products will not connect even to one another.\n\nI will update this review as things progress."}
{"Author": "Ken", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cumbersome setup. Ultimate nightmare. Worst experience I've ever had with technology.", "Text": "I just about returned this the day I got it after a slew of difficulties setting it up... Part of it was user error, part learning curve, part software issue. I must say, after getting over the big hump, I just love this thing. I'm a Newby at zwave tech, and the snobs on the forums frustrate that reality, but after the learning curve it's pretty awesome (and I consider myself a tech guru). Here's a quick tip: 2gig doesn't work with this unit, and also if you have old hardware / sensors you're using, they must be excluded before they will pair with SmartThings (and resetting your old unit doesn't fly). These two facts would have changed my initial experience. A dozen sensors later and I'm now a huge fan. Smartthings with IFTTT is pretty neat. Don't give up like I almost did. It's worth the fight.\n*********************************\nUpdate 4/4/16:\n\nI finally gave up. Headache after headache of dealing with unresponsive devices, false alarm activations, no alarm activations, lights not working sometimes, just to name a few issues... I couldn't even reset the device without contact support, as I \"was not authorized\" to reset my own device... A disaster all the way to end!"}
{"Author": "M. Tidrick", "Date": "on October 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Smart", "Text": "After the initial migration from a V1 hub, I am very happy. A lot of the actions fire much quicker."}
{"Author": "T. Hobson", "Date": "on October 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "First home hub - updated 10/14/15", "Text": "This is my first hub. It has been easy to use so far and does everything I need. I initially had pretty limited uses, and everything has worked as advertised so far. I have added several routines and home modes since initial setup and everything has worked as expected. Overall, this has been a very nice experience from unboxing, initial connection, and now daily use."}
{"Author": "Rich B.", "Date": "on October 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This product is amazing. You have to take a look at the ...", "Text": "This product is amazing. You have to take a look at the community where folks help to contribute code that can be used for many devices!"}
{"Author": "Brad Crow", "Date": "on October 2, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome smart home platform", "Text": "Upgraded from the previous version of the hub to this one and it has been great. The migration process was tedious but the SmartThings team was a tremendous help. Things are much faster and more responsive. I have had an issue or two but SmartThings customer support went above and beyond to get them fixed."}
{"Author": "treimer", "Date": "on October 1, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy! Everything works great!", "Text": "I was initially looking for a way to control a z-wave lock. What I found was so much more powerful. I have successfully linked up my existing X10 modules and my Vista-15p alarm panel to make my home truly \"smart\".\n\nSetup was simple and fast. My z-wave devices were added very easily. I was up and running quickly. Performance in instantaneous. I haven't experienced any lag our disconnections.\n\nI am really impressed with the open platform and huge development community. I'm a software developer. So I'm pretty comfortable with rolling up my sleeves and getting under the hood. The IDE is easy to use and enables you to push Device Type and SmartApp changes immediately.\n\nI procured a Raspberry Pi to handle the X10 and alarm integrations. That little $35 gadget has so many possibilities.\n\nI ran into one minor issue with the mobile app. I emailed support and got a response in less than 5 minutes that my problem was fixed. Fantastic!"}
{"Author": "Ryan7777", "Date": "on October 1, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Complete and Utter garbage. Seriously flawed in just about every respect.", "Text": "I have the older hub, but it's the same thing, same app etc... STAY AWAY!!! This \"thing\" is the most frustraiting POS ever made and forced upon man. Seriously. IT-IS-TERRIBLE!!! The hub is fine. It just sets there, takes up a little bit of space and speaks z-wave and zigbee, but only when it feels like it...\n\nThe biggest problem with smartthings is the horrid user interface in the form of a smartphone app. I have the iOS version and it is utter s***.\n\nThe smartthings developers must have taken UI programming in hell by the worlds most evil sadist, perhaps satan himself? Whoever taught these guys how to build a UI needs to be exiled to space or the bottom of the ocean where they cannot harm humanity any further.\n\nSeriously, if you like icons that mean nothing to anyone and drill down menus within drill down menus that lead anywhere but common sense, where your sure to find nothing but madness and rubber rooms, then maybe this is for you. I'd rather screw sheetrock screws into the bottoms of my feet slowly than deal with looking at that app any longer. It is MADDENING!!! I've seen fewer things in my day less intuitive than the \"smart\" things app. Them even using the word \"smart\" with anything involving this junk makes me angry. Break stuff angry. Think office space and the printer, but replace the printer with the hub...\n\nThey could fix this a little bit perhaps by offering software that runs on a computer where things could be layed out in some manner that is quick and easy, but no, that is for their \"IDE\" that allows for writing your own smart apps, which is cool. I actually think that it's a great feature and I've used it to incorporate my alarm system, but day to day useage and managing everything that matters is only available in that horribly frustraiting app that seems to be designed to make you cry.\n\nSince smartthings was acquired by Samsung, I was hoping they would get some talent and oversight that might help the situation, but no, they just release new versions of the same madness and B.S. - ugh.\n\nThis is all coupled with the fact that logging into the IDE isn't even on the main freaking smartthings webpage. No, they hit you with advertising, and then you poke around aimlessly until you find the login is under the \"shop\" menu - you know, in case you want to buy more madness... And logging in? Maybe you will get lucky and your password works, OR you get told your login is wrong and you have to reset your password... And then mayyyybeeee it'll let you login. Maybe. Sure you don't want to buy something first? App is the same thing, log out, try to log back in, no dice, incorrect login... Change password, maybe it'll let me in, probably not for a few more tries.\n\nSometimes the door will unlock when it's supposed to, sometimes it won't, sometimes my wife's phone will show she's left home, sometimes is probably never most of the time. Outdoor lights on during the day, sure, why not... Maybe they won't come on during the night. Hey, why don't we unlock the front door when no one is home and everyone is miles away? Anything goes!\n\nYeah, home automation \"can be like that\" but with smartthings, it is only ever \"like that\". You are guaranteed to suffer, to be frustrated, to be angry, pull your hair out, curse, scream, hover over the hub, cackling madly, holding a claw hammer and speaking in tongues about bad things, very bad things.\n\nI would seriously smash my hub into a thousand pieces and light those pieces on fire if my wife hasn't threatened to have me committed if I do....\n\nMy best advise is to save yourself and buy a brick, like and actual brick used for construction and put it wherever you would have placed your smartthings hub, and if you ever find yourself about to buy into smartthings, take the brick and smash one of your fingers, hard, and consider that pain, and then rethink buying into smartthings...\n\nI am not a Luddite, I am an electronics technician who is versed in several programming languages and works on multimillion dollar systems on a daily basis. I understand the technology. I understand mesh networks and zwave and sometimes needing repeaters, and geofences and \"solar flares\" sometimes disrupting RF etc. But I do not understand how a company who got bought by someone as big as Samsung can get away without a \"house cleaning\" when they release crap like this and have as many problems getting it together. Crowd funding has been over forever now, beta is over... Now get with it and fix s***!!!"}
{"Author": "Jason Sansone", "Date": "on October 1, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Step Backward", "Text": "The software is beta at best. A great deal of promised functionality, functionality that was in V1, is broken or just missing. Considering this is supposed to be from Samsung, and the launch was delayed from April, it's hard to have any patience for the developers \"just a few more days\" excuses."}
{"Author": "Jason W.", "Date": "on October 1, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Home Automation Hub!", "Text": "I love the new Smartthings v2, it is well put together and seems to just work. Though I have only been using it a few weeks I feel like it has a ton of potential for automating my home once I add more devices. This hub makes me want to buy more zwave devices. My first attempt at home automation was a Vera3 and it kind of worked but everything about it felt cheap and only half realized. With the Smartthings hub I feel like everything they are doing is well executed and i'm really excited to see the updates over the next year. This would be a 5 star review except for a few features that are missing and mentioned in my cons.\n\nPros:\n- No issues adding devices\n- Great community that is creating the apps that Smartthings doesn't seem to want to.\n- App is solid.\n- very responsive, ~1s for device response after sending a command.\n- It just works (which is very important in home automation)\n\nCons:\n- No multi user support yet, though they say it is coming.\n- No built in Dashboard style interface for wall mounted tablets.\n- Nest/Drop cam support are missing and aren't ever expected.\n- A lot of obvious apps require the community to come up with a solution like Code management of Zwave locks.\nNo wifi support so you cant walk around with the unit to include previously installed light switches, locks, etc. I had to walk around my house with a 150ft Ethernet cable which people don't normally have lying around their house."}
{"Author": "M. Sammon", "Date": "on September 30, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "this is by far the better of all smart home controllers bc you are not ...", "Text": "with all technology comes patience. but patience is always rewarded. this is by far the better of all smart home controllers bc you are not restricted to one brand. you can control multiple brand and growing bc of the developers community. plus its owned by samsung which means its not going under like other companies..wink wink ;)"}
{"Author": "Tor Tovsland", "Date": "on September 28, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good product but painful migration from hub version 1 to version 2", "Text": "I got this hub and followed the instructions by a fellow reviewer to just move my \"things\" in the API web site to the new hub, however that doesn't work; they show up but they don't talk to your new hub. Got an email from smartthings support, you have to manually remove \"things\" from the old hub, then add them to the new hub. I did all of that in about 30 minutes. The problem is that when you add a device to the new hub you need the device to be within 15 feet of the hub. I reconnected my thermostat by using a 50 ft ethernet cable to my hub. Not for the non-tech savy. 5 stars for the product and zero stars for the migration prosess = 3 stars"}
{"Author": "mmollat", "Date": "on September 28, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings Hub - HomeRun!", "Text": "I learned of this product from an email I received from Amazon Echo. Link Echo with SmartThings to get the best of home automation. Ordered a SmartThings outlet module as well as the Samsung SmartThing hub. Hub was obviously on backorder until the new hub came out in Sept. Day finally arrived, installed the hub and outlet for my TV. Then I linked it with Echo. For the first day, Alexa was control my TV with my voice. It was great! Come next day, I get a lovely message on my phone that the hub was inactive. Sure enough, checked the hub and no light. There was no activity light on the ethernet cable. Read on the support pages and followed their FAQs and my hub was dead. No biggie, request a new one from Amazon. This is why I love shopping at Amazon. Waited two days again and got another Hub. Same thing... Installed and once again, TV was working flawlessly with Alexa in controlling my TV. Next day arrives again, another lovely message on my phone, hub inactive. WTF?! Same behavior!! the Hub seems to be unresponsive! This time, I sent an email out to SmartThings support. Still haven't heard from them. I'm going to wait for one more day. If I dont hear from them, I'm just going to request a refund!\n\n****Update****\nAmazon and Smartthings worked collaboratively in helping me figure out the issues I was having. Turns out, I had a bad power supply. When I received my hub replacement, I replaced everything except for the power supply. So my issues continued even with the new hub. And to be clear the first hub was not the problem. The reason why it would work one day and fail the next was because it was running on batteries. When in battery mode, you only have about 12 hrs before it kills battery. Hence why the next morning my hub seemed to be non responsive. After working with Smartthings support, we identified the issue and they shipped me out a new power supply immediately.\n\nThe hub is working flawlessly, specially when paired with Echo! I want to thank Amazon support as well as Smartthings for helping me out! This product now deserves 5 star!"}
{"Author": "DLay", "Date": "on September 28, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cool and fun once everything is setup and configured", "Text": "I'm new to home automation and didn't have any previous hubs to compare to, but this hub is awesome and hooking it up to other smart devices was fun and easy. I don't have a lot of devices in my house but I can see people getting annoyed having to reconnect every device. I only have 5 devices connected and looking to add more in the future. I don't notice any weird long delay when manually switching off devices or when they're on a schedule. The SmartThings app works well, I did purposely try to break it by switching things on and off very fast just to experiment; saw there was a delay or inconsistency of what's being displayed as off but physically the device can actually be on. Other than that, I would recommend!"}
{"Author": "S.", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible customer support, buggy product, not enough logic in the app, needs an api", "Text": "I really want to like this thing... Unfortunately it stopped working. Suddenly it says that my hub is not connectable, and no matter what I try, I can't get it to connect.\n\nAnd unfortunately 4-5 days ago I tried to contact them, and have still received no response.\n\nedit: I ended up receiving a good unit and everything is working now. If I have time I will write more and change this review."}
{"Author": "M. Savage", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Glad I switched really like Smartthings hub.", "Text": "I've been dabbling with home automation over the last year and was frustrated with the wink hub I was using. With inconsistent performance and one bricked hub later I was about to pull it out but when I got the email that the pre-order of the second generation smartthings hub was ready I bought it that day. Now with a full week under my control I am so glad I switched platforms more on that in a bit, no doubt I was a little hesitant since I had about a dozen ge link bulbs and tripper door sensors I was worried I wouldn't be able to use them but after I migrated my 20+ lights and sensors over I was blown away. Not only did some of them work faster and worked as consistent as I expect out of a home automation system but some devices like my smartstrip and other zwave sensors displayed data like battery remaining and power consumption, I was not missing the wink platform at all now. One thing they advertised with the v2 smartthings hub is they run some apps locally so not every request has to go to the cloud this is very noticeable with the wink platform there would be times lights wouldn't even come on or when they were working there was the noticeable delay duty to other having to go out to the cloud and was very inconsistent. With this smartthings hub it is blazing fast like when I open a door or request a light or even let one of my motion sensors act as a switch the come on almost instantly. I've only had it a week but I'm really glad I spent the money."}
{"Author": "KYLE KNOLL", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great hub and easy to use", "Text": "I've have my new v2.0 hub for a few days and it has worked great so far! I've paired a douzen dimmer switches, some motion sensors, and a Honeywell thermostat. I learned quickly that my existing devices had to be removed from my old hub/network before I could discover them with this hub.\n\nThe only issue I've had to date it that when I create a Routine to dim a dimmer down to 10% it is still ver bright (much brighter than you'd expect for 10%)."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer (Canada)", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't connect, can't get it to work, slow customer response, version 2 not yet ready.", "Text": "I purchased the new Smartthings hub version 2 from Samsung about one week ago. I still can't get it to work after trying all the steps in the support and community sections of their website. The hub is just not responsive, can't connect and can't download the new firmware. According to their community blog, many bogus units were shipped since their new hub model was released in early September and many users are currently going through the same problems (and are very frustrated...). See their community blog. There is a full section on that.\n\nI tried to reach their customer support team. It took over 3 days to get a response. What they suggested i try did not work either. Seven days later and a bunch of hours lost, I am trying to return it, but I am still waiting on getting the details I need to do so...\n\nThis product is not ready. I would not recommend to buy it until Smartthings fix it. I hope this happens quickly."}
{"Author": "Pchamp", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simplifying device automation", "Text": "This is my first time owning a hardware automation unit. I own devices like Sonos, Hue bulbs, Alexa, Harmony and others. I've been using software and cloud solutions like Tasker and IFTTT to automate device tasks.\n\nNow using Smartthings, I am able to simplify the automation process. I really like the 'Routines' feature that allow auto control in one swoop. There are plenty of smart apps to automate just about whatever. I customize the more uniquely complex tasks like automatically changing bulbs to the exact color and shade that I want since the smart app only offer solid colors.\n\nI've run into a couple of errors but none have been show stoppers. As I add more zigbee/z-wave devices, I am becoming more satisfied with my purchase."}
{"Author": "Person from the USA", "Date": "on September 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "you'll know that they all look like a high school science project at best and absolute ...", "Text": "I come from many, many years of using Veralite. It's worked ok but if you have ever seen UI7 or used any of Vera apps, you'll know that they all look like a high school science project at best and absolute garbage at worst.\n\nI finally decided to dump Vera and buy this product. OMG. It's like I've been teleported from the old days of ntalk, Solaris OS and Netscape navigator. I successfully migrated all my switches and sensors and now am a happy user of a solid product.\n\nNote that the ability to add a family member is not working yet, so that's a disappointment. Everything else works great!"}
{"Author": "Eric Pryor", "Date": "on September 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "#1 Automation Hub", "Text": "There have been a few negative reviews here, but I'm not quite sure why. Mine works great. My network consists of 6 Kwikset locks, 2 Honeywell thermostats, 12 Aeon Labs outlets, 2 Linear garage door openers, and 35 Leviton light switches. All of them work just fine and I had no trouble pairing them. The responsiveness of the devices is almost instant and they report back to the hub almost instantly when you manually use them as well. I think people having the most problems are people that had the old hub and did not follow the migration instructions. This is the best automation hub out there right now, and I have tried a few. It is either natively compatible with tons of Z-wave, ZigBee, and WiFi devices, or someone from the community has written one that you can paste into your API for it to work. SmartThings is responsive to it's customer base and the tech support is fine (although through email)."}
{"Author": "JSS", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I hope you like being a beta tester", "Text": "I am very surprised this is a \"verson 2.0\" hub because it feels very unpolished and buggy. Basic features are not yet ready such as adding additional users, bluetooth connectivity, integration with Nest thermostats or Dropcam cameras, and no ability to change door lock codes etc. It's also a real shame you have to be within 10 feet of a device to pair it. Even my old Vera Lite hub had the option to run off batteries and allow you to bring the hub close to devices for pairing.\n\nI think Smartthings relies too heavily on the community. And while it is great having a community, finding what you need within the community can be a real chore. Smartthings Hub 2.0 will eventually be great. I think Samsung was just pushing to get product out the door and will update all the issues later. I wish I had known of these shortcomings before purchasing the unit because I didn't sign up to be a beta tester.\n\n**10/2/2015 UPDATE** A week after submitting a support ticket I finally received a reply from Smartthings support stating an update would be available on Tuesday, 9/29. Well, it is now Friday, 10/2 and there has been no update (I've been checking multiple times a day). All my comments from the beginning of this review are still accurate. I'll give Smartthings another couple weeks to get their act together before requesting a return."}
{"Author": "Mikey K.", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good for the DYIer", "Text": "got ours a couple days ago. setup was easy, the app handled everything. no problems so far! was able to pair up 3 devices, though it did take a bit of effort (which should be expected). imo, this device is a good middle ground between hiring an outside contractor and total DYI. its streamlines the work, but is definitely not 'easy', as I think many that are complaining expected. great product. happy to have it!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Okay...", "Text": "This product is okay. It constantly does not recognize when I am home unless I have the app open on my phone or until after I have already opened a door and by then the alarm has already been triggered. The app is terrible! There are always issues with it and it constantly stops working. The potential seems to be there but it needs a lot of work. The battery backup is pointless because you have no way of monitoring the device without being connected to your network and if you Internet goes out you also are unable to use the app even if your home network is intact. This is a major flaw, even my home a/v receiver app will work without internet."}
{"Author": "Nick Snyder", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy new user", "Text": "I have been using Staples Connect since the day it was released. Picked it up because of the local processing however they have basically abandoned it. Last major update was April '15 and it barely added anything. Anywho...\n\nI was very nervous switching to Smart Things but after a week with the hub I have to say I am very happy. There is a bit of a learning curve and some quirks to work out but once you get the hang of it, its a pretty solid system. The feature set compared to Staples connect is massive and I think its only going to get better.\n\nCustomer service is overwhelmed with requests and support so they delay in helping you is a few days. That being said, when they do get back to you, they are very helpful and honest. They will tell you if something is broken or disabled. Also, the Smart Things community is extremely active and helpful as well. While waiting for customer service to get back to you, I usually check the forums and can either find the answer or someone very willing to help.\n\nPersonally I am very glad I switched and look forward to things and features yet to come."}
{"Author": "Jonathon", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buggy Garbage", "Text": "Update! Some of the issues I was having with the app not responding and lack of status updates appears to have been corrected. I tried using it again today and everything worked as it should. Two stars until I can get EVERYTHING working as it should.\n\nTo preface: I have tried a lot of smart hub solutions and am very familiar with everything they can do, the bugs they have, and the overall reliability. I joined the Smart Things to an existing zwave network.\n\nI have been wasting hours upon hours setting this up only to have a horrid experience. There are just too much basic functionality that doesn't work correctly.\n*Can't add other users. WHAT?!\n*On setup, renaming a device, you had to click the device, click the menu for the device, and edit the device. I had to go back and forth twice for every single device I tried to rename because the screen wouldn't load. Then, once I renamed it and clicked save, it would error out have the time and not save the name. I would have to repeat the process.\n*Dimmer Switches are impossible to use. It has a little circle with a tiny puck on it. When you put your finger on the puck and try to spin it to dim the light, the whole damn screen goes with it. It is ridiculous.\n*I have a Honeywell zwave thermostat and I am unable to control the fan, it is always stuck on auto.\n*Updates from devices are VERY slow. If I turned I light on, I should see an update within a minute on the app. Nope, I never saw it update the true status, I would close the app/open the app, and wait. It still thought my GE switches were in the last state the app left them in. Absolutely useless.\n\nTo top all of that off, you HAVE to use the app for setup and control. Smart Things has a VERY primitive interface on their website to do very basic setup tasks but that is it. No website to truly control it from a PC.\n\nI currently have a Vera 3 which has been reliable over the last 3 years that I have been using it. I was just sick of firmware updates constantly breaking things and no IFTTT support. I wanted something with a cleaner app as well. I REALLY thought Smart Things would be my answer. I think it will be one day, but as of now, Version 2 is a step back from Version 1."}
{"Author": "PJ", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I now like my SmartThings", "Text": "I now like my SmartThings. I especially applaud the fantastic customer support. I received some SmartThings outlets that would not pair with my SmartThings hub. Customer service worked with me to eventually, determine that the outlets were defective. They sent me new outlets. Now all is good (well better) when using SmartThings.\n\nI didn't give them 5 stars because they have some issues to work through as far as adding other members of your househole and having the hub realize when they arrive/leave my home. Would like that to be tracked via the mobile device.\n\nBeing an early adopter takes patience. Working with these kind and smart people at SmartThings makes working through the problems, palatable!\n\n*****************************************************************************************************************************************************************\nI decided to buy Smartthings because Echo will integrate with it. I was excited about the possibilities to create a wireless smart home. After weeks of anticipation, my Smartthings 2.0 hub arrived. What a let down! None of my devices are discoverable. My app crashed in the middle of the set up. So many issues that I don't know where to begin to find the root cause. I contacted customer support (which is only via email because they're slammed with complaints) but have yet to hear back from them.\n\nI'm extremely disappointed. First impressions are lasting. This is the last time I'll deal with Smartthings! Giving them 1 star was generous."}
{"Author": "bobfromholland", "Date": "on September 25, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much Faster than V1", "Text": "I just replaced my V1 hub with the new V2 hub. The V2 hub is much faster and more responsive. I unpaired all the old Z-Wave devices and repaired them to the new hub. Everything now works the same as before except much faster. I did run into a couple of issues which I'll explain.\n\nI discovered that my Aeon Z-Wave repeater had died completely when I tried to unpair it. It was under warranty and has been returned for replacement.\n\nI had difficulty unpairing my Aeon Labs Aeon Labs ZW078-A Z-Wave Heavy Duty Smart Switch using the V1 hub. I found from the SmartThings user community that I could also use the V2 hub to unpair a device even if the device was connected to the V1 hub. The V2 hub was able to unpair device that the V1 hub could not. Also, I wasn't able to repair the ZW078-A switch successfully until I factory reset it by holding its button for greater than 20 seconds. As a bonus the ZW078-A switch now automatically identifies as \"Aeon Outlet\" and works without a custom device driver."}
{"Author": "giovanna free", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "big let down", "Text": "I was very excited to get this! However, i am very disappointed in this unit.\nI have a schlage and kwikset z wave locks. The unit does not poll the node frequently. That means if you manually lock or unlock it, it can be 24 hrs before it updates the status. Thats horrible!! Also, ypu cannot creat PIN numbers or get notifications on who is using them. I asked before and they said this was a feature they were going to include. I emailed customer support and they said that this feature will be coming soon (so like next year).\n\nThis unit has great potential with accepting z wave zigbee and wifi. Also, the bluetooth feature is not yet active. Another let down. The unit had great options but for the person who loves tinkering and setting up cool scenes, i feel this not worth it. I'll be sending this back and buying a vera edge or another veralite."}
{"Author": "S. Burns", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Manufacturing defects - avoid!", "Text": "As many others have reported, the reset button is misaligned with the case which is causing continual reboots. Really poor quality and unusable"}
{"Author": "eid8801", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An improved hub prepping for the future", "Text": "Youre really buying potential here. The bluetooth radio, usb are not not enabled right now and migrating from version 1 to version 2 is a bit of a pain. But ver 2 has battery backup, more local functions for more reliable function rather than relying on cloud for everything. (Local function is limited to lights so far but this will increase as smartthings gets going).\nwink is not looking too healthy while smartthings has samsungs support. So at least st looks secure for now. You need to read what is compatible with st. As smart device manfucturers become more proprietary, some will not work with smartthings well. For example, nest devices... But smartthings is an open system and has potential to work with most smart devices- zwave, zigbee, bluetooth. But politics and economics may interfere. St has a thriving community of developers making smartapps even if a device is not officially supported."}
{"Author": "Gina's Mom", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth the powder", "Text": "I have been using V1 of the smartthings hub for quite a while now. In general, I was satisfied with it, even though it would periodically lose connection my Belkin Wemo switches. But I have been trying for 3 days now to get the V2 hub set up. I am really beginning to regret my purchase. Especially since now my V1 hub has lost control of virtually all of my devices. As my grandma would have said - this thing isn't worth the powder to blow it to h*ll."}
{"Author": "Nikolay", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Well built and solid item.", "Text": "Looks solid."}
{"Author": "David D.", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great experience so far", "Text": "I delayed buying a V1 hub once I learned about the V2 hub coming out. I have not purchased any other smart hubs so I'm coming at this as a person fresh into the smart home arena. My initial impression is very positive overall. As of now I only have a handful of sensors set up so maybe things will change over time, but for now I am happy with my purchase. Here's my experience.\n\nI get my V2 hub and start the setup through the app. The first time I input my Welcome Code it doesn't accept it so I get a little worried, but on the second try it works. I have already replaced one of my light switches with a GE ZWave switch so I go to add the device to my hub. The switch is about 10 feet away from the hub. The hub is searching for ZWave devices, but cannot see anything even as I push the button on my GE switch which supposedly puts it in pairing mode. I trying moving the hub closer and still no luck. I reset the hub a couple of times and start the pairing process again, but still no luck. I do a little research on the forums, but don't really get any helpful info. I go try to pair one more time and suddenly it works. I don't think I did anything differently than before, but I was happy to finally get it added. Once it was added I felt the setup for the device was pretty straight forward. I then install a second GE switch and am able to get it paired with my hub on the first try. I then install a GE in-wall electrical outlet, but I cannot get it to pair. I move the hub within 10 feet of the outlet, do multiple resets on the hub and it still cannot see the outlet. After about 20 mins I do a little research on the Internet and learn you can do an \"exclude\" function on the outlet which I think is about like a reset. I do this and am instantly able to pair the outlet with my hub. I install another light switch and it works right away. I then am able to pair a garage door opener on the first try. Finally, I install one last GE light switch identical to the others I have installed. I am able to pair this one immediately, however during the configuration process I keep getting an message saying \"an unexpected error has occurred\" and am not able to finish the configuration on the switch. I am able to control the switch, but it will not allow me to rename it or add it to a room group. I do a little research in the SmartThings forums and learn there is a website you can go to and configure your hub and associated devices (ide.smartthings.com). I go to the website and am able to rename the device and add it to a room group. Initially, though, the light switch does show the correct name in the app, but it still says it is \"Not Configured\". Since the device is fully functional I don't worry about it too much, but I guess my OCD just doesn't like having that \"not configured\" device showing up in my Marketplace. A few hours later, though, I decided to try and run the configuration again and it works. So I'm not sure what the problem was, but it did work itself out.\n\nI have set up a few scheduled events to turn a lamp on and off at certain times and to turn my porch light on and off at sunset and sunrise respectively. Those have worked flawlessly so far. I felt the Smart Lighting was pretty intuitive and easy to work with. Also, you can set up scenes where basically with one push of a button it will do multiple events. So for instance when I push \"Good Night\" it turns off all of my interior lights, but leaves the porch light on. I could also have it do things like lock the doors, but I don't have any smart locks yet.\n\nI will say there is a little bit of a learning curve in the app and it does still need some refinement. For example, why do I go to the \"Marketplace\" to add new devices? That sounds like where I should just buy devices (though you can do that as well). I also wish the app would be a little more useful for troubleshooting connection issues. Saying \"an unexpected error occurred\" doesn't really help much. Is any error really expected? How about telling me something more specific like is the issue with the app or the hub or the device?\n\nObviously, at this point things are still pretty basic for me. I am going to add some more light switches, a couple of motion sensors, and a smoke detector. I will see if I can get lights to react properly with the motion sensors and smoke detector.\n\nOverall, I'm happy with my purchase. Despite the small amount of frustration with a couple of the devices I think this thing has great potential.\n\n**Update 9/28/2015** - I am now up to 20 devices and everything is still working well. Most of them are light switches, but I also have a smoke detector and a Foscam that I am using as a motion detector (with a third party smart app). The response time of all my devices has been good, usually no more than a second with the exception of the Foscam. Since I am using a third party smart app for that it processes through the cloud. Any function/scene that uses only approved smart apps and approved devices will process locally and will process a lot quicker, which most of my devices and smart apps are.\n\nThe only real problem I have is when the smoke detector goes off SmartThings hub should send me a text message on my phone and turn on all the lights in my house. The hub does send a text message, but it does not turn on the lights. Other than that, though, I have been able to set up all the other functions I want. I have a couple of motion detectors coming later this week and a garage door opener coming next week so we will see how those integrate.\n\n**Update 9/29/2015** - I just added a couple of motion sensors to my hub. They were easy to connect and work as advertised so now I have a basic security system. If motion is detected while the system is armed I get a text message/push notification on my phone and all of the lights in my house turn on. The hub itself has been working great for me. I will still say the SmartThings app needs a little work to make it a better layout and a little more user friendly, but overall I'm still pleased.\n\n**Update 10/11/2015** - I have added a couple of open/close sensors for my front and rear doors and added my LiftMaster garage door opener. Overall, I am still happy with SmartThings, but I am removing one star and going down to 4 stars. My main issue right now is the SmartThings support. I still have not been able to resolve the issue I mentioned above with the smoke detector. Support takes about 3 or 4 days to reply. I understand they may be backed up on support tickets with the initial launch, but then again doesn't that speak something about the state of the product they launched? My initial support e-mail got a reply within a day, but since then it's been about 3 or 4 days between each e-mail. The support rep keeps asking me questions mostly in quickly written e-mails only a few sentences long. They have only made a couple of quick suggestions, none of which worked and one I had already tried anyway. Basically, at this point support is worthless for me. It is only because everything else I have set up works as I want it to that I'm still satisfied overall with my hub. I truly hope they do not end up alienating a lot of customers due to the excessively long support times. They should have hired more people to cover the initial surge of support tickets that often come with product launches. They also need to get to redesigning the app to make it more user friendly and adding useful features like grouping items together in other categories besides Rooms.\n\n-- UPDATE 12/1/2016\nWhile there have been a few ups and downs with this system overall I would say there are a lot more ups. I am still happy with this and I have seen improvements in reliability and functionality since I first bought this as the SmartThings team continues to make improvements. The app was also redesigned so it is better than before, though it might still need a little polishing to make it a little more user friendly. As I have added several devices since my first review they have all pretty much worked flawlessly. I have added a couple of Hue color bulbs and they work great, though there is a lack of color control for routines. You can change colors manually or for the Alarm function (i.e. they can turn red if the security system goes off), but I cannot find any way to change them through a normal routine. Also, SmartThings will integrate with the Echo so if you spend $50 on and Echo Dot you can have some pretty cool voice control of your home! It's not perfect as it is mostly just basic functionality (I can turn my hue bulbs on/off, but cannot change the color through voice), but it is still pretty useful and fun."}
{"Author": "Donald Friese", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The center piece of any home automation system.", "Text": "Amazing product. The V2 is worth the upgrade. Allows more functionality with newer products. Easy setup and the BEST customer support bar none. Highly recommend over any other home automation hub."}
{"Author": "Peter M", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't work, poor tech support", "Text": "Product detects none of my devices like it should. Tech support has not been available or responded at all."}
{"Author": "Alex", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub and Easy to Setup", "Text": "I decided to take a plunge on the smart things as I was waiting for the v2 iteration. I read all of the complaints regarding the first generation of the hub. With that being said, it's a great tool to automate your home. So far I have 3 light switches with dimmers connected to the hub. The whole setup process took less than 10 minutes. I am a technical person, and I hate to read the manuals. The hub must be plugged in to you router. In my case, I have it plugged into the 8-port TrendNet switch which connects to the Airport Extreme router. You then need to input the 6 digit product code which is on the back of the manual. After that, the hub quickly found my light switches. Overall my satisfaction is 9/10 so far. I'd like the landing page on the application to point to something different other than \"home security\". As I am currently using another company for my house alarm and smoke/water detection, I find this feature of the app not useful at all. What's great about the app is an ability to download 3rd party apps as well, and use them to create \"themes\". For instance, good bye theme could dim the lights as you're falling asleep and turn them off completely. There are a good 20 other apps that can help you automate lighting alone. Overall I'm a happy camper, and this is definitely what I was looking for plus more!"}
{"Author": "penguin22", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One hub to rule them all", "Text": "I bought the SmartThings Hub directly from SmartThings after researching and not being pleased with various aspects of other options. This is my first entry into Home Automation and was paired with a number of GE switches, dimmers, outlets, along with two Nest Protects, some Aeon Labs and Monoprice products.\n\nInstallation was very simple and the first z-wave switch went in with no problem and allowed for control from both Android and Windows Phone straight away. I have since expanded to 20 connected devices and have added automated actions based on sunrise, sunset and specifically timed events. Integration with Amazon Alexa is natively supported and is an amazing benefit as I can turn on and off lights by voice, which is surprisingly useful; e.g. run upstairs and ask Alexa to shut off my office lights that I left on downstairs!\n\nThe capabilities and open nature are a huge plus with this hub over other options; for example, Nest Protects are not natively supported and Windows Phone does not have an official Nest app. Through the community, I was able to add code that provided support for both the wired and wireless Nest Protect and I now have status and can create actions based on the smoke/CO2 detection.\n\nOne of my concerns with a HA hub was performance and consistency of commands. Having read about the, now defunct, Wink hub, people mentioned a fairly consistent 3 second delay. with the SmartThings Hub, whether through the application, automation, or through integration with the Aeon Labs Minimote and Amazon Alexa, actions are immediate. A plus of the second gen hub is local processing, which I have nothing to compare to, but I have already benefited from the battery backup as I had some electric work being done and maintained control of wireless sensors and geo fencing (mobile presence) with no power to the house.\n\nAs you can tell, I am a happy camper. If there is one area that I am excited for, it would be the reported updated app version that is expected sometime in the near future. This came directly from SmartThings staff from the community section of their site. The current app works, but there is room for improvement. Ultimately I will not knock the hub for this as it works fine across platforms and did not use the older app, which I have read had better functionality in areas. I imagine the new app was necessary for the new hub and parity with improved functionality is coming soon."}
{"Author": "Dpmartin", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Still in Beta Testing", "Text": "I was disappointed with my v1 hub, but held out hope for v2. I had v1 installed in my lake home and the plan was to upgrade to v2. When I did, lights came on randomly and I lost the ability to control my lighting. Then I switched back to the v1 unit and after 14 hours it isn't working as well as before. I have control of about 20% of what had been installed under v1. Will the v1 unit regain control of my lighting? I don't know yet.\n\nMy plans to install another v2 unit in my Winter home have been cancelled. Plans to tell my friends how great it all worked out are also cancelled. Bad reviews, bad word of mouth. SmartThings is toast...Can anyone recommend where to go from here?\n\nAmazon should make it clear that shoppers should check the reviews of v1 and v2 separately. Neither system is ready for prime time. The fact that Amazon's Echo supports SmartThings was the main selling point to me. Now backing of a product by Amazon means less in my mind than it did last week."}
{"Author": "brianwallen75", "Date": "on September 24, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hopefully they expand support especially now that they are part of Samsung but I am a little disappointed that I could not just", "Text": "I had high hopes that I could use my existing z-wave products with this. Only some products are supported. Hopefully they expand support especially now that they are part of Samsung but I am a little disappointed that I could not just hook up my existing thermostat"}
{"Author": "John K. Russell", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good", "Text": "i received my Smartthings hub 2 today. In about 4 hours have it setup and working with several devices. All but one device paired the first time i tried and one took about 20 minutes to unpair from my Veralite and repair. Pairing with Amazon Echo worked on the first try."}
{"Author": "Phil Miller", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Upgrade to the SmartThings 2.0 Hub, it's worth the effort.", "Text": "I pre-ordered/purchased the SmartThings 2.0 Hub directly from SmartThings Shop, however, I have been so pleased with both the product and the support I received setting it up, that I felt compelled to post a review on Amazon since this is where I normally buy just about everything. I had been a SmartThings 1 Hub / System user for quite some time (and had over 60 \"things\"). I was really apprehensive about upgrading because there is currently no tool for migrating to a new hub, or easy upgrade path. At the same time, I wanted to experience the advantages of the new Hub (i.e. battery backup, works even when Internet Connection down, video capabilities, etc.) so I decided to move forward. In preparation for the migration, I logged into https://graph.api.smartthings.com/login/auth and took some screen shots of my device list (to capture any changes I had made to device types) and also made note of (and captured edit screen for) everything listed as \"in use by\" for the more complicated device setups I had done on the the SmartThings 1 Hub (i.e. - my DSC Alarm System integration, configuration for Garage Doors, etc.). After reviewing this article on the migration process (https://support.smartthings.com/hc/en-us/articles/205956110-How-to-migrate-your-SmartThings-setup-to-Hub-v2) I initiated a chat session with SmartThings support to ask for their assistance on getting started with this process. I worked with a technician named Ryan who was incredibly helpful. In fact, he told me that I could schedule a time to get a dedicated resource to help me with the migration (which I promptly did) and he (Ryan) was assigned to assist me. He spent the the better part of 5 hours helping me get all of my \"things\" properly removed, getting my old hub disassociated from my account, and then getting the new hub up and going . He explained the importance of the sequence in which things should be added, and stuck with me on the phone nearly the entire time. Towards the end, once I had the hang of things on the strategy and process for getting everything added back to the new hub, he had to drop off the call to deal with another scheduled meeting. He promised to call me back after that meeting to make sure I had been able to complete the process and to help me with any remaining issues, which he promptly did. He was able to help me get my final issues resolved and when we got off the phone (which was about 6pm his time on Friday night), my entire system was back up and working again on SmartThings Hub 2.0. I still had a lot of alerting rules, etc. to setup, however, everything was properly setup and communicating with the new Hub. The support I received was way above and beyond what I am used to getting from other companies and I would highly recommend this product (in part) for this reason.\n\nIt has now been a few weeks since I completed the installation and I could not be more pleased with the new product. In addition to being noticeably faster, When a motion detector detects motion or another trigger action occurs (i.e. door opens or closes) the programmed responses are immediate (no perceptible delay). I have already had an unplanned power outage and seen the product work as advertised with battery operated devices (such as my door locks) during the outage. I love the way that everything is grouped together by rooms with the new 2.0 version of their mobile app. By upgrading to the 2.0 version of the hub, I have addressed many of my concerns about the limitations of the system if the power or internet goes down, I also have a faster and more reliable system, and I have laid the foundation for integrating video capabilities for improved home security. In summary > upgrade to the SmartThings 2.0 Hub, it's worth the effort."}
{"Author": "Intellibeam", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung SmartThings Hub v2 unboxing by Intellibeam.com", "Text": " Quick unboxing of the Samsung SmartThings Hub version 2 released September 2015."}
{"Author": "Photon", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Migration to V2 is a pain", "Text": "Migration to V2 is a pain. Have to delete everything, create new account and good luck detecting devices. My Hub V2 won't detect my devices that all exist and work perfectly well on V1. Guess I got one of the bad ones I heard about. Sending it back and hope I can go back to V1."}
{"Author": "BioHacker", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I really like the ability to schedule and link events via the ...", "Text": "Was excited to get the new, updated Samsung SmartThings Hub. The SmartThings hub apparently no longer accepts many Z-Wave devices that I already own and have been using with my Wink Hub. Today I just added a GE Z-wave light switch, and only the Wink hub, but not the SmartThings hub would find it. It also doesn't appear to work with my Nest 1080 camera.\n\nI really like the ability to schedule and link events via the SmartThings App (and wished Wink had this too) but I can't afford to throw out all of the door, window, and motion sensors (all Z-Wave) that I already have, to get the more expensive ones that Samsung is selling on their SmartThings website. Having a small group of proprietary devices is a poor idea, in my opinion, and unless Samsung figures out a way to make this work with a broader range of Z-Wave devices, I'll be forced to return it."}
{"Author": "Chaaad", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent Support by the Smartthings Staff Overcomes Initial Issues", "Text": "Update:\nWithin a few hours of my original review below, I was contacted by Smartthings Support with a few suggestions to remedy my issues. (That is huge because with most technical support you have to go through a call tree and then wait on hold before finally reaching someone reading a script with little technical knowledge of the product.) Anyway, one of the issues was resolved by doing a Z-Wave Network Repair and the other turned out to be a hardware problem with the Z-Wave device. I was extremely impressed with the timeliness of the call and the professionalism and knowledge of Riley, the Support Tech. The only reason I'm not changing my review to five stars is because of the lack of migration support. I was still able to complete the migration in an afternoon, so I can live with that.\n\nOriginal Review:\nI was a V1 user and everything others have said about the painful migration to V2 is true. Samsung provides no path/assistance so it's basically starting over - actually it's a little more difficult than starting over because you first have to disassociate all your devices from the old hub before you start associating them with the new hub. That means you have to dig up manuals for all those devices to ensure you know how to accomplish this.\n\nIn addition to those issues, it appears that the new hub has a shorter range than the old one. I have two devices (Aeon Open/Close Sensor & GE Outdoor Smart Switch) that worked fine before, but don't work with the new hub. I was able to associate them with the new hub but they don't respond to commands. I tested the range by bringing them closer to the hub and they all worked fine. Then I moved them back to their original location and they stopped working again.\n\nAnd finally, all this touting the \"local processing\", I just haven't seen any difference in the speed or reliability of the system because of this.\n\nSo it comes down to whether or not you see the battery backup as a big enough advantage for all the disadvantages. I don't."}
{"Author": "Jon", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Steaming Pile of Rubbish", "Text": "What a steaming pile of rubbish this white plastic box is - I seriously cannot believe that I actually purchased this item thinking great I can link all my gear together - wrong - LIFX does not work, SONOS deletes it's self every time the APP open up - You cannot control SONOS - This plastic piece of Junk would not even boot up when plugged in - Customer Service had to reset it twice and then it just got stuck trying to connect it - then the 'things' (further pieces of plastic which are so cheaply made they rattle ) don't work and you have to pull them apart to reset them and then they still don't work. It looks cheap, and performs cheaply because it is cheap.\nThis is the VERY low end of Home Automation hence the price tag - you get what you pay for at the end of the day... rubbish!"}
{"Author": "Spinoza", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I purchased the original system which was a frustrating, ...", "Text": "I purchased the original system which was a frustrating, unreliable POS. I am reluctant to shell out a hundred bucks just to be another beta tester of their system."}
{"Author": "Kurt B.", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Horrible migration from v1 to v2", "Text": "What a pain in the ...... Horrible migration from v1 to v2. I am an early adopter and this product makes me want to give up on my smart home dreams. If you have a few hours to waste and the patience of a Saint give it a shot...... Mine is going back."}
{"Author": "Tim Steele", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An admitted fan of SmartThings - and the new Hub2", "Text": "I've been a SmartThings user for about a year now. Home automation is a fast-moving, ever-changing world. Not everything is roses. I've been very vocal at times when things weren't working like I wanted them to. But I do believe SmartThings is the way to go. They are ahead of the curve and their products are becoming more varied, stable, and robust.\n\nA warning to Hub1 users who might not have heard this - there's no migration process for moving your devices from the hold hub to the new one. They are working on a migration tool, but it doesn't exist yet. If the prospect of uninstalling all your SmartApps, then devices, then resinstalling them one at a time sounds too daunting, hold off for now.\n\nBut I got my hub up and running with minimal effort and had migrated about 70 devices over a weekend. Everything is working as well (or better) than it did before."}
{"Author": "pups_", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I just bought the Samsung SmartThings Hub and it is so much better. I think a lot of people that like ...", "Text": "I did my homework before but decided to choose the wink hub 1st because it is cheaper. I made a mistake. I just bought the Samsung SmartThings Hub and it is so much better. I think a lot of people that like the wink hub did not try the new Samsung SmartThings Hub so they don't know the difference. You can do your own research but from my own experience, the SmartThings Hub is a lot easier to setup, so far it's working great so it's more reliable. The respond is faster too when you turn on and off your lights. There is a delay with the wink hub for me when I turn on and off my lights with GE in wall switches."}
{"Author": "Long Johnson", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "BUYER BEWARE: BAD BATCH OF UNITS", "Text": "There is a defective batch of hubs floating around. The SmartThings forums has a long thread going on with people having all kinds of problems getting this thing set up. It is sticking at the \"Setting up your hub\" screen and is completely unusable. They are sending out $100 white bricks and not acknowledging it nor do they have the support capability to handle the demand right now as they have disabled their live chat.\n\nI just had to personally return mine after wasting hours trying to figure out what the heck was wrong with this thing. I don't know if linking is allowed here but just do a google search for \"stuck setting up hub\" with the quotation marks and the forum thread is the first result. It's too bad, I was hoping to get into home automation but we are off to a really bad start here in terms of customer service and the product itself."}
{"Author": "NAF", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Defective Units, Grinding Slow Support", "Text": "1. If you want to deal with a company that only offers support via e-mail (with turnaround times greater than 2 days) then you should go for this hub.\n\n2. I purchased the hub and they ended up sending defective units to a number of customers- The MAC addresses on the NICs of these units do not register correctly with smartthings. In the end, what you have is a brick sitting there with a green light and you can't do anything with it.\n\n3. Their support is slammed... if you have an extensive setup, I guarantee that you will run into problems migrating from whatever else platform or even the v1 hub. Forget about hearing back from their support in team in any decent amount of time. I have yet to hear back from them. Smartthings dropped the ball on this v2 hub launch- they do not have enough support staff to handle the overflowing number of issues. Just check out their forums.\n\nEDIT: They did just now offer to replace the hub with expedited shipping and threw in a free sensor for the trouble.\n\nEDIT 2: Changing rating to 4 stars: I was overnighted a new hub and I am glad to report that while my initial experience with the defective hub was disappointing, after receiving the new device (and the free multi sensor that they threw in for the inconvenience), the hub lives up to the expectations. The response times on the devices is much faster than the old hub and setting it up was a breeze. Their support, while slow, did end up taking care of the issue I had earlier... I just wish they had more support staff to deal with the huge influx of new users to this platform and the general v2 launch. In the end, the hub does work well and the integrations and community that Smartthings has is pretty much unmatched (except for maybe OpenHAB)."}
{"Author": "Anthony", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, works great so far", "Text": "Easy setup, works great so far. Using it for simple controls (timers, auto locks, etc.) So far no complaints."}
{"Author": "Jacques", "Date": "on September 22, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't upgrade ! it forces you to delete everything you've done and start from scratch... Huge FAIL.", "Text": "Huge Mistake and a Colossal pain..\n\nFirst off let me start by stating that i'm a huge Home automation fan and have been using Smarttings successfully for quite some time... I have a mish-mash of items such as Hue bulbs, Zwave dimmers/switches, Smartthigns water sensors, Sonos, amazon echo/alexa and even an IR blaster to control the TV via a Smartapp that i wrote..... So effectively, i was ALL IN on Smartthings and spent Hours and Days setting up a house with sensors in the attic and every conceivable room in the house.\n\nNow here comes the new HUB. I ordered it because i figured performance might be a little better and it might have some cool new features i could leverage. I get the new hub, plug it in and i figured it would upgrade my old stuff to the new hub.... WRONG.... After a contacting support ( Have to give the support guys kudos... they are very helpful ) I was told that you have to delete every thing you had and start everything from scratch ... you have to remove all your smart apps, locations, Macros,Nest integration, etc...... And of course the device discovery with the new hub isn't working.\n\nAt this point i feel like the product managers at Smartthings are completely disrespectful of my time. When you sat around the table to discuss upgrade i can't believe you thought to yourself... forget the customers , their time and investment in the platform isn't worth protecting...\n\nShame on you for disrespecting your customer's time.\n\nI can't wait to see what Google/Nest does with the REVOLV acquisition , because i will be first in line to switch over.\n\nSorry Smarttings, You just lost your biggest fan and frankly former product advocate and evangelist..."}
{"Author": "Richard N Kidd", "Date": "on September 21, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung has destroyed a great product", "Text": "We received the SmartThings hub today, and we were looking forward to the 2nd gen device, after enjoying the 1st-gen device. As of now, only one of us in the household is able to use it. When we tried to add me to the account it says this feature is \"coming in the future.\" What??? Being able to have multiple people associated with the hub is one of the most prominent features of V1. I am also unable to delete the old hub from my account, and we have had a ton of issues with setup. Samsung has successfully ruined this product."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on September 21, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good bye Smart Things, shame on you, Samsung, for putting your name on this lame product.", "Text": "UPDATE:\nSmarttings hub is completely useless piece of plastic if your Internet is down, your alarm setup will be doomed. Have no idea why they even bother with backup batteries?\n\nVerdict : so far it's still a lame startup project.\n\nwell, just received it today and first impression is way below average:\n\n1. Android soft is VERY laggy and I'm using S5 which is a pretty fast smart phone. App constantly freezes, refuses to respond, location settings are horrible.\n2. There's no way to use your Z-Wave door lock as a security device trigger or use it in presence mode setup.\nYes, you can register it from Security Devices menu by selecting Door Locks but you can't use it in actual security automation!\nThis is just lame, and may be the reason I'll return this whole bundle back to Samsung to work on it a bit more before start selling unfinished, untested product.\n3. oh yeah, you \"allowed\" to use only few \"approved\" cameras which look like toys!\n\nLooking towards Nexia, seems more serious people are working there, ready to pay $9/month just to quit from this small kids playground called \"home automation when it works\"\n\nUPDATE:\n\nI've decided to simply return this undone product until Amazon's return window are still open.\nLike other customers said \"I don't want to be a free beta tester\".\nI've been waiting for the All-In-One home automation solution but after trying Smart Things I realize that my dreams are far to come true.\nThe brain of their system is their App which is simply horrible example of home automation app:\nIt's absolutely non intuitive, non logical, glitchy and very, very far from all-in-one solution.\nYou have to \"install\" endless numbers of in-app add-on apps to make you home automation more or less possible, more than half of these add-on apps are written by volunteers developers!!! and in general the idea of installing dozens of add-on apps is crap and non sense.\nI can simply download separate manufacturer app for each of my devices and I don't need this crappy app storage named Smart Things App which is missing so many basic features!\n\nGood bye Smart Things, shame on you, Samsung, for putting your name on this lame product."}
{"Author": "K. K", "Date": "on September 20, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Be wary if you already have V1 of this hub! You will not be able to migrate and be ready to call support and wait days", "Text": "Edit: I decided that a one star review is not fair as the ST hub and ecosystem are really the best out there. That said... support is beyond lackluster and needs serious work. Migration needs addressed for V1 to V2 hub users.\n\nSamsung/Smartthings provides no migration path for existing customers. If you own a v1 hub you will NOT be able to migrate your devices to the v2 hub without manually removing and excluding (where necessary).\n\nOn top of that this migration process is broken and ST was aware of this before shipping these new hubs. Many users have spent 10 hours or more just getting things moved only to find out that clearing out the old hub fails with errors (meaning you cannot add your new v2 hub to your account) so they (including myself) have to sit and wait however many days it's going to take for ST support to respond to an email to \"clean out our profile.\"\n\nIt's clear all of this was known before shipping but never made clear to purchasers until after receiving their units.\n\n(If you are a v1 hub user) Pass on this one (for now) or you will be in for a ton of headache."}
{"Author": "Dave Points", "Date": "on September 20, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "a", "Text": "Ordered Sept 2015..don't do as I did. this arrived much faster than advertised only two days when I was expecting this and take a month. Unfortunately after much research I've determined that this app can only be used by one person in the household at one time. This makes it worthless to multiple user household this should have been advertised."}
{"Author": "Nate P.", "Date": "on September 20, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Like it much more than Vera Edge so far", "Text": "Received this earlier today and just finished moving all my devices over from my Vera Edge to the new SmartThings v2 hub. While Vera has significantly improved the experience over the last year, interacting with SmartThings seems to be much easier and faster. SmartThings also seems to have more and better maintained apps than Vera does for UI7. For devices/services that aren't officially supported (such as MyQ or Nest), there's an awesome developer community with apps / plugins available to manually install--I found this manual installation process to be pretty easy (though I'm in IT, so maybe I'm biased). Battery backup is also a plus.\n\nI would recommend SmartThings v2 to anyone looking to get started in home automation and not wanting a second job in maintaining the system."}
{"Author": "Jim H.", "Date": "on September 17, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Might be a great product, but I'm so annoyed by the setup that I'll never know.", "Text": "First thing: I never tried this V2 hub. Turns out there is no migration tool for my V1 hub, which means I'd need to spend hours reconnecting and reconfiguring my switches and settings. Would rather spend that time moving to a more robust, better supported system, so I returned the device without using it. The setup is a bummer and there was no warning in advance, so I only learned about the requirement when I read the migration instructions online.\n\nSo here it is: a one-star review by someone who's not used the product."}
{"Author": "Jason", "Date": "on September 7, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One of the best that are out there right now - But the HA sector needs Improvement!", "Text": "Let me start by saying I enjoy this product. I love HA, and tinkering.\n\nIn the Home automation industry I own: Amazon Echo (BTW buy this now!), Samsung SmartThings Hub, VeraLite, Wink, and Harmony Hub.\n\nSome of these work in conjunction with others, some don't. There are a lot of immature developing systems in the industry- there are ups and downs to all of them.\n\nWhat this is not:\nThis is not a system for the light hearted. This is not a system for non-technical persons that won't spend the time to get it the way they want. This is not an inexpensive hobby.\n\nThis is not a \u201cHome Control Device\u201d\n\nWhat it is:\nA means to Automate anything your heart desires. You may need a little know how, patience, and ingenuity but just about anything is possible. Just because I said it\u2019s possible does not mean it\u2019s inexpensive or easy. Some things will take a lot of work to do the way you want.\n\nThis is a \u201cHome Automation Device\u201d\n\nPros:\nIf you like to tinker, you can automate just about anything with a little know how, and patience. They have an amazing developer community that will likely jump at your problems and many will offer to code things for you.\n\nDevices are pretty easy to add and automate as long as they are on the officially supported list. This list seems to make pretty good progress, they are continually adding items.\n\nI cannot say enough about the many, many helpful community members, but please Search topics, and try to find your probably already answered questions!\n\nI have never personally contacted support, but am told that they are extremely helpful.\n\nSince I\u2019ve had it the box seems like it's been pretty reliable.\n\nI am by no means a coder - but it is relatively easy to add non-officially supported devices with the help of many tutorials on the community site (they are also currently being cross referenced and organized into a non-official community driven Wikipedia!)\n\nAmazon Echo Integration - I can tell Alexa to turn on or off any of my lights, it\u2019s Greatly increased WAF.\n\nLogitech Harmony Integration - I can set up automations to dim lights when watching tv at night, turn them up when paused, etc. (I haven't personally gotten into this yet, because it is not user friendly according to community. But I will be working on it soon when I have time.\n\nLogitech Harmony Controlled through Echo - Yes you can set it up so that you can tell Alexa to Start Movie mode, Turn on the DVD player dim the lights start the popcorn, Again told it's not user friendly but I will be getting into this when I have time.\n---\nCons:\nThere is not TOTAL local control. You have to have an internet connection to run anything that is not official supported for sure - this likely won't ever change.\nIn particular this makes using ST as a DIY security system (which they are currently trying to market it as) iffy at best. On this same subject there I am not using st in this manner Strictly because the system isn't mature enough. Look at the community posts about this if it\u2019s your intended use. Presence Tags, Beacons, locks, and Keypads desperately need more support and the only thing that would make me use it in this manner with a Siren (#2 in b/e deterrent) is local control over all security devices including locks. However to quote a community member \"My use case is not your use case\". You may find \"enough\" support/workarounds for your specific use case.\n\nThere are only 3 officially supported ZigBee repeaters and they aren't cheap. You're looking at $55.00/ea. to extend your ZigBee mesh if needed. The plus side is Lowes may have some lesser expensive repeaters coming out that if not officially supported the community will inevitably unofficially support (have I mentioned they're awesome?). In contrast you can expand your Z-Wave mesh for ~$25.00/ea.\nHaving a strong mesh can reduce: system lag, devices not updating, and presence problems and it can increases: range, stability, and battery performance. Many community problems (devices not working properly/reliably, battery life to name a few) are due to weak mesh.\n\nMany of their \"Officially supported\" device types do not offer all of what the device has to offer. For instance I am using an unofficial device type for my lock because the official one cannot handle assigning opening codes/management. Therefore I lose local control. This is a common occurrence, and mostly targets \"power users\" so I don't believe it's high on their list atm.\n\nCurrently you cannot add multiple users.... This is Huge - My WAF was extremely low because I moved from a system where she had her own user and now does not. ST has said it's \"working on it\", but other than that there is no eta.\n\nConclusion:\nFor the technologically inclined:\nThis is a Great system. There currently isn\u2019t another system as Open as them with the same protocols. They are the furthest along in this regard. In my opinion they\u2019re setting the bar for the power user that others should strive for, but it is an admittedly low \u201cofficial bar\u201d. And is just high enough with the \u201cUnofficial community support\u201d. If they didn\u2019t have the community it would be much worse than Iris, Wink, or Staples.\n\nFor the Average Joe:\nThis is a pretty good option. If you stick close to official device types and smartapps you will do just fine. You will be able to automate many things. If you wish to tinker a little bit you can do a few more. Or if you are willing to ask for help/search a forum/wiki for answers you will be able to learn some fun things about HA.\n\nFor the Un-Technological Folk:\nThis could go either way. Even if you stick to the Official device types and smartapps you will probably need to read a FAQ or Two to get started. It isn\u2019t that difficult to do basic automations\u2026 But the easy ones to create may not do what you desire. It will take some time to set up, but it isn\u2019t difficult.\n\nFor the Plug and Player:\nStay far far away. If you are not willing to spend a little time to set up and familiarize yourself this system is not for you. Do not walk\u2026 Run away from this system. If you are still interested in HA talk to the nearest professional installer."}
